or in northern Uganda<br>The <font size=-1>UN</font>'s unhappy family<br>Blockading the Palestinians<br>Privatisation in El Salvador<br> ...in Uruguay<br> ...in Ecuador<br> ...and in Paraguay<br></ul><br><h3>EUROPE</h3><ul>Russia's muscular regions<br>Ingushetia's success<br>German angst over immigration<br>Italy's bizarre election campaign<br>Europe's shaky pillar of justice<br>Backsliders from <font size=-1>EMU</font><br>France's language malaise<br></ul></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><h3>BRITAIN</h3><ul>Mad cows and politicians<br>Elections for Ulster<br>Gun control<br>Barometer: Public borrowing<br><a href="br1.html"><font size=-1>GP </font>fundholding isn't working<br></a><a href="br2.html">Improving divorce<br></a><a href="br3.html">Trustbusters at loggerheads<br></a><a href="br4.html">In Brief<br></a>Bagehot: Labour and spending<br></ul><br><h3>BUSINESS</h3><ul>Computer retailing's difficult boom<br>Contrasts in British engineering<br>India's way with software<br>Resurgent in Tinseltown<br>Michael Jackson's curious Kingdom<br>Russia's biggest tax dodger<br>Face value: Donald Cruickshank<br></ul><br><h3>MANAGEMENT BRIEF</h3><ul><font size=-1>AT&T</font> and <font size=-1>NCR: </font>marriage from hell<br></ul><br><h3>FINANCE AND ECONOMICS</h3><ul>Europe's stockmarkets get in trim<br>Brussels' baffling bourse<br>The <i>jusen</i> saga continues<br>The mess in Mexican banking<br>More muni-market mayhem<br>Inflation and investments<br>Multilateral aid and lost souls<br>Chancellor Kohl's secret agents<br>Economics focus: Television<br></ul><br><h3>SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY</h3><ul>A row about climate change<br>Inheriting alcoholism<br>Looking at microscopes<br>Planes without tails<br>Evolution on islands<br></ul><br><h3>MOREOVER</h3><ul>Splits in the Orthodox church<br>High-tech museums<br>Johnson on everyday English<br>Interviews v letters<br></ul><br><h3>OBITUARY</h3>