<html><head><title>The end of patriarchy</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>



<h1>The end of patriarchy</h1>


<p><b>Life without father is bad for everyone</b></p><ul><li><a href="6ex149.html">A M<font size=-1>AN'S</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Steve Humphries &amp; Pamela Gordon. <br>
<li><a href="6ex150.html">D<font size=-1>ISMEMBERING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>ALE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Joanna Bourke. <br>
<li><a href="6ex151.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>MAGE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> M<font size=-1>AN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By George Mosse. <br>
<li><a href="6ex153.html">L<font size=-1>IFE</font> W<font size=-1>ITHOUT</font> F<font size=-1>ATHER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By David Popenoe. <br>
<li><a href="6ex154.html">N<font size=-1>O</font> M<font size=-1>ATTER</font> H<font size=-1>OW</font> L<font size=-1>OUD</font> I S<font size=-1>HOUT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Edward Humes. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>


<p>POOR men. They die faster and live more dangerously. Their genitals are shrinking and their sperm counts supposedly dropping. They are increasingly violent and are slipping in school. Male bastions like the pub, the football stadium and the military have been stormed. The fast-changing economy is creating jobs more suited to women. What's a bloke to do?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The voguish response is: become more like women. Aggression is out; nurturing is in. Competition is out; co-operation is in. Men should be more sensitive. They should become handier about the house and less concerned with work. They should be dab hands with the nappies, and more in touch with their emotions. Such New Men would find real contentment through voluntary partnerships with New Women.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To some extent, this is happening. Many of today's young men are not at all distressed if their wife makes more money, or if their boss is a woman. The sight of fathers tenderly snuggling their infants is so common as to be invisible. And more men are turning down promotion or relocation in order to give more time to their families.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In this sense, today's younger men look and sound very different from those who make up "A Man's World", a collection of oral histories of British men who came to adulthood in the first half of the century. Most had stay-at-home wives and manual jobs. They were sexually inexperienced at marriage, and scared of babies. They valued stability, hard work, stoicism and dinner on the dot. They were, perhaps, the last generation of patriarchs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To modern ears, much of the testimony in "A Man's World" clangs. A retired building labourer says of his family life: "My job was to go to work and bring home money to keep them and provide them with warmth and clothing." His wife's was to have dinner hot and ready. Another says on why he did not see his daughter's birth: "It was taboo. It would've frightened us to death." These are not New Men.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the fact is, other than scattered spottings in California's Berkeley, north London and a few Swedish suburbs, the New Man does not exist. He is a theoretical construct. Yet, at the same time, particularly for the less educated, it is increasingly difficult to fulfil the roles of provider and protector that is expected of Traditional Man.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New Men, of course, are apt to tell pollsters that they would like to to take more household responsibility. We have heard that song before, notes Joanna Bourke in "Dismembering the Male", her survey of how the first world war affected British perceptions of masculinity. The soldier had no alternative but to do his own sewing, cooking and tidying at the front, and many thought that "war-time experience in domestic chores had rendered him a perfect helpmate." In fact, Tommy (like <font size=-1>GI</font> Joe) returned to hearth and home and left the women's work to the women. The same pattern recurred after Hitler's war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Their grandsons are easier to bully into doing the dishes but, as a look at European households by the Family Policy Studies Centre found, "the pace of change can only be described as leisurely." Similar research from America produces the identical conclusion. Even in Sweden, where it has been national policy for decades to make both the public and private spheres strictly gender-neutral, the reality is that this is far from the case. New Men may be thicker on the ground there than anywhere else, but very few take paternity leave and the jobs women go to are overwhelmingly "female" ones like day-care and nursing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, as George Mosse notes in "The Image of Man", the idea of what constitutes manliness--think of the Boy Scout oath--is an enduring one. He traces it back to the mid-19th century, a dating that is less than persuasive. The restrained, brave, handsome, athletic family man whom men respect and women adore sounds much like Mr Darcy or the knights of the Round Table. The idea that moral superiority is related to a man's physical attributes, of which Mr Mosse makes much, goes back to the Romans. And the European male physical stereotype--"clean-cut and fit"--dates back at least to many women's favourite sculpture: Michelangelo's "David".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;David Popenoe is more interesting when he argues in "Life Without Father" how similar the male model is across societies, stretching back to pre-history. There has never been a society, he asserts, where men have done most of the child care; there has never been a society where the father was not expected to act as provider. And marriage developed everywhere to encourage men to stick around their children. The problem, he concludes, is that this model of manhood is eroding--and that America is much the worse for it. Why?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He begins by noting that there are undoubted behavioural differences between the sexes--level of aggression, cognitive skills, sensory sensitivity and sexual behaviour. The New Man model assumes that men will be willing to accept roles for which they have not been well-equipped--full-time infant care, for instance--in exchange for giving up those for which they are--killing mastodons, say. Because this is unlikely to happen on a mass scale, the effect of the model has been to devalue men's traditional value to the family: that of bread-winning. All too often, the male response has been flight. Sometimes through abandonment; more often through non-marriage or divorce.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a problem because fathers who do not live with their children lose interest in them. For men, marriage and parenthood go together; when they lose the marriage, they often stop being fatherly. In America one in five divorced fathers has not seen his children in the past year; more than half do not see them regularly--patterns common to other countries as well. Fathers who do not see their kids do not much feel like paying for them; and failure to pay child support is a growing problem all over the West.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a sense of what a fatherless society looks like, try the American inner city. More than two-thirds of black Americans are born out of wedlock; and there are 180 areas in the national census in which 90% or more of homes with children lack a father. Lots of the boys end up in the juvenile justice system, which Edward Humes describes in "No Matter How Loud I Shout", a dispassionate, devastating work of reportage that records a year in the life of Central Juvenile Hall in Los Angeles. From this account it is only too apparent that a lack of resident fathers is a large cause of America's increasingly violent, sometimes psychopathic, juvenile crime wave.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The real problem with men these days, then, is that they simply are not around. For every New Man, there are thousands of divorced dads who forget their kids' birthdays and dozens of young men who figure fatherhood ends at conception.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the way men define their role has remained remarkably consistent. Surveys show that being a good provider is at the top of the list. What has changed is that fewer men, and more women, can fulfil that role. It is striking that, in the 1993 British Social Attitudes Survey, those men with the least education were the most likely (72%) to agree that "a husband's job is to earn the money; a wife's job is to look after the home and family." And these, of course, are the men who are least likely to be able to earn enough to support a family.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The evidence is that men who cannot support a family do not form one; nor are women particularly eager to marry them. For all the fuss about New Men, and kinder, gentler family life, the sad fact is that patriarchy has ended in the West not because men have given in to the principled arguments about equality and fairness, but because they have given up on fatherhood itself. That is bad news for everyone--perhaps men most of all.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
