<html><head><title>The power of suggestion</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Consumer culture</b></p>
<h2>The power of suggestion</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex164.html">O<font size=-1>UT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> G<font size=-1>ARDEN</font></a>: T<font size=-1>OYS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> C<font size=-1>HILDREN'S</font> C<font size=-1>ULTURE</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> A<font size=-1>GE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>TV</font> M<font size=-1>ARKETING</font>.&nbsp;  By Stephen Kline. <br>
<li><a href="6ex152.html">A<font size=-1>DCULT</font> <font size=-1>USA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By James Twitchell. <br>
<li><a href="6ex165.html">N<font size=-1>EW</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> I<font size=-1>MPROVED</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Richard Tedlow. <br>
</ul>




<p>IN 1977, 20% of the children's toys sold in America were based on cartoon characters licensed from television; in 1987, 70% of them were. For their success, He-Man, She-Ra, My Little Pony and the Droids could thank Marc Fowler, the loyal supporter Ronald Reagan appointed in 1981 as head of the Federal Communications Commission, the body which oversees broadcasting in the United States.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Fowler liked to describe television as "just another appliance--a toaster with pictures". And he changed the rules governing the form and timing of television advertisements aimed at children to permit the transmission of far more of the programmes that starred these toys.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The story of the invasion of the toybox by monsters from the gogglebox appears in two recent books. Both are written by professors, and both treat the marketing of consumer goods as a foundation of modern culture. But the two academics, Stephen Kline and James Twitchell, draw different lessons from their analysis. Mr Kline frets. He thinks children are harmed when their culture is shaped by businessmen whose chief interest is shifting product. Mr Twitchell is entranced. He looks more widely at modern American culture, in which he sees advertising--which he confesses he loves--as the central institution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This Adcult, as Mr Twitchell calls it, swamps old distinctions between high and folk culture, enlisting the creations of both as it tries to imbue the world of manufactured objects with meaning. Others may regard this as a sinister matter of monster corporations deluding the public. Mr Twitchell does not. He describes it as a "conversation"--an exchange in which consumers are active participants, shaping products and advertising as they express their desires in the marketplace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such novelists as Jane Austen, he says, understood the way goods can carry a freight of meaning before economists did, and, like a novelist, he wants the conversation he reports to be entertaining. He writes wittily and enthusiastically, though his fondness for the work of Madison Avenue causes him to lapse occasionally into slogans that might themselves be tag-lines from advertisements.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Adcult" is based partly on a course on advertising and society that Mr Twitchell teaches at the University of Florida. It contains both analysis and a handy history of advertising. Occasionally the non-American reader may be baffled by a reference to some classic advertising campaign from that country, but at least many of the print advertisements mentioned are reproduced among the excellent illustrations. Mr Twitchell's book is a thoroughly enjoyable invitation to scrutinise the ubiquitous medium of modern American culture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kline's "Out of the Garden" is narrower in scope but more detailed in its argument than "Adcult", and more serious in its purpose. He is not just saying violent stories produce violent children. His concern is that when society lets children's television fall wholly into the hands of business it fails to make the most of the power of these programmes to shape culture. He draws on careful studies of boys and girls at play with their toys to build a detailed picture of how watching television is now the main way that children learn to fit into the world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Mr Twitchell's history shows, many of the most innovative advertising pioneers were influenced by religion. One such was Asa Griggs Candler, a devout Methodist who created the greatest American marketing success of all. He bought Coca-Cola from its inventor in 1891, and that year sold 19,800 gallons of the fizzy drink. When he retired 25 years later, sales had increased 500-fold, to 9.7m gallons. For the energy that drove this growth, Mr Candler thanked Christianity, which "raises the productive forces of any life to its highest power." His story, and that of his equally dynamic allies, rivals and successors in the cola business, is told in Richard Tedlow's reissued history of mass marketing in America, "New and Improved".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Tedlow, a teacher at Harvard Business School, traces the development of America's consumer culture through the history of its most successful manufacturers and retailers, rather than through advertisements. As well as the "cola wars" between Coke and Pepsi, he describes the rivalry of Ford and General Motors, the home-catalogue shopping businesses of Sears, Roebuck and Montgomery Ward, and the rise and decline of <font size=-1>A&P</font> grocery stores. In each case success came through moving early, and selling cheaply and in volume, rather than through high mark-ups on the goods sold. Vigorous, compelling men drove these companies to the top with boldness and flexibility, and by doing so helped build the muscular marvel of 20th-century American capitalism. They are exciting tales. Mr Tedlow tells them well.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
