<html><head><title>Old fox</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand</b></p>
<h2>Old fox</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex169.html">M<font size=-1>EMOIRES</font> I<font size=-1>NTERROMPUS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand. <br>
<li><a href="6ex170.html">D<font size=-1>E</font> <font size=-1>L</font>'A<font size=-1>LLEMAGNE,</font> <font size=-1>DE</font> <font size=-1>LA</font> F<font size=-1>RANCE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand. <br>
</ul>

</i>
<p>"HISTORY will judge!" he used defiantly to retort in the face of the barrage of criticism which dogged him throughout the 50 years of his political career. But, ever distrustful of his fellow man, the late French president evidently felt it advisable to give history a bit of a nudge in the right direction from beyond the tomb by providing his own version of the more hotly contested elements of his life--notably his attitude to France's Vichy war-time government and to German unification--in two posthumous works. <i>"</i>M&eacute;moires Interrompus<i>" </i>(Interrupted Memoirs) is a series of heavily-edited conversations with a French journalist, Georges-Marc Benamou. "De l'Allemagne, de la France" (On Germany, On France) is a text hastily written by Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand himself in the last eight months of his life between his departure from the Elys&eacute;e Palace and his death from cancer in January.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are not the last, soul-baring confessions of a dying man, but two passionate, though not always convincing, treatises in his own self-defence in answer to his detractors. No, he never flirted with anti-Semitism or the extreme-right as a young man, he says. No, he never swore an oath of allegiance to the Vichy government; he only held a lowly, contractual post in the regime. Yes, he accepted the "francisque" medal in early 1943 for loyal services to the Vichy government, but only as an alibi for his under-cover activities in the Resistance; this was probably "an error of judgment". Yes, his first meeting with de Gaulle (in Algiers in December 1943) was not easy, but nevertheless passed off much more cordially than is generally supposed. He claims always to have had a "deep admiration for his (de Gaulle's) character, courage, and intelligence". No, he never sought to oppose or delay the move to German unification in 1989-90. Indeed, he protests, he was one of the first of the world leaders both to predict it and to proclaim it a "legitimate" aspiration of the German people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of the ground covered in the two books has already been well-harrowed by the late president and others. Those areas which were dark before remain dark (his relations with Ren&eacute; Bousquet, secretary-general of the Vichy police, the Observatory affair, etc). Mitterrand provides us with no new hard evidence or titillating revelations. Although elegantly written, his lengthy, almost pathetic attempt to convince the reader of his prescience over, and early support for, German unification (to which all but 30 pages of "On Germany, On France" is devoted) is tedious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But much of his so-called "m&eacute;moires" (in fact covering only the years 1940-71) is a delight, full of romantic cloak-and-dagger exploits and amusing anecdotes, including one in which Mitterrand claims to have saved de Gaulle's life by hanging on to his legs as the triumphant leader of the Free French was about to be precipitated out of an upper-storey window of the Paris city hall by an over-exultant throng following the liberation of the capital in August 1944.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is almost certain that anything by or about Mitterrand, France's most complex, cultured and enigmatic president, will go to the top of the bestseller lists in France. It is less certain that these two books will contribute much to an impartial assessment of Mitterrand's so anxiously sought place in the annals of history.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
