<html><head><title>Insularity</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr5.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>European Britain</b></p>
<h2>Insularity</h2><ul><li>M<font size=-1>ISSED</font> C<font size=-1>HANCES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Roy Denman. <br>
</ul>

<p>IN NOVEMBER 1955, at the Messina conference that laid the foundations for today's European Union, Britain's representative, a pipe-smoking Oxford-don-turned-civil-servant called Russell Bretherton, made a brief comment:
<ul><font size=-1>
The future treaty which you are discussing has no chance of being agreed; if it was agreed, it would have no chance of being applied. And if it was applied, it would be totally unacceptable to Britain . . . Monsieur le pr&eacute;sident, messieurs, au revoir et 	bonne chance.</font></ul>


In the view of Sir Roy Denman, a one-time assistant to Bretherton and later a senior official in the European Commission, the miscalculation of Messina was just one of many that Britain has made to its eventual detriment. The current inter-governmental conference to review the Maastricht treaty will, he fears, be another. Britain will pursue a minimalist, obstructive agenda. "An inner core in Europe, headed by France and Germany, will form an economic and monetary union, which will soon broaden into a federation. For Britain this is likely to be yet one more missed chance."</ul>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sir Roy's argument is that in a global economy of interdependent elements, individual voices need to sing in harmony if they are to command an audience. That is why Britain, for all its surface nationalism, has willingly sacrificed sovereignty by joining the <font size=-1>GATT</font>, <font size=-1>NATO</font> and--in 1973, after much pleading--the European Community. And it is why, he says, Britain will miss its chance if it rejects a single European currency for the sake of national sovereignty. That will leave Britain "outside, once a world power, now an offshore irrelevance." In other words, British Eurosceptics should remember that sovereignty without influence is meaningless.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which may well be sound advice (not least because of America's enthusiasm for European co-operation and its diminishing interest in a "special relationship" with Britain). But Sir Roy spoils his case in two ways.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first is his resort to the "if only" school of history. According to Sir Roy, who has much time for Neville Chamberlain and very little for Winston Churchill, Britain both could have and should have stayed out of the second world war, leaving Russia to crush Hitler's Germany. "It would have been a very different world. Britain, France and the Low Countries would have remained intact." But would neutral Britain, France and the Low Countries have been able to live with the moral consequences of turning a blind eye to the Nazis' genocidal rampages? In decrying "the wrong war at the wrong time" Sir Roy is surely too cold-blooded in his assessment of what makes politics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book's second weakness is his lazy assumption that Britain's next missed chance--staying out of a putative European "inner core"--will be a mistake, just as earlier ones were. Conceivably, even probably, it will be. But to make his case Sir Roy should first answer some obvious Eurosceptic charges: that France, with its nation-state tradition, will eventually be at odds with federalist Germany; that the inner core, with its strong currency and addiction to social benefits, will price itself out of jobs and into electoral unpopularity; that the inner core will perversely divide the European Union and its "single market" just as it is seeking to embrace new ex-communist members.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, Sir Roy is tempted to extrapolate: because the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s integrationists can boast four decades of a prospering, "ever closer union", as the various treaties put it, a federation--shades of a United States of Europe--is both desirable and inevitable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Does Sir Roy therefore despair of Britain? Not entirely. But read between the lines and it is plain that he suspects a Labour government under Tony Blair would find the hurdles just as hard as the Tories under Margaret Thatcher and John Major.
<ul><font size=-1>
Britain never had a serious house-clearing revolution. The royal family, the church, the law, the army, the City, the landowning class, inherited money and their concentric circles have continued without a radical break for centuries. The result has been that Britain has largely become a cosy backwater, a back-slapping, 18th-century-type oligarchy, its boardrooms stuffed with clapped-out politicians, Foreign Office retreads and sundry cronies of the Establishment.</font></ul>


On the other hand, he might usefully have noted that, at least for now, Britain can boast lower unemployment than France, Germany, Italy or Spain; that its financial markets dwarf any on the continent; and that its armed forces are held up by President Chirac as a model for France.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
