<html><head><title>The fat years</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>British diplomacy</b></p>
<h2>The fat years</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex177.html">T<font size=-1>O</font> L<font size=-1>IE</font> A<font size=-1>BROAD</font></a>: D<font size=-1>IPLOMACY</font> R<font size=-1>EVIEWED</font>.&nbsp;  By Michael Shea. <br>
</ul>

<p>WHEN Michael Shea, then a young diplomat, arrived in Addis Ababa, he was told he should see something of the country. He spent a morning in a Land Rover being shown the source of the Blue Nile and other sights of Ethiopia. Then, parked under a tree, he awaited a sandwich and a drink of water. Instead, the driver set out a table with white cloth, silver and glasses, a bottle of chilled white wine and other necessities for a decent lunch. The driver replaced his khaki jacket with a steward's tunic and, with a napkin over his arm, showed Mr Shea to his chair at the table and proceeded to serve him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For "an honest man" to be "sent to lie abroad for the good of his country", in the famous remark of Henry Wotton, an Elizabethan diplomat, there have to be some compensations. Fortunately, there is always the larder. Mr Shea later ended up in Romania when it was run on starvation rations by the brutal, and inefficient, Nicolae Ceausescu. However, the British embassy freezer was kept stocked with food brought in once a month from Denmark. The embassy cook, Gina, was outstandingly good, Mr Shea recalls, and increasingly fat. The waistlines of the embassy staff "gradually came to resemble hers."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even better, gluttony is diplomatically respectable. "Diplomats in their thousands are dining for Britain every moment of the day," says Mr Shea. Hospitality "is the key lever" offered by every diplomatic service. Munching for Britain may pall when you are offered by the Chinese more than 20 courses, each more filling than the last. But the conscientious diplomat never forgets that across the dining table may pass the intelligence that is eagerly awaited at home to gain some advantage over a competitor. No wonder ambassadors employ the very best chefs. National honour is on parade. A disastrous souffl&eacute;, a rotten wine, and the cleverest talk falls flat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Shea's revelations, seated comfortably in the belly of his fascinating book, help to explain why diplomats tend to be, if not fat, then well filled. Diplomats may deny this, lying with their usual aplomb; but the evidence is there to see at, for example, any Brussels top-level meeting. The slim, craggy Carruthers figure is rare outside the pages of a novel. "Time to adjourn, Mr Chairman? This talk about food subsidies is making me awfully hungry."


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
