HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:31:44 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:11 GMT
Content-length: 6325
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Friendly natives</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Imperial Britain</b></p>
<h2>Friendly natives</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex171.html">E<font size=-1>MPIRE</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>RITISH</font> I<font size=-1>MPERIAL</font> E<font size=-1>XPERIENCE</font> <font size=-1>FROM</font> 1765 <font size=-1>TO</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> P<font size=-1>RESENT</font>.&nbsp;  By Denis Judd. <br>
<li><a href="6ex144.html">M<font size=-1>UKIWA</a>:</font> A W<font size=-1>HITE</font> B<font size=-1>OY</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> A<font size=-1>FRICA</font>.&nbsp;  By Peter Godwin. <br>
<li><a href="6ex160.html">M<font size=-1>ALCOLM</font> M<font size=-1>AC</font>D<font size=-1>ONALD</font></a>: B<font size=-1>RINGING</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> E<font size=-1>MPIRE</font>.&nbsp;  By Clyde Sanger. <br>
</ul>

</i>

<p>RIGHT at the end of "Empire" Denis Judd comes out with two findings which seem to puzzle him. The first is that India "seemed to have kept the impact of British rule to a minimum". The second is that so few of "Britain's ex-colonial peoples seemed to bear the metropolitan power a lasting grudge."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a shame that these ideas are allowed to surface only at the end of his book. They would have been interesting starting points instead of throwaway comments. He concludes lamely--against the drift of what goes before--that in imperial matters, the British "did their best...not, perhaps, the most inspiring or memorable epitaph for the greatest of the fallen European empires, but it may be the most accurate and truthful, and hence the most acceptable."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Acceptable? Do you mean, Mr Judd, that this is the only conclusion on which those who believe they-were-a-damn-sight-better-off-under-British-rule can agree with the evil-imperialism-colonialism-capitalism-racism brigade? Or do you mean that despite your feelings that the empire was a "bad thing", you have to admit the British empire did not do such terrible damage to mankind after all?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; "Empire" has other throwaway revelations, such as the suggestion that the British empire was not greater than the sum of its parts but rather the contrary. For all the pomp and circumstance about the imperial dream, Mr Judd shows that free trade triumphed over imperial trade. Only by the second world war, when the empire was in terminal decline, did trade between Britain and its empire exceed 35% of all British trade. So much for imperialism being the handmaid of mercantilist capitalism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the empire represented only a third of British foreign commercial interests and is fondly remembered by its victims. Instead of opening up these interesting ideas this book serves up standard interpretations of British imperialism. Chapters (derived from lectures originally conceived in the mid-1970s?) dwell on the "expansionist tendencies of capitalism" or "the ruthless use of military and naval firepower" and the "oppression, violence, discrimination and sheer selfishness that had characterised so much of British imperialism".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After such an interpretation how can anyone conclude that the Brits were not such a bad lot after all? The answer lies (hidden) in this book. Where do you find a grudge against the British? Not in Uganda or Ghana, Singapore or India but among Afrikaners in South Africa, Qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois in Canada and Australians. And especially among die-hard white Rhodesians, whose fight against the winds of change is recalled by Peter Godwin in a beautiful, painful and subtle memoir of growing up in Ian Smith's redoubt.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What really upset the empire was the imposition of liberal principles by the home country on the independent but narrow-minded puritans on the frontiers. The pattern was repeated in Kenya, Southern Rhodesia and South Africa, and to an extent is being played out in Canada and Northern Ireland even now.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That liberal tradition mixed with self interest against "imperial interests", led Britain, late and often deviously, to back the "native" peoples against the colonists. In countries where there were no colonists but only imperial rule, British hegemony (rule would be too strong a word for many of those pink bits on the old maps) was not too bad and often a great deal fairer than the beastly kings and tyrants that had gone before, and in many cases came after. But colonies and imperial possessions were ultimately not in Britain's interest and they were shuffled off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among those who helped bring the empire to a gentle end was Malcolm MacDonald, who served as colonial secretary after the second world war and then as governor of Malaya and Kenya, and eventually as the roving trouble shooter in the Commonwealth. Clyde Sanger (<i>The Economist's</i> Ottawa correspondent) has written a detailed and thoughtful assessment of this charming and energetic ambassador for Britain as it shook off its empire. "I was just the messenger," MacDonald is quoted as saying but he not only made the message palatable, he sometimes devised it. He was instrumental in Kenya and India in befriending the anti-imperialists who inherited the empire--a policy of magnanimity and prudence which made the end of empire relatively smooth.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
