</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Bloody reckoning</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Cambodia</b></p>
<h2>Bloody reckoning</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex166.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> P<font size=-1>OL</font> P<font size=-1>OT</font> R<font size=-1>EGIME</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Ben Kiernan. <br>
</ul>

<p>ONLY one state has been represented at the United Nations by a government in exile. This was Cambodia, from 1979 to 1992. To the world's enduring shame the government that represented Cambodia in those years was run by the Khmers Rouges, who in 1975-79 committed one of the worst genocides in modern history--violence and terror which according to Ben Kiernan led to the deaths of as many as 1.5m in a population of 8m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Drawing upon interviews with 500 survivors and the extraordinarily detailed archives of Tuol Sleng, the regime's main torture and death camp in Phnom Penh, Mr Kiernan painstakingly reconstructs the horror of one of the century's most violent revolutions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not the first account of Pol Pot's terror. Elizabeth Becker, Nayan Chanda and David Chandler have written good studies of those years. But Mr Kiernan's is perhaps the most complete and the closest to Cambodian sources. Most of the interviews by Mr Kiernan, who teaches at Yale University, were done in 1980 after the removal of the Khmers Rouges when Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia, took the capital and provided the backing for a pro-Vietnamese communist government. He interviewed many of this new regime's leaders, most of who were ex-Khmers Rouges. The author does not explain why he waited 16 years for this study, although he has written several monographs on Cambodia's "revolution".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His main argument is that this was neither a proletarian uprising nor a peasants' revolt but a search for power by the Cambodian Communist Party (<font size=-1>CPK</font>) led by Pol Pot. To Mr Kiernan, "the power accumulated by the <font size=-1>CPK</font> Centre was unprecedented in history," a sweeping statement which ignores Stalin's Russia, Hitler's Germany or even more recent regimes such as the late Kim Il Sung's in North Korea or the late Enver Hoxha's in Albania. In fact, as Mr Kiernan himself shows, Pol Pot was challenged by other Cambodian communists, most strikingly in a revolt in the east of the country. Interestingly, that revolt, in May 1978, would have been a more propitious moment for the Vietnamese to step in than when they finally did, early in 1979.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meticulous though Mr Kiernan's account of the Cambodia terror is, he sheds little new light on why it was so ferocious or why the death toll was so high. He chronicles the savagery of the Khmers Rouges towards national minorities such as Cambodia's Vietnamese (most of whom, though, wisely fled in 1975) and its Muslim Chams. By highlighting Pol Pot's demonic vision of creating a "pure" Cambodia, he often loses sight of the fact that the dictator's overriding aim was to seize power to build a socialist Cambodia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Khmers Rouges having liquidated the non-communist opposition, Cambodia's new Vietnamese masters had to recruit to its regime Khmer Rouge defectors. But this was not the only reason for the harshness of Vietnamese-backed rule. Vietnam's masters in Hanoi wanted to impose their own communist orthodoxy throughout Indochina. They resisted the entry of non-communists into Cambodian politics until 1992 when the <font size=-1>UN</font> established its Transitional Authority (<font size=-1>UNTAC</font>) there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dreadful though the Pol Pot years were, they were, sadly, not unique in East Asia. Killing on a similar scale occurred in China in the early 1950s, and again during the Cultural Revolution there in the mid-1960s; and, on a smaller scale, similar ferocity was seen in Indonesia in 1965-66 when President Sukarno was overthrown in a bloody coup and many thousands of Indonesian socialists and communists were murdered. A comparative look at the Khmers Rouges is still awaited.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
