<html><head><title>On the record</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Vietnam</b></p>
<h2>On the record</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>AR</font> I<font size=-1>N </font> Vietnam.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
</ul>



<p>IF FOR any reason you have to mug up on America's war in Vietnam, there are many worse places to start than in the newspaper morgue at the <i>New York Times</i> or in the <font size=-1>CBS</font> archive of news-scripts and videos. For the price of a Broadway show, multimedia puts these in reach of the general public. This <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is that rare thing: a useful and intelligent example of how to present huge amounts of data--written, spoken and filmed--concerning a divisive piece of recent history.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After introductory sounds of Asian music, breaking twigs and gunfire, the menu screen fills with eight panels. One offers a brief historical overview with key points or names in blue to click on for more information. The other seven panels lead to troves of fact, text and image for users to rummage in at will. The chronology (also with "hypertext" highlighting) runs from mid-1940, when Japanese troops occupied French Indo-China, to July last year, when President Clinton re-opened diplomatic relations with Vietnam. It covers both the war and, for background, events elsewhere. Each page, turned to a sound that could be marching feet or card-shuffling, is tiny. But there is a month-by-month time-line that can speed the search. The "Biography" contains profiles of 147 generals and politicians taken from the <i>New York Times</i>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a record of the war from America's point of view. "Weapons", mainly about American hardware, is for military buffs. "Honors" lists the names of America's dead. "As it happened" is a stock of short video-clips, mainly from <font size=-1>CBS</font> broadcasts. The maps are imaginatively chosen. They include historical and physical ones as well as town plans. But, as is normal with <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, they are awkward to use and too small in scale to be really useful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This disc's real resource is its "Library". It includes: dozens of historical documents--letters, memos, communiqu&eacute;s, speeches, agreements (not always, it has to be said, clearly sourced or with cuts indicated); a bibliography; a list of documentary and feature films on the war; as well as the text of the Paris Peace Accords of 1973.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Library" also has extracts from the Pentagon Papers, a secret and pessimistic official study of the war which Daniel Ellsberg, one of its authors, bravely leaked and the <i>New York Times</i> in 1971 bravely published. It includes dozens of <font size=-1>CBS</font> news transcripts, among them Walter Cronkite's famous broadcast of February 27th 1968 just after the communist Tet offensive, in which he delivered his "speculative, personal and subjective" judgment that the only way out for America was to negotiate "not as victors but as an honourable people who lived up to their pledge to defend democracy and did the best they could."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The generals and politicians in Hanoi knew from the start that theirs was a two-front war--on the ground in Vietnam and in the hearts and minds of America. After the war a convenient myth developed in some quarters in America that the war was "lost" on television and Mr Cronkite's broadcast was exhibit <font size=-1>A</font>. This was bunk. America's leaders never convinced a majority of Americans that the war was winnable or, indeed, of what it was for. Mr Cronkite was giving America the plain truth.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
