<html><head><title>Foul professionals</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr10.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Economic woes</b></p>
<h2>Foul professionals</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> T<font size=-1>HIRD</font> R<font size=-1>EVOLUTION</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Harold Perkin. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE many thousands who got a lift from "The State We're In" by Will Hutton should buy "The Third Revolution" for another stomp on the free-market economy, this time against the backdrop of the global economy. Even those unfashionable people who did not relish the polemic against Thatcherite Britain by the economics editor of the<i> Guardian</i>, who has since become editor of the <i>Observer</i>, can fruitfully grind through this book with gritted teeth. For Harold Perkin pours out facts useful to anyone trying to form an open-minded view of the ingredients of good government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is not open-minded: his specs are almost permanently steamed up. "On any objective view the experiment under the Reagan-Bush and Thatcher-Major regime has done more harm to their economic growth and social cohesion than either Hitler in the second world war or Stalin, Khrushchev and Brezhnev in the cold war." This excerpt shows what the professor means by "objective view".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "third revolution" of his title is the unstoppable rise of the tertiary, or service, sector in the advanced economies. This is a timely topic, because there are still many people in the rich world who find the perspective of jobs with an intangible output hard to accept. Whereas landlords dominated farm-based economies, and capitalists dominated the industrial phase, the high ground in the post-industrial era is held by professionals who control the scarce resource of "manifold forms of expertise". The challenge, Mr Perkin thinks, is to stop these indispensable pros from exploiting societies to the point of collapse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His two arch-exploiters are the Russian <i>nomenklatura</i>, who subverted the Communist experiment and thus caused it to fail, and now the greedy bosses of multinational companies and the free-market zealots who are ravaging the societies of Britain and the United States. His model professionals are to be found in Japan and especially Germany.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For supporting evidence the reader might well turn to the index to seek "unemployment", "job-creation", "employment" or any other mention of the problem that bedevils Germany, or of the remarkable rate at which the American economy is creating jobs and firms. Incredibly he would find none. The fact that caring Germans are now prescribing a mild dose of free-market salts to Germany to price its struggling <i>Mittel</i><i>stand</i> companies back into all-round contention does not fit the thesis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a huge pity that somebody as knowledgeable as Mr Perkin cannot sift the British and German experiences for the lessons on employment and wealth creation that they can offer each other. Only an intellectually dishonest free-marketeer can ignore the German model's remarkable productivity, or not wonder whether the staggering pay-and-benefit packages currently being given to corporate bosses in Britain and North America do not stoke the "them and us" mentality that has so bedevilled British labour relations over the years. And only somebody equally dishonest can refuse to find anything refreshing in a market-oriented shake-up of some of the established functions of the European state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bigger dilemmas than this book describes face the world economy. How do you combine national government with business that transcends nations through the rise in the role of foreign direct investment? The sales of subsidiaries abroad now amount to one-fifth of the output of the world economy, and comfortably exceed direct exports. How does a government best promise social justice while creating the minimum of economic rigidity in the process? Mr Perkin provides food for such useful thought, but also kills the appetite in anyone but a fellow obsessive. Luckily for his publisher there are plenty of these about at the moment.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
