<html><head><title>Demonised</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>American employers</b></p>
<h2>Demonised</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex162.html">B<font size=-1>RUTAL</font> B<font size=-1>OSSES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Harvey Hornstein<br>
</ul>

<p>HARVEY HORNSTEIN has perhaps been unlucky in his timing. His insistence that American bosses are far more brutal than their counterparts in Japan reads oddly in the light of the revelations from Normal, Illinois, where Japanese managers allegedly permitted the bullying and molestation of their female staff.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But then it is hard to have any sympathy with someone who has such a disregard for history. He insists that today's American bosses are more brutal than their predecessors. Yet the government is more vigilant than ever before about everything from health and safety to racial and sexual abuse. The workforce is arguably better educated than in the past, and certainly more conscious of its rights. And the booming economy means that unhappy workers are more likely to be able to find another job than they have been for a decade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is more, the latest management fads are shifting power from bosses to their underlings. The spread of desk-top computers has allowed companies to strip away layers of middle managers. The popularity of team-based production means that more and more workers are managing themselves. And senior managers keep their jobs only if they meet demanding performance measurements.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A growing number of workers are showing that they know how to get rid of unpopular bosses. At Morrison Knudsen, for example, the employees not only undermined their boss, William Agee, by sending adverse reports to the board, but held a riotous party when he was sacked.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No doubt some ambitious American <font size=-1>P</font>h<font size=-1>D</font> is preparing a rebuttal to Mr Hornstein, which shows that, far from being brutal, the bosses too are victims, just like everybody else in the United States.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
