<html><head><title>Saving the earth</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>



<h2>Saving the earth</h2>
<h2></h2><p><b></b></p><ul><li><a href="#1">F<font size=-1>INANCING</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Stephan Schmidheiny, Federico Zorraquin and the World Business Council for Sustainable Development.  <br>
<li><a href="#2">N<font size=-1>ATURE'S</font> K<font size=-1>EEPERS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Stephen Budiansky. <br>
<li><a href="#3">U<font size=-1>NCOMMON</font> G<font size=-1>ROUND</font>.</a>&nbsp;  Edited by William Cronon. <br>
<li><a href="#4">M<font size=-1>IRAGE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Russell Clemings. <br>
<li><a href="#5">H<font size=-1>OW</font> M<font size=-1>ANY</font> P<font size=-1>EOPLE</font> <font size=-1>CAN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>ARTH</font> S<font size=-1>UPPORT?</font> By Joel Cohen.</a><br>
</ul>
<A row rages over man's use and abuse of the earth. "Books in Brief" listens in to the debate
 </td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>F<font size=-1>INANCING</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font>.<br>
 By Stephan Schmidheiny, Federico Zorraquin and the World Business Council for Sustainable Development.  <br>
<i>Press; 236 pages; $22.50 and &#163;14.50</i><br>
<a href="6ex148.html">Extract</a> - <a href="6jb148.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt148.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>AT FIRST sight financiers and environmentalists have little in common. The first want to make money, the second to save the planet. "Financing Change", written by green-minded businessmen, shows that the two groups are beginning to strike up a relationship.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Insurance and reinsurance firms, for example, now worry that global warming might lead to more natural disasters and hence higher insurance pay-outs. Bankers are having to heed the environmental liabilities of their business borrowers (in America some banks have been held liable for contaminated land which once belonged to their clients).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fund managers are regularly lobbied by green pressure groups which try to persuade them not to invest in this or that forestry, mining or oil company. The growth of ethical investment funds has made financial analysts more aware of the moral concerns of small investors. Even the bosses of polluting companies have begun to recognise that greenery sometimes increases profits: using raw materials more sparingly can cut costs as well as emissions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless there is still a big gap between environmentalists and most financiers. Polls suggest that most financial analysts still think green issues are irrelevant to their jobs. In Britain ethical funds represent a mere 1% of all funds under management. Although cutting pollution can bring down costs, cutting it to zero would put most natural-resource companies out of business. The strength of this book is that it points out that--in certain circumstances--companies will make more money, or lose less, if they turn green. That is likely to impress them more than any appeal to their moral sensibilities.</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>N<font size=-1>ATURE'S</font> K<font size=-1>EEPERS</font>.<br>
 By Stephen Budiansky. <br>
<i>Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson; 310 pages; &#163;20.</i><br>
<a href="6ex145.html">Extract</a> - <a href="6jb145.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt145.html">Biography</a><br>
</i>
</i></td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>U<font size=-1>NCOMMON</font> G<font size=-1>ROUND</font>.<br>
 Edited by William Cronon. <br>
<i>Norton; 560 pages; $29.95 and &#163;24</i><br>
<a href="6ex155.html">Extract</a> - <a href="6jb155.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt155.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>IN THE eyes of many greens anything that man does is likely to upset the world's natural order. Hence, they argue, man should avoid interfering with nature at all costs. These two books attack that argument.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Natural" landscapes are nothing of the sort, says Stephen Budiansky. In North America, for instance, people are wrong to imagine that the first European settlers there entered a true wilderness. American Indians had regularly set fire to forests to clear them of undergrowth. Many of the "wild" moorlands of Europe are the result of peasants burning forest to graze cattle. Countless species of plants and animals have become dependent on these man-made habitats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Budiansky also attacks the idea that nature is inherently stable. He argues that its "normal" state "is to be recovering from the last disaster". Species have regularly collapsed and revived as storms, floods, fires sparked by lightning and other acts of God have destroyed their habitat. Some species have learnt to depend on such disasters (moose, for instance, follow fire to eat the resulting flush of green shoots).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Uncommon Ground" deals with similar themes. It comes out of a seminar held at the University of California at Irvine to explore "contemporary environmental problems from a broadly humanistic interdisciplinary perspective". Predictably, a number of the academics who contribute chapters prefer long, pretentious words where short ones would do. Even so there are interesting discussions on the idea that wilderness is a human creation, and on the distrust between environmentalists and those, such as farmers and foresters, who actually work with nature.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some will see both books as anti-green. In fact, they are more subtle. They expose some mistaken assumptions in the arguments used by environmentalists. Good environmentalists will adapt their arguments accordingly.</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>M<font size=-1>IRAGE</font>.<br>
 By Russell Clemings. <br>
<i>Sierra Club; 247 pages; $28</i><br>
<a href="6ex146.html">Extract</a> - <a href="6jb146.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt146.html">Biography</a><br>

<p>IN A book subtitled "The False Promise of Desert Agriculture", Russell Clemings argues that much irrigated land throughout the world has become either waterlogged or salinated. In these regions, he says, the productivity gains brought by irrigation have been short-lived.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is it fair to describe desert irrigation as a "false promise"? As Mr Clemings recognises, it is a farming technology which has helped world food production to grow as fast as world population in recent decades, thus helping to save millions from starvation. Although it has caused environmental problems, these may be eased either by improved technology (Mr Clemings himself praises "drip irrigation") or higher water prices (in many countries subsidised water encourages farmers to use too much).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Drawing on the work of anthropologists, Mr Clemings argues that the ancient Sumerians hastened the collapse of their civilisation by over-irrigating their land. Unless modern irrigation systems are improved, he says, "future archaeologists may be left to puzzle over what became of us as well." A little over the top, perhaps?</td></tr></table>
<a name="5"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>H<font size=-1>OW</font> M<font size=-1>ANY</font> P<font size=-1>EOPLE</font> <font size=-1>CAN</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> E<font size=-1>ARTH</font> S<font size=-1>UPPORT?</font> By Joel Cohen.<br>
<i> Norton; 532 pages</i>; <i>$30 and &#163;22.50</i><br>
<a href="6ex147.html">Extract</a> - <a href="6jb147.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt147.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>HIS is a fascinating question, involving calculations about food security and the world's natural resources. Rather than answer it, however, Joel Cohen prefers to sit on the fence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nowhere in the book does he estimate how many people the earth can support. (Estimates by scholars cluster between 4 billion and 16 billion, compared with about 6 billion now.) His conclusion is painstakingly cautious: "The possibility must be seriously considered that the number of people on the earth has reached, or will reach within half a century, the maximum number the earth can support in modes of life that we and our children and their children will choose to want." The implication is that the earth will support more people, provided they put up with more unpleasant conditions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are excuses for Mr Cohen's caution. The earth's carrying capacity is a complicated concept. It depends on a large range of variables including geographical space, food, water and energy. It depends on the standard of living that people can expect to maintain. It depends on the speed of technological progress (how fast grain yields can increase, for example).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet he ought to have made a stab at an answer. For if the world's population is about to hit a ceiling of some sort, drastic policies to curb population growth need to be introduced fast. If not, then earthlings can rely on economic growth and technological progress to solve most of these problems.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
