<html><head><title>New takes</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr13.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Steven Spielberg</b></p>
<h2>New takes</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex163.html">S<font size=-1>PIELBERG</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Frank Sanello. <br>
</ul>

<p>THIS is a perfectly awful dive-bomb of a book, one that appears to have taken a week to research and two days to write, allowing for intervals for junk food. Frank Sanello is happy to leave "sort of like", "et al" and "buh duh bup" sticking from his prose like giant crumbs. Give him a phrase he likes, such as Steven Spielberg's remark that he is "the guy in the corner at the party eating all the dip", and he will repeat it not three times, but four for good measure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why read it, then? Because Mr Sanello has the knack of picking out facts and anecdotes that are particularly revealing about his subject; and because his subject is fascinating. In commercial terms, Steven Spielberg is the most successful film director of all time. In 1993-94 he earned more money, $335m, than any other entertainer in the world, displacing Michael Jackson. Yet the maker of "Jaws" (box-office gross $115m), "E.T." ($700m) and "Jurassic Park" ($850m) has always longed to be seen as a great and serious director, not merely a money-spinner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With "The Color Purple" in 1985, a film about abused black women, he ventured for the first time, as he put it, into "the deep section of the pool". But he could not direct anything great, he later explained, until he had fathered children and, through his children, "seen God". When both these things occurred, in 1992, he began to make "Schindler's List".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That film, a masterly and harrowing account of the rescue of Polish Jews from the Holocaust, marked the moment when the Academy finally recognised him with Oscars in almost every category (having palmed him off with technical awards for "E.T." and "Jurassic Park"). But, more than that, it marked Mr Spielberg's middle-aged discovery of his Jewish roots. Growing up in suburban Scottsdale, Arizona, he had tried desperately to integrate, even to the point of sticking down his huge nose every night with duct tape. His most vivid childhood memories of his Jewishness were of trying to conceal a pot of boiling lobsters from a visiting rabbi, and of being set upon as "a filthy Jew" at school. He persuaded the leader of those bullies to leave him alone by offering him a star part in a film he was making with his father's 8mm camera. And so a career was born.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although he kept his Jewishness concealed, remarkable <i>chutzpah </i>helped him to rise. Taking the bus tour of Universal Studios one day, he simply got off the bus, wandered about, found an empty office and squatted there for two years. Eventually, he persuaded Sid Sheinberg, the head of production, to look at his amateur films; one so impressed Mr Sheinberg that, in 1966, Mr Spielberg was put under contract for $275 a week. The genesis of "Jaws", in 1974, was almost as extraordinary. Mr Spielberg happened to notice the galleys of the script lying in the production offices of Zanuck and Brown, and begged to be allowed to direct it. The film had already been assigned to Dick Richards; he was taken off the case.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The technicalities of film-making are not Mr Sanello's forte. He is more interested in the human side (Harrison Ford's continual diarrhoea, Julia Roberts's hard time on "Hook", Kate Capshaw's run-in with countless insects and 4,500 snakes in "Indiana Jones"). He enjoys the expensive gadgets (the five rubber sharks in "Jaws", all called Bruce, who kept sinking and cost $1m; E.T., also made of rubber, who cost $1.5m; the comparatively cheap computer-generated dinosaurs of "Jurassic Park").
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reader does not learn much about Mr Spielberg's techniques as a director, save that he was taught by his friend George Lucas to draw out each scene on story-boards before shooting, and that he worships David Lean. But this may be because Mr Spielberg never credited himself with much originality as a director until he made "Schindler's List". Before then, he admitted, he tended to steal his best effects from the great directors of the past.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With "Schindler", however, he threw away the crane and the dolly track and even returned to a hand-held camera, so anxious was he to get close to his story. That story, like all his other films, was an attempt to come to terms with his past. "Schindler's List" explored the repressed Jewish side, not without guilt and shame on Mr Spielberg's part: he had been taught to count by a neighbour who used, as a teaching aid, the concentration-camp number tattooed on his arm. Before that, "Poltergeist" had expressed another childhood terror, ghosts crawling from a crack in the wall; and "E.T." and "Empire of the Sun" had expressed the misery of separation that Mr Spielberg felt when his parents divorced. He has never made a film, he says, which was not about some creature or thing which he feared or believed in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now that he has grown up, where will Mr Spielberg go next? In 1994 he set up his own studio, DreamWorks <font size=-1>SKG</font>, with Jeffrey Katzenberg, ex-head of film production at Disney, and David Geffen, a record mogul who is also the richest man in Hollywood. Bill Gates of Microsoft has been recruited to create interactive computer videos.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much will depend on what Mr Spielberg can find to direct. After "Schindler's List" he said he saw no reason why he could not make happy or frivolous films again; he was an optimist at heart. Yet nothing has come his way except the silly "Casper", on which he was executive producer; and nothing is lined up except a sequel to "Jurassic Park" next year. Having scaled his mountain, Moses-like even to the luxuriance of his beard, it is hard for Mr Spielberg either to move, or to come back down.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
