<html><head><title>Heroes and humans</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Irish dramatists</b></p>
<h2>Heroes and humans</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex167.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>AMUEL</font> B<font size=-1>ECKETT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Lois Gordon. <br>
<li><a href="6ex168.html">B<font size=-1>ERNARD</font> S<font size=-1>HAW</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>SCENT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>UPERMAN</font>.&nbsp;  By Sally Peters. <br>
</ul>

</i>
<p>FROM reading these two books you might conclude that the only attributes held in common by George Bernard Shaw and Samuel Beckett were nationality and vocation. Before Lois Gordon's book you might have held the belief that both were also hypochondriacal, but she passionately disputes even this in the case of Beckett.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The weakness of her book has its origin in her references to Deirdre Bair's "Samuel Beckett: A Biography", and her apparent desire to repudiate it--especially in the matter of Beckett's supposed indifference to the second world war, his introspection and his general eccentricity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A richer book might have allowed for all these Samuel Becketts to exist in the one person, despite the objections of those who knew him and, indeed, despite the worship of those who knew him. For worship produces a sort of secular saint--in Ms Gordon's terms heroic, responsive to the suffering of humanity, and deeply involved in the normal pains of being alive. No doubt at times he was.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Her book is further affected by a trust in the journalistic approach to history. The title promises a picture of Beckett's world, but Ms Gordon's view of the world is painted in the narrow colours of the books and accounts of the times. Her long series of notes at the back of the book alert the reader to her faith in written evidence, her clerking skills and indeed her research powers. But one suspects somehow that, in looking for Samuel Beckett, a more radical lamp is required--a requirement not altogether fulfilled by Ms Gordon's frequent evoking of what Beckett <i>might</i> have read, <i>might</i> have seen, <i>might</i> have thought.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hers is a brave attempt to enter the exterior world of Beckett  propos the decades he lived through, but the interior man eludes her. Maybe this was the ambition of Beckett's interior world--to remain as hidden and as pristine as the moon. You could walk in his garden but never his house.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However the book comes magnificently alive in a chapter on the friendship of Beckett and Joyce. In fact Ms Gordon's power somehow to enter the inner world of James Joyce is remarkable by contrast. She gives a tremendous portrait of him in his later days, as sad as a street ballad or an aria, struggling against the tides of war and infirmity. This is truly a heroic picture, and the heroic nature of the picture arises from the strange communality of Joyce's experience--the manner in which his sorrow for the woes of mankind arose from his ferocious sharing in those woes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And so from the victoriously private world of Beckett to the victoriously public world of Shaw. Sally Peters's fine scholarly book is long and the type is maddeningly small. She has to contend with the vast cornucopia of subject matter relating to Shaw, for the trouble with Shaw is that to write about him authoritatively you have to be interested in all the things he was interested in, from philandering to phrenology.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On his hypochondria she is superb and on the roots of it she is seemingly wise. Similarly Shaw's fusion in his own mind with Shakespeare, to the degree that he scrapped parts of "Cymbeline" and gave it an entirely new ending, as if Shakespeare had "spoiled" it, is interestingly discussed. And most intriguing is her search through the hints of Shaw's doings for the evidence of his homosexuality, even if his homosexuality seems as elusive as a bittern hiding among the water-reeds. She works hard to get a decent light on Shaw's puzzling sex life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, to some degree, it is a curiosity of Beckett and Shaw that the more they are discussed the more they seem to disappear. Both are unknowable. In fact the more you know, the less. And in Beckett's case the suspicion remains that he chemically altered the ground of his life so that exposition cannot flourish there.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
