<html><head><title>Saints and sinners</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr15.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Italian travel</b></p>
<h2>Saints and sinners</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex105.html">U<font size=-1>MBRIA</font></a>: A C<font size=-1>ULTURAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font>.&nbsp;  By Ian Campbell Ross. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE Umbri, who gave their name to the Italian region of Umbria, were mysterious people who lived a thousand years before Christ. They left little behind them but a few massive walls and seven bronze tablets, discovered in the 15th century at Gubbio. On these are inscribed some rules, the most striking of which detail the precise ways in which any of their neighbours unlucky enough to be captured by them should be sacrificed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reader of Ian Campbell Ross's cultural history realises pretty soon how apposite such rules must have been. Umbria has seen more than its share of sudden, violent death. Earthquakes, plague and famine were commonplace, but the savage despoliation of invaders even more so, starting with the Etruscans who seized most of the ancestral lands of the Umbri. At least the Etruscans introduced a little civilisation. Their legacy was a tradition that happily survives: they introduced, he says, "new methods of banqueting, and the use of wine"; they even had their own bibulous deity, pleasingly named Fuflans. Later on wave after wave of marauders thundered through, on their way to Rome: Ostrogoths, Lombards and Byzantines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the Middle Ages, the Guelphs and Ghibellines were the principal murderers. They slaughtered each other by the dozen, and by every conceivable method. Mr Ross's prose becomes clogged with lists of named villains and their imaginative atrocities. The Oddi slew the Baglioni, and vice versa; Lucrezia Borgia ruled malevolently in Spoleto and Arrigo Monaldeschi della Vipera in Orvieto. Perugia and Assisi, though separated only by 20km, warred for centuries--yet in those two cities alone there are countless works of art, created by sublime painters and architects while battles raged, quite literally, around them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Ross loves these cities and their masterpieces. When he has finally dispatched the last of the bloody tyrants to an unquiet grave, he turns to the real heroes of Umbria, the saints and the artists. To read his luminous descriptions of Lorenzetti's "Deposition", or his praise of St Francis (patron not only of all Italy but of Europe and the International Green Party) is to want to book your ticket to Assisi immediately.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He also likes his food and provides a useful chapter about what to eat in Umbria--and what to avoid. He clearly approves of the little brown lentils of Castellucio and provides a tasty-sounding recipe for them, but he does not recommend the McDonald's in Perugia, nor does he lament the passing of such local delicacies as <i>sbobba</i>, <i>smulicato</i> or <i>sanguinaccio</i>, concoctions of cabbage, maize and pigs' blood--though <i>stinchi dei morti</i> are, he assures us, nicer than they sound. The wines, too, command respect: the best way to taste a really good Vin Santo is, he says, to find a small producer prepared to invite you in for a glass.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His book ends with a gazetteer, suggesting scenic paths through the main cities and diversions to the remoter hill-top towns. He provides information about the location of the tomb of Hugh of Hartlepool and of a nearly contemporary monument to Thomas  Becket. And he adds that Hendrich van den Broeck, a Dutch painter, is known in Umbria as Arrigo Fiammingo--Harry the Fleming in English.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For this is not a conventional guide-book. The reader soon becomes used to Mr Ross's interests and aversions. He will mention, with a shudder, where you could find a plaster figure of a friar wearing an Inter Milan soccer shirt, but he trusts you to avoid the spot. He has no patience with St Rita. Beyond mentioning that the modern basilica to the patron saint of impossibilities is tasteless, he leaves you alone to discover that in her little town of Cascia, which attracts huge numbers of pilgrims, you can buy walking sticks topped by bicycle-bells and hung with flasks of disgusting, if potent, liqueur. You never know--you might, one day, be glad of that information.



<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
