<html><head><title>College knowledge</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>College knowledge</h2>
<p><b>Multimedia advice for British students is catching up with that in America</b></p><ul><li><a href="#1"><font size=-1>PUSH</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
<li><a href="#2"><font size=-1>ECCTIS</font>.</a>&nbsp;   <br>
<li><a href="#3">W<font size=-1>HICH</font> U<font size=-1>NIVERSITY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
<li><a href="#4">S<font size=-1>TUDY</font>L<font size=-1>INK</font>.</a><br>
</ul>

<p>WITH more than 100 universities and 700 further-education colleges to choose from, Britain's students have little ground for complaint about lack of choice, though being students--and British--they will probably still complain. Deciding where to go can be daunting.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Four <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> guides are available to help the current generation of computer-wise sixth-formers make their choices. "<font size=-1>ECCTIS</font>", "Which University" and "StudyLink" rely mainly on information from the universities themselves. "<font size=-1>PUSH</font>" gives an alternative, student's eye view. Each has a search mechanism to help students narrow down which subjects interest them, and what sort of institution they would like to study at. From a shortlist of universities and colleges matching their specifications they can then find out more about the courses each provides, as well as the housing, sports, fun and other things they can expect.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Frustratingly, with each of these <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, the amount of detail given varies a lot from university to university. "Which University", for instance, has a file for each institution with fairly scant information on the courses it offers, the cost and availability of on-campus housing and so forth. But 19 universities have, in addition, provided "multimedia prospectuses" with video and audio clips, photographs, and more detailed information on what life is like there. These may be worth watching if you are already interested in going to the university concerned, though genuinely useful material is scattered thinly amid a mass of waffle and self-promotion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Liverpool's multimedia prospectus is among the best on the "Which University" <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>, though it soon becomes tiresome watching smug students pop up to say how wonderful Liverpool and its university are. Better are the video clips which give a real taste of what life on campus is like or what makes Liverpool University special--a glimpse, for example, of the hospital for horses run by Liverpool's veterinary faculty. Less hype would make more space for, say, a view of chemistry practicals and history seminars, or perhaps even a day in a student's life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The current edition of "StudyLink" is similar in many ways to "Which University", though its multimedia clips are even less sophisticated. However, a new version is about to be released, and its publishers say it has been revamped, with a layout that is easier to use and has more information on each university.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ECCTIS</font> does without flashy video clips, and is in many ways the best and certainly easiest for narrowing down choices--either by study area or by geographical region. For each course at any university there is a summary of the topics covered, including special options, and an indication of the exam grades that applicants will need to be accepted. There is other useful information such as a careers guide by the Law Society for those thinking of becoming solicitors after completing their degree.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>PUSH</font> <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> ought to be the ideal antidote to gushing, officially approved electronic prospectuses. It sets out to say what each university is really like, and it is certainly more frank than the other guides. The management of Bolton Institute of Higher Education is unlikely to be pleased by <font size=-1>PUSH</font>'s judgment that it lacks atmosphere and has a "tatty, crowded and smoky" canteen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <font size=-1>PUSH</font> is too erratic in what it chooses to say about each university, and its authors seem to have spent too much time on feeble attempts at student humour and not enough on research. It would be more useful to know what the students have to say about on-campus housing, the state of the library and the quality of teaching. <font size=-1>PUSH</font> is not much help with these.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It has strong points, though. It has a clear guide to the complex system of applying for university places. It also gives a useful snapshot of what local pubs and clubs are like. The disc is easy to navigate and when the audiovisual presentations are running a handy indicator shows how much longer it has left to run.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As most schools have access to the Internet, pupils planning to go on to university or college will also find it worthwhile to seek out the home pages of any institution that they are considering applying to. The quality and quantity of information provided varies--many institutions have barely begun to build their Internet sites, while others have quite sophisticated presentations. Wolverhampton University's site is the best place to start, not just because it is one of the slickest, but also because it has a hypertext map of Britain to take you to every other university or further-education college on the Internet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wolverhampton's site includes an interactive prospectus describing the courses on offer. It has details of student accommodation and local maps. A student-union section tells you about bands playing at local venues, the price of beer at student bars, and lots more. And WorldWide Telematics has a site with links to all further-education colleges in England which are on-line, plus summaries of government inspectors' reports on them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;American students have an even bigger choice of colleges and universities than their British counterparts--so a trawl through the Internet for information and tips is advisable, though as in Britain, the quality and quantity of information on offer is highly variable. Each of the 3,000-plus colleges and universities in the United States has its own Internet site, often with pages provided by the student union. Much of the information in such pages is aimed at current, rather than prospective students--such as small ads and on-line versions of the college newspaper. But at least they give a few clues to what the student's life is like. And "CollegeView" and "Internet College Exchange" are on-line American versions of "Which University", helping users to narrow down their choices of course and college.</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left><font size=-1>PUSH</font>.<br>
<i>McGraw-Hill; &#163;58.75 (single-computer version); &#163;175.08</i> <i>(school networks).</i><br>

</td></tr></table>
