<html><head><title>Fast forward</title></head>
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="6gr17.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Cinema on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Fast forwardC</h2><ul><li><font size=-1>OREL</font> A<font size=-1>LL</font> M<font size=-1>OVIE</font> G<font size=-1>UIDE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
<li>B<font size=-1>LOCKBUSTER</font> E<font size=-1>NTERTAINMENT</font> M<font size=-1>OVIES</font> <font size=-1>&</font> V<font size=-1>IDEOS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
<li>M<font size=-1>ICROSOFT</font> C<font size=-1>INEMANIA</font> '96.</a><br>
<li>C<font size=-1>RITERION</font> G<font size=-1>OES</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>OVIES</font>.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
<li>E<font size=-1>PHEMERAL</font> F<font size=-1>ILMS,</font> 1931-1960.</a>&nbsp;  <br>
</ul>

</i>
</i>

<p>NOT so long ago, the film historian and the conscientious film critic had to slog through a library of cinematic reference books to select scenes from movies they wanted to study on a <font size=-1>VCR</font>. With the advances made in the multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font>, their desks have changed dramatically. All those films guides and encyclopedias have been supplemented, and often supplanted, by a small rack of <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s packed with the equivalent of many thousands of pages of printed text and pictures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the scholar's and critic's ideal world the <font size=-1>VCR</font> would also be redundant. But for the time being it still has a role to play: playing the actual films. Today's <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s offer only short extracts from films, and of poor quality. Even on a 22-inch screen, a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> film cannot be viewed at a width of much more than three inches without losing resolution. And because a 90-second clip from, say, "Amadeus" takes up approximately 12 megabytes of disk space, even the prodigious capacity of a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> cannot cope with many such clips.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until further advances are made in data compression, makers of film <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s face a choice. They can either offer an encyclopedia that catalogues many thousands of films or they can opt for classic clips. With 90,000 entries, Corel takes the encyclopedic route in its "All Movie Guide". But it also has a nice feature: you can scan through a map of the world, click on a place and see a film clip linked to the country or region you choose. Blockbuster's "Movies &amp; Videos" is also an encyclopedia, but seems set on enticing its viewers to hire or buy videos from this video-rental giant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft's film <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is more fun. The presentation is slick and it has a good mix of background information, sound and stills. The editors' choice of clips is excellent. For instance, Butch Cassidy (Paul Newman) learning that the Sundance Kid (Robert Redford) cannot swim even to escape certain death at the hands of bounty hunters. Don't worry, Butch reassures his buddy, the fall will probably kill you anyway. There are articles on more than 850 movie topics from such reference books as Ephraim Katz's film encyclopedia as well as biographies and filmographies of 4,000 performers and a score of 90-second movie clips. But if you already have the '95 version don't bother to buy the '96 one: the improvement is not striking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Criterion Goes to the Movies" from Voyager is even better than the offerings from Microsoft. It has more than 140 clips to play with, and lots of information to satisfy film buffs. The clips are gems. In "Goldfinger", James Bond is about to be dissected by the laser of a 22-carat villain. He demands: "You expect me to talk?" Nefarious chuckle. "No Mr Bond, I expect you to die." Pleasing additions are the original trailers for many of the films, so you can get an idea of the way "The Wizard of Oz" was sold to the public in the 1930s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Voyager's "Ephemeral Films, 1931-1960" is a more specialised project. It pulls together 600,000 training or advertising films from the golden age of American film. The tone is one of moral guidance, backed up by hard work. Sexism is uninhibited. "What to do on a date" (1951) offers advice for the anxious young man. Find out whether your girl would like a skating party or wienie roast. If she opts for the latter, politely state that that is just what you wanted to do. And for the young ladies? In "Three Smart Daughters" (1938) they procure a date thanks to their sewing skills.


<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
