<html><head><title>Lost innocence</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Italian fiction</b></p>
<h2>Lost innocence</h2><ul><li><a href="6ex175.html">S<font size=-1>ETA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Alessandro Baricco. <br>
<li><a href="6ex172.html">U<font size=-1>TO</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Andrea De Carlo. <br>
<li><a href="6ex173.html">E<font size=-1>LIANTO</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Stefano Benni. <br>
<li><a href="6ex174.html">C<font size=-1>ORRUZIONE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Giorgio van Straten. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>THOUGH sometimes written off as an exhausted medium, the Italian novel is in surprisingly good health. Critics have blamed its supposed decline on natural decay, on murder by television or on the obligatory reading of Italy's 19th-century classic by Manzoni, <i>I promessi sposi</i> (The Betrothed), which schoolchildren must struggle through. Yet routinely the arrival of a fresh set of authors proves the doomsayers wrong.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alessandro Baricco is among the most readable--and prolific--of the new generation, as well as being probably the most talented. His "Seta" (Silk) is set in provincial France in the 1860s ("while Flaubert was writing 'Salammb&ocirc;"') and concerns Herv&eacute;, a man of 32 who works for a silkworm breeder. The worms come from Africa but a virus infects them and Herv&eacute; is sent to procure a supply in Japan, a land not yet open to foreign merchants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A traditional novelist emulating Conrad would have devoted chapters to describing an adventurous journey across Europe and Asia in the 1860s, with a dramatic clandestine entry into the forbidden territory. Mr Baricco covers all that in one paragraph and repeats in almost exactly the same scanty phrases Herv&eacute;'s many subsequent trips, thanks to which he is able to set up a flourishing silk trade back home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What interests Mr Baricco and makes this little book such a pleasure is the romance between the Frenchman and a mysterious girl who may or may not be Japanese and with whom, on one of his trips, he finally succeeds in spending a night of love. Later, in France, Herv&eacute; receives letters which he believes to be from her and has them translated by the Japanese madam of a brothel in N"mes. These letters and a surprising ending to this intriguing tale confirm Mr Baricco's gift as a story-teller.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;" Uto" is by another prolific young writer, Andrea De Carlo, a prot&eacute;g&eacute; of Federico Fellini's who realised he was better at novel-writing than making films. Uto, a charismatic teenager with a gift for the piano, is shaken by the suicide of a friend his own age. His mother sends him off for a "spiritual" holiday with a family they know who live in a Krishna-type community in Connecticut. As in Pier Paolo Pasolini's film "Theorem", but less morbidly, the boy bewitches them all. By the end, he has become the community's new guru.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr De Carlo seems uncertain about how far he wants his tale to be taken as a satire on Hermann Hesse's "Siddhartha" and the changes in his style of story-telling are disconcerting. Some of the writing is like a film treatment. Yet he cannot avoid creating sympathetic engagement with his characters, and the novel, in the main, is an agreeable read.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unusually for a contemporary Italian novelist, Stefano Benni is funny. He also writes for the stage and recently did a re-worked version of "Hamlet". His "Elianto" (Sunflower) is aimed at the cybernetic generation. In understandable language he conveys a crazy vision of coming eco-social breakdown in a landscape usually reserved for film. His allegorical satire at the expense of Italy's politicians--some of the caricatures are easily recognisable--is not done with a light touch. But his cluttered urban scene with "smogscrapers" on the horizon seems drearily credible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A topical theme is even more present in Giorgio van Straten's "Corruzione" (Corruption), published by Giunti in its well-regarded "Mercury" series. The background is one of Italy's most notorious recent scandals, Tangentopoli, and the "Clean Hands" investigations. But this is not a political pamphlet. The novel's narrator becomes involved in politics after the disappearance of a friend from student days. It emerges that the friend is fleeing from compromise and scandal--like so many others suspected of having "dirty hands".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In heartfelt innocence on leaving university, the narrator, the missing friend and two fellow students had made a pact to meet again at the age of 40 and take a year's sabbatical together for a sailing trip round the world. The trip is never taken. The book's mood is set on the opening page when the narrator's seven-year-old son asks: "Daddy what's the most beautiful thing in the world?", and Daddy, after thinking, replies: "The smell of a place you're visiting after a long time." The boy, understandably puzzled, says: "No, I meant something you can touch, like a football or a computer."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is this "smell of a place where you've been before" which the narrator is seeking as he investigates his friend's disappearance that makes this an allegory both wistful and pungent.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
