<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><br><h2>What the world is reading</h2><p>Going into the summer of 1996, American readers of hardcover fiction are more than usually reluctant to wander and wonder abroad. They are sticking mostly to novels written by their fellow Americans. Translators are almost as under-worked in Britain, where "Slowness" is a rare bestseller by a novelist whose mother tongue is not English. But the British list is not as low-brow as the American one. Books by such serious writers as Roddy Doyle, Melvyn Bragg, Milan Kundera and Doris Lessing jostle against steamy page-turners from Jilly Cooper and Catherine Cookson. Italian novelists dominate the Italian list, where aspects of love are a recurring theme. The German list is much more cosmopolitan than the rest. Indeed, Germans seem keener on reading novels written by foreigners than by their fellow Germans.<br><h3>Fiction bestsellers<a href="#foot">*</a></h3><ul><li><a href="#usa">United States</a><li><a href="#br">Britain</a><li><a href="#It">Italy</a><li><a href="#gr">Germany</a></ul></td></tr></table><a name="usa"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>United States</h4><ol><li>Moonlight Becomes You<i> by Mary Higgins Clark</i>. &#160; Retirement-home intrigue by serial-thriller writer </li><li>Malice<i> by Danielle Steel</i>. &#160; A woman overcoming life's abuses</li><li>Primary Colors<i> by Anonymous </i>. &#160; B*ll and H*ll*ry R*dh*m Cl*nt*n</li><li>First King of Shannara<i> by Terry Brooks</i>. &#160; Prequel on fall of Druid scholars </li><li>The Horse Whisperer<i> by Nicholas Evans</i>. &#160; Wrangling as therapy in Montana</li><li>Spring Collection<i> by Judith Krantz</i>. &#160; Family secrets in the fashion world</li><li>In the Presence of the Enemy <i> by Elizabeth George</i>. &#160; Celebrities' kid kidnapped </li><li>The Celestine Prophecy<i> by James Redfield</i>. &#160; Ancient new-age wisdom</li><li>Neanderthal <i> by John Darnton</i>. &#160; Primitive protohumans</li><li>Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire<i> by Steve Perry</i>. &#160; What the movies don't tell you </li></ol></td></tr></table><a name="br"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>Britain</h3><ol><li>Appassionata<i> by Jilly Cooper</i>. &#160; Sex in the shires</li><li>The Woman Who Walked Into Doors<i> by Roddy Doyle</i>. &#160; Wife battering in Dublin</li><li>Credo<i> by Melvyn Bragg</i>. &#160; A 6th-century Northumbrian tale</li><li>The Sett <i> by Ranulph Fiennes</i>. &#160; A Midlands accountant pieces together the events which wiped out his personality</li><li>The Gap Into Ruin: This Day All Gods Die<i> by Stephen Donaldson</i>. &#160; Space-age opera (cont'd)</li><li>Shock Wave <i> by Clive Cussler</i>. &#160; Dirk Pitt versus sinister South African diamond-mine concern</li><li>Maskerade <i> by Terry Pratchett</i>. &#160; Satire on modern British life</li><li>The Upstart<i> by Catherine Cookson</i>. &#160; Class antagonism in Victorian England</li><li>Slowness<i> by Milan Kundera</i>. &#160; Two tales of seduction, 200 years apart</li><li>Love, Again<i> by Doris Lessing</i>. &#160; Diary of 19th-century French girl transforms 20th-century lives</li