<html><head><title>To Lie Abroad</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl177.jpg"><img src="cs177.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>O</font> L<font size=-1>IE</font> A<font size=-1>BROAD</font>:<br> D<font size=-1>IPLOMACY</font> R<font size=-1>EVIEWED</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Michael Shea. <br>
<i>Sinclair-Stevenson; 272 pages; &#163;17.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6jb177.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="6bt177.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Extract</p></b>

Image and Reality
<p><ul> These, then, are the qualities of my ideal diplomatist. Truth, accuracy, calm, patience, good temper, modesty and loyalty. They are also the qualities of an ideal diplomacy. </ul> 'But,' the reader may object, 'you have forgotten intelligence, knowledge, discernment, prudence, hospitality, charm, industry, courage and even tact.' I have not forgotten them. I have taken them for granted. Harold Nicolson</ul></p>
<p>Splendid requirements or insufferable arrogance? Diplomacy has changed dramatically since these words were written. Or has it? It has had plenty of time to change. An office of Secretary of State responsible for Foreign Affairs dates, after all, back to the Middle Ages with permanent ambassadors appointed from the fifteenth century on. By 1782, when the Foreign Office itself was established, the staff consisted of two Under-Secretaries and a mere dozen other clerks and paper keepers. Over two hundred years later (1993-4), there are some six and a half thousand members of the Diplomatic Service, two thousand eight hundred of them serving in 216 separate overseas countries.</p>
<p>For those who argue that diplomacy is in archaic and terminal decline, the rich and rounded regal phrases of the various letters of credentials I have been issued with in my time may offer some ammunition. Elizabeth the Second, by the Grace of God of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and Her other Realms and Territories Queen, Head of the Commonwealth, Defender of the Faith. To all and singular to whom these Presents shall come, Greeting!</p>
<p>Whereas it appears to Us expedient to nominate some person of approved Wisdom, Loyalty, Diligence and Circumspection [n.b. the Capital Letters] to represent Us . . . Now Know Ye that We, reposing especial trust and confidence in the discretion and faithfulness of Our Trusty and Well-beloved Michael Shea, have nominated, constituted and appointed, as We do by these Presents nominate, constitute and appoint him, the said Michael Shea to be Our First Secretary and Head of Chancery at Bucharest... Giving and granting to him in that character all power and authority to do and perform all proper acts, matters and things which may be desirable or necessary for the promotion of relations of friendship, good understanding and harmonious intercourse between Our Said Realm and Romania... and for the protection and furtherance of the interests confided to his care; by the diligent and discreet accomplishment of which acts, matters and things aforementioned he shall gain Our approval and show himself worthy of Our high confidence . . .</p>
<p>Such over-flamboyant and antiquated, or rich and distinguished (depending on your taste) language has, in my view, a charm that is well worth preserving, but whatever one's view, it proves nothing about the decline of diplomacy or the real worth of the British diplomatic effort.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
