<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>N<font size=-1>ATURE'S</font> K<font size=-1>EEPERS</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Stephen Budiansky. <br>
<i>Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson; 310 pages; &#163;20.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt145.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

For over a hundred years nature-lovers have held fast to the belief that
preserving the wild means keeping people out. But as Stephen Budiansky
dramatically demollstrates in Nature's Keepers, nature is much more chaotic
and chancier than those who believe in the balance of nature' would have us
think. The almost religious conviction that nature is constant, eternal and self-
regulating, except when man intrudes, is fundamentally wrong.
<p>In the last few years the new science of mathematical ecology has begun to make sense of many of the battling paradoxes of nature. With a wealth of examples from plant and animal life, Budiansky shows how this new research is being applied to actual problems such as the elk overpopulation in Yellowstone National Park or the grouse underpopulation on Scottish moors</p>
<p>This research and these insights are of the greatest importance to wildlife conservation today, as well as enriching our appreciation of the natural world</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
