<html><head><title>A Man's World.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl149.jpg"><img src="cs149.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A M<font size=-1>AN'S</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Steve Humphries &amp; Pamela Gordon. <br>
<i>BBC; 198 pages; &#163;12.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

During the first half of the twentieth century the distinctions between men and
women were far more rigid than they are today. Whilst men enjoyed greater
power and social standing, they were also the focus of a whole set of
preconceived ideas and expectations as to how they should behave both in their
private and public lives.
<p>A Man's World, and the six-part BBC television series it accompanies, explores the experience of masculinity in Britain between 1900 and 1960. Through the personal testimonies of men from all walks of life, an extraordinary picture emerges of what it meant to be male during this time.</p>
<p>In all their roles--soldier, worker, lover, father--the ideals of strength and courage lay at the heart of what was expected of a 'real man'. But beneath the male display and pretence lurked deep anxieties; men were often more uncertain about themselves than they admitted. A Man's World is a moving testament to this. By persuading the men of this period to open up and talk honestly and intimately about their life experiences, Steve Humphries and Pamela Gordon have reached far beyond the limited confines of textbook theories, and have provided an exceptional picture of the way men really thought and felt about their world.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
