<h2>N<font size=-1>EW</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> I<font size=-1>MPROVED</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Richard Tedlow. <br>
<i>Harvard Business School; 528 pages; $17.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt165.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

Featuring a new introduction by the author that considers the impact of
technology and the electronic environment, this seminal history of mass
marketing is an account of how the United States became the world's first and
foremost consumer society.
<p>In New and Improved, Tedlow traces the evolution of U.S. markets in this century. Considering the roles of demographic change, advances in transportation and communication, and corporate culture, he illustrates the dynamics of competition by recounting the epic confrontations between Coke and Pepsi, Ford and GM, A&P and its rivals, and Sears and Montgomery Ward.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
