<html><head><title>To Lie Abroad</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl177.jpg"><img src="cs177.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>O</font> L<font size=-1>IE</font> A<font size=-1>BROAD</font>:<br> D<font size=-1>IPLOMACY</font> R<font size=-1>EVIEWED</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Michael Shea. <br>
<i>Sinclair-Stevenson; 272 pages; &#163;17.99</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt177.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

The Diplomatic Service is one of the most powerful institutions in the British
Establishment, yet few on the outside know what life is really like in the world
of diplomacy. Sent 'to lie abroad' for the benefit of the country, we expect our
diplomats universally to conform to a limited number of stereotypes - the
stuffed-shirt ambassadors in the glittering embassies of the more prestigious
capitals; the wheyfaced bureaucrats in Brussels; the ginsoaked consuls sent to
languish in the steaming hell-holes of the former empire; and the cunning
operator who, even after the collapse of Communism, still deals in espionage
and betrayal.
<p>But to what degree are these images true ones? There is so much more to what the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and its staff at home do, as well as in British Embassies, Consulates and Missions overseas. In this book, Michael Shea, for twenty years a diplomat himself, takes a lively and amusing backwards look at his former profession. He draws on a delightful selection of other people's writings on the subject to provide an informed and informative account. From Harold Nicolson to W. H. Auden, from Lawrence Durrell to Douglas Hurd, this blend of fact, fiction and poetry explains something of the mysterious but critical process of diplomacy and the oiling of the wheels of international relations.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
