<html><head><title>Brutal Bosses.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl162.jpg"><img src="cs162.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>RUTAL</font> B<font size=-1>OSSES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Harvey Hornstein<br>
<i>. Riverhead; 192 pages; $19.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt162.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

On-the-job mistreatment has become so common--an estimated ninety percent
of the nation's workforce suffer abuse by superiors at some point in their
careers--that tales of cruel bosses have emerged as an oral storytelling tradition
of the late twentieth century. In Brutal Bosses, Harvey Hornstein applies his
expertise to these horrific and all-too-familiar survivors' stories to reveal the
subtle causes and toxic effects of abuse at work, and to blaze a path for the
return of dignity to the workplace.
<p>Based on the narratives of hundreds of working men and women, from factory workers to corporate executives, Brutal Bosses provides not only a grim and revealing portrait of routine oppression by bosses but a clear vision for transforming the system that allows them to thrive. The author, a professor of psychology at Columbia University and a veteran senior management consultant, reveals the crucial differences between "tough" bosses and abusive ones; the strategies various types of supervisors (Duhumanizers, Blamers, and Rationalizers) use to copy with their own pressures and then pass on to subordinates; and the kinds of bosses (Conquerors, Performers, and Manipulators) who despotic behavior stems not from working conditions but from their own malicious characters.</p>
<p>Brutal bosses is an intelligent and empowering look at the outrageous conditions--which promote everything from hypocrisy to hurled desk objects-- that so many employees face daily. It is an in-depth critique of the circumstances and people responsible for our toxic environments; a useful guide to the ways past numerous pitfalls to a healthier and more productive workplace; and a call for an end to the suspension of common courtesy and civil rights from nine to five.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
