<html><head><title>Brutal Bosses.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl162.jpg"><img src="cs162.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>RUTAL</font> B<font size=-1>OSSES</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Harvey Hornstein<br>
<i>. Riverhead; 192 pages; $19.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6jb162.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>

Harvey A. Hornstein is a professor of social-organizational psychology at
Columbia University Teachers College, and has served as a consultant to senior
management groups throughout the world for more than twenty years. A former
director of the National Training Laboratories' Centre for Professional
Development and a practicing psychotherapist, he lives in New York City.<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
