<html><head><title>Spielberg.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl163.jpg"><img src="cs163.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>PIELBERG</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Frank Sanello. <br>
<i>Taylor Publishing; 274 pages; $22.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt163.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

Spielberg
<p>With mega-blockbuster hits like Jaws, E.T., and Jurrassic Park on his resume, Steven Spielberg has been setting and breaking box-office records for almost two decades. And after the critically acclaimed Schindler's List won the director longoverdue recognition for the serious side of his work, his career has reached phenomenal heights of success. But although his genius has created some of the most memorable movie magic ever to appear on the big screen, there is more to this Hollywood mogul than special effects or Academy Awards can convey.</p>
<p>Spielberg: The Man, the Movies, the Mythology will take you beyond the hype, affording you an unprecedented view of the personal life of the man behind the camera. From a look at his childhood, troubled with experiences of anti- Semitism that would haunt him into his adult life, to an account of his tumultuous relationships with actress Amy Irving and present wife Kate Capshaw, this book offers insight into the private events which have given shape to his very public life and art.</p>
<p>Of course, Spielberg also invites you behind the scenes and onto the sets of the films themselves, revealing the methods used to create such technically complex blockbusters as Close Encounters of the Third Kind, Jaws, and Jurassic Park, as well as exploring the director's (sometimes rocky) relationships with such stars as Richard Dreyfuss and Julia Roberts. From accounts of Bruce, the notorious robotic shark whose endless malfunctioning plagued the production of Jaws, to the difficulty of coaxing a terrified Kate Capshaw to shoot a scene involving 20,000 centipedes in Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom, you get the inside scoop on the trials and tribulations of filmmaking and a deeper understanding of Spielberg's indisputable influence on the art.</p>
<p>Drawing from interviews with such Spielberg associates as Robin Williams, Dustin Hoffman, Harrison Ford, and Amy Irving (as well as from more than a half-dozen conversations with the director himself), long-time entertainment reporter Frank Sanello presents a compelling and lucid account of the life of one of the greatest directors of all time. With fifty intriguing photos from both his films and personal life, Spielberg will be an absorbing read for casual fans and movie aficionados alike.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
