<html><head><title>Umbria</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl105.jpg"><img src="cs105.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>U<font size=-1>MBRIA</font>:<br> A C<font size=-1>ULTURAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Ian Campbell Ross. <br>
<i>Viking; 448 pages; &#163;20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6bt105.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

Umbria is becoming increasingly familiar to adventurous visitors to central
Italy. With its dense woodland, vines and olive-groves, Umbria has become
known as the 'Green Heart of Italy'. The tag, however, tells only part of the
story of this fascinating region. Taking its name from a people who lived a
thousand years before the birth of Christ, Umbria was settled by Etruscans and
Romans, and was a cradle of early Christianity; St Benedict, founder of western
monasticism, was born here. The region was also home to one of the gentlest
and most-loved of all saints, St Francis of Assisi.
<p>In the late Middle Ages, many of the region's towns - chief among them, Perugia - grew into powerful independent city-states, at first as republican communes and later under the control of sometimes ruthless despots. At the same time, cultural life flourished, with Assisi's great basilica becoming a repository of medieval architecture and painting unsurpassed anywhere in Europe. Subsequently, Umbria produced or nurtured some of the greatest painters of the Renaissance, including Piero della Francesca, Perugino, Pinturicchio and the young Raphael - much of whose art is still to be seen in the buildings for which it was intended. The region's later history, as part of the Papal States, saw once powerful cities reduced to sleepy provincial towns - vividly described by travellers from Montaigne to Smollett and from Goethe to Henry James. After Italian unification in 1861, however, Umbria underwent a remarkable industrial revolution. Today, it is a lively modern region which benefits from its geographical position at the crossroads of Italy.</p>
<p>This book begins by looking at the creation of 'Green Umbria' and helps visitors understand how the landscapes and settlements of the region came, over the course of three thousand years, to take on the distinctive appearance they have today. There is a separate chapter on Umbrian painting from the Middle Ages to the present day, and a final chapter celebrating the variety of foods and wines with which Umbria is abundantly provided. A detailed gazetteer helps visitors to plan their own exploration of this endlessly fascinating region.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
