<i>Viking; 448 pages; &#163;20</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="6jb105.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>

Ian Campbell Ross is a Fellow of Trinity College, Dublin, where he teaches
English Literature. He writes extensively on eighteenthcentury British and Irish
literature and the novel His previous publications include Public Virtue, Public
Love: The Early Years of the Dublin Lying-in Hospital, the Rotunda and
critical editions of Laurence Sterne's Tristram Shandy and Henry James' The
Europeans. He lived in Umbria for a year and now returns there as often as
possible.<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,rev">Search</a>
