<html><head><title>Picking lives apart</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr1.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>Picking lives apart</h2><p><b>How to write a good biography and avoid reading bad ones</b></p><ul><li><a href="1ex1-1.htm"><font size=-1>TCHAIKOVSKY</font></a> &nbsp; By Anthony Holden</li><li><a href="1ex1-2.htm"><font size=-1>GEORGE ELIOT</font></a> &nbsp; By Frederick Karl</li><li><a href="1ex1-3.htm"><font size=-1>FANNY STEVENSON</font></a> &nbsp; By Alexandra Lapierre</li><li><a href="1ex1-4.htm"><font size=-1>FISHER'S FACE</font></a> &nbsp; By Jan Morris</li><li><a href="1ex1-5.htm"><font size=-1>H.G.: THE HISTORY OF MR WELLS</font></a> &nbsp; By Michael Foot</li><li><a href="1ex1-6.htm"><font size=-1>THE ROOSEVELTS: AN AMERICAN SAGA</font></a> &nbsp; By Peter Collier with David Horowitz</li><li><a href="1ex1-7.htm"><font size=-1>VERA BRITTAIN: A LIFE</font></a> &nbsp; By Paul Berry and Mark Bostridge</li></ul>A WOMAN who for years swore she  would never write an autobiography is now at work on the second volume of her life. With a pack of biographers closing in, Doris Lessing decided to tell her own story first, even though she thought it 'bad manners to write about the living'.</p><p>	The public appetite for lives is voracious, but many of the books commissioned to satisfy it should have been pulped before publication. No sooner is a person dead or famous than authors flock to their word-processors to beat the pack with the first true life of, say, Lee Kuan Yew or Fred West. Anniversaries, or better still centenaries, have the same bandwagon effect.</p><p>	Last year three people had a go at Graham Greene shortly after his death. Long after his death the same fate has befallen Tchaikovsky, only it is worse. Instead of scholarly inquiry into the development of genius, the arguments have been hijacked by the fact that he was homosexual. The burning issue has become whether Tchaikovsky was happy to be gay, or whether he was hounded to the point of suicide by homophobic persecution. Anthony Holden's version is probably the best, though even he feels duty-bound to devote a disproportionate number of pages to the prevailing theme.</p><p>	Surrounded by all these books, are there ways to sort good from bad? Are there rules of thumb for the writing of less pulpable and more exemplary lives? A simple but easily missed point is that the subject must matter, or at least be interesting. That does not necessarily mean very well-known. One of the best English biographers working today is Claire Tomalin, who has made something of a speciality of writing about women who have influenced famous men. She it was who revealed the true story of Nelly Ternan, the mistress of Dickens. He himself went to great lengths to cover his tracks, but Ms Tomalin removed the covering and, incidentally, shed a harsh new light on a world-famous author whose high moral public stand was belied by the shabbiness of his private life.</p><p>	Ms Tomalin's recent book, 'Mrs Jordan's Profession', did much the same for King William IV. This havering Hanoverian lived with Dora Jordan for 20 years, during which the actress bore him ten children and supported them all by her indefatigable and enormously popular work. Yet he abandoned her and left her to die penniless in a French pension. Tragic as her story is, the warm enthusiasm of her character shines through the letters quoted by her admiring biographer. In one she wrote: 'I find laughter agree with me better than crying.'</p><p>	A second essential for a good biography is that it be selective. Details are important. When Eleonora Duse, a great Italian actress, lay dying in a hotel room in Pittsburgh, she described the town as 'la plus hideuse ville du monde'. Her remark was eagerly snapped up by a local journalist who was to describe her death the next day. Excitedly his newspaper declared that she had considered Pittsburgh an ideal vacation spot. This story, related in William Weaver's excellent life of Duse, is exactly the kind of thing that should appear in a biography. This lonely end in Pittsburgh illustrates the indomitable spunk of a woman who never learned English, but whose histrionic performances in Italian or French filled American theatres. And it is also a reminder of the danger of relying too heavily on oral evidence, even when it comes from eye-witnesses.</p><p>	But the pursuit of detail can be overdone. There is a school of writing which knows no restraint. Take a man like Samuel Beckett: an interesting subject, beyond a doubt, but the reader is mainly fascinated by what drove him to write his extraordinary plays. Some years ago Deirdre Bair wrote about him at length, but she never knew when to stop - it is not interesting to learn on which date he suffered a third attack of athlete's foot, unpleasant as that affliction most certainly is.</p><p>	What we might call the Athlete's Foot syndrome afflicts far too many biographers currently cashing in on the lives of the famous. If you include every detail, inevitably you produce a very big book, though that does not necessarily mean it is a good one. Witness the obese life of George Eliot by Frederick Karl, a professor of English at New York University. It is a tome seriously flawed by errors of judgment, interpretation and style.</p><p>	Style is the third ingredient, after an interesting subject and accurate detail. Every life contains longueurs, but the good biographer knows how to ease readers through them. A French novelist, Alexandra Lapierre, chose, perhaps understandably, a novel method of doing this. When her subject, Fanny, the wife of Robert Louis Stevenson, is enduring patches of uncharted domesticity, Ms Lapierre invents some excitement. She pictures Fanny enjoying ecstasies of sexual passion or breathlessly describing her thrilling needlework in excited gasps. But such romantic creativeness detracts risibly from any sense of accuracy. Belief is suspended - for good. An old hand like Peter Levi makes a much better job of it. His life of Tennyson is a model of its kind. He felt no need to invent anything. When Tennyson was going through a rather thin letter-writing time, Mr Levi found the one example that explained it: 'I would as soon kill a pig', wrote Queen Victoria's poet laureate, 'as write a letter.'</p><p>	A sense of balance is very important. Recently, several authors have become carried away by a pet theory. There has been a spate of books condemning the mothers of famous men. It becomes mighty tedious to read that Baudelaire, for example, or E. M. Forster were stifled and suppressed by over-protective mothers, when much of the evidence points to these women having done their best to make reasonable human beings out of their extremely tricky sons.</p><p>	Similarly, it is just possible that Christina Rossetti was the victim of sexual abuse by her father and that Emily Bronte suffered from anorexia. Recent biographers of these two writers have allowed such fantasies to tip their books over into polemic. By the same token, a great Restoration poet, Lord Rochester, was not averse to a glass or two, but that is no excuse for mentioning alcoholism on virtually every page (nor for listing, as does Jeremy Lamb, the 12 Steps to Discovery as defined by Alcoholics Anonymous): if Rochester had been nothing but a drunk, we would never have heard of him.</p><p>	Sympathy with the subject is a great help. Jan Morris's life of Admiral Jacky Fisher is suffused with it: she declares herself to be half in love with him, half wanting to be him. Her biography is a jeu d'esprit, a homage which eschews the usual scholarly paraphernalia, but which convinces the reader at every turn that she knows, and can tell us, exactly what the man was like. She has been all over the world in his footsteps; she has even tried on his hat. We cannot fail to believe her. </p><p>	Sympathy can go too far. Michael Foot, a former leader of the British Labour Party, has written a fascinating life of his hero, H.G. Wells, but has chosen to ignore the problem of racism, an issue that really should be confronted, given Wells's enthusiastic espousal of eugenics. And sometimes the impression is given, possibly unwittingly, that an author sets out to give a sympathetic portrait but becomes disillusioned on the way. Andrew Motion's award-winning life of Philip Larkin is probably remembered primarily for revealing that Larkin enjoyed porn. The suspicion remains that Mr Motion's discovery of Larkin's collection of smutty magazines tipped him from admiration to disgust. And Diana Souhami might have thought she had a good idea when she set out on a combined life of Cecil Beaton and Greta Garbo, who once enjoyed a brief affair. But so little is known of Garbo, and so much is discreditable about Beaton, that the reader is left feeling that all they had in common was overweening vanity.</p><p>	Happily, while we grimly await the many lives of O.J. Simpson, there are still some excellent biographies about if you choose carefully. Of the current crop, the best pickings include a fascinating saga about the Roosevelts, by the experienced partnership of Peter Collier and David Horowitz, and, another team-effort, a life of Vera Brittain by Paul Berry and Mark Bostridge. Both are written with informed elegance and flair - and neither will break your wrist.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
