<html><head><title>Enlightenment luminary</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr3.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Enlightenment luminary</b></p><!-- heading - may be h2 (eg picking lives apart review) --><h2>Just books</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex3-1.htm"><font size=-1>THE LIFE OF ADAM SMITH</font></a> &nbsp; By Ian Ross</li></ul><p>GIVEN the resurgence of free-market  thought since the early 1980s and the recent passing of two anniversaries (the bicentennials of the publication of the ''Wealth of Nations'' in 1976 and Adam Smith's death in 1990), it is surprising to find that no full-length biography of him has appeared in over 100 years. Closer examination, however, shows Smith to have been a retiring, gentle figure, who divided his life between the University of Glasgow, his hometown of Kirkcaldy, to which he returned after a brief continental tour as tutor to the young Duke of Buccleuch, and nearby Edinburgh, where despite his favour for free trade he ended his life as controller of customs.</p><p>	His mother, who lived into her 90s, remained the only woman in Smith's life. He was unassuming, refused to sit for portraits and described himself as a ''beau in nothing but my books''. He shunned publicity (''I never suffer my name to appear in a newspaper'') and controversy when possible. Although he could claim the close friendship of David Hume, a fellow Scot, and the acquaintance of Voltaire, Quesnay, D'Alembert and other philosophes, he was, in Hume's words, affected by ''indolence and love of solitude''.</p><p>	Even the stories which have been told to spice up his academic bachelor's existence, such as his being kidnapped by gypsies at the age of three or falling into a vat while touring a tannery, turn out to be apocryphal. His most remarkable personal characteristic was absent-mindedness. Ian Ross relates how Smith was visited by a certain noble lady ''as he was going to breakfast, and falling into discourse, Mr Smith took a piece of bread and butter, which, after he had rolled it round and round, he put into the teapot and pour'd water upon it: some time after he poured it into a cup, and when he had tasted it, he said it was the worst tea he had ever met with.'' Samuel Johnson, who disliked what he supposed was Smith's scepticism, declared him a dull dog.</p><p>	Such details as we know of Adam Smith's private life do not provide scintillating reading. Mr Ross accepts this and has written more of an intellectual biography. He shows how Smith's education and personal acquaintance make the ''Wealth of Nations'', his masterpiece, ''in many respects a typical product of the Scottish Enlightenment''. At Glasgow, Smith was taught by Francis Hutcheson, a moral philosopher whose ideas on the benevolence of the ''Author of Nature'' profoundly affected his views.</p><p>	He also came into contact with the work of Euclid and Newton (one contemporary described Smith's system of political economy as a work of ''moral Newtonianism''). From Newton he acquired the ''pleasure to see the phaenomena which we reckoned the most unaccountable all deduced from some principle''. The connecting principle that Smith was to discover in the economic functioning of society was the operation of self-interest tempered by competition, which togather produced the beneficent effects as if guided by some "hidden hand". </p><p> Smith's friendship with two great economic thinkers of his day, Hume and Quesnay, a leader of the Physiocrats, led him to apply his Enlightenment taste for system-building to political economy. He drew upon the laisser-faire ideas of the Physiocrats but disagreed with their suggestion that agriculture was the sole source of economic surplus. Instead, he divided the ''whole price of the  annual product'' into ''the rent  of land, the wages of labour,  and the profits of stock''. From  Hume's ''Political Discourses''  he garnered the anti-mercan tilist ideas that changes in the  inflow or outflow of bullion  influence interest rates and that commerce flourishes where there is civil liberty. Smith's vision was essentially conservative because he believed that material and cultural progress would come about through the effect of ''natural justice'' rather than politics.</p><p>	While Mr Ross might have gone into more detail on the sources of many of Smith's fresh and pertinent observations, which make the ''Wealth of Nations'' a work of literature rare among economic tracts, he does show how his subject's ideas on competition were shaped by his time at Glasgow and Oxford universities. It was Smith's belief that the endowments of Oxford and the tenure of its dons, combined with its monopoly of degrees, stultified the older university. In Glasgow, by contrast, half the professors' fees were paid by students voluntarily attending lectures. From this he concluded that ''the rivalship of competitors, who are endeavouring to jostle one another out of employment, obliges every man to execute his work with a certain amount of exactness.''</p><p>	Joseph Schumpeter famously remarked that the ''Wealth of Nations'' did not contain ''a single analytic idea, principle or method that was entirely new''. Edmund Burke said the same thing more sympathetically when he called the work ''an excellent digest of all that is valuable in former Oeconomical writers with many valuable corrective Observations" , and added that, as those observations were founded on human nature, they would last. This seems, to date, to be so. Mr Ross's achievement in this biography is to have revealed the intellectual sources for his work while reminding us of the practicality, modesty, generosity and essential kindness of this great man.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
