</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Science on CD-ROMs</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Science on CD-ROMs</b></p><h2>Good mousers</h2><ul><li>A BRIEF HISTORY OF TIME<br>By Stephen Hawking. <i>Jim Mervis and Robit Hairman; Creative Labs; $34.99 and &#163;32.99</i></li><li>LAST CHANCE TO SEE<br>By Douglas Adams and Mark Carwardine. <i>Voyager; $49.95 and &#163;34.99</i></li><li>THE OXFORD SCIENCE SHELF. <i>Oxford University Press; &#163;39.99</i></li><li>MULTIMEDIA ENCYCLOPEDIA OF SCIENCE &amp; TECHNOLOGY. <i>McGraw-Hill; $1,300 and &#163;795</i></li><li>THE MULTIMEDIA ENCYCLOPEDIA OF MAMMALIAN BIOLOGY. <i>McGraw-Hill; $495 and &#163;299</i></li><li>THE EYEWITNESS ENCYCLOPEDIA OF SCIENCE. <i>Dorling Kindersley; &#163;59 and $80</i></li><li>THE WAY THINGS WORK. <i>Dorling Kindersley; &#163;59 and $80</i></li><li>THE ULTIMATE ROBOT. <i>Byron Preiss Multimedia and Microsoft Home; $29.95 and &#163;29.99</i></li><li>BIOSPHERE. <i>Morgan Interactive; &#163;29.95</i></li><li>WATER. <i>Yorkshire International Thomson Multimedia; &#163;52.95</i></li><li>REDSHIFT 2. <i>Maris Multimedia; $59.99 and &#163;39.99.</i></li></ul><p> IT IS no surprise to find a multi media version of Stephen Hawking's "A Brief History of Time" among the first popular science CD-ROMs. But it is a surprise to find that the transition from book to CD-ROM has been successful. Books that tell a strong story are not generally well served by hypertext (electronic footnoting that lets you click-and-skip from highlighted bits to others more explanatory or less boring). The stronger the tale's forward drive, the less it encourages looping in  and out on different routes  through the material. Stretches of  film, often the first extra medium  of the "multi" to be added, are  more linear even than text, and invite spectating rather than interacting.</p>  <p> Hypertext works better with grab-bags of material, where the order in which things happen counts less than finding them when you want. "A Brief History of Time" turns the book into a lucky dip by admitting users to Mr Hawking's study, sparsely but intriguingly furnished with a desk, a book, a portrait of Einstein, a doorway leading to Mr Hawking's space-ship and, perched on the desk, a tortoise. Mr Hawking is also about.  </p><p>The "Hawking craft" offers animated sequences on the outskirts of black holes and the fate of a little bespace-suited Mr Hawking as he tumbles down one. Fortunately, the unelongated Mr Hawking remains ever-present at the bottom of the screen to carry the reader back to the safety of his study. And for those who want plain words, there is always the book on the desk.<p></p>	"Last Chance to See", from a book and television series about endangered species by Douglas Adams and Mark Carwardine, has beautiful pictures, still and moving, of rare animals. But they are simply illustrations strung along the text, both printed on the screen and narrated by Mr Adams. Little is gained compared with videotape.<p></p>	Encyclopedias are truly grab-bags, and several are available on CD for science enthusiasts. They range from dry reference works to colourful compendia that invite browsing and discovery. At the Gradgrind end of the scale, the Oxford University Press has bundled its "Concise Science Dictionary", "Dictionary of Computing" and "Dictionary for Scientific Writers and Editors" on to a single disc, "The Oxford Science Shelf". No more than words here, but plenty of them - terms as obscure as "gnotobiotic" and "semi-Thue system" are defined briefly but with enough precision to keep a reader afloat in Nature (a science magazine itself available on CD-ROM).<p></p>	Dearer and more detailed is McGraw- Hill's "Multimedia Encyclopedia of Science &163; Technology", 18 volumes-worth, according to its elegant folder, on a single disc. Dense articles, written by scientists, describe scientific terms, theorems and experiments with enough precision to help an undergraduate solve problems.  </p><p>McGraw-Hill also produces a more specialised disc, the "Encyclopedia of Mammalian Biology", which incorporates more film and sound than its general encyclopedia, along with much technical detail. Like the "Encyclopedia of Science and Technology", it is dense, and a valuable resource for the library, but not entertaining enough to lure a browser for long.<p></p>	"Entertaining while informing" is the battle-cry of the children's CD-ROM crowd. Dorling Kindersley specialises in such things, and at their best they come dangerously near to convincing the user that "science is fun". Its "Eyewitness Encyclopedia" is much less comprehensive than the OUP disc or McGraw-Hill's. It is not really a place to look up words or phrases, but rather a way into learning about big scientific themes. As on the Hawking disc, explorations start in a room, a buzzing, jumbled laboratory, but once a route into the material is chosen, the user is free to roam.<p></p>	Dorling Kindersley has done an equally pretty job with "The Way Things Work", a book by David Macaulay which lacks narrative drive and so lends itself to dipping. Mr Macaulay's illustrations of inventions invite animation; on the printed page they are threaded with arrows and dotted lines to show how the machines depicted move. A woolly mammoth lumbers through the proceedings trumpeting and mumbling as it explores one invention after another.<p></p>	"The Ultimate Robot" by Microsoft aims for some of the same effect, but blends much more fantasy with a modicum of hard facts about robots. Film clips of famous robots (Robbie, R2D2) are fun, but the subject seems more an excuse than a theme, and the disc mainly coalesces around a collection of Isaac Asimov's robot short stories that would be better read in paperback. </p><p> A common topic on science discs is the environment. Ecology is a science of interconnections, and this is good for hypertext. But neither "Water" nor "Biosphere" exploits the chance. "Water" pigeon-holes its topic, while "Biosphere" is an encyclopedia of life on earth. Both would help in school but neither uses multimedia to produce more than the sum of its media parts.<p></p>	Astronomy, which mixes observation with mountains of data, has brought forth one of the few scientific discs aimed at adults which does go beyond what books and films together could offer. Maris Multimedia describes its "Redshift 2" as an on-screen planetarium. It is this and more. The night sky as it would appear from any given point (designated either by a city or by longitude and latitude) on the earth's surface at any date can be summoned to the screen, and then animated as it swings through the night, or evolves over centuries. Constellations can be picked out, or asteroids, comets or other heavenly bodies. Clicking on any star will produce a dense window full of information about it.<p></p>	Your point of view can be shifted farther afield, to any of the other planets, or their moons. Learning the full scope of what is possible would be to acquire considerable knowledge of astronomical techniques and language; those already so equipped will find the disc offers them broad scope for exploration. Almost alone among discs, it allows for interrogation of components in moving pictures - the user can click on a star for information about it even when it is progressing across the field of view. </p><p> Extra material includes film of numerous space flights (many of them Russian; Maris's programmers are Russians working in Moscow, where their work comes cheaper), and illustrated lectures in cosmology and astrophysics. Though complicated, the disc strongly suggests that interactive CD-ROMs have the potential for conveying scientific knowledge that most products on the market have not touched.  </p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
