<html><head><title>Beat writing</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Beat writing</b></p><h2>The best mind of a generation</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex7-1.htm"><font size=-1>ALLEN GINSBERG: JOURNALS 1954-58</font></a> &nbsp; Edited by Gordon Ball</li><li><a href="1ex7-2.htm"><font size=-1>COLLECTED POEMS 1947-1985</font></a> &nbsp; By Allen Ginsberg</li></ul><p>''YOU old fool, at your age, why are you discouraging the young? There's been a revolution in poetry.'' So did a drunken Allen Ginsberg complain to W.H. Auden during a visit of homage to the big man on Ischia in 1957. Auden, who had a pompous side, said something like ''Pshaw'', and sent Mr Ginsberg packing.</p><p>	The 31-year-old poet was momentarily hurt but, deeper down, undented. Sober or chemically enhanced, Mr Ginsberg was used to asking the grown-up world rude, wide-eyed questions and getting smacked in return. On that literary ship of fools known as the Beat Generation, he was about the only wanderer who always seemed to know what he was up to. When he met Auden, his poem ''Howl'' was in its fourth printing and making him famous. Soon afterwards in Oxford, Auden apologised to Mr Ginsberg for treating him ''like a shit'', sensing, perhaps, a voice behind the brash, messy clown.  </p><p>''Howl'' is now in its 51st printing, and Mr Ginsberg's chanting bass fills halls at poetry readings all over the world. The University of Colorado has bought his papers for, it is reported, more than $1m; Penguin Books has just re-issued an extended version of his collected poems; and there is a steady flow of supplementary matter, including these early journals: a jumbled mix of diary entries, poems, dreams and wavery line drawings.</p><p>	The journals were done before Mr Ginsberg took the public stage as poet-protestor in the 1960s. For the more famous episodes - his tweaking of Castro's beard for Cuba's harshness to homosexuals, his crowning in 1965 as ''King of the May'' by Prague students, his anti-war activities in 1968 - readers will need Barry Miles's biography (''Ginsberg''; Viking; 1990). The journals record rather Mr Ginsberg's frantic travels in lower Bohemia, his loft- and bed-hopping with different poet-boyfriends. They give a jagged picture of a very close, very male and often envious Beat brotherhood just before stardom and acceptance broke it apart.</p><p>	But for the public performances, but for the merry pranks, but for his transformation into near-bald but tanned and wise survivor, would anyone still listen to, let alone read, Mr Ginsberg? Doubters, of whom there were always many, would say ''No''. So it is good to have the ''Collected Poems'', which takes us all the way to 1985.  </p><p> When in that same year Helen Vendler, a noted critic, anthologised American verse she gave 36 pages to Mr Ginsberg, more than to anybody else. If you consider that her book included, with odd omissions, modern masters of American high verse from Wallace Stevens to Robert Lowell, this was homage indeed. </p><p>Of course, the detractors said that she needed space for Mr Ginsberg: those raggedy lines of his are so loose-breathed, his style is so long-winded; and, as he shuns form, no wonder he never knows when to stop. But Mr Ginsberg's poetic models - Smart, Blake, Whitman - also relied on mountainous verbal build-ups and on anguished or exalted personal experience to carry them through.</p><p>	Anguish Mr Ginsberg knew early, which may have toughened him for the drugs, ruinous love affairs and later run-ins with the law. His angry politico-poetic manifesto, ''Howl'' (1956), came after a spell in mental hospital (he pleaded insanity to avoid prison when implicated in a friend's theft). His other masterpiece, ''Kaddish'' (1961), was a funeral elegy occasioned by the madness and death of his mother.</p><p>	Besides these high points, there are servings of piffle-verse, jottings that incline to doggerel. A different author-editor might have struck them out. But spontaneity was always the Beat thing. Mr Ginsberg even time-stamps poems to stress their immediacy. ''The Little Fish Devours the Big Fish'' is datelined ''Intercontinental Hotel Bar, Managua, January 25th, 1982, 11pm''. Sometimes emotion is recollected after several  hours: ''One Morning I Took a Walk in China'' is clocked at 9.30 pm.  </p><p>For Mr Ginsberg, you sense, the hour may matter more than the year. All writers have ups and downs. But most change in style. Strikingly, Mr Ginsberg wrote in his 50s almost exactly as he did in his 20s. A sign of not growing up? Maybe. But also of finding a voice early and staying with it. (His father, Louis, was a poet: the son, in a way, was born to it.) There are strong poems here beside ''Howl'' and ''Kaddish'', some revealing formal craft as well as emotional lung-power: his homage to Whitman, ''A Supermarket in California'' (1955), and many of those published in ''The Fall of America'' (1973) and ''White Shroud'' (1986). </p><p> Like it or not, no voice better echoes his times than Mr Ginsberg's. He was a bridge between the literary avant-garde and pop culture. Like television and advertising, his language is full of slogans and syntactically unbuttoned. He is funny and volatile in his emotions, unashamedly (religiously?) frank about the demands of the body and its disappointments, scavenging in his literary references, fast and pre-packed in his judgments. Though maddeningly interested in his most banal reactions - to mining a Nicaraguan harbour, to unwanted phone calls, to outbreaks of wind - he is at least open about his self-fascination. In a ''me-too'', instant-playback world where every voice counts, why not write as it all is, here and now, for him? </p><p> In most writers self-preoccupation is usually mortal. But Mr Ginsberg has the balancing gifts of promiscuous curiosity and an almost sappy, American optimism (odd as that qualifier sounds these days). In 1855 Whitman wrote: ''I celebrate myself/And what I assume you shall assume/For every atom belonging to me as good belongs to you."  Mr Ginsberg, you feel, still believes every word. </p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
