<html><head><title>Overseas Chinese</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr9.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Overseas Chinese</b></p><!-- heading - may be h2 (eg picking lives apart review) --><h2>Family affairs</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex9-1.htm"><font size=-1>LORDS OF THE RIM</font></a> &nbsp; By Sterling Seagrave</li></ul><p>WHEN he was still coherent, China's  patriarch Deng Xiaoping liked to give apocalyptic warnings about what would happen if communist rule were overthrown. He foresaw chaos, civil war, and - to make sure foreigners got the point - a flood of 100m Chinese refugees. But given the success of earlier emigrants, Mr Deng's threat sounded almost like an inducement.  </p><p> In Hong Kong and Taiwan, where the population is overwhelmingly Chinese, economic miracles have been wrought with few natural advantages other than human enterprise and deep harbours. Singapore (77% Chinese) has managed the same trick. In Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia, Chinese minorities have provided much of the impetus for prolonged booms. They have also reaped many of the rewards.</p><p>	These exiles, moreover, have supplied much of the capital, expertise and marketing network behind China's own economic explosion. In his book on the overseas Chinese in Asia and the Pacific, Sterling Seagrave puts their number at 55m, accounting for a notional "gross national product" of $450 billion - of the same order as that produced by the 1.2 billion people in China itself. When Mr Deng opened China's doors, he did so first in four "Special Economic Zones" (SEZs), chosen to attract the overseas Chinese. </p><p> The SEZs were close to the setting-off points for three of the most important dialect groups among the Chinese diaspora: the Cantonese, who predominate in Hong Kong; the Fujianese or Hokkien, who make up 85% of Taiwan's population, and much of Singapore's; and, less well known, the Teochews from around Shantou.</p><p>	The Teochews are a force to be reckoned with. They include Hong Kong's most respected billionaire, Li Ka-shing; the Ma family which controls the Oriental Press Group there; and most of the Chinese community in Thailand, including the Sophonpanich family, who built up the Bangkok Bank.  </p><p> An earlier, if temporary, overseas Chinese, Sun Yatsen, the first president of the Chinese Republic, once famously compared the Chinese people to "a heap of loose sand". He said they lacked "national spirit", and "have only family and clan solidarity". This observation might seem outdated. After Sun, China was swept by a revolution that was as much nationalist as it was communist. And Chinese everywhere often share a far stronger sense of ethnic community than do, say, Europeans.</p><p>	But the attachment felt by Chinese emigres to the provinces and villages of their forefathers bears out Sun's sense of the strength of family and clan ties. A banker in Singapore makes a trip back to the family home on China's Hainan island, which he has never seen, but where he tries to buy land. A Hong Kong developer, Gordon Wu, says he was inspired to build his "superhighway" from Shenzhen to Canton by seeing the New Jersey turnpike and feeling his province should have one too.  </p><p> According to Chinese statistics, a staggering $220 billion-worth of "foreign" investment was committed to China between 1979 and 1993. Of that, about 80% was promised by firms in Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan and Singapore. Still more overseas Chinese money is concealed in the figures for investment from elsewhere in South-East Asia, and from North America and Europe. Of course, family sentiment was not the main propellant. China was short of capital and over-endowed with labour at a time when Hong Kong and Taiwan in particular were short of land and workers, but rich in cash. China was where there was money to be made.</p><p>	But Mr Seagrave is right to draw attention to the importance of clan and dialect networks within the overseas Chinese community and relatives left at home. It is not just the Cantonese, Hokkien and Teochews. There are the Shanghainese, the Hainanese, the Hokchia and the Hakkas. This last group, whose geographic origins are obscure, has the distinction of having produced three Chinese leaders at once - Mr Deng, Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui and Singapore's Lee Kuan Yew.</p><p>	The investment numbers hide another large but unquantifiable amount of mainland Chinese "hot" money that has been shifted off-shore, to a safer haven, and reinvested back in China. Mr Seagrave traces the roots of this practice to the age-old antipathy of the official class for grubby traders. When Jardines moved their domicile from Hong Kong to Bermuda in 1983, there was a Chinese outcry at this lack of loyalty. When Li Ka-shing shifted a large chunk of his assets to the Cayman Islands earlier this year, there was barely a murmur. Such caution is the hallmark of a Chinese merchant.</p><p>	If Mr Seagrave's book has a hero, it is Lee Kuan Yew, whom he calls the "Thomas Jefferson of the Pacific Rim", and "the unseen hand behind the Mainland boom and the emergence of a Greater China". The story of the overseas Chinese in Asia has not just been an unbridled success. It has also been a story of occasional ethnic strife and even vicious persecution: in Singapore under Japanese occupation in the second world war, in Indonesia and Malaysia in the mid-1960s, and in Vietnam after reunification. Mr Seagrave praises Mr Lee for having built a racially harmonious Singapore. About that, he seems more confident than the Singaporean government, which remains highly sensitive to anything capable of inflaming ethnic tension. And he admires the Singaporeans' "shrewd and eloquent" authoritarian philosophy. Fashionably, Mr Seagrave takes the view that democracy and Asia are incompatible, and that "few Asians who have given the matter any serious thought" mind about this.</p><p>	Not true. Or at least, like many of Mr Seagrave's assertions, overstated. But, as an impressionistic picture of the history, wealth, power and, in some cases, skulduggery of the overseas Chinese, he has produced a gripping read. About some things he and Lee Kuan Yew are dead right, including Mr Lee's encomium on the virtues of guanxi, which is Chinese for "connections". "The Anglo-Saxons do it, the Jews do it, so do the Hindus and the Muslims." But for the Chinese more than anybody, as Mr Lee has suggested, "Networking is the natural thing to do."</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
