<html><head><title>Books in brief: Contemporary History</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>

<p><b>Books in brief</b></p>

<h2>Contemporary history</h2>

<ul>
<li><font size=-1><a href="#1">GOOD-BYE, MACHIAVELLI:</a> GOVERNMENT AND AMERICAN LIFE</font> &nbsp;<br>By Bernard Wishy</li>

<li><font size=-1><a href="#2">THE LOST VICTORY:</a> BRITISH DREAMS, BRITISH REALITIES, 1945-1950</font> &nbsp;<br>By Corelli Barnett</li>

<li><font size=-1><a href="#3">PEACE AND DISCONTENTS, GAZA-JERICHO 1993-1995</a></font> &nbsp; &amp;
<br><font size=-1><a href="#3">THE POLITICS OF DISPOSSESSION:</a> THE STRUGGLE FOR PALESTINIAN SELF-DETERMINATION, 1969-1994</font> &nbsp;<br>By Edward Said</li>

<li><font size=-1><a href="#4">A NEW PHILOSOPHY OF HISTORY</a></font> &nbsp;<br>Edited by Frank Ankersmit and Hans Kellner</li>
</ul>
</td></tr></table>

<a name="1"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>
<p><b>GOOD-BYE, MACHIAVELLI: GOVERNMENT AND AMERICAN LIFE.</b><br>
By Bernard Wishy. <i>Louisiana State University Press; 346 pages; $34.95</i>.</p>

<p>THIS is a history of a 400-year-old  struggle between two competing ideas about government in America: that it should grow and grow or shrink and shrink. Most accounts of the development of government in the United States have focused on the big 20th-century surges in federal power: the New Deal, the two world wars and the Great Society. Historians have tended to write as if America before this century was a place of individual freedom and laisser-faire. Not so, argues Bernard Wishy. From the very beginning, taming the wilderness and settling a continent required public as well as private effort.</p>

<p>	From the first English settlement at Jamestown in 1607 to the 1994 Republican "Contract with America", "Good-bye, Machiavelli" traces the tension between advocates of bigger government and its opponents, who thought it inimical to economic growth and to individual liberty. But the state, the author counters, was indispensable both to economic growth and to personal freedom: whether in developing the West, ending slavery, industrialising the economy, winning wars against tyrants or securing rights for women and blacks.</p>

<p>	Though cogently argued and entertainingly written, the book relies too heavily on old research and tails off when it comes to the "Reagan Revolution" in the 1980s. Mr Wishy's own proposals for improving American government are less coherent than his account of its undeniable achievements as it grew.</p>
</td></tr></table>

<a name="2"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>
<p><b>THE LOST VICTORY: BRITISH DREAMS, BRITISH REALITIES, 1945-1950.</b><br>
By Corelli Barnett. <i>Macmillan; 528 pages; &#163;20</i>.</p>

<p>	IN HIS "Pride and Fall" series, Corelli  Barnett dwells on the discrepancy this past century between British pretensions and Britain's actual wealth and weight. "The Collapse of British Power" (1972) showed the British Empire to be more a political and military liability than an asset to Britain between the world wars. "The Audit of War" (1986) exposed inefficiencies in state economic controls during wartime. </p>

<p>	"The Lost Victory" argues that the post-war Labour government under Clement Attlee failed to seize the opportunity to forge a national corporate strategy to regenerate British industry. Resources ought to have been channelled into growth areas of the economy through investment in plant and technical training. But, as Britain's former rivals rallied, the chance faded.</p>

<p>	Instead Britain's global overstretch - political, strategic and financial - was eagerly resumed by Attlee and his government colleagues under the illusion that Britain, at the centre of the Commonwealth, would remain the "third world power", thus laying an immense burden on an economy drip-fed by American loans. Post-war spending by "liberal idealists" on the fulfilment of the wartime dream of "New Jerusalem", full employment and a comprehensive welfare state, is argued to have stifled public and private investment in industry and contributed to economic decline.</p>

<p>	As he traverses Britain's history in the 20th century, Mr Barnett shows admirable consistency in argument. But this does tend to make each new book in his "Decline and Fall" series slightly less exciting and more predictable than the last.</p>
</td></tr></table>

<a name="3"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>
<p><b>PEACE AND DISCONTENTS, GAZA-JERICHO 
1993-1995.</b><br>
<i>Vintage; 197 pages; &#163;6.99; Pantheon; $12</i>.<br></p>

<p>
<b>THE POLITICS OF DISPOSSESSION: THE  STRUGGLE FOR PALESTINIAN SELF-DETERMINATION, 1969-1994.</b><br>
<i>Vintage; 450 pages; &#163;9.99; Pantheon; $15</i>.
<br>By Edward Said.</p>


<p>IN TWO sets of essays Edward Said ar gues that the Palestinian movement of national liberation - a phoenix out of the ashes of pan-Arabism after the 1967 defeat - has become little more than a municipal government engaged in a "Vichy-like collaboration" to provide basic services to just 45% of its people.</p>

<p>	"A Palestinian Versailles" has been forced upon a Palestinian leadership increasingly removed from popular support and internationally isolated after its foolish backing of Saddam Hussein during the Gulf war. Mr Said, a former Palestinian National Council member and a Columbia University professor, has no faith in the showbiz pomp of White House ceremony and questions whether "Final Status" talks will ever begin. He decries Yasser Arafat's "almost magical sense that American would take care of our problems", despite a consistent history of great-power neglect and American hostility to the very idea of Palestinian self-determination.</p>

<p>	Several targets are familiar from Mr Said's 1980 book "A Question of Palestine": Israeli duplicity (the "doveish" Peace Now movement of the intellectual left is particularly harshly treated); the lack of a Palestinian voice in the western media; and the fickleness of Arab "allies". But they are sharply spiced in these essays by unrelenting criticism of the PLO and its leader. According to Mr Said, Mr Arafat negotiated the agreement struck in Madrid in September 1993 without legal advice and, more culpably still, caved in before the Palestinians could reap the full benefit of the change made by the intifada - the Palestinian uprising - on western perceptions of the Palestinian cause.</p>
</td></tr></table>

<a name="4"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>
<p><b>A NEW PHILOSOPHY OF HISTORY.</b><br>
Edited by Frank Ankersmit and Hans Kellner. <i>Reaktion Books; 289 pages; &#163;12.95</i></p>

<p>WRITTEN for the thoughtful reader  who stares in a looking glass and sees a mirror, the 12 essays in this volume dwell on the vexed question of objectivity in historical writing. If all history is "discourse" of some sort - a fashionable way of saying that how we see the past depends on where we are looking from and what our motives are - is there a pin-pointable difference any more between solid research and just making it up?  </p>

<p> We live, the authors argue, in a "post-historical world". They do not mean, as Francis Fukuyama argued, that liberal democracy was now everywhere the goal and that "history" - the long clash of ideologies - was at an end. Rather do they mean that historical "facts" should be treated as artefacts and the writing of history as a sub-division of "fiction".</p>

<p>	This sort of thing is infuriating to practising historians who can tell fact from factoid, without, in a deep way, being able to explain why. But until they or their philosophical representatives can say why convincingly, this fashionable irrationalism is likely to spread.  </p>

<p> One of the more sober essays, by Nancy Partner, reminds us that the world of near-news, factoids and docudramas is not new. Greek, Roman and medieval history-writing, she shows, was full of "incorporated fictions" that have close similarities to "post-modern" ways of writing history. The common view among historians - that they obediently follow the dictum of Ranke, a noted German forebear, to record only "what really happened" - may be wrong, she suggests: as historians we are in the end more Greek than German. That sounds catchy. But is it true? If fiction can be incorporated into history, it can also be excised. Factoids cannot be older than the facts. And ancient lineage does not, in any event, make factoids more believable. </p>

<br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a>

</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
