<html><head><title>Travel guides</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Travel guides</b></p><h2>Long distance writers</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex13-1.htm"><font size=-1>LEADING THE BLIND: A CENTURY OF GUIDE BOOK TRAVEL, 1815-1914</font></a> &nbsp; By Alan Sillitoe</li></ul><p>TRAVEL books are not what they were.  Not only are they filled with garish and redundant pictures, showing you the monument you are looking at in unnecessary size; they are soft, anodyne and, except for their ruthless but largely invisible selectiveness, without judgments or opinions. A British writer, Alan Sillitoe, who is best known for "The Loneliness of the Long-Distance Runner" and "Saturday Night and Sunday Morning", has made a hobby of collecting guide books from the past century, when ladies and gentlemen of discernment (and means) travelled with their own teapots, soap and india-rubber inflatable baths; when two pistols in the belt were recommended for those taking "the road to the east"; and when Baedeker and Murray were not shy of heaping insults on foreign parts and on their inhabitants, particularly their cooks and hoteliers.  </p><p> French restaurants, for instance, provided pitiful amounts of solid food, and the hotel floors were "black with the accumulated filth of years". In Germany, hotel proprietors rudely and obtrusively insisted on joining guests at table. Travellers in Italy were enjoined always to sleep on the second floor, where they would not smell the drains, and to choose iron bedsteads, "which are less likely to harbour the enemies of repose"; in Naples, they were told to avoid "that horrible condiment called pizza". Greece had savage dogs, Russia appalling trains, while the Hungarians "almost surpass the Americans in the filthy habit of spitting." To judge from these guides, the English traveller abroad was excessively obsessed with cleanliness, and took a morbid interest in charnel houses, cemeteries, mass graves and drains.</p><p>	By the mid-19th century tourism had taken on most of its modern colour, with predatory customs officers, over-crowded carriages, day-trippers, and small boys somersaulting before ancient monuments in the hope of a handful of change (when this happened in front of the Pyramids, travellers were advised, "application should be made to the sheikh"). Nor was England itself immune, despite the insufferable superiority of its representatives abroad.</p><p>	In the closing chapter of this delightful compendium, a few sharp points are made about visits to the home country. London in 1850 was reported to have 15,000 pickpockets, and the smoke of the metropolis "is often traced as far as Reading". Further afield, the town of Matlock in Derbyshire was already besieged by gimmicks and gift shops - a nice point which reminds us that many supposedly "modern" cultural developments are often much older than we like to imagine, particularly developments we - or some of us - turn our noses up at. Guide books nowadays might enthusiastically describe the arrival of the tourist store as another chance to shop till you drop. But Mr Sillitoe seems to agree that the ancients got it right: once day-trippers are let loose on a place, "the descent to Avernus becomes a veritable glissade".</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
