<html><head><title>Anti-Enlightenment visionary</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr2.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Anti-Enlightenment visionary</b></p><!-- heading - may be h2 (eg picking lives apart review) --><h2>In paradise</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex2-1.htm"><font size=-1>BLAKE</font></a> &nbsp; By Peter Ackroyd</li></ul><p>THE life of William Blake is a thankless  one for a biographer. From his birth as the son of a hosier in 1757, to his death as a humble engraver in 1827, he never left London: except once, when he got as far as the Sussex coast. He married the first woman who ever appealed to him, a dark-eyed servant girl called Catherine, and never looked for, or seemed to need, other companionship. This now-revered artist and poet spent his days in obscurity, bending over copper plates, mixing colours and scribbling verse; occasionally he visited friends or went to the theatre. And that was that.</p><p>	But Blake was also living in another world, equally perilous for the biographer: a realm of extreme spiritual sensibility, extraordinary visions, ghosts, giants and angels. The material world (''the vegetative universe'', in his scornful term) was nothing but the dark underside of a dazzling spiritual landscape. When Blake wandered through London, in all the mud and stink and commercialism of the age, he saw ''Spires and Domes of ivory and gold''; inside the dark workshops he glimpsed ''the golden looms, which weave all created things''. Cosmic struggles between Good and Evil took place on the corner of Broad Street; through Islington ran a river in which polluted souls were purified. For Blake, this world was both truer and more real than the one his contemporaries could see. It was, to him, not a question of artistic imagination but of sensing the hidden divinity in human life.</p><p> Most of his contemporaries thought him mad, and it is not hard to see why. Blake did not merely incorporate his visions into startling engravings and dense epic poems; he also talked about them, in a normal and natural way, in pubs and at dinner parties. At Lady Caroline Lamb's one night, he remarked to a perfect stranger: ''I have conversed with the Spiritual Sun; I saw him on Primrose Hill.'' He told friends how, as a child, he had seen a tree full of angels in Peckham Rye; how the Angel Gabriel had tapped him on the shoulder in a tavern; how the Ancient of Days (Blake's prototype creator-figure, bending from heaven to measure out the world with dividers) had appeared to him at the top of the stairs. ''I have very little of Mr Blake's company,'' his wife once confided to a friend, ''He is always in paradise.''</p><p>	His enterprises never made money. Despite the help of loyal and self-sacrificing friends, who bought his work and even invented commissions for him, he never found a lasting audience. Blake was a supreme colourist and master of line, but his subjects - muscle-bound humanoids, lamenting patriarchs, net-like rocks and ruins - are often baffling and unattractive. His verse could be downright bad. The author of the incandescent ''Tyger, Tyger'' and the wonderful ''World in a Grain of Sand'' often got bogged down in sagas of intolerable obscurity.</p><p>	Blake could find few people willing to publish him. In the world's eyes therefore he remained nothing more than a labourer, too poor either to hire an apprentice or to join his guild. Samuel Palmer, one of a group of starry-eyed young artists who came  to worship Blake in the  1820s, just before his death,  remarked that ''his clothes  were threadbare, and his  grey trousers had worn  black and shiny in front,  like a mechanic's.''</p><p>	Blake was not always  self-effacing. He could be  fierce, didactic and rude;  for, after all, he believed  that he was a seer in the  world of the blind. But in  Peter Ackroyd he has found  the gentlest of biographers.  Mr Ackroyd does Blake the considerable service of taking his visions as seriously and soberly as he did. He treats them as authentic, which is as they should be, and not simply as some fantastical reaction to the industrialism and commercialism of the age. He sympathises deeply with Blake's struggles to pin down the indescribable on paper or on the engraver's plate.</p><p>	There is also no better man than Mr Ackroyd, Dickens's biographer too, to follow Blake through London. He knows what buildings Blake would have passed, where the farmyards were, which trees grew in which gardens, at which corner he would have smelt oysters or coffee; he is familiar with the songs, the slang, the advertisements and even the graffiti. Above all, he is expert at tying the transcendent to the particular. Those ''dark Satanic mills'', far from being in the industrial north (which Blake never knew), were the Albion flour mill on Blackfriars Road; Jerusalem, close by, was in Lambeth Vale, where the present black ghetto was a place of fields and vineyards.  </p><p> But Mr Ackroyd loads the reader with pages of literary criticism, catalogue-trawling and dry lists of commissions. His editor to whom this text was sent evidently bowed the knee before such displays of erudition. A wiser one would have put the red pencil to work. Blake is also badly served by the book's designer. The illustrations, rightly, are plentiful and apposite, but most are so muddily reproduced on poor paper that there is no pleasure in looking at them. Now that Blake has his audience at last, he deserves a better memorial.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
