<html><head><title>Microsoft</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr4.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Microsoft</b></p><!-- heading - may be h2 (eg picking lives apart review) --><h2>Gates of Wrath</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex4-1.htm"><font size=-1>I SING THE BODY ELECTRONIC</font></a> &nbsp; By Fred Moody</li><li><a href="1ex4-2.htm"><font size=-1>MICROSOFT SECRETS</font></a> &nbsp; By Michael Cusumano and Richard Selby</li></ul><p>IF YOU know even the most elementary  facts about Microsoft, you know that it is an extraordinary company, and that Bill Gates, the man who co-founded and still runs it, is an extraordinary man. Twenty years ago the firm did not exist. Today Wall Street values it more highly than any other company, at $59 billion. This price reflects not only the company's present huge sales and profits, but its remarkable dominance of one of the fastest-growing industries in the world. How did Microsoft do it?</p><p>	Both these books tell you a lot about Mr Gates and his company. As you read them, far from feeling that you understand how Microsoft did what it did, you marvel ever more at its achievement. At the outset Fred Moody confesses that he too is bemused. Michael Cusumano and Richard Selby pretend that they have unravelled the mystery - none too convincingly. In the end it seems that Mr Gates and his creation are not merely extraordinary but miraculous.</p><p>	''I Sing the Body Electronic'' is an account of the year Mr Moody spent as an honorary member of one of Microsoft's product teams. His group was at work on ''Explorapedia'' - a CD-ROM encyclopedia for children, intended to be a junior version of Microsoft's ''Encarta''. The tale is one of appalling pressures, missed deadlines, breakdowns in communications, clashes of personality, needless frustrations and unforced errors; also, in the end, of a product that set new standards and seems destined to make Microsoft pots of money. Disarmingly, Mr Moody observes: ''I still cannot tell whether [these pages] contain a story of success, of failure, of success disguised as failure, or of failure disguised as success.'' What they do contain is a fascinating story, very well told.</p><p>	''Microsoft Secrets'' stands in contrast to Mr Moody's revealing journal. It is a book by, and too much for, students of management. You know this because of the leaden language and the relentlessly purposeful structure: chapters have subtitles such as ''Pioneer and Orchestrate Evolving Mass Markets''. The book is less dire than that implies - it is full of information and the signal-to-waffle ratio, for this sort of book, is high - but whereas you glide pleasantly through Mr Moody's account, the journey through ''Microsoft Secrets'' is a trudge.</p><p>	Together the books do yield what Messrs Cusumano and Selby might call synergising feedback loops. Mr Moody's view of Microsoft is from the ground up. The picture he paints is one of chaos on the cusp of failure. ''Microsoft Secrets'' is how things look to the generals on the hill: the detail is blurry, but larger forces can be discerned; the anarchy has a direction after all.</p><p>	But Bill Gates, on both accounts, is the hub. He knows everything, especially the things his teams wished he didn't know. He asks the hard questions, and if he doesn't get the right answers he bangs his head on the table. Arguably, no lesser force of intellect and personality could harness Microsoft's assembled brainpower to commercial purpose, especially when you consider the form in which the brainpower arrives. As Mr Moody tells it, Microsoft's software engineers conform to stereotype: one-track personalities, actual or retarded adolescents, pulling all-nighters, writing code with Alice in Chains at top volume. These social misfits have to work not only with each other but also with the product designers who tell them what the programs are to do. As one senior manager quoted by Mr Moody says:</p><ul><p>	Designers are invariably female, are talkative,  live in lofts, have vegetarian diets, and wear  round objects in their ears. Developers [programmers] are invariably male, eat fast food,  and don't talk except to say 'Not true'.</p></ul><p>	Communication between two such groups would be strained even if the task at hand were easy. It isn't. Yet the company works, and how. The imperative of impressing Bill - or, more often, of disappointing him less than last time - helps. The way Microsoft organises itself serves the same  purpose. Small teams of de signers and developers work  together. When people suc ceed, they get more resources  of every kind. If they fail, they  are starved (not literally, you  understand), or closed down.  It is a kind of internal market,  with Mr Gates as the visible  hand.</p><p>	In due course, the industry  must experience another tec tonicshift - as big as the decline of the mainframe and the rise of the PC. For now, two forces are pulling in different directions. In Microsoft's favour is that it has discovered economies of scale and scope where there were thought to be few. This is true not just in marketing and distribution but also, nerds in garages notwithstanding, in developing programs. Software ''engines"  (chunks of programming) that do text-processing, or user-interfacing, or whatever, can be developed once, and then used in different products. Ability to exploit such economies gives Microsoft a big advantage over would-be competitors.</p><p>	Pulling the other way is the company's success. To help attract and motivate its workers, Microsoft has given generously of itself in stock options. Its best people are rich enough to retire - and young enough to use their wealth to start new companies. At first Microsoft worked for IBM. If Microsoft should suffer Big Blue's fate, the giant may once again be slain by one of its own.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
