<html><head><title>New German novels</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr6.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>New German novels</b></p><h2>A wide open field</h2><ul><li>STILLEBEN MIT WILDEM TIER<br>By Martin Mosebach. <i>Berlin Verlag; 175 pages; DM34</i></li><li>FASERLAND<br>By Christian Kracht. <i>Kiepenheuer und Witsch; 166 pages; DM29.80</i></li><li>DER CAMPUS<br>By Dietrich Schwanitz. <i>Eichborn; 382 pages; DM38</i></li><li>33 AUGENBLICKE DES GL&Uuml;CKS<br>By Ingo Schulze. <i>Berlin Verlag; 270 pages; DM36</i></li><li>HELDEN WIE WIR<br>By Thomas Brussig. <i>Verlag Volk und Welt; 323 pages; DM36</i></li><li>EIN WEITES FELD<br>By G&uuml;nter Grass. <i>Steidl Verlag; 784 pages; DM49.80</i></li></ul><p>BIG events can be a curse for  novelists, swamping their fiction or reducing it to reportage. But die Wende - the "turn" five years ago when the two Germanies united - seemed to be just the thing to help German novelists over the national writer's block so many of them were noisily suffering from. Unification thrust two estranged societies together. Lives got remade or broken. Old masks came off, new ones were put on. An over-lit, well-trodden landscape became again an unmapped zone of snakes and ladders. It was, or seemed, the stuff of fiction. </p> <p> Although Germans devour literary novels, non-German novelists in translation are their favourites, to judge from best-seller lists. This trend, far from new, was identified and lamented in the 1980s: the lions of post-war German fiction - Heinrich B&#246;ll, G&#252;nter Grass - were dead or past it; younger writers were too cramped by these giants or wrapped up in themselves to tell good stories. So it was said. The complaints were taken up, amplified and  made a career of by Germany's  best-known critic, Marcel Reich- Ranicki, who has a TV book show  and who has made the cover of Der Spiegel magazine twice, which may be a record for a literary watchdog in Germany, and perhaps anywhere.<p></p>	Tinged as they were by exaggeration and chauvinism - novel-writing is not an Olympic sport - there was truth in the complaints. Not that Germany lacked accomplished writers. Patrick S&#252;skind, for example, dazzled readers in 1985 with "Das Parfum", a clever tale set in 18th-century Paris about an amoral, murderous orphan with a preternatural sense of smell.  But that book stood out against a parched background. Too much west German fiction was - and is - marred by over-introspection or pedantry. Hanns-Josef Ortheil and Peter Kurzeck, to take two well-regarded writers, have a tendency to offer shapeless musings on their moods, their breakfast choices and their other daily habits. An up-and-coming Frankfurt writer, Martin Mosebach, undermines his well-executed, amusing stories - "Stilleben mit wildem Tier" (Still life with wild animal) is his latest book - by letting his hand slip with descriptive detail.<p></p>	Whatever else unification did for German letters, it broke the stale pattern of literary debate, which pitted western dilettantes against eastern dissidents, refinement against commitment, right-wing young fogeys against left-wing '68ers. The upshot, to everyone's relief, is more of a free-for-all. "Germany" still engrosses some writers, including G&#252;nter Grass, the country's best- known living writer. But others are at ease with less daunting themes.<p></p>	In "Faserland", for example, Christian Kracht satirises the pampered heirs of Germany's Wirtschaftswunder as he follows them from the fashionable North Sea island of Sylt to villas on Lake Constance. He knows whereof he writes. His father was a right-hand man to Axel Springer, a post-war conservative press baron, and his novel's rich, bored and nameless narrator went, as he did, to Salem, a high-toned Swabian boarding school. Mr Kracht nicely catches the bewildered cynicism of those who have been raised to think they are special but suspect they are not, save for having pots of money. "Faserland" (frayed land), a pun on "fatherland", is a belated and deliberate German answer to the American "brat-pack" novelists such as Bret Easton Ellis. </p><p> Foreign influences are clear, too, in Dietrich Schwanitz's satire, "Der Campus", which records the half-comic fall of a Hamburg literature professor, Hanno Hackmann. The snobbish allure of his wife, Gabrielle, an impoverished aristocrat from the East, has worn off and Hackmann takes up with the fetching but neurotic Babsi, a student. Accused of rape, Hackmann is brought down by a cabal of self-seeking, leftish colleagues.<p></p>	"Der Campus" owes an obvious debt to the Anglo-American university novel and to David Mamet's play, 'Oleanna". But it is telling, also, in German terms. Such a book 25 years ago would have satirised those "immovable pyramids", the reactionary professors then athwart German academic life. Mr Schwanitz's target, rather, is political correctness.  Until unification, a doubt hung over many East German novelists, unfair as it was: were they not better martyrs than writers? Since then some of them, most obviously Christa Wolf, have been harried by the charge they were not martyrs enough. But several younger eastern writers are coming up who seem free of those old toils.  In "33 Augenblicke des Gl&#252;cks" (33 moments of happiness), a Dresden-born  writer, Ingo Schulze, gives what he calls "an outsider's view of present-day St Petersburg", which makes it sound as dull as travelogue. But Mr Schulze spent a year there running an advertising free-sheet and, it seems, reading all the Russian classics he could. An admirer also of Raymond Carver, he has pulled together 30 or so loose-knit low-life scenes from the Russian-German cultural mishmash that has fermented in Pushkin's city over the past half decade. Both vivid and cliched, it reads like an account of a long ride across St Petersburg in a collective taxi where you find yourself, by turns, next to whores, religious lunatics, old communist crocodiles, Gogol, Chekhov and Nabakov.<p></p>	A more focused work is Thomas Brussig's "Helden wie wir" (Heroes like us) which tells of disaffected youth in the last days of East Germany through the eyes of Karl Uhltzschts, a secret policeman's son. In part, this is a long plaint for East Germany's "lost generation" which grew up with neither faith nor prospects after the failed Prague Spring of 1968. So far, so familiar. But Mr Brussig has laced his book with extravagant sexual escapades, which have shocked people who half-thought that behind the drab curtains on those grim eastern streets dissidents were all reading Solzhenitsyn and Milton Friedman.  </p><p> As for Mr Grass, his two previous books were flops. And he has had almost nothing but derision from critics for his "unification" novel, "Ein weites Feld" (A wide field). But as Mr Grass with sly pride told this reviewer: "For once the readers may have trumped the intellectuals." His new book has sat high on or atop the best-seller list since publication last August.  Set in Berlin in 1990, "Ein weites Feld" has as its premise Mr Grass's well-known hostility to German unification. But it is a novel, not a tract. Fonty, its main character, is an old man nicknamed for a late-19th-century writer whom he - like Mr Grass - admires, Theodore Fontane, a novelist and sceptical chronicler of Germany's earlier unification. Fonty, who has been Wehrmacht soldier and East German cultural official, works menially in the Treuhand, the trust agency selling off East German state assets. He is watched by Hoftaller, a police spy. In the course of the novel, an illegitimate daughter reappears.<p></p>	So devised, Mr Grass's novel is a perfect instrument for tracing echoes and parallels across German writing and history. Not everyone will accept Mr Grass's dim verdict on his country nor want to read about "Germany" in a novel, especially one so thick. But no other living German novelist could have pulled off such a feat. For all its faults, this is the work of a grand old man: rich in ear, wide in view and sure enough of his own powers to pay easy homage to an earlier German master. </p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
