<html><head><title>United Nations</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr8.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>United Nations</b></p><!-- heading - may be h2 (eg picking lives apart review) --><h2>America's idea</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex8-1.htm"><font size=-1>A GLOBAL AFFAIR</font></a> &nbsp; Edited by Amy Janello and Brennon Jones</li><li><a href="1ex8-2.htm"><font size=-1>UNITED NATIONS</font></a> &nbsp; By Stanley Meisler</li><li><a href="1ex8-3.htm"><font size=-1>THE RWANDA CRISIS: HISTORY OF A GENOCIDE</font></a> &nbsp; By G&eacute;rard Prunier</li></ul><p>WHEN he was told, in 1960, to whisk a  UN force to the Congo, Brian Urquhart, top peacekeeper at the time, was under the impression that Leopoldville (now Kinshasa) was on the Indian Ocean, not the Atlantic, side of Africa. Nevertheless, he got 3,000 men to the right place in three days. Nowadays it would take three months and more - and the untrained soldiers would turn up with no more than the stuff they stood up in. The UN, it does not need the old-timers to grumble, is not what it was.  </p><p> No doubt, times past are better to read about than they were to live through. ''A Global Affair'', a coffee-table-size collection of memories and essays, with an introduction by Sir Brian, now a sage at the Ford Foundation, has a collection of stunning photographs, all interesting and some of the old ones very funny: a soldier in Egypt ushering a camel from a railway line; UN outings to the beach; conspiracy-plotting faces at the Security Council; nice American ladies stitching a UN flag. The newer ones are sadder, showing famine and grief. Has the spirit gone out of the UN, its peacekeeping activities in retreat, thought wrong by many? If so whose fault is it?</p><p>	Blame can be generously scattered. The UN's procedures are tired, archaic and cumbersome, its members tend to expect miracles without pain to themselves - a no-risk, no-cost war. Political scientists chatter of globalisation, ignoring the depth of the north-south divide and the fragmentation of ethnic conflict.</p><p>	The UN's learning experience as it picks up the debris left by civil wars has been widely picked over by commentators, sympathetic or hostile and with varying success, in order to distinguish what seems to work from what does not. Naturally, it is the failures that are remembered - particularly in America, now going through one of its anti-UN fits.  </p><p> Yet, as Stanley Meisler's excellent political history of the UN underlines, America was largely responsible for the UN's birth and, as the leading power in the Security Council, is now partly responsible for its decline - and not just because it does not pay its bills. ''The United Nations was mainly an America idea'', writes Mr Meisler, a reporter for the Los Angeles Times, and its structure, he points out, closely follows plans prepared by American diplomats during the second world war.Roosevelt spoke of the need for four policemen - America, Britain, the Soviet Union and (pre-communist) China - to keep order in the post-war world: if some aggressor ran amok, he said, the policemen operating within the new organisation would stop him before he got started.</p><p>	Then as now, America judged the UN in terms of its own agenda: the world body, it thinks, works well when it does what America wants, or provides a cover for America to do what it believes to be right.The first big test of this was the Korean war, a UN operation because the Soviet Union, which would have vetoed it, was boycotting Security Council sessions in 1950. America fought the war under a UN umbrella; it invoked the UN on every step it took, even when that step shunted the UN aside.</p><p>	Remembering this, writes Mr Meisler, Javier Perez de Cuellar, the UN's secretary-general in the early 1990s, refused America's request that the anti-Iraq coalition should fly the UN flag. The Gulf war was authorised by the UN, but the secretary-general did not  want a repeat of the Korean  war model when America  used the UN's name at every  turn but tolerated no  interference.</p><p>	The dispute continues, at  the heart of those peace-en forcement operations in which  the big powers, the NATO gi ants, believe that the UN  should be seen but not heard.useful in its way but not to be allowed to confuse things with a show of independence.  Traditional peacekeepers on traditional UN missions took their UN orders quietly. Not so the big powers on less traditional missions: some look over their shoulders to their national governments, chafing at UN restraints;the Americans in Somalia bypassed the UN, though they blamed it when things went wrong.</p><p>	True, the UN embarks on peacekeeping only at the Security Council's behest; true, too, that there have been absurd moments as the UN secretariat played at soldiers. The question is whether it is healthy for a club of 185 sovereign nations to be seen, in its most public role, as the instrument of the five permanent members of the Security Council, above all the United States. Plainly not. But, writes Mr Meisler, when Americans realise that the UN is not theirs alone, they tend to turn their backs on it.</p><p>	Such a time is now, with a Republican Congress using its expressed disgust at an unreformed UN as an excuse not to pay its dues. But matters were even worse 15 years ago. The Security Council was paralysed by the cold war and the General Assembly was a seething cauldron of anti-Americanism and anti-Zionism: Americans at that time, says Mr Meisler, saw the UN as blathering, incompetent and corrupt (and, to a point, still do); they wondered whether it had any right to exist at all. </p><p> He recollects Charles Lichtensteinsplng?, President Reagan's deputy ambassador at the UN in 1983, urging the whole caboodle to sail off from New York ''into the sunset'': geographically inexact but leaving ''no confusion about his distaste''.</p><p>	American ambassadors are key figures in the UN's history: Daniel Patrick Moynihan blistering the assembly for its anti-Zionism; Thomas Pickering winning his way without ever having to ram a resolution down the council's throat. Mr Meisler writes perceptively of them, and also of the secretary-generals, those curious centre-stage figureswho are not just unelected but randomly picked. How else could the UN have been landed with its first secretary-general, Trygve Lie, a clumsy diplomat who helped to get the organisation off to a bad start, let alone Kurt Waldheim, whom Mr Meisler bluntly calls a Nazi and a liar, who came later and stayed longer?</p><p>	Mr Meisler's hero is Dag Hammarskjold, a visionary intellectual who ''seemed to restore the soul that had somehow slipped away in the UN's first few years''. No successor has been able to measure up to Hammarskjold, killed in an air crash in the Congo, but the present incumbent, Boutros Boutros-Ghali, is an intriguing character in his own right. When his name came up in 1991, the Americans were unenthusiastic: they thought him too old and too passive. In fact, he has turned into the most stubbornly independent and activist secretary-general the UN has ever known and the Americans hate him for it.  </p><p> But even the most active and independent secretary-general cannot make Security Council members do what they do not want to do. As the horrors of the Rwanda genocide became known, Mr Boutros-Ghali called on the council for swift action. The council, under America's leadership, procrastinated: in the aftermath of Somalia, Bill Clinton had laid down new peacekeeping conditions and these, the Americans insisted, had to be satisfied.</p><p>	Nobody knows how many lives might have been saved if the UN had responded faster: General Romeo Dallaire, the brave Canadian on the spot, says that, given a few motivated soldiers, he might have fended off many of the massacres. What in fact happened inside Rwanda is told with painful clarity by G&#233;rard Prunier in ''The Rwanda Crisis" . The dreadful tale is the sharpest indictment that can ever be made against the United Nations - and its members.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
