<html><head><title>Northern Ireland</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr10.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Northern Ireland</b></p><h2>Peace or pause?</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex10-1.htm"><font size=-1>BEHIND THE LINES: THE STORY OF THE IRA AND LOYALIST CEASEFIRES</font></a> &nbsp; By Brian Rowan</li><li><a href="1ex10-2.htm"><font size=-1>FIGHTING FOR IRELAND?: THE MILITARY STRATEGY OF THE IRISH REPUBLICAN MOVEMENT</font></a> &nbsp; By M.L.R. Smith</li><li><a href="1ex10-3.htm"><font size=-1>JOHN HUME: PEACEMAKER</font></a> &nbsp; By George Drower</li><li><a href="1ex10-4.htm"><font size=-1>THE TROUBLES: IRELAND'S ORDEAL 1966-1995 AND THE SEARCH FOR PEACE</font></a> &nbsp; By Tim Pat Coogan</li></ul><p>THE onset of the troubles in Northern  Ireland 25 years ago produced a welter of books on the historical and contemporary causes of the crisis. The onset of peace (or at least of the "peace process") has produced the same result. And, just as the hopeful atmosphere of the early 1960s seemed greatly at odds with the outbreak of such serious fighting, so the exceptional violence of the early 1990s seems an unlikely harbinger of the current ceasefires.</p><p>	Brian Rowan's detailed analysis of the coming of the IRA and loyalist ceasefires in the autumn of 1994 makes indispensable reading. He is the BBC's chief security correspondent in Northern Ireland and it is hard to see why anybody would want to do his job. Not even a "day off work" or a family dinner can distract Mr Rowan from his dedication to collecting, and presenting, all the facts, rumours and innuendos that he can from his many contacts in the terrorist world. His diligence has produced an honest, fair-minded and clearly-written book that traces the political background to the silencing of the guns, and the way in which peace finally emerged.</p><p>	Mr Rowan places much emphasis on the discussions between John Hume of the SDLP, leader of the constitutional nationalists, and Gerry Adams of Sinn Fein, leader of the militant nationalists. Sinn Fein was coming to realise that the "ballot box-armalite" strategy was failing. Mr Hume combined his characteristic hard-headedness with a genuine humanitarian desire to end the violence. He pointed out to Mr Adams the political advantages of a pan-nationalist front, which might also bring in the Irish government and the American president as persuaders for an overall settlement. In the short term this made matters worse, as loyalists decided that the Hume-Adams tactic could only add strength to their enemies. But this tactic offered a formula that would at least satisfy nationalist aspirations in theory.The book gives appropriate space to the loyalist ceasefire, all too often neglected by commentators. To use one of Mr Adams's favourite cliches, it takes two to tango. </p><p>	M.L.R. Smith lectures at the Royal Naval College in Greenwich, which some might consider an unlikely place of origin for a student of Republican military strategy. But here again the value of honest and critical work is demonstrated. He has read copiously, and with great insight, the publications, statements and speeches of Republicans. He shows that the IRA is not the self-confident, single-minded organisation that it, and its analysts, suppose it to be, but one that is chronically insecure, and wracked by contradictory notions of what it stands for, and of how it means to achieve its ends.  </p><p> He points out that the very acts of warfare that were designed to give Irish Republicanism its edge exposed the movement's contradictions. The unionists were fellow-Irishmen, suffering from a false consciousness; but the war on "British imperialism" provoked loyalist attacks on Roman Catholics, which could be met only by sectarian reprisals in return. How could this be squared with the ideals of Wolfe Tone, the nationalists' 18th-century Protestant martyr, and the secular republican tradition?</p><p>	John Hume, perhaps the most significant figure in modern Irish nationalism since Eamon de Valera, is adept at wrong-footing the unionists so that they appear to be at fault. And there is consequently a risk that his key role in bringing about peace will result in a suspension of critical judgment of his character and behaviour.  </p> <p> In George Drower's hands, Mr Hume has certainly escaped what would be his finest tribute - a genuinely incisive biographical study. But Mr Drower at least queries some aspects of his subject's behaviour. He recalls, for example, Mr Hume saying that unionists' protests against the Anglo-Irish Agreement of 1985 showed their contempt for law and order - a rich remark coming from a man who had consistently avoided any declaration of support for the Royal Ulster Constabulary when it was engaged in combating nationalist violence. But Mr Drower might have taken further the sharp criticism made of Mr Hume by Eamon McCann, a fellow civil-rights activist of the 1960s. He notes but does not dwell on Mr McCann's characterisation of Mr Hume as a "one-issue politician sailing through history in a sealed capsule."</p><p>	There is a dedicated provincialism, even parochialism, about Mr Hume, which stands oddly alongside his international reputation as a peacemaker. But then Northern Irish politics are dedicatedly provincial and parochial, and this apparent defect gives Mr Hume his strengths. He knows his own people well, and he knows unionists well enough to outsmart them again and again. The statesmanship with which he is credited has yet to be fully realised.</p><p>	For the peace effort to succeed, Irish nationalists as well as Ulster unionists must rethink their ideas and tactics. In doing this they will not be helped by Tim Pat Coogan's study of the troubles, which are described in the title of his book as "Ireland's ordeal"; Northerners of all persuasions will smile wryly at the idea that the south of Ireland - which thankfully, if not altogether honourably, has escaped the relentless horrors inflicted on the north - has been in some way an equal partner in the ordeal.  </p><p> Mr Coogan writes with characteristic flow and emotion, and shows his distaste for all political violence. But he has a simple answer to a complex question. His view of Ireland and Irish history is coloured by his belief that nationalism is in the right - albeit nationalism shorn of its sectarian overlay - and that unionism is an illusion sustained by the past and present exigencies of Britain's Tory party. If only it were so simple. </p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
