<html><head><title>History of the theatre</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="1gr12.gif" alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>History of the theatre</b></p><h2>The play's the thing...</h2><ul><li><a href="1ex12-1.htm"><font size=-1>THE OXFORD ILLUSTRATED HISTORY OF THEATRE</font></a> &nbsp; Edited by John Russell Brown</li><li><a href="1ex12-2.htm"><font size=-1>THE CAMBRIDGE GUIDE TO THEATRE</font></a> &nbsp; Edited by Martin Banham</li></ul><p>THEATRE has always provoked uncon trollable passions. The first fatal performance recorded in the "Oxford Illustrated History" dates from the Roman Empire: when an actor in a client province expressed anti-Roman feelings, loyalists in the audience stormed the stage and killed him.</p><p>	Medieval theatre, like medieval art, concentrated on religious themes, which had an equal power to arouse. In 1454 a fanatic in Florence, detecting blasphemy, climbed on to a mobile stage during a pageant and hurled one of the actors to the ground. By 1561 theatre was being used to express social discontent and a part-time actor was sentenced to death in Edinburgh for being involved in a banned production of the dangerously socialist tale of Robin Hood. In the ensuing riot, city officials were forced to lock themselves in prison.</p><p>	Nationalist sentiments came to the fore in the mid-18th century, when a visit to London by French dancers provoked six days of anti-French demonstrations. In the infamous Astor Place riot in New York in 1849, 31 people were killed as a mob protested against the appearance of an English actor, William Macready, a bitter foe of America's Edwin Forrest.</p><p>	By then the theatre had grown into a powerful enough force for riots to be sparked by artistic considerations. In 1830 conservative Parisians were incensed by Victor Hugo's wilful breach of the formal rules of classical drama in "Hernani". In St Petersburg six years later, the furore over "The Government Inspector" was provoked partly by Gogol's unfamiliar naturalism. Yet as Peter Thomson, a contributor to "The Oxford Illustrated History", notes: "Very rarely in theatre history has controversy damaged the box office."</p><p>	In the 20th century, the stage became openly political. This was despite widespread censorship, which persisted in Eastern Europe until the collapse of communism, in Britain until 1968 and even, de facto, in America, where McCarthy-era witch-hunting discouraged the production of plays with a socialist message. In the 1920s Germany spawned left-wing dramatists such as Bertolt Brecht and Ernst Toller, who in 1919 was chosen president of the short-lived Bavarian Soviet Republic - a precedent for Vaclav Havel, who similarly swapped fantasy for reality when he became president of Czechoslovakia in 1990.</p><p>	"The Oxford Illustrated History", composed of 13 separate essays by 16 authors, traces the development of the theatre chronologically and coherently. "The Cambridge Guide", expanded and revised since it was first published in 1988, ranges wider. Encyclopedic in format, it is both a serious reference book and a source of delight and surprise for the casual browser, reflecting the richness of theatre itself.</p><p>	The Cambridge guide contains profiles of hundreds of playwrights and actors as well as thorough histories of theatre in different countries. More than 100 topic-based headings deal with such varied phenomena as burlesque, castrati, critics, female impersonators, nudity and the well-made play ("thrives on fortuitous entrances and exits, mistaken identity and quid pro quo").</p><p>	The engrossing essay on stage food reveals that it was the tradition for Audrey in "As You Like It" to munch a raw turnip, and that in the cause of realism Rosetta Le Noire put on 23lb in 1944 from wolfing chocolate mints in "Anna Lucasta"philip yordan. Highlights of "animals as performers" include alligator wrestling, rats dancing the saraband, trained bees, mathematical pigs, sea lions cavorting with chorus girls and cats singing "O Tannenbaum". In an encyclopedia of this range there are invariably judgments that can be challenged. Overall, though, this admirably accessible work of scholarship seems settled in for a long run.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
