<html><head><title>Multimedia feature: interactive fiction</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><P><!--<TABLE width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD valign=top align=left>--><IMG src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></TD><TD align=right valign=top><!--<IMG src="1gr14.gif" alt="review graphic"> </TD></TR></TABLE>--><TABLE cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><TR><TD valign=bottom align=left><IMG src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></TD><TD> 
<P>
<B>Multimedia feature: interactive fiction</B>
<H2>But is it story-telling?</H2>

<P>
YOU are lost. To your left lies an unmarked path; to your right
another one just like it (or not?). Behind you is the prospect
of a long, boring trudge back the way you came. Somewhere ahead
is the vague promise of an interesting ending, but for all you
know you forfeited that with a wrong turn three hours ago. Sigh.
Another day at the frontiers of <A href="http://is.rice.edu/~riddle/hyperfiction.html">interactive fiction</A>
and it has gone predictably, prosaically wrong.
<P>
To see the shelves of computer software shops, you would hardly
think this reaction a frequent one. The multimedia industry is
awash with attempts to reinvent story-telling with computers:
dozens of &quot;interactive films&quot; on CD-ROM, such as &quot;Phantasmagoria&quot;
(Sierra Online) or &quot;Under a Killing Moon&quot; (Access Software)
; fictional worlds to explore like &quot;Myst&quot; (Broderbund);
even works of &quot;hyperfiction&quot; on the Internet. </p><p>But the
enthusiasm of the industry - and the curiosity-driven purchases
of new multimedia consumers - should not obscure the fact that
interactive fiction is all too often a failure, if a story in
any standard sense is expected. Software that tries both to tell
a tale and to interact (to give, that is, the reader-viewer a
chance to make real decisions that will affect the flow of the
story-line) usually leads to the same blighted spot: where all
plot is lost and the only satisfying end is the off-switch. </p><p> Despite
the millions of dollars that software companies and publishers
are throwing at this much-hyped field, interactive fiction is
still a technical novelty, attracting more programmers with literary
ambitions than the reverse. Perhaps one day better writers, directors
and actors will make interactive fiction work. So far the evidence
points to deeper problems. </p><p> Computers were first used for story-telling
in the 1970s. University students wrote &quot;Adventure&quot;,
a mainframe computer program that let users explore an imaginary
world (described in text on a screen), looking for clues to the
game's secrets. The first such efforts were just treasure hunts.
But as the Dungeons-and-Dragons fad spread, computer tales took
on the flavour of a Tolkien-like novel, with characters, dialogue,
scene-setting and rudimentary plot.</p>
<P>
In such story-games, the reader-player plays a character, telling
him (usually) what to do from a limited vocabulary of pidgin commands
(&quot;Go South&quot;; &quot;Hit dragon with sword&quot;; &quot;Speak
to wizard&quot;). Stay alive, collect the right stuff and an elementary
story emerges. Interactive films have become visually a bit more
advanced: filmed actors move through 3-D computer-rendered scenes.
But they use the same story- game model. Do everything right,
and you reach the end; mess up and your character gets stuck or
dies.
<P>
The game creates a world and populates it with characters. You
explore it by directing the central character. When you arrive
at a certain place or meet someone, the game triggers a bit of
pre-scripted dialogue or action, depending on where you have already
been, what you have done, and what things you happen to be carrying
(these stories still depend heavily on searches for keys and the
like). You are given tasks; until you complete them, you cannot
get to the next major part of the story. In this model there is
usually the thread of a single tale, which the player has to discover.
Having done it once, a player could mechanically walk the character
through the storyline again without detour. But that would be
a mistake. What is revealed is generally a cliched plot, badly
acted, with no character development - a sub-made-for-television
dud that mostly involves traveling from one place to another to
pick up arbitrary objects.
<P>
Other models are more successful. Some CD-ROMs offer fictional
worlds to explore. &quot;Myst&quot; is an example. It has only
a hint of a story-line, which the viewer may never fully unveil;
instead, when the right doors are opened, these games, like Advent
calendars, reveal little scenes. They have proved popular (&quot;Myst&quot;
has been a CD-ROM bestseller since it was released early last
year), but not for their story-telling. They are, above all, beautiful
puzzles. <p> Still others, such as &quot;Voyeur&quot;, are fleshed-out
stories with different pre-set outcomes, depending on the player's
choices. Taken a bit further, this becomes &quot;tree fiction&quot;,
where at each juncture in the narrative the reader chooses what
will happen next (&quot;If Scrooge is awoken by a rattle of chains,
press 1; if he sleeps all night peacefully, press 2&quot;). Since
tree stories quickly become unmanageable (ten two-choice branches
need more than 1,000 endings; 20, more than 1m) authors who use
trees fall back on artifice: regardless of how you choose, you
get one of, say, four endings.
<P>
One embellishment is &quot;advanced footnoting&quot;. This lets
you &quot;pause&quot; the story and explore a place or character,
without changing the story-line: you can prolong favourite scenes
(another round of croquet with the Red Queen?) or have a session
in the psychiatrist's chair with a troubled hero.
<P>
This last device sounds promising. Knowing a character more can
change your understanding of his later actions. As one critic,
<A href="http://sushi.st.usm.edu:80/~barthelm/06sept/06-jurge.html">Jurgen Fauth</A>,
points out, the &quot;director's cut&quot; of the film &quot;Blade
Runner&quot; includes 30 seconds of additional material that changes
the rest of the movie's meaning completely. But it is hard to
pull this off: fiction involves filters, selection, invention.
Fiction is imagined reality. Show too much, and fiction becomes
prosaic. Funny characters cannot be funny all the time.
<P>
The snag with most electronic stories is that they tamper with
the foundation of narrative: structure. When stories wobble and
change with our whim, they lose their believability, and with
it our willingness to care. Multimedia entertainment works at
the extremes: all-interactivity, minimal plot (&quot;Doom&quot;;
Id Software and other action games) and all-plot, minimal interactivity
(books with hypertext additions, such as the conversion of <A href="http://www.wonderland.org/Works/Lewis-Carroll/alice-in-wonderland/">&quot;Alice in Wonderland&quot;</A>),
but between them is disaster. <P>
In an early interactive fiction piece, &quot;Afternoon: A Story&quot;
(Eastgate), the reader finds the sentence: &quot;I want to say
that I may have seen my son die this morning.&quot; Clicking on
the word &quot;son&quot; takes the reader down one path; clicking
on &quot;die&quot; or &quot;I want&quot; leads to a totally different
narrative. But what the typical reader wants to know is: which
is the right word to click on? Which path generates the closest
thing to a satisfying linear story, the sort that life, experience
and thousands of years of story-telling have taught us to expect?
For every path taken, there is the path not taken. In frustration,
we re-read the story, trying to exhaust all the possibilities
in the search for the satisfying tale that surely must lie somewhere
within. No wonder interactive fiction is such a troubled domain.
That search for the &quot;right path&quot;, after all, is heresy
to the interactive evangelists. There is, to them, no right way
to read an interactive story, just as there is no right way to
explore a new city. Each person, the argument goes, is both reader
and writer, creating by his choices a unique story of his own.
And no version is more right than the next.
<P>
This may be an exciting new game with image and text. But it is
not story-telling as we know it. Take <A HREF="http://www.mcs.net/~jorn/html/spot/kibospot.html">&quot;Christmas 2000: Spot's Third First Christmas&quot;</A>
(actually a playful Internet experiment in tree fiction, but illustrative
nonetheless). At each point in the story, the reader has to choose
what happens next. Has Spot stumbled upon Utopia or just a computer
illusion? You decide. This is amusing for a while, but at the
end, the reader is left asking (or would be, if the story were
engaging in any way) &quot;but what really happened to Spot?&quot;
Read the story once, and Spot dies; read it again, making different
choices, and he doesn't. Which is the &quot;real&quot; - the story-teller's
- outcome?
<P>
Therein lies the real trouble with interactive fiction. It asks us to believe in parallel universes, in each of which different things happen to the same characters. None is more real than any other. And since we, mono-universists that we are,find it impossible to imagine such a thing, the characters lose all their reality. We stop caring about them and their arbitary lives, and the whole consensual illusion of storytelling collapses. There is no Spot. And we could hardly care less.

</P><BR>
<A href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</A>  -
 <A href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</A> </TD></TR></TABLE>
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
