<html><head><title>Multimedia feature: research tools</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><p><b>Multimedia feature: research tools</b></p><h2>Scholar @ work</h2><p>AS the information revolution altered scholars' lives? Predictably from dons, the answer is a grudging "yes" and a wish it were "no". This is the biggest technological change for them since Gutenberg. But they cringe at broad judgments.<p></p>	How much of a revolution depends on the field. Scientists are quickest to see the change, but they have been using computers and the Internet longer than anyone. Specialists in the social sciences and humanities have not made up their minds.  </p><p> The real revolution is for those who deal - in every sense - with current information. When CNN calls you for an interview about a purged Politburo official, a couple of clicks on the computer take you into the Internet in search of the Reuters and even the New China News Agency wire services. You can then nip across to America's National Public Radio or the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation sites on the World Wide Web to listen to their commentaries recorded earlier. Pundit heaven.<p></p>	More extensive on-line research costs  money, but is available. You can  read the full text of back copies of  newspapers and magazines and  even some academic journals.  Your library may have some on CD,  but anything older than the mid- 1980s will probably require you to wander into the library stacks in search of dusty papers. More's the pity. When browsing the electronic library on your computer, there is no need to whisper and your computer can play that favourite Bruce Springsteen CD while you are on-line.<p></p>	The revolution in information management is obvious. There are thousands of books and journals either on-line or on CD. Books that are out of copyright are being added at a rapid rate. Project Gutenberg in the United States aims to have 10,000 books on-line by 2001, just in time for handheld, affordable computers the size of pocket calculators (will they be waterproof enough for the bathroom reader?). Ancient manuscripts or private papers are already being scanned and stored electronically, although little of that material is yet available on-line. Nevertheless, the ability to search all this at laser-speed makes research easier, as well as more efficient and comprehensive.<p></p>	The easy availability of electronic information also has its perils. People who make money from publishing on paper are loth to make it easy for material to be e-mailed for free to thousands of on-line readers. Their printed pages are already susceptible to scanning and subsequent electronic transmission, and the men in suits have yet to perfect ways to restrict and charge for at least some of the information that is now sloshing around for free.<p></p>	There are other worries. As that Reuters story you downloaded last week is gone, how can you check footnotes? For what use are footnotes if not for checking? Daily papers have many editions. Some stories appear in only one. Others change between editions or appear on different pages under new titles. Footnote fetishists are also in trouble when they try to cite information drawn from on-line interviews, or from discussion groups or databases that change every day. Can scholars live with "virtual footnotes"? Then there is that speech you "heard" on RealAudio at the National Press Club in Washington by browsing over to its Web site but which has now disappeared. There is a lot more information, but not all of it hangs around long enough to be traced.<p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
