<html><head><title>Extract</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl3-1.jpg"><img src="1cs3-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>THE LIFE OF ADAM SMITH</h2><p>By Ian Ross. <i>Oxford University Press; 495 pages; &#163;25; $35</i></h2><p><a href="1jb3-1.htm">Jacket copy</a> - <a href="1bt3-1.htm">Biography</a></p><p><b>Extract</b><br><p>A small Town in Scotland the place of my nativity</p><p>The Fife seaport of Kirkcaldy, ten miles across the Firth of Forth from Edinburgh, was the scene of Adam Smith's baptism on 5 June I723. Possibly this was his birth-date, though there is no annotation on the 'Register of Baptisms in the Kirk of Kirkcaldie' (Bonar, 1932: 208), stating 'born this day', as there is in the case of Smith's great friend David Hume (Mossner, I980: 6). It is reported, however, that as an infant Smith was 'infirm and sickly' (Stewart i.2), and understandable anxieties of the time about infant mortality and salvation often hastened baptism (Flinn, 1977: 284).</p><p>	Hume, already 12, had begun his studies at Edinburgh University and, continuing them with 'Success', was to become the leading man of English letters of his era. Smith's birth-date places him among a cluster of others who contributed markedly to an age of intellectual distinction in Scotland: Thomas Reid, philosopher, born 17I0, already a student at Marischal College, Aberdeen; Hugh Blair, critic, born in I7I8; William Robertson, historian, born I72I; Adam Ferguson, pioneer sociologist, born I724; James Hutton, geologist, born I726; Robert Adam, architect, Joseph Black, chemist, and John Hunter, anatomist, all born in I728.</p><p>	Outside Scotland, Newton was nearing the end of his life, dying in I727. Swift was to become a national hero in Ireland in 1724 on publishing the Drapier's Letters, attacking English political and economic control. Pope in I723, suspected by the Government of Jacobite sympathies, was translating Homer and editing Shakespeare. In that year, Berkeley and Francis Hutcheson were both teaching in Dublin. No philosophical work had been published by Berkeley since the Three Dialogues of 1713, but Hutcheson was working out the moral philosophy to be presented in his Inquiry into the Original of Our Ideas of Beauty and Virtue (I725), an inspiration for Hume and Smith. On the Continent, Leibniz had died in 17I6, and Kant was born in 1724. Thomasius (d. I728) was nearing the end of his career in 1723 at Halle, when Wolff was expelled and began teaching at Marburg. Voltaire in 1723 published his epic poem La Henriade in its first form, and Rousseau was still serving out his time as an engraver in Geneva. Not yet an economist, Quesnay received the title of Surgeon-Royal that year, and was in practice in Mantes, near Paris. The later philosophes, Diderot (b. I7I3) and d'Alembert (b. I7I7), were schoolboys. Another of the philosophes, d'Holbach, was born the same year as Smith, and the economist Turgot four years later. Back in I723 became cantor at the Thomaskirche in Leipzig, and composed the St John Passion, while Handel had been away from Halle for some time, and was composing Italian operas in London. In America that year, Franklin at 17 moved from Boston to Philadelphia, and found work as an already expert printer. Washington's father was managing an estate in Westmoreland County, Virginia, where George was born in I732. Jefferson's father was training as a surveyor, and moved out to the edge of western settlement in Virginia, to Goochland County, where Thomas was born in I743.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
