 desk, propped against the wall. A framed picture depicting a wall on which a graffitist has written "Hardcore Software" hangs above the bookcase. Next to it hangs a poster depicting one of the Our Gang kids as an exuberant grade-school Jimi Hendrix brandishing an electric guitar and dressed in 1960s rock-and-roll garb. Its caption reads, "Buckwheat Say... Rock 'n' Roll... O-Tay!" Several computer mice, each with a mousetrap snapped shut on it, are hanging by their cables from the ceiling.</p><p>	The floor of the cave, covered with discarded papers, books, children's toys, a pacifier, a pillow, a blanket, and two chairs, is all but unnavigable.</p><p>	A boyish twenty-five-year-old wearing a T-shirt, blue jeans, and boat shoes without socks sits at the desk, his attention directed at the largest of his computer screens. He is conventionally good-looking, with spectacles, an athletic build, and hair hanging nearly to his shoulders. He sports a three-day stubble on his face, grimy skin, and glittering brown eyes that never blink. His shirt is drenched in sweat.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
