<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl1-1.jpg"><img src="1cs1-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>TCHAIKOVSKY</h2><p>By Anthony Holden. <i>Bantam; 490 pages; &#163;18.99</i></h2><p><a href="1bt1-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>The life of Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky, perhaps the most popular classical composer of all time, has been shrouded in mystery and myth for more than a century. Thanks to the subterfuge of his family, with the subsequent blessing of the Soviet authorities, the world has been given a false portrait of a composer whose life was in truth as poignantly tragic as so much of his music.</p><p>Best known for his first piano concerto, his ballets Swan Lake and The Nutcracker and his operas Eugene Onegin and The Queen of Spades, Tchaikovsky also wrote passionate songs, haunting chamber music and lyrical orchestral scores. After years of critical neglect, written off as 'too popular' a composer, he is now enjoying an overdue renaissance, hailed as one of the great melodists and orchestrators of musical history. With the gradual opening of archives in post-Soviet Russia, there has been a parallel resurgence of interest in the true facts of his life - and his mysterious death.</p><p>In 1893, a week after conducting the first performance of his masterpiece, the Pathetique symphony, Tchaikovsky was dead at the age of only fifty-three. Why would he have drunk a glass of unboiled water, as his family told posterity, knowing there was a cholera epidemic in St Petersburg? And why does the cholera story not ring true? Could it have been a cover-up for a more sinister truth: suicide or even murder?</p><p>This is the denouement of an absorbing new biography by Anthony Holden, whose BBC Omnibus film on Tchaikovsky recently re-opened the files on his tragic end. Holden sees the composer's death as the logical climax to his tortured life as a promiscuous homosexual. It is a grim irony, he argues, that the same torments which bequeathed us so much great music also brought Tchaikovsky's life to so premature a close.</p><p>The product of four years' research in archives around Russia, Europe and the United States, Anthony Holden's biography will stand for many years as the definitive new portrait of an ill-starred genius, whose life and career were quite as colourful and passionate, and ultimately as moving, as his music.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
