<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl1-2.jpg"><img src="1cs1-2.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>GEORGE ELIOT</h2><p>By Frederick Karl. <i>HarperCollins; 704 pages; &#163;25</i></h2><p><a href="1bt1-2.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>George Eliot, the author of Middlemarch, Adam Bede, Silas Marner, Felix Holt, The Mill on the Floss and Daniel Deronda was the greatest literary heroine of the nineteenth century, and has remained so until our own day. At the peak of her career she was, with Florence Nightingale and the Queen herself, one of the three most famous women in Victorian England.</p><p>The last full biography of Eliot was published over twenty-five years ago. Frederick Ikarl's magnificent new book draws heavily upon previously unpublished letters, from Eliot herself and from her circle, to create a significantly revised portrait of her both as a woman and as an artist. He argues that her entire life, from late childhood onwards, was a process of continuous transformation: from Mary Anne, to Marian, to Mrs George Henry Lewes, to George Eliot; he demonstrates how as George Eliot, her work embodies her own profoundly held beliefs about morality, individuals and society (a society which changed more rapidly during her lifetime than ever before) and how she communicated these beliefs to others.</p><p>In 1854 Eliot ran away with Lewes, a married man, and they were effectively ostracised by society. Karl argues that this was a pivotal move, which provided stability in Eliot's personal life and was the source of many of the creative conflicts on which she later drew in her fiction. But he rejects the view of previous biographers that Eliot depended on men. Rather he sees each of her relationships with the freethinker, philosopher and reformer Charles Bray, with Dr Robert Brabant, one-time physician to Coleridge and a theologian, with John Chapman, publisher of the Westminster Review, with Herbert Spencer and finally with Lewes as a form of absorption of their place in the masculine world that was denied to her directly.</p><p>George Eliot revelled in contradiction, paradox and irony, and behind the famous public face was her abiding secretive self. She played out her fears, and then shadowed them throughout her fiction, transforming herself from a country girl in to a figure who made all knowledge her domain. This biography, is an unforgettable portrait of one of the most remarkable writers of modern times.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
