<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl1-5.jpg"><img src="1cs1-5.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>H.G.: THE HISTORY OF MR WELLS</h2><p>By Michael Foot. <i>Doubleday; 318 pages; &#163;20</i></h2><p><a href="1bt1-5.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>H.G. Wells (1866-1946) was one of the intellectual giants of his time. Famous on both sides of the Atlantic for his bestselling books and prolific journalistic output, he played a leading role in all the most important controversies of his turbulent age. He lived through momentous times which included both World Wars and the Russian Revolution. Other thrilling issues also prevailed throughout his life such as the fight women's rights, liberation from Victorian values of sexual morality, arguments about democracy and Communism and, of course, Socialism in all its many Shades.</p><p>In this inspired new biography Michael Foot, long-time sympathizer with most of the causes for which Wells fought so resiliently, argues that it is time for  Wells's reputation as a writer to resume its former glory. He brings new insights into his extraordinary life and works, arguing that several of Wells's novels are masterpieces, and will restore his reputation as a literary figure when most of his detractors are forgotten. He casts fresh light on the women Wells loved and who loved him-among them four of the most independent-minded women of his century, his wife Jane Wells, Amber Reeves, Rebecca West and Moura Budherg - showing their influential role in guiding him towards some of his greatest heights of literary and intellectual achievement.</p><p>As a personal friend of Wells in his youth, and strongly influenced by him in his own political beliefs, Michael Foot is uniquely placed to bring new life to one of this century's most colourful and controversial heroes. Wells himself said of Foot's biography Brendan and Beverly, "It is magnificent. Do it again and again." A more fitting endorsement for his preferred biographer could hardly be found, and in H.G: The History of Mr Wells Michael Foot has risen to the occasion once more with his customary brilliance and wisdom.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
