<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl1-6.jpg"><img src="1cs1-6.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>THE ROOSEVELTS: AN AMERICAN SAGA</h2><p>By Peter Collier with David Horowitz. <i>Andr&eacute; Deutsch; 542 pages; &#163;20</i></h2><p><a href="1bt1-6.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>The story of the Roosevelts is usually seen as a tale of two presidents, and of two families, the Oyster Bay and Hyde Park branches, that had little to do with each other. Now comes an explosive new portrait, The Roosevelts: An American Saga, which offers a unique view of America's longest-lasting and most powerful dynasty. It shows for the first time how the Roosevelts divided into two branches and began an epic battle for the family legacy, and how the ideals of the two presidents were passed on to members of later generations, ennobling some and crushing others.</p><p>	There is Teddy, the flamboyant politician and Rough Rider, who passed on an ethos of sacrifice and achievement to his children. There is Theodore Jr, handpicked by his father to carry on the traditions of Oyster Bay but unable to complete the mission. And Alice, Teddy's acid-tongued, fiercely loyal daughter, whose antics became the talk of Washington. There is also Eleanor, who translated the unhappiness of her marriage to FDR into political activism, eventually becoming First Lady of the World. And finally Franklin, who made an alliance with Eleanor to become the nemesis of the Oyster Bay Roosevelts and, ironically, a truer heir to Teddy than any of his own children.</p><p>	The Roosevelts is a riveting tale of triumph over heartbreak and frailty, but it is also a daunting story of the vanity of human wishes.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
