<html><head><title>Biography</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl1-7.jpg"><img src="1cs1-7.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>VERA BRITTAIN: A LIFE</h2><p>By Paul Berry and Mark Bostridge. <i>Chatto & Windus; 592 pages; &#163;25</i></h2><p><a href="1jb1-7.htm">Jacket copy</a></p><p><b>Biography</b><br><p>PAUL BERRY was Vera Brittain's close friend for twenty-eight years and is her Literary Executor He is the joint editor of Testament of a Generation: The Journalism of Vera Brittain and Winifred Holtby and the author of By Royal Appointment: A biography of Mary Ann Clarke, Mistress of the Duke of York, and joint author of Daughters of Cain: The Story of the Nine Women Executed since Edith Thompson in 1923. Before retirement he was a Senior Lecturer at Kingsway-Princeton College, London . He lives in Sussex.</p><p></p><p>MARK BOSTRIDGE was educated at Westminster School and Oxford University, where he won the Gladstone Memorial Prize. A former research assistant to Shirley Williams, he has reviewed for the Times Literary Supplement, the Times Educational Supplement and The Literary Review, among other publications. He currently works for BBC Television and lives in Richmond, Surrey.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
