<html><head><title>Biography</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl3-1.jpg"><img src="1cs3-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>THE LIFE OF ADAM SMITH</h2><p>By Ian Ross. <i>Oxford University Press; 495 pages; &#163;25; $35</i></h2><p><a href="1jb3-1.htm">Jacket copy</a></p><p><b>Biography</b><br><p>Ian Simpson Ross is Professor of English (Emeritus) at the University of British Columbia. He is the biographer of Lord Kames, Smith's patron. He has written a study of the Scottish poet William Dunbar, and has edited, with E.C. Mossner, Smith's correspondence for the Glasgow edition of his works.</p> <br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
