<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl7-1.jpg"><img src="1cs7-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>ALLEN GINSBERG: JOURNALS 1954-58</h2><p>Edited by Gordon Ball. <i>Viking; 489 pages; &#163;25</i></h2><p><a href="1bt7-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>An important contribution to American literary and cultural history, these personal journals of the Beat poet Allen Ginsberg from his crucial formative years as an artist are essential reading for everyone interested in the Beat Generation and the poetry of Allen Ginsberg.</p><p>	Spanning the years 1954-58, these journals offer a moving account of the young Ginsberg's emotional life: his discovery of and struggle to accept his homosexuality; the torment and exhilaration of his love affair with Peter Orlovsky - probably the most important intimate relationship of his life; his friendships with Jack Kerouac, Gary Snyder, Gregory Corso, William Burroughs, Neal Cassady and others; and the death of his mother, the most deeply disturbing event of this period of the poet's life, which eventually resulted in 'Kaddish', Ginsberg's masterpiece. These are also the years when Ginsberg made some of his most radical discoveries in poetics - including his development of the long line of verse which bore fruit in the controversial poem 'Howl', whose publication and the obscenity trial that followed have become milestones in American history.</p><p>	The journals move from Ginsberg's heady times in Berkeley and San Francisco to the momentous trip he took to Morocco with Orlovsky in 1957 and on to adventures and encounters in the Arctic, Mexico, Paris, Amsterdam, London and New York Rich in intimate detail and reflect on, the journals offer an engaging portrait of one of the most influential American poets in the making.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
