<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl9-1.jpg"><img src="1cs9-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>LORDS OF THE RIM</h2><p>By Sterling Seagrave.<br><i>G.P. Putnam's Sons; 354 pages; $27.50. Bantam; &#163;16.99</i></h2><p><a href="1bt9-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>From the acclaimed historian and bestselling author of The Soong Dynasty comes a groundbreaking examination of the complex web of Chinese operations which dominate the Far East's booming economies.</p><p>'Be so subtle that you are invisible. Be so mysterious that you are intangible. Then you will control your rivals fate.' So wrote Sun Tzu in The Art of War, and no group has taken his advice more to heart than the Overseas Chinese, a vast, highly interconnected network of fifty-five million expatriate Chinese who control up to two trillion dollars in assets, and not only dominate the Pacific Rim but are making increasing inroads into the West.</p><p>Part economic analysis, part Pacific Rim history, part flamboyant chronicle of fortunes won, lost and won again, Lords of the Rim is a rich engrossing, superbly researched and spectacularly told account of who the Overseas Chinese are and how they got to be so powerful. Spanning thousands of years, it encompasses stories of murder and betrayal, bravery and corruption; of triads, syndicates, kingmakers, merchants, emperors, generals, spies and pirates.</p><p>Consistently praised both for his scholarship and for his ability to weave multiple strands into a fast-paced narrative, Sterling Seagrave provides us not only with a masterful history, but with a cautionary tale - for the Chinese strategies that have proved so successful for so long are just as effective today. Lords of the Rim provides a fascinating insight into both the past and the future of the world's Pacific economy.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
