<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl13-1.jpg"><img src="1cs13-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>LEADING THE BLIND: A CENTURY OF GUIDE BOOK TRAVEL, 1815-1914</h2><p>By Alan Sillitoe. <i>Macmillan; 246 pages; &#163;15.99</i></h2><p><a href="1bt13-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>Guide books were the educated dogs which led the blind traveller, giving the latest information on travelling conditions as well as instructing on the places to visit, and their range, even in the nineteenth century, was extremely wide. Murray and Baedeker guides, as well as covering all parts of Europe, featured Peking, Canada, the United States, Japan and New Zealand.</p><p>Alan Sillitoe has been collecting these guides for many years and has now culled together some of the most fascinating and unusual information from them. He builds up a provocative and engaging piece of social history and conveys what it was like to travel in the</p><p> hundred years leading up to the Great War - the pleasures, dangers, traps and rare experiences which the</p><p>tourist was warned against but still often encountered.</p><p> He becomes an imaginary nineteenth-century tourist and visits Switzerland, where he explains the dangers and delights of Alpine climbing, Germany and the Rhine with its multitude of disgraceful gaming houses; he dallies throughout Italy, contesting with the heat, the insects and the interminable beggars. He is advised against cock and bull fighting in Spain where for the most part he has to fend for himself. He bemoans the terrible condition of Hungarian inns, relates the ceaseless bartering needed in Turkey to achieve anything and the spectacular sights of the Holy Land and Russia. Throughout, the sense of isolation and wonderment at a foreign land is apparent and confirms the variety of different cultures available to the nineteenth-century traveller. On his return even England is not the country it had appeared to be.</p><p></p><p>Leading the Blind is a unique piece of social history which preserves in travel book aspic a whole world now mostly foreign to us on the surface, but whose customs and cultures have remained largely the same. As such it is as informative and instructional today as the guides it analyses of yesterday.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
