<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl4-1.jpg"><img src="1cs4-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>I SING THE BODY ELECTRONIC</h2><p>By Fred Moody.<br><i>Hodder and Stoughton; 311 pages; &#163;17.99. Viking Penguin; $23.95</i></h2><p><a href="1bt4-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>When Microsoft was founded in 1975 by Bill Gates and Paul Allen, few imagined it would manage to surpass both General Motors and IBM in market value by 1993. Now the world's largest supplier of personal computer operating systems, the culture and influence of Microsoft on the industry has been profound. Continuing their pre-eminence in multimedia applications, in 1995 Microsoft launches its CD-ROM 'Explorapedia' - a ground-breaking children's encyclopaedia.</p><p>For a whole year, Fred Moody participated in every step of Explorapedia's creation. He become the team's confidant, sounding board and scribe, from the corporate meetings where Bill Gates and his managers singled out multimedia as the only hope for Microsoft to maintain its blistering growth, to the endlessly frustrating design process where artists and programmers, educators and marketers battled each other over the vision and reality of what Explorapedia could be: the perfect balance between technical innovation, constricting disk space, artistic charm and educational content.</p><p>I SING THE BODY ELECTRIC describes what it takes to manage the exhilarating, visionary and turbulent process of creating the next generation of computer products and is an inspiring and fascinating look at Bill Gates's empire from the inside.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
