<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl8-1.jpg"><img src="1cs8-1.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>A Global Affair</h2><p>Edited by Amy Janello and Brennon Jones. <i>Jones and Janello; 304 pages; $35</i></h2><p><a href="1bt8-1.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>A Global Affair is better than a UN tour in revealing United Nations history and the extraordinarily diverse group of people who have contributed to it.</p><p>Brian Urquhart, the former UN Under Secretary-General for Special Political Affairs and the most highly respected former UN official alive introduces the book with a personal reflection on his half century involvement with the United Nations; Fourteen veteran journalists and other longtime UN observers from The New York Times, The Times of India, The Washington Post, The Financial Times of London and other publications contribute informative essays that trace the UN's history in key areas, from peacekeeping and disarmament to nurturing the world's children and safe-guarding the environment. Dozens of humorous and passionate anecdotes are contributed by UN insiders, the journalists who cover them, and the advocates and celebrities who have supported and prodded the UN. All of this together with nearly 400 stunning photographs - gleaned from archives throughout the world - bring UN history alive as never before.</p><p>A Global Affair is evocative reading for older generations and a book of revelation about the world around them for younger ones.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
