<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl8-2.jpg"><img src="1cs8-2.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>United Nations</h2><p>By Stanley Meisler. <i>Atlantic Monthly Press; 288 pages; $24</i></h2><p><a href="1bt8-2.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>On the eve of the fiftieth anniversary of the United Nations, Stanley Meisler has written a compelling popular history. He explores the U.N.'s culture, its adventures in war, and its evolution into a key international player. In a lucid, colorful account, he brings the personalities and events of this history alive, from Roosevelt, Stalin, Truman, and Gromyko, who set the stage at the birth of the U.N., to U.S. Ambassador Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who walked out of the General Assembly over the Third World's anti-Zion resolution. It is a story filled with action and heartbreak.</p><p>With the end of the Cold War, the U.N. believed it could fulfill the vision of its founders, but disillusionment set in when the debacle in Somalia became the great watershed, the test of whether the U.N. could enter the era of peace enforcement. Meisler lauds many of the U.N.'s achievements but questions its future. His portrait of the U.N. is cautious, optimistic, and powerfully informed.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
