<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl8-3.jpg"><img src="1cs8-3.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>United Nations</h2><p>By G&eacute;rard Prunier. <i>Columbia; 250 pages; $29.95</i></h2><p><a href="1bt8-3.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>THE RWANDA CRISIS<br>History of a Genocide Gerard Prunier</p><p>In the summer of 1994, the tiny African nation of Rwanda exploded onto the international media stage, as internal strife reached genocidal proportions. But the horror that unfolded before our eyes had been building steadily for years, even decades, before it captured the attention of the world</p><p>	In THE RWANDA CRISIS, renowned Africanist Grard Prunier offers the broad, clear-eyed historical perspective that Western readers have needed to fathom how the brutal massacres of the past year came to pass. In his lucid discussion, Prunier shows how the genocidal events in Rwanda were part of a deadly logic, a plan that served central political and economic interests.</p><p>	In the process, THE RWANDA CRISIS makes great strides in dispelling some of the racist myths surrounding the people of Rwanda in particular, and Africans in general, propagated by European colonialists in the nineteenth century and carved into "history" by Western influence.</p><p>	THE RWANDA CRISIS demonstrates how the kindling for cultural dominance and subjugation among the Hutu and Tutsithe central players in the recent massacreswas fanned by racially obsessed Europeans</p><p>	Expertly leading readers on a journey through the troubled history of the country and its surroundings, Prunier moves from the pre-colonized Kingdom of Rwanda, through German and Belgian colonial regimes, and on to the 1973 coup. The book chronicles the developing refugee crisis in Rwanda and neighboring Uganda in the 1970s and 1980s, and offers the most comprehensive account available of the evolution of the genocide</p><p>	In the aftermath of this devastating tragedy, THE RWANDA CRISIS is the first far-reaching perspective on the events available to American readers. Prunier details the long-standing resentments that led to the massacres, and considers prospects for the future of Rwanda.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
