<html><head><title>Jacket copy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><a href="1cl10-3.jpg"><img src="1cs10-3.gif" alt="jacket thumbnail"><p>Full image</a></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><h2>John Hume: Peacemaker</h2><p>By George Drower.<br><i>Gollancz; 223 pages; &#163;16.99. Distributed by Trafalgar Square; $29.95</i></h2><p><a href="1bt10-3.htm">Biography</a></p><br><p><b>Jacket copy</b><br><p>John Hume's decisive role in the Northern Ireland peace process has brought him nomination for the 1995 Nobel Peace Prize and recognition as a pivotal player in the move to end decades of violence in a province hidebound by centuries of prejudice and entrenched positions.</p><p>	Dubbed the greatest Irish politician this century, Hume has been a consistent exponent of reason and moderation, and as leader of the SDLP he has been the principal spokesman of Ulster's Catholics, providing Irish nationalism with a peaceful and credible alternative to the IRA. For three decades he has been at the turbulent centre of Irish politics, adopting a moderating stance between the extremes of Gerry Adams and lan Paisley and courageously carrying through his conviction that the true solution to the problem of Northern Ireland cannot be imposed: it has to be agreed by all sides.</p><p>	This new biography, based on extensive interviews with friends, foes and colleagues, charts Humes political career from his early years in the Derry civil rights movement to his position as the linchpin of the peace process, and provides an up-to-date account of the character and personality of a man who amid the bitterness and blood-letting of Ulster politics has had the intellect and vision to see beyond sectarian divides.</p><br><a href="http://www.economist.com/review/">Review Index</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/">The Economist</a></td></tr></table></body></html>
