http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev2/2rt1/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113185946 text/html 10519
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:55:58 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:01 GMT
Content-length: 10333
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Murder in mind</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr1.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h1>Murder in mind</h1>
<p><b>The American school of ''hard-boiled'' detective thrillers has brought British crime writers out of their ''cosy'' past</b></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex1-6.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> D<font size=-1>ARK</font> R<font size=-1>OOM</font></a> &nbsp By Minette Walters. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-3.html">A<font size=-1>N</font> I<font size=-1>MAGE</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> D<font size=-1>IE</font> F<font size=-1>OR</font></a> &nbsp By Mike Phillips. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-7.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>UMMONS</font></a> &nbsp By Peter Lovesey. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-4.html">L <font size=-1>IS</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> L<font size=-1>AWLESS</font></a> &nbsp By Sue Grafton. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-8.html">S<font size=-1>MOKE</font></a> &nbsp By Donald E. Westlake. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-1.html">P<font size=-1>AINT</font> <font size=-1>IT</font> B<font size=-1>LACK</font></a> &nbsp By Mark Timlin. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-5.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ERMAIDS</font> S<font size=-1>INGING</font></a> &nbsp By Val McDermid. <br>
<li><a href="2ex1-2.html">F<font size=-1>ENCE</font> J<font size=-1>UMPERS</font></a> &nbsp By Robert Leuci.<br>
</ul>
<p>THE genteel reputation of British crime writers took a severe knock recently when they aired their bloody linen in public. The affray was provoked by the stately P.D. James, when she said on radio apropos her deep interest in moral choice: ''That's why my murderers, women and men, are intelligent, well-educated people.'' If you set the detective story in ''the pits of the worst possible inner-city area, where crime is the norm and murder is commonplace, you don't get moral choice.''
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first howl went up in <i>Red Herrings</i>, the magazine of the Crime Writers' Association (<font size=-1>CWA</font>). Chaz Brenchley, a gory chronicler of the under-class, contended that his inner-city neighbours in Newcastle were confronted with more moral dilemmas than are dreamt of among the middle classes. Others piled in to extol the merits of social realism and huge press coverage ensued<i> </i>in <i>The Times </i>and elsewhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Crime writers lapped up the publicity. For though the genre is hugely popular, literary editors customarily provide just a few column inches a month for short appreciations of a lucky few novels. Snobbery is rife. ''I'm afraid I don't read crime,'' say blue-stockings of both sexes. This helps explain the persistence of the misperception that British writers are still mired in the Golden Age of the classic whodunnit, when Margery Allingham, Agatha Christie, Dorothy Sayers and others reigned supreme. In fact, crime fiction is vibrant, experimental and choc-a-block with penetrating observations on contemporary society: these days, if the butler did it, he might well be a cocaine-sniffing, trans-sexual, foot-fetishist.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much of this innovation and energy is owed to American influence, and to a rewarding relationship between American and British crime writers. On both sides of the Atlantic, crime fiction is a broad church. It encompasses what Americans -- confusingly under the generic title of mysteries -- call the ''cosies'' (detective stories and domestic crime) as well as what they call the ''hard-boiled'' (urban-jungle thrillers).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among the toughest eggs is Nick Sharman, the hero created by Mark Timlin, Lady James's most venomous assailant. In ''Paint it Black'' he persuades a drug dealer to talk by blasting his Alsatian dog with an Uzi machine-gun, takes vengeful action against baddies at every turn and punctuates the clubbing, head-butting and shooting by saying: ''I'll blow your head off then piss in your neck.'' Subtlety is not Mr Timlin's long suit, but he is racy and knows the underside of London.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dashiel Hammett and Raymond Chandler, the originators of the hard-boiled school, rescued the gumshoe from the mean streets of pulp magazines. Chandler is a metaphor for transatlantic symbiosis. Although he was born in America and spent most of his life there, his English public-school education provided the literacy and wit that lifted his books to a standard that his successors still strive vainly to reach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;British writers are struggling to catch up, but the great practitioners of the hard-boiled school are still American: George V. Higgins, James Lee Burke, Elmore Leonard and Robert B. Parker (up until his Spencer began emoting like a New Man). Americans score on depth, complexity and authenticity. To read ''Fence Jumpers'' by Robert Leuci, an ex-New York cop, is to acquire a stunning insight into the vicious world of crime and punishment in parts of the city where boys opt to become criminals or cops or both. As in Mr Timlin's harsh world, moral choices are all around and they are very tough. Does a good man shop his partner when he finds he's in the pay of the Mafia, or do love and loyalty take precedence?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America led the way too in moving beyond traditional hard-boiled heroes. Walter Mosley created a famous black sleuth -- the precursor to Sam Dean, a Caribbean journalist who stars in '''An Image to Die For'', the latest in a series of pacey British thrillers by Mike Phillips. The big innovation, however, came from America with Sara Paretsky and Sue Grafton, whose female private eyes acquired such a following that for a time male gumshoes seemed likely to become an endangered species.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Paretsky's V.I. Warshawski has begun to pall as readers get fed up with her moralising and her incredible indestructibility. Ms Grafton's Kinsey Millhone, being neither bionic nor always right, is more attractive. She could also have a long life, for Ms Grafton called her first Millhone story ''A is for Alibi'', and thus opened up a market for 26 books (crime readers are notorious suckers for a series). But Ms Grafton's latest Millhone thriller, ''L is for Lawless'', is little more than competent, with none of the cleverness, topicality and zest of Val McDermid's tales of Kate Brannigan, a Mancunian investigator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since there is nothing cosy about many contemporary crime novels, squeamish readers have a new divide: nasty and nice. In ''The Mermaids Singing'', Ms McDermid has moved to the nasty end of the spectrum. It is a terrifying story of a historically-minded psychopath who tortures and murders young men with the help of home-made apparatus faithfully copied from the past. Bang up-to-date in her use of psychological profiling and computer technology, Ms McDermid is mining a rich seam, for the British specialise in the psychological suspense novel. Ruth Rendell -- particularly under her Barbara Vine pen name -- excels at the genre. Patricia Cornwell, an American, is also hugely successful, but she is better at dissecting corpses than personalities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recently, Ms Rendell has acquired a worthy competitor in Minette Walters, who is on a roll, having in 1993 won the Edgar Allan Poe Award of the Mystery Writers of America, and in 1994 the <font size=-1>CWA</font> Gold Dagger. Her fourth novel, ''The Dark Room'', is an intelligent, gripping and well-written study of a young woman with amnesia who in mourning her lover and her faithless best friend has to accept that either she or her father might have murdered them.
</p><b>Refined mayhem</b>
<br>Cosies, however, are still much loved. Peter Lovesey's ''The Summons'' is a classic. Two years after resigning in a huff, the difficult but inspired ex-Superintendent Peter Diamond is called back to re-open one of his old cases to see if he sent the wrong man to jail for murder. It is a fine example of the straightforward detection at which Mr Lovesey excels and which any Golden Age luminary would have admired.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Television has helped boost the popularity of Mr Lovesey and other writers of the well-made British mystery. On both sides of the Atlantic, millions watch Colin Dexter's Inspector Morse and Ms Rendell's Inspector Wexford, and fondly remember Mr Lovesey's Victorian detective, Sergeant Cribb. The next treat will be the appalling Superintendent Andy Dalziel and his teeth-gritting side-kick, Inspector Peter Pasco -- the superb double-act created by the mordant Reginald Hill.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But irony and mockery do not travel well. 'Take out the jokes if you want to sell here'', is the dispiriting advice given from time to time by American editors to British writers. However, one New Yorker, Donald E. Westlake, has made a highly successful career being amusing about crime. In ''Smoke'' he tells of Freddie, a burglar who becomes invisible -- a condition which is professionally useful, but personally difficult. Mr Westlake's sense of fun and the cleverness of his observation make for an enjoyable confection, though one rather bland for the British.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <i>vive la difference</i>. It would be a sorry day if the transatlantic cross-fertilisation led to uniformity, rather than the diversity that has brought crime writing to its present exciting and robust state.


</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
