<html><head><title>Still coloured by apartheid</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr2.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>New South African novels</b></p>
<h2>Still coloured by apartheid</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex2-5.html">S<font size=-1>HORT</font> <font size=-1>NOT</font> T<font size=-1>ALL</font> S<font size=-1>TORIES</font></a> &nbsp By Gomolemo Mokae. <br>
<li><a href="2ex2-2.html">W<font size=-1>AYS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> D<font size=-1>YING</font></a> &nbsp By Zakes Mda. <br>
<li><a href="2ex2-6.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>EASONS</font></a> &nbsp Edited by Andries Walter Oliphant. <br>
<li><a href="2ex2-3.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>LEXANDRA</font> T<font size=-1>ALES</font></a> &nbsp By Isaac Mogotsi. <br>
<li><a href="2ex2-4.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>MELL</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>PPLES</font></a> &nbsp By Mark Behr. <br>
<li><a href="2ex2-1.html">S<font size=-1>HE</font> P<font size=-1>LAYS</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> D<font size=-1>ARKNESS</font></a> &nbsp By Zakes Mda. <br>
</ul>
<p>APARTHEID pinned down the wings of South African writers, arousing their rage and defining their vision. The apartheid novel was darkly political. Stories unfolded in the dim light of persecution, humiliation and the deprivation of human dignity. It was also intensely introspective, pushing repeatedly at the meaning, and burden, of ''South Africanness''. Under apartheid, South Africa propelled a generation of white novelists into international view: Alan Paton, Nadine Gordimer, Andr Brink, J.M. Coetzee, Breyten Breytenbach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;South African novelists, awakening the political consciousness, straddled two worlds: the creative and the political. Mr Brink, in a lecture given earlier this year, went so far as to say, provocatively:
<ul><font size=-1>In the years of the South Africa of liberation, literature may have played, as I have tried to argue, an invaluable role; at the same time there has been an erosion of the imagination. A dangerous movement from what Dorothy Sayers once called a 'poetry of search' towards a 'poetry of statement' took place.
</font></ul>Now that liberation has come, has it unleashed a fresh creative spirit? Who is who among the new generation of black novelists, emerging in the shadow of their celebrated white compatriots?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the most refreshing black novelist to emerge in South Africa this year is Zakes Mda. Better known as a playwright, he published his first two novels, ''Ways of Dying'' and ''She Plays with the Darkness'', within months of each other. One set in South Africa, the other in the small neighbouring country of Lesotho, both play on the interaction between the unmagical poverty of everyday life and the magic of mythical African tradition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In ''She Plays with the Darkness'', the outwardly contented people of a Lesotho mountain village:<ul><font size=-1>are a sad people inside, tormented by the knowledge that one day the great mist will rise and suffocate them all to death. And no one can do anything about it . . . Even those who have the gift of controlling lightning and of sending it to destroy their enemies are powerless against the mist.
</font></ul>Such magical gifts are taken for granted. Even the village herdboy, who leaves for the city, which ultimately corrupts him, remains in their grip. When he returns to the village, dressed in a suit and driving a smart car, he does not challenge the intellectual collision of the cultures of his youth and adulthood. Fantasy and legend just are.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Death preoccupies Mr Mda. In ''Ways of Dying'', Toloki, a lonely down-and-out who hangs out by the Cape Town docks, discovers a vocation as a ''professional mourner'', paid to wail and ululate at the funerals of poor township folk. ''Death becomes me, it is a part of me,'' says Toloki. ''I cannot live without death.'' He slowly discovers a capacity within him for loving through his friendship with Noria, a childhood companion, after mourning at the funeral of her young son; and, in return, teaches her to live again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Again, fantasy is never far from their lives. Toloki pastes photographs torn from <i>Home and Garden</i> to the wall of Noria's tin shack: photographs of black leather sofas, peach-coloured kitchen units and landscaped Italian gardens. Together, sitting on the floor of the shack, they stroll through the garden, lounge on the king-size bed and let temporary magic restore their souls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though Mr Mda's novels are not explicitly political, the politics of poverty, struggle and racial subordination burst in on the characters. Noria's young son is killed, ''necklaced'', by youths belonging to a political movement for ''being a sell-out''. Similarly with Isaac Mogotsi's first novel, ''The Alexandra Tales'', an interesting though less compelling story of a boy growing up without his mother in a black township. His political awakening to the injustices of his life -- his grandmother, for decades a loyal, deferential domestic servant in a posh white villa, evicts him from her tiny servant's room for daring to play with the white child of the ''baas'' -- is initially only tangential to the story.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The intrusion of the political into South African novels may be inevitable so soon after the negotiated collapse of apartheid. It is hard to imagine a South African novelist writing, say, a domestic English comedy; South Africans are only slowly learning to laugh at themselves. Perhaps it is too soon, or perhaps they are too entrenched, to expect new writing to cast off the old ways of seeing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor is the quest for understanding apartheid's grisly past yet fulfilled; it has barely begun. The disarmingly simple tale that Mark Behr tells in his first novel, ''The Smell of Apples'', is of Marnus, a boy growing up in an Afrikaner family in the shadow of his father, a general in the South African army. The chill of the story is not just a sinister twist at the end, which blows away the innocence of young Marnus. It is the way Mr Behr builds up the warmth and love of members of a suburban white family, abiding by their own uncomplicated truths, who turn out to be the very people committing crimes in the name of apartheid.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, few in the new generation of novelists are black. ''It has always been the case that novel-writing was never a genre popular among black people,'' says Mr Mda. ''Black people tended to write for other reasons: art was not art for its own sake but to mobilise people.'' During the 1970s and 1980s, black writing and politics were seldom divisible. And, politically, poetry was a more useful form than the novel: easy to memorise and conceal from the censors, it could readily be recited at township readings. Mongane Wally Serote, for instance, took his poetry into exile, where he worked for the African National Congress.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Short stories also have a richer black tradition than novels. Some critics trace this to the African oral tradition of story-telling. Others identify more recent roots. The earliest black writers, starting with Solomon Plaatje at the start of this century, learnt their craft through essays in journals and newspapers: a form that led readily to short stories. The heyday of black writing, in the 1950s, turned around the magazine journalists of <i>Drum</i> and their racy Sophiatown lives of beer halls and jazz. New short stories include ''Short not Tall Stories'', a collection by Gomolemo Mokae, one of whose short stories also appears in ''The Change of Seasons''. He pokes fun at, among other things, the duplicity of Africans who fail to live by the traditional mores they preach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politics, of exile, jail, protest and now Parliament, has captured the minds of black South African intellectuals for more than a generation. Publishers grumble today that would-be black novelists continue to send in derivative manuscripts, flat tales of white villains and black heroes, set in jails or detention. ''We reached such a level of desperation,'' says Glen Moss, head of Ravan Press, a traditional publisher of black writing, ''that we combed our out-of-print backlist this year and relaunched them.'' In the past two years, Ravan has taken on only two new novels: Mr Mogotsi's, and ''The Year of the Tapeworm'', a first novel by Chris van Wyk, which comes out next February. Political apartheid may be buried, but its literary undoing seems to have only just begun.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
