<html><head><title>Tigers and dragons</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr3.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Asian powers</b></p>
<h2>Tigers and dragons</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex3-1.html">A<font size=-1>SIA</font> R<font size=-1>ISING</font>: W<font size=-1>HY</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA</font> W<font size=-1>ILL</font> P<font size=-1>ROSPER</font> <font size=-1>AS</font> A<font size=-1>SIA'S</font> E<font size=-1>CONOMIES</font> B<font size=-1>OOM</font></a> &nbsp By Jim Rohwer. <br>
<li><a href="2ex3-2.html">C<font size=-1>HINA</font> A<font size=-1>FTER</font> D<font size=-1>ENG</font> X<font size=-1>IAOPING</font></a> &nbsp By Willy Wo-Lap Lam. <br>
<li><a href="2ex3-3.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> P<font size=-1>RACTICE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> P<font size=-1>OWER</font>: U.S. R<font size=-1>ELATIONS</font> <font size=-1>WITH</font> C<font size=-1>HINA</font> S<font size=-1>INCE 1949</font></a> &nbsp By Rosemary Foot. <br>
</ul>
<p>

NEVER judge a book by its cover . . . nor, in the case of Jim Rohwer's, by its title, its blurb or even by its first 25 pages. Such boosterism may sell books but Mr Rohwer, a former Asia editor of <i>The Economist</i> and now chief economist at <font size=-1>CS</font> First Boston in Hong Kong, is astute enough to know that Asia as a whole is not rising. And he certainly knows that the dozen East Asian economies which interest him most are not set on a trajectory of unending growth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, as Mr Rohwer himself notes, the success of some East Asian economies looks set to lift the region merely back to where it was in 1900: one-third of world <font size=-1>GDP</font>. With similar hard-headedness, he warns everybody to be wary of predictions, recalling a World Bank forecast in 1960 that projected the Philippines and Burma as the region's success stories. Unfortunately, he sometimes disregards his own sound advice -- by suggesting, for instance, that Shanghai will be Asia's ''financial capital'' and that the Russian Pacific will be ''Californiaized''.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In avoiding the usual ''run round the rim'' type of analysis, Mr Rohwer spends curiously little time discussing Japan or Korea, and dwells instead at length on the fashionable phoenixes of China (including sinified Asia) and India. So much interest in India is novel in such a Pacific-chic book, and serves mainly to show how different Indian conditions are from those in East Asia. His struggle over how to judge Lee Kuan Yew, the man he calls ''the Moses of East Asia'', is a thread that helps knit the text together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reader can be grateful that the assertions in the book's sub-title are not quite what they seem. This is not a study of American competitiveness, but of the potential of a new market. Mr Rohwer provides good evidence in support of Paul Krugman's thesis that there is nothing miraculous or culturally determined about East Asian growth and that the modernisation of the region is set to slow.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a book which is, with all its faults, the best general introduction to the region, Mr Rohwer remains optimistic, but his list of persistent problems makes it hard to understand why. He worries about the lack of institutions to entrench property and personal rights, about the continuing willingness of the United States to provide security for the region, about markets being closed to Asian goods, and about environmental damage. Most of all he worries about China -- will it accept the constraints of interdependence or will it be a nationalist great power out to dominate the region?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Willy Wo-Lap Lam sees China as fractured by factionalism and expects post-Deng China to be ''crisis-ridden''. The political system is ''feudal and corrupt''. Economic liberalisation ''has reached a bottleneck''. The ''socio-economic costs of reform are becoming prohibitive''. He writes of ''regional warlords'' and the ''expanding role'' of the armed forces -- and this in the country that Mr Rohwer counts on to take up the economic slack as Japan, South Korea and the South-East Asians slow down!
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, like so many China-watchers, Mr Lam finds it hard to remain glum about China, no matter how overwhelming the evidence of a system in crisis. China-watchers are fond of pointing out that the Chinese meaning of the word crisis includes a sense of danger and of opportunity, and Mr Lam latches on to the latter. He foresees a China that could make the best of its regional divisions, evolving a civil society where there are pockets of economic prosperity; a China where the regions will eventually be able to take over the capital. He even foresees a possibility that the armed forces will so stupidly block reform that they precipitate precisely the revolution that China needs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If any outside power can have an impact on how China and East Asia turn out, it is that wobbly superpower -- the United States. Rosemary Foot, Europe's leading authority on Asia's contemporary history, recalls that America was unpredictable on how it handled China even during the cold war. Its policy-makers took some time to see that China was constrained by domestic upheavals and scared stiff of the Soviet Union. When the Americans finally understood that China could be useful in their struggle with the Soviet Union, they then tumbled too far in love with their new-found friend. Hence their deep disappointment when China murdered its children in 1989.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Ms Foot gets closer to the ''post-cold-war era'' her carefully documented study runs out of confidential documents, but her analysis remains cautious and astute. She notes that China and the United States grew closer as China cast off communism and its support for revolutionary movements. But as they grew closer, and as their common enemies faded, the Chinese and the Americans did not necessarily like what they saw.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As China replaces Marxism with nationalism, many Chinese regard the United States as a decaying country that is envious of rising powers. And nationalism is an especially difficult emotion for Americans fully to understand. They are still stirred by the ideal of the melting pot, and want to export it to the world. So there is an increasing conflict between Chinese nationalism and Americans' missionary impulse. Americans know that they have to trade with China, but the warmth of relations across the Pacific is chilled by the rising sense of Asian cultural chauvinism, of which Chinese nationalism is the leading edge. Americans have to hope that East Asians will grow rich enough, fast enough, so they become as un-nationalistic as they are themselves. And that China does not cast a long shadow over its already successful East Asian neighbours.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
