<html><head><title>What else is new?</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Asian futurology</b></p>
<h2>What else is new?</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex4-1.html">M<font size=-1>EGATRENDS</font> A<font size=-1>SIA</font></a> &nbsp By John Naisbitt<br>
</ul>
<p>THE author of ''Megatrends'', which was published in 1983 and spent more than two years on the <i>New York Times</i> bestseller list, has returned to the fray with a feverish account of the ''eight Asian megatrends that are changing the world''. As befits a man who deals with the ''mega'', John Naisbitt is good on the big picture, and most of his main themes are sensible, although they will hardly come as news to Asia-watchers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Attentive observers (and some not so attentive ones) will have already spotted that large parts of Asia are moving ''from villages to megacities'' and that many Asian industries are changing ''from labour intensive to high technology'' -- to quote two of the megatrends. Still, Mr Naisbitt is probably right that non-specialists in the West have not grasped the scale of what is going on, and need telling.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, Mr Naisbitt is so keen to grab his reader by the lapel that he strips his book of all nuance and scepticism. The effect can be ludicrous. In attempting to answer the question ''What can Asia teach the West and its young people?'', he seizes upon an anecdote about a South Korean, lying beneath the wreckage of a department store that collapsed in Seoul last July. After ten days trapped under rubble, the young victim refused to sell his story to the media. Mr Naisbitt recounts that:
<ul><font size=-1>Choi would have none of it. 'They don't understand my pain,' he said. 'They just want to make money. I don't believe in that.' Can Asia's philosophy and teachings help to spark off a global moral renaissance, led by Asians?
</font></ul>Mr Choi's self-restraint was doubtless laudable, but Mr Naisbitt seems to be missing the big picture. Is a young South Korean trapped under a collapsed building really a symbol of Asian moral superiority? Is it not more telling that the building collapsed in the first place? Particularly since its collapse can be blamed directly on the very greed that Mr Naisbitt seems to think Asians are free of. South Korean construction companies were in the habit of padding their profits by bribing officials to let them ignore safety codes. The result has been a series of similar disasters in South Korea, and in Thailand and southern China as well. Greed, corruption and its consequences are in fact endemic across developing Asia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Naisbitt's curious blind spot points to the central weakness of his book. Although he portrays himself as a man unearthing startling new ''megatrends'', his book is in fact deeply conventional in its analysis -- from its fashionable pessimism about western welfarism, to its compulsory trot around the ''Asian values'' circuit and its stress on the importance of overseas Chinese business networks. This flaw is made inevitable by what seems to be a complete absence of fresh research. ''Megatrends Asia'' reads as if it were written at one sitting by a man who had decided to stay up for a week, pounding at a keyboard, gulping down black coffee and working through a pile of press cuttings. Such a method may be suitable for a student with an essay crisis. It will not do for a book which purports to be a serious work of analysis.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
