HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:56:55 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:02 GMT
Content-length: 4336
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Headed south</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>American politics</b></p>
<h2>Headed south</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex5-1.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> N<font size=-1>EXT</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> N<font size=-1>ATION</font></a> &nbsp By Michael Lind. <br>
</ul>
<p>MICHAEL LIND, a prolific 32-year-old contributor to political periodicals, writes with the hubris of youth. He has the self-confidence to analyse the history of the United States and to produce what he calls ''the first manifesto of American liberal nationalism'' which ''is the only path'' capable of leading ''to an America in which you and your descendants would want to live.''
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This book does not, of course, live up to its author's self-appraisal. But alternately brilliant and sophomoric, insightful and obtuse, it is an original, disturbing and provocative portrayal of America's past and an intriguing prescription of its future.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lind asserts that there have been three genuine revolutions in American history. The war of independence and its aftermath established the first American republic. The national community was identified with the Anglo-Saxon or Teutonic elements of the population. Protestantism served as the civic religion, and a grand compromise promoted unity by protecting slavery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From 1875 to 1957, what he calls the second republic was open to all whites and dominated by the north-eastern establishment. It rested on an extra constitutional compromise between the white elite and majority embodied in racial segregation and racist immigration restrictions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike its predecessors, which were nation-states, the third and current republic now has the outward trappings of a multi-national state. Its ideology proclaims the absence of a coherent national community and the existence instead of five national groupings, purportedly defined by race -- white, black, Hispanic, Asian and Pacific Islander, and Native American. The attenuated civil religion is one of authenticity, he says, stressing conformity to particular racial, social or religious sub-culture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ''tokenism'' of social preference programmes camouflages a system in which the white elite benefits from the political division of wage-earning white, black and Hispanic Americans. Without this tactic, it is doubtful that the ''white over-class'' would have been able to carry out what Mr Lind says was its agenda -- destroying unions, reducing wages and shifting the burdens of taxation from the rich to the poorer classes -- with so little effective popular opposition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lind believes that the continuation of multi-cultural America for a generation or so would result in a Brazilianisation of the United States, a splitting along class lines. The rich would flourish in a decadent America with third-world levels of inequality and crime. His goal is to bring about the fourth American republic. It would be a colour-blind, gender-neutral regime committed to individual rights. An activist government would promote equality, particularly through an affirmative effort to raise wages. The racial problem would be solved through inter-marriage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lind's facts are often wrong; his assertions are often overstated; and his vision often blurred. Even so, readers with the knowledge to supply their own corrections will find their view of America enlarged and challenged by his exceptional insights.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
