<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000279-B026-24</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev2/2rt6/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113190133 text/html 6464
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:57:47 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:02 GMT
Content-length: 6279
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Bad ol' boy</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr6.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>American politics</b></p>
<h2>Bad ol' boy</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex6-1.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICS</font> O<font size=-1>F</font> R<font size=-1>AGE</font></a> &nbsp By Dan Carter. <br>
</ul>
<p>
IT WAS only a generation ago. Yet today the 1960s seem unbelievably remote: all that long hair, pot-smoking, Woodstock, even the pre-<font size=-1>AIDS</font> sexual permissiveness. In politics too, the era of the Vietnam war, the civil-rights movement and student demos seems distant. Most of the decade's political figures -- Johnson, Nixon, Wilson, de Gaulle, Mao -- are long gone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, looking back, the 1960s were a crucial influence on today's politics, especially in America. Perhaps surprisingly, that influence is stronger on the right than on the left. In America, two politicians in particular were forerunners: Barry Goldwater, an Arizona senator and the losing Republican candidate in the 1964 presidential election, and George Wallace, the perpetual governor of Alabama. Both are still alive; both have been subject to recent biographies that reassess their legacy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of the two, George Wallace may have been the more significant. Dan Carter, a history professor at Emory University, calls him ''the most influential loser in 20th-century American politics''. The sub-title of his book is ''George Wallace, the Origins of the New Conservatism, and the Transformation of American Politics.'' And he disdains the image in last year's authorised biography by Stephen Lesher of Mr Wallace as a somehow lovable populist. Mr Carter sees the governor's legacy as pretty bad.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is no less remarkable for that. From humble beginnings, Mr Wallace became the dominant southern politician of the civil-rights period, serving as governor of one of the South's most unreconstructed states four times (with his wife, Lurleen, serving once in between). This book adds little to what is already known of his story, with two exceptions. One concerns Nixon's efforts to deny Mr Wallace a platform for a 1972 presidential challenge by stopping his bid for the Alabama governorship in 1970; this stretched not just to financing Mr Wallace's opponent with dubious cash payments, but to using the Internal Revenue Service to harass Mr Wallace's brother. The second is new information on the background and motives of Arthur Bremer, the man who in 1972 all but assassinated Mr Wallace at a Maryland shopping mall.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The shooting finished Mr Wallace's career. Yet in three respects he had set the tone for the politics of the 1990s. He pioneered the exploitation of race as a hot-button issue to attract white voters in the north -- as well as cementing its use in the South. When he spoke of segregation today, tomorrow and forever, his message was obvious. While deprecating welfare scroungers, rioting in inner cities and rising crime, he left no doubt as to the presumed colour of the perpetrators. When George Bush ran his notorious Willy Horton commercial in the 1988 presidential election campaign, he was following the Alabaman's lead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wallace's second legacy lay in his attack on the federal government. This was also about segregation: the old cry of ''states' rights'' was simply a demand for the South's racial policies to be left alone. But Mr Wallace expanded it into a general attack on Washington and a demand for delegation of powers to state and local governments -- familiar stuff to students of Newt Gingrich's Republican Party. Not that Mr Wallace really believed in rolling back the state. As this book shows, he loved spending programmes and the patronage they created; indeed, he financed his election races from contributions from construction firms that needed government contracts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third of Mr Wallace's achievements, if they can be called that, was to remind America of the political importance of the South. He himself never did more than win the Alabama governorship and, running as an independent candidate for the presidency in 1968, carry the five Deep South states. But he alerted the Republican Party to its chance of stealing the South from the Democrats, and not just in presidential elections. Nixon's southern strategy confirmed his party's lock on the southern presidential vote. In 1994, the Republicans went one better, seizing majorities of all southern congressional seats -- a switch that underlies their new majority in Congress. In pointing the way to Republican majority at all levels, Mr Wallace helped to consign the Democrats to their present parlous state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The wheel thereby comes full circle; for few have suffered more from this change than black Americans, especially in the South. So long as the Democrats were in the majority, blacks -- as overwhelmingly Democratic voters -- could expect some political sustenance. But the Republican Party has more or less stopped trying to win black votes. In the new majority, that means that blacks are all but disfranchised again. This is one more reason for sadness at the refusal of Colin Powell to run for president as a black Republican -- and for bemoaning George Wallace's legacy.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
