<html><head><title>One man's tale</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr7.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Ex-Yugoslavia</b></p>
<h2>One man's tale</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex7-1.html">B<font size=-1>ALKAN</font> O<font size=-1>DYSSEY</font></a> &nbsp By David Owen. <br>
</ul>
<p>HEDGED as it had to be, the praise America got for the Dayton agreement last month was deserved. Its earlier diplomatic interventions in the Yugoslav conflict were less glorious, as David Owen was well placed to observe. He was the mediator for the European Union (<font size=-1>EU</font>) until last summer and, though he can be over-critical of aspects of American policy, there is truth in his view that America helped ''prolong the war of the Bosnian Serbs in Bosnia-Hercegovina''. His book, together with two path-breaking <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>s containing maps, interviews and unpublished documents, is a must for anyone with views, whatever they are, on this terrible war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No diplomat's diplomat, Lord Owen is rude about Warren Christopher, the American secretary of state. Mr Christopher, he says, had not read even a one-page summary of the Vance-Owen plan when he himself visited him to discuss it. Yet, as he frankly admits, his own cutting words to J.R. Apple of the <i>New York Times</i> about President Clinton's team made things begin badly with the Americans.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there was much more to it than <i>faux pas</i>. Most seriously, Lord Owen blames America for undermining the peace plan put forward by him and Cyrus Vance, the United Nations mediator, that would have preserved a Bosnia-Hercegovina of ten autonomous cantons. To the Americans it ''rewarded aggression'' and left Bosnia's Serbs with too much land. They gave the plan grudging support; but in May 1993, when Bosnia's Serbs rejected it, insisted that any new one leave the Serbs with even more land.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lord Owen links America's coolness to the Vance-Owen plan to its fear of committing American peacekeepers. Serb rejection did save the Americans from sending 20,000 or more soldiers. Yet, whatever was in American minds, the plan's failure lay more in ex-Yugoslavia than in Washington. The Bosnian Serbs wanted their own, joined-up republic, not a trio of separate cantons. The Serbs, by most counts, held 70% of Bosnia-Hercegovina -- almost half again what the plan was to leave them. No outsider was about to force them back, and their Yugoslav enemies, the Bosnians and Croats, were at each other's throats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lord Owen dispels his reputation as a Serbophile appeaser. He found Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, repugnant. Though exasperated by Alija Izetbegovic's indecision, he never forgot that Bosnia's president was the one republican leader who had never been a communist. Twice Lord Owen argued for air strikes to get the Serbs to make peace, but failed, as did the Americans, to bend the ears of the British and French, who thought bombing would end the <font size=-1>UN</font>'s peacekeeping and aid work. The <font size=-1>UN</font>'s usefulness was exaggerated, Lord Owen thought. But he was against American calls for ''lift-and-strike'' -- arming the Bosnians and bombing the Serbs. Without a firm peace proposal, this, in his view, risked worsening the slaughter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of the region's republics, save possibly Macedonia, was wholly blameless in Yugoslavia's collapse into civil war. All sides have done vile deeds. Lord Owen is sensitive to both points, at times too much so. He developed a rapport with Slobodan Milosevic, Serbia's president, and sensed before the Americans that after 1993 Mr Milosevic had real reasons for wanting the war to end. Perhaps Lord Owen should have said more about Mr Milosevic's part in starting it. He mentions a <font size=-1>UN</font> ballistic report on the market-place explosion killing 69 Sarajevans in April 1994 that traced the mortar shell's path to Bosnian positions, not a later, more detailed one that concluded it might equally have come from Serb positions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>, a ''standard edition'' has the whole book as well as media interviews and press articles by Lord Owen, reached by clicking on red words in the text. More useful, perhaps, is the ''academic edition'' with its extra archive of thousands of documents, including reports to the <font size=-1>EU</font> Council of Ministers and the <font size=-1>UN</font> Security Council, <font size=-1>UN</font> resolutions and details of peace plans -- a gold mine for serious students and a publishing landmark. At the cost of some sloppy text editing, the book itself is astonishingly up-to-date. Its strong opinions will stoke fires. Taken as a whole this package, like its author, is brilliant and fascinating, if also partial and, at times, intemperate.

</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
