<html><head><title>Are you lying comfortably?</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr17.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Sigmund Freud</b></p>
<h2>Are you lying comfortably?</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex17-1.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>EMORY</font> W<font size=-1>ARS</font>: F<font size=-1>REUD'S</font> L<font size=-1>EGACY</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> D<font size=-1>ISPUTE</font></a> &nbsp By Frederick Crews and others. <br>
<li><a href="2ex17-2.html">A C<font size=-1>RITICAL</font> D<font size=-1>ICTIONARY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> P<font size=-1>SYCHOANALYSIS</font> (S<font size=-1>ECOND</font> E<font size=-1>DITION)</font></a> &nbsp By Charles Rycroft. <br>
</ul>
<p>THE immense literature on Freud continues to accumulate. As one might expect, the fiercest attacks on psychoanalysis are coming from America, the country which, over 50 years ago, so wholeheartedly embraced Freud's theories that it was very hard for anyone to gain a leading position in psychiatry without training as a psychoanalyst. Now, one extreme view has been replaced with another. Indeed, the pendulum has swung so far in favour of ''biological psychiatry'' and treatment with drugs that psychiatrists in training have hardly heard of Freud and are in danger of repudiating all forms of ''talking cure''.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Frederick Crews, an emeritus professor of English at the University of California, Berkeley, caused shock to the psychoanalytic establishment by publishing three articles damning of Freud in the <i>New York Review of Books</i> in 1993 and 1994. These are now reprinted in book form, together with a selection from the many critical letters which they provoked.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his first two essays, Mr Crews's querulous polemic is so intemperate that it fails to give Freud credit where credit is undoubtedly due. He is on stronger ground in his withering discussion of the so-called ''recovered memory'' movement in psychotherapy with which America is plagued. But the bearing of these abuses on a fair assessment of Freud and his theory of psychological repression is questionable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For most of this century the incidence of the sexual abuse of children was greatly underestimated. Freud himself originally attributed cases of hysteria to childhood sexual abuse. Later, famously, he changed his mind, concluding that ''memories'' of abuse were more likely to be a later disguise for the sexual wishes of small children. Fruitful as that was for Freud's theory of repression, it was vulnerable to the retort that parental abuse was real. Now a different error is being made. Parents are being accused of sexually abusing their children on the flimsiest of evidence. Families are being disrupted on quite inadequate grounds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no limit to human credulity and gullibility, and this is as true of psychiatrists as it is of their patients. What is alarming is the possibility that, after the recovered-memory movement has been fully discredited, the cycle will repeat itself with a return to the former state of error in which childhood sexual abuse and its ill effects will once again be underestimated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Freud himself postulated that the mind protected itself by ''repressing'' memories of painful events, that is, by making them unconscious and relatively inaccessible. Although psychological research has been unable to validate the concept of repression, many people will confirm that something like repression operates in their own lives. When people are inadvertently reminded of something painful in their lives, such as a bereavement, it is not uncommon for them to burst into tears and say something like: ''I hadn't realised how much so-and so meant to me.'' Although the event itself may be clearly recalled, it appears that the painful emotions connected with it can be repressed. The same holds true of battlefield trauma or other horrifying experiences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is almost certainly false that somewhere in the brain memories of painful incidents are accurately stored and can be recovered intact. Memory is far too fragmentary and unreliable for that. What is in question is how far actual incidents can be repressed rather than the distressing emotions connected with them. Here the only thing is to await more research.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Compared with the currently fashionable savage dismissal of everything Freud wrote, the criticisms of him by Wittgenstein, who thought much about the mind as a philosopher, seem almost benign. As recounted in Jacques Bouveresse's valuable book, Wittgenstein perceived that Freud's edifice of theory was not a science, but gave him credit for ''great imagination''. Wittgenstein saw that psychoanalysis could be both important and mistaken -- a theory which might not be objectively true, but which provided a fertile point of view which could be modified and corrected by later thinkers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wittgenstein also appreciated the healing power of story-telling: even if Freud's explanations of neurotic symptoms and human behaviour were not scientifically grounded, telling a coherent story of human life which had seemed unintelligible was itself therapeutic. In that, Wittgenstein anticipated a modern view of Freud advanced by Charles Rycroft and others, that psychoanalysis is really an interpretative system, not the science its originator claimed. This generous-minded view informs the revised and enlarged edition of Dr Rycroft's ''A Critical Dictionary of Psychoanalysis'', first published in 1968. No other book explains psychoanalytic concepts and their origins so wittily, accurately and concisely. It is invaluable as a work of reference.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Freud, like Darwin and Marx, caused a revolution in the way we think about ourselves. His was, in ways, a prophet's life: he went through a period of emotional stress and emerged with a revelation based upon his own self-analysis. It is possible to believe that<i> </i>much of psychoanalytic theory is wrong, yet realise the debt owed to Freud. One of Mr Crews's most telling critics, Morris Eagle, stresses the educative value of psychoanalytic theory in prompting research and further understanding of the varieties of human nature. Freud was a gifted clinical observer, as his papers on depression and on obsessional neurosis demonstrate, but he gains no credit from Mr Crews, who may not have read the relevant papers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although psychoanalysis in its original form is not more effective than other forms of psychotherapy, Freud's technique of listening to distressed people over long periods has had a beneficial effect upon many forms of psychotherapy. His observation of what he called ''transference"  -- a patient's emotional attachment to the psychoanalyst -- was deservedly influential in understanding how humans respond to authority figures, from politicians to gurus. His insistence that neurotic problems originate in early childhood has made people more inclined to understand children's emotional needs, rather than automatically to punish them when they fail to conform. Freud was wrong in many respects, but 20th-century man -- and woman -- was indebted to him.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
