HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:58:21 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:03 GMT
Content-length: 5234
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The client is usually wrong</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Italy</b></p>
<h2>The client is usually wrong</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex9-1.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>RISIS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> I<font size=-1>TALIAN</font> S<font size=-1>TATE:</font> F<font size=-1>ROM</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> O<font size=-1>RIGINS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE </font>C<font size=-1>OLD </font>W<font size=-1>AR</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> F<font size=-1>ALL OF</font> B<font size=-1>ERLUSCONI</font></a> &nbsp By Patrick McCarthy. <br>
</ul>
<p>JUST three years have passed since the aptly named ''clean-hands'' drive by local magistrates against corruption brought on the collapse of Italy's post-war order. Top politicians were prosecuted; Italy's system of election was made less extravagantly proportional and the old line-up of parties, dominated by Christian Democrats, vanished. Nevertheless, plenty of Italy's old political crocodiles remained as did many of the country's old problems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Italy's second republic, as optimists called it, got off to a shaky start. Silvio Berlusconi, a television mogul turned politician, was elected to power under the new rules in March 1994. Seven months later his government ended amid the same kind of party feuding that had brought down most of its 52 post-war predecessors. This foreseeable pratfall is the starting-point of this fine essay on the sins of contemporary Italian statecraft by Patrick McCarthy, who is a professor of European studies at the Bologna Centre of Johns Hopkins University.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He traces those failings to history. Italy was made one state in 1860-70, but not one economy. After 1945, given the proper will and the right policies, the country's politicians might have used the powers of a modern state to narrow the north-south divide. Instead, ''clientelismo'' -- patronage politics -- lined politicians' pockets. In the south the Christian Democrats, who ran or joined every post-war government, made deals with the Mafia and used state-owned industries as vote-machines and cash tills. Even Christian Democrats who wanted change were thwarted by the failure of the party's countless factions ever to agree for long on any policy but ''more of the same'', and by the inertial weight of the Catholic church.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So long as the cold war lasted, the Christian Democrats had the perfect excuse to keep Italy's only large opposition party -- and only serious foundation of any durable alternative government -- out of power. Not that Mr McCarthy has much illusion about Italian Communists, despite their vaunted successes in regional government. They too put party above country, in his view, and share blame for Italy's failure to produce a more modern and more effective public administration.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the end of the 1980s the game for Christian Democrats was up. Many things came all at once: the end of the cold war, economic recession, the importation of budgetary constraints on Italy by its European partners. But Mr McCarthy rightly looks deeper. Italian society, he says, had changed. A new class of small businessmen not reliant on public contracts wanted a leaner, cleaner administration. Mr Berlusconi's victory was due not just to his owning three television channels but to the popularity of his message: less state, more private initiative.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There was, all the same, Mr McCarthy underlines, ''a marvellous irony about the messenger''. Mr Berlusconi had built two fortunes, in construction and in television, using close links with politicians. He was a special friend of the now disgraced former Socialist leader, Bettino Craxi. On entering politics, he had horrendous debts to state-owned banks. In power, he was much quicker to put friendly managers in charge of state-owned television, his competitor, than to trim public spending.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr McCarthy is too wise to predict with any certitude what comes now. He doubts, though, in a brief concluding chapter, ''The Elusive Citizen'', whether those who ended Italy's first republic -- the urban middle classes of the north, the small businessmen of Lombardy and the anti-Mafia movements in the south -- will any longer be ''bought off by the new version of clan government offered by Berlusconi''.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
