http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev2/2rt10/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113190216 text/html 4689
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:58:30 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:01 GMT
Content-length: 4504
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The old gang</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr10.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>British politics</b></p>
<h2>The old gang</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex10-1.html">SDP: T<font size=-1>HE</font> B<font size=-1>IRTH,</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> D<font size=-1>EATH</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>OCIAL</font> D<font size=-1>EMOCRATIC</font> P<font size=-1>ARTY</font></a> &nbsp By Ivor Crewe and Anthony King. <br>
</ul>
<p>SO WAS it all for nothing? The attempt to break the mould of British politics; the splitting of the Labour Party; the heart-rending personal dilemmas and the gut-wrenching feuds between former friends; the political virgins seduced from family and fireside to walk the streets for a new party; the political careers of some of the most talented politicians of their generation smashed, utterly smashed; and it was all for <i>nothing</i>?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;'Fraid so, according to this wonderful account of the brief life of the Social Democratic Party (<font size=-1>SDP</font>) by two academics at Essex University, Ivor Crewe and Tony King. Both of them advised the new party in its early days, so they are hardly unsympathetic observers. Yet their conclusion is unblinkingly stark:
<br>
<ul><font size=-1>Someone who returned to Britain in the mid-1990s after having lived abroad (and been out of touch) through the 1980s would find very little difference in the British party system. There has been no partisan realignment in the electorate, no enduring shift in the balance of power among the three main parties, no sustained growth of centre-party support, no hung parliaments or coalition governments, no alteration in the electoral system, no major redesigning of the nation's political agenda.
</font></ul>
<br>
The <font size=-1>SDP</font> then was a failure. But the authors are perhaps less convincing in showing that it was an inevitable failure. They mercilessly expose the party's tactical errors, many of them attributed either to the failure of Roy Jenkins, its first leader, as a vote-getter, or to the failure of David Owen, its second leader, as a human being. Mr Crewe and Mr King rightly conclude, however, that even if these mistakes had been avoided, the party would probably have flopped.
</font></ul><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is less clear is what would have happened had things gone differently in the Labour Party. Suppose that Tony Benn, the leftist candidate, had defeated the right-wing candidate, Denis Healey, for Labour's deputy leadership in 1981 instead of losing by 0.8%. Suppose that this had led to a much larger exodus of Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s to the <font size=-1>SDP</font>. Suppose in consequence the <font size=-1>SDP</font> had seemed a natural home for working-class voters fed up with Labour's left-wing radicalism. History might have turned out differently. The <font size=-1>SDP</font>'s failure is beyond question; that its failure was inevitable is not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, although the <font size=-1>SDP</font> failed, what it stood for has survived. It was a party that was hard-nosed about economics, but tender-hearted on social questions. It insisted that, unlike the two big class-based parties, it stood for the whole nation, rather than any section within it. It tried not to claim a monopoly of wisdom (at least, not until David Owen became its leader). It espoused ethics in politics. It consciously sought the centre ground. All these desirable objects have survived its demise, today encapsulated in Tony Blair's Labour Party.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
