</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Piercing accents</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr11.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>England's stately homes</b></p>
<h2>Piercing accents</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex11-1.html">A<font size=-1>NCESTRAL</font> V<font size=-1>OICES</font> & P<font size=-1>ROPHESYING</font> P<font size=-1>EACE</font>: D<font size=-1>IARIES</font> <font size=-1>1942-1945</font></a> &nbsp By James Lees-Milne. <br>
</ul>
<p>FIRST question to any diarist: Why did you do it? For yourself or posterity? James Lees-Milne has a clever answer: ''I merely thought it might be possible to entertain my grand-children or great-grand-children-to-be.'' Never for an instant, he claims, did he imagine his memoirs might be printed. It would just be a record of a life in England during the second world war. ''How, what and where he ate, how much he paid for his bread and margarine, how he travelled . . . and how he was affected by bombs, blast and the beastliness of the whole process.''
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cost of bread and margarine does not figure much in these diaries but you learn a lot about the beastliness of the people Mr Lees-Milne meets as he travels around the stately homes of England in war-time. Their near-destitute owners had been encouraged by the government to bequeath their crumbling, elegant homes to the National Trust. He had the wonderful job of finding the most deserving.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In between convoluted journeys by train, motor car and bicycle to obscure villages down hidden lanes and byways, Mr Lees-Milne retreats to London society --  mostly the relations of the dotty old dukes and duchesses in the said stately homes. Together they give him scope to indulge his greatest talent: to make the most scorchingly acerbic remarks in the most innocent and casual way. Not meant for publication? Pull the other one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The comments and their victims are woven into every page. A few examples:
<br>
<ul><font size=-1>King Zog is frankly a cad. He wants to buy </font><i>The Times</i> newspaper and told Auberon, `And I won't give a penny more than ten million for it.' The princesses were present and he overheard them openly speculating on his sexual potentialities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The princess, being afraid of air raids, sits in the passage outside her flat on a milking stool.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mrs Greville has left Marie Antoinette's necklace to the Queen, 20,000 to Princess Margaret and 25,000 to the Queen of Spain . . . She was a lady who loved the great because they were great and apparently had a tongue dipped in gall. I remember old Lady Leslie once exclaiming: `Maggie Greville! I would rather have an open sewer in my drawing-room'.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Hoares took me round the house [Stourhead], which is packed to the brim with good things, and some ghastly things like cheap bamboo cake stands . . . [Sir Henry] spoke very little, and that little addressed to himself. Lady Hoare recalled that in the first war they were reduced to eating rats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;I was a little surprised, until Sir Henry looked up and said 'No no Alda. You keep getting your wars wrong. That was when you were in Paris during the Commune.'
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We motored to Six Mile Bottom where we met Professor Trevelyan [an historian]  . . . He is as dry as a stick and totally lacking gaiety and humour. He is very uncouth in his dress and person, and has long, untrimmed hair down the back of his neck. I was sitting behind him and as we approached Blickling he took out his false teeth and cleaned them with his handkerchief. I remember watching old Lord Dysart do this in the lavatory at Brooks's. He was very blind and was scrubbing his set with one of the hairbrushes.
</font></ul>
<br>These two diaries, first published in 1975 and 1977, are like a secret store of sweets, to be nibbled and chewed a page or two at a time: delicious and slightly addictive.

</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
