<html><head><title>Shark alert</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr12.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Mutual funds</b></p>
<h2>Shark alert</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex12-1.html">F<font size=-1>IDELITY'S</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font></a> &nbsp By Diana Henriques. <br>
</ul>
<p>FIDELITY is a financial services group with some $390 billion of assets under management. Although it has successfully branched out into discount stockbroking and pension-fund management, it is mostly held to be synonymous with mutual funds, which are roughly the American equivalent of British unit trusts. Yet in 1972, when Ned Johnson took over management of Fidelity from his father, it had just $3.9 billion of mutual-fund assets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm's rise to power is a big chapter in contemporary financial history. It did not create demand for mass-market investment vehicles. But it did more than any other financial company, with the possible exception of Wall Street's Merrill Lynch, to meet and shape that demand. Fidelity's insight was to see that mutual funds could be treated as inherently similar to any consumer product. With novel direct-mail tactics and clever marketing around a core of highly visible funds and fund managers -- such as the $51 billion Magellan fund and Peter Lynch, its uncannily successful manager until he retired in 1990 -- Fidelity created a money machine that sucked in investors' cash almost as fast as it could create new funds (today it has 223 separate ones).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm wields awesome power on behalf of the investors who own its funds. For instance, it is reckoned to control 8% or more of the shares of some 250 companies and more than 3% of some 550 companies. Its funds dwarf rivals' offerings -- even ignoring the huge Magellan fund, Fidelity's average equity fund invests $1.3 billion, while the typical rival has less than $300m to play with. The firm trades more securities by itself than all but the biggest stock exchanges.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fidelity's recipe for success has, unsurprisingly, involved breaking a few eggs along the way. Diana Henriques's premise is that a devil's kitchen lurks behind the slick public image that the firm has cultivated with consummate skill. Specifically, she wishes to expose the tension between the firm's public leadership of its industry and the private, almost reclusive bent of the Johnson family that controls it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, for all the author's investigative efforts, her revelations are unexciting and her arguments unconvincing. By coincidence, in August, just as the book was in production, Ned Johnson gave the firm's senior staff 51% of the firm's voting shares -- a measure driven by tax planning that certainly shifted power away from the Johnson family. Knowledge of this might have allowed Ms Henriques to reflect on new possibilities -- for instance, that the firm might one day become publicly owned, resolving the central tension that so exercises her.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, Ms Henriques has written a much-needed book. The history of the mutual-fund industry has been sadly neglected in print. She acknowledges that she has drawn heavily on an unpublished thesis by Natalie Groh, a Harvard academic who interviewed many of the industry's pioneers during the 1970s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The industry's efforts to establish regulatory approval and then to explore its latitude are well described. So are its flirtations with successive generations of crooks and con-men, notably Bernie Cornfeld, a spiv whose antics during the 1960s led to his arrest in Switzerland in 1973 (though he was never convicted of anything), and Robert Vesco, who took control of Cornfeld's troubled company and then fled into exile as regulators and creditors closed in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By setting out this background to Fidelity's rise, Ms Henriques has more than justified her efforts. The firm is not squeaky clean -- that much is clear from her descriptions of its sometimes belated efforts to close compliance loopholes. But its blemishes, at least those that she describes, are not sufficient either to strip it of credibility or to tarnish its remarkable success.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, Fidelity is perhaps the best prism through which to view the fast-growing mutual-fund business in the United States. The firm's faults and failings, as well as the questions of conflicts of interest, are common to most others in the business. Much more needs to be written on that broader subject, and Ms Henriques has helpfully opened the door for future authors.

</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
