HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:59:06 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:01 GMT
Content-length: 11394
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>International relations</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>International relations</h2>
<p><b>As a regular service for readers keen to keep up with more academic debates in economics, business and current affairs, we offer a selection of short reviews. This month's topic is international relations</b></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#13,1">I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL</font> R<font size=-1>ELATIONS</font> T<font size=-1>HEORY</font> T<font size=-1>ODAY</font></a> &nbsp Edited by Ken Booth and Steve Smith.<br>
<li><a href="#13,2">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>ATION</font> S<font size=-1>TATE</font></a> &nbsp By Kenichi Ohmae. <br>
<li><a href="#13,3">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>ATION-</font>S<font size=-1>TATE</font></a> &nbsp By Jean-Marie Guhenno; translated by Victoria Elliott. <br>
<li><a href="#13,4">T<font size=-1>HE </font>A<font size=-1>MBIGUITIES OF </font>P<font size=-1>OWER: </font>B<font size=-1>RITISH </font>F<font size=-1>OREIGN </font>P<font size=-1>OLICY SINCE 1945</font></a> &nbsp By Mark Curtis. <br>
<li><a href="#13,5">R<font size=-1>ETHINKING </font>I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL </font>R<font size=-1>ELATIONS</font></a> &nbsp By Fred Halliday.<br>
</ul>
<p></td></tr></table>
<a name="13,1"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL</font> R<font size=-1>ELATIONS</font> T<font size=-1>HEORY</font> T<font size=-1>ODAY</font><br>Edited by Ken Booth and Steve Smith.<br><i> Polity Press; 384</i> <i>pages; 45. Pennsylvania State University Press; $65</i><br>
<a href="2ex13-1.html">Extract</a> | <a href="2jb13-1.html">Jacket Copy</a> | <a href="2bt13-1.html">Biography</a></p>
THESE essays by mainly American and British scholars are a handy introduction to the ever more popular discipline known as <font size=-1>IR</font>: international relations. Steve Smith opens with a map of " isms''. <font size=-1>IR</font> theories are often classified into ''three Rs'': realism, espoused by Machiavellians for whom states are in a struggle of all against all; rationalism, derived from Grote, a founder of international law, who thought rules could temper state conflict; and revolution, the Kantian tradition that a world of states will give way to a quite new order.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nowadays, debate among <font size=-1>IR</font> specialists is fiercest at two points. One is between scholars who focus on state-state relations and those who stress ''transnational'' or non-state ties, particularly economic ones. The second concerns method: is <font size=-1>IR</font> really a subject of its own? What distinguishes it from economics, history and politics? ''Foundationalists'' square off on this question against ''anti-foundationalists''. The first believe that among people who study international affairs some ''foundation'' is needed -- a rough agreement about how the world works. The ''anti-foundationalists'' are sceptical about whether any theory of international relations can ever be objective: they all serve somebody's interest. Other articles in the book show how ''global'' issues -- the environment, feminism, moral questions as well as international economics -- are reshaping <font size=-1>IR</font>.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="13,2"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>ATION</font> S<font size=-1>TATE</font><br>By Kenichi Ohmae. <br><i>HarperCollins; 224 pages; 16.99.</i> <i>Free Press; $24.50</i><br>
<a href="2ex13-2.html">Extract</a> | <a href="2jb13-2.html">Jacket Copy</a> | <a href="2bt13-2.html">Biography</a></p>
</td></tr></table>
<a name="13,3"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>ATION-</font>S<font size=-1>TATE</font><br>By Jean-Marie Guhenno; translated by Victoria Elliott. <br><i>University of Minnesota Press; 160 pages; $19.95</i><br>
<a href="2ex13-3.html">Extract</a> | <a href="2jb13-3.html">Jacket Copy</a> | <a href="2bt13-3.html">Biography</a></p>
WHAT, besides a hyphen, distinguishes these essays? Both authors are practitioners more than theorists. Kenichi Ohmae worked for a management consultancy; Jean-Marie Guhenno has been France's envoy to the Western European Union. Neither is wholly successful at knitting in politics and economics with international relations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Ohmae describes, with some exaggeration, the extent of ''globalisation'' in economics and business. Easier travel, swifter moving capital, internationalised companies and ever wider information networks are creating, he argues, a ''borderless world'' without nation-states. But are they? Even Mr Ohmae seems unsure. Smaller, ''regional states'' are springing up, he says: frontier-straddling economic zones. Though packed with useful figures, his book lacks perspective on the rise of the modern state and is too sweeping about its early demise.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Guhenno's book contains almost no figures but has a firmer historical grasp. The nation-state and its offspring, liberal democracy, are under pressure, Mr Guhenno believes: both from without, because of the globalisation of information; and from within, because of the rise of ethnic movements.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The state has always posed a problem for liberals. How to reconcile their vision of society as a set of individuals rationally calculating their self-interest with acceptance of majority rule, obedience to law and loyalty to nation? Classically, the answer was that ''social virtues'' were in everyone's interest and that their natural expression was the state. But how true is that when money and people can go where they please in search of profit or jobs, and when the state's economic role is under increasing attack?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This book's original title, ''La Fin de la Dmocratie'', suggested too gloomy an answer. In the English version, the author corrects his fire: familiar democratic institutions will weaken as nation-states do; what matters is the preservation of democratic values such as liberty and tolerance, though Mr Guhenno is not notably clear how that should happen.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="13,4"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE </font>A<font size=-1>MBIGUITIES OF </font>P<font size=-1>OWER: </font>B<font size=-1>RITISH </font>F<font size=-1>OREIGN </font>P<font size=-1>OLICY SINCE 1945</font><br>By Mark Curtis. <br><i>Zed Books; 256 pages; 14.95 and $25</i><br>
<a href="2ex13-4.html">Extract</a> | <a href="2jb13-4.html">Jacket Copy</a> | <a href="2bt13-4.html">Biography</a></p>
THIS radical view of British foreign policy by a former researcher at the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London asserts that Britain was ''a major, systematic contributor to much of the world's suffering and horrors'' over the past half century. Britain has, according to Mark Curtis, relentlessly pursued its national interests under the guise of principle, exploiting poor countries and abetting horrible third-world wars, often as a subservient ally of America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many readers will decide without further ado to give this book a miss. Yet despite its over-condemnatory tone, it is a good example of something foreign-policy makers must take growing account of: a large, well-informed and argumentative body of people demanding more morality in diplomacy. The need to reconcile <i>raison d'tat</i> and moral principle when justifying foreign policies is hardly new. But during the cold war, when ideological conflict blanketed all, western governments often let that skill slip. For results, you need look no further than western policy towards Bosnia.
</td></tr></table>
<a name="13,5"><br></a>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<hr size=5 width=170 align=left>R<font size=-1>ETHINKING </font>I<font size=-1>NTERNATIONAL </font>R<font size=-1>ELATIONS</font><br>By Fred Halliday.<br><i> Macmillan; 304 pages; 37.50</i><br>
<a href="2ex13-5.html">Extract</a> | <a href="2jb13-5.html">Jacket Copy</a> | <a href="2bt13-5.html">Biography</a></p>
THIS useful book describes some of the main academic approaches to international relations: good old (mainly British) empiricism -- roughly the view that understanding world politics requires no special theory of its own, just masses of reading, a few languages if possible and lots of examples; American ''behaviouralism'', a rather forlorn-looking effort to gain insight by international data-crunching and by applying lessons from abstract systems such as game theory; ''neo-realism'', a more economic version of the old notion of ''the anarchy of states'' by which peace or war is a matter of the balance of power; and historical materialism, a Marxist cousin of realism, which stresses class or ideological friction as the source of world conflict.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fred Halliday goes on to examine the actors other than states that are playing an increasing part on the world stage, including, for example, women's organisations. This leads him to ''value'' questions in world politics, and the growing attention they get.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After pondering how most <font size=-1>IR</font> experts failed to predict the end of the cold war, the book suggests new lines of research. These include: does having an economic common denominator -- free-market capitalism -- make peace and security among states more or less likely? How might a small number of widely accepted though not always similarly defined public ''virtues'' -- loyalty, identity, security, equality and freedom -- become the basis of ''legitimate moral debate'' among nations?
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
