<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000279-B026-259</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev2/2rt14/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113190340 text/html 6596
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:59:45 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:02 GMT
Content-length: 6411
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Playful</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr14.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Shakespeare on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Playful</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex14-1.html">R<font size=-1>OMEO</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> J<font size=-1>ULIET</font></a> &nbsp Attica Cybernetics. <br>
<li><a href="2ex14-2.html">M<font size=-1>ACBETH</font></a> &nbsp Attica Cybernetics. <br>
</ul>
<p>AS HE might have put it: ''What's in a name? That which we call a play By any other name would please as much.'' Many will scoff at the notion that a play by Shakespeare on a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> could rival the enjoyment of sitting on a plush seat in a hushed theatre to watch it performed by the Royal Shakespeare Company (<font size=-1>RSC</font>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In some senses (literally as well as figuratively) the sceptics are right. But, before they condemn these two <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s out of hand, they might reflect upon the fact that the appreciation of Shakespeare's poetry has already been through many phases, all of which say much about the lives and times of the audience.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The plays were written in Elizabethan England, where all roles were played by males. Actors had to shout to be heard above rowdy spectators who behaved like modern soccer fans. Food was sold during performances, people wore large hats, there were no intervals and the stench that came from tight standing crowds of unwashed people was a powerful part of the sensory experience. (Elizabeth I, who had a reputation for fastidiousness, was said by a contemporary to take a bath once a month, whether she needed it or not.) Plays were staged in broad daylight and, England being England, drizzle often soaked the audience.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, Shakespeare's words needed to entertain a much less attentive audience. As Jonathan Miller, a 20th-century Renaissance man, notes on the ''Romeo and Juliet'' <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>, the poetry was part of a complex experience in which the listeners took what they could from the jumble of senses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In this spirit of invention, Shakespeare on these <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s satisfies some senses and not others. One smashing success is the way the presentation of text is accompanied by a fine Shakespearean actor reading it. Sir Anthony Quayle is the voice of Macbeth, Albert Finney is Romeo and Claire Bloom is Juliet. Let the disks spin on and the listener-viewer is soon absorbed in the lyricism of the lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The<i> </i>visual aspects are less successful. Only snatches of past performances of the plays are provided, and even the fastest machines cannot yet smooth out the jerky pictures. Nonetheless, a virtue of the video images is the chance to hear a different reading of the same text, and to glimpse some of the more memorable recent renditions of great scenes. Jonathan Pryce's Macbeth from a 1986 performance and Jane Lapotaire's portrayal of Lady Macbeth from a 1983 performance are powerful, albeit too brief. Celia Johnson's playing of the nurse in ''Romeo and Juliet'' is pure gold. The <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s sound archives yield up the voices of Sir John Gielgud and Judi Dench, and its video archives even offer two scenes from an adaptation of ''Macbeth'' in Zulu in 1972.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The presentation of a fully searchable text and the highest quality audio performances is reason enough to applaud. For those who get easily lost in convoluted plots, there is help from a clever timeline and brief summaries of scenes. Difficult words and phrases are highlighted so that a click of the mouse explains all those uncertain meanings: what is ''to flear'', and is it good to be told that ''you kiss by th'book''? Follow the mouse and the meanings become clear. It is a valuable service. As the expert commentary explains, Shakespeare's vocabulary of 34,000 words is twice that of an educated modern person. He invented more English words than anybody else who ever lived.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another virtue of the new technology is the ability it gives users to draw on far more specialist commentary than is available even in the <font size=-1>RSC</font>'s excellent theatre programmes. The main themes are highlighted (and linked directly to the text and audio). Germaine Greer discusses the bawdy aspects of ''Romeo and Juliet'', Peggy Ashcroft fate in ''Romeo and Juliet'', Sinead Cusack kingship in ''Macbeth''. There is expert commentary on the contradictions in the timing in act five of ''Romeo and Juliet''. Ronald Harwood explores Shakespeare's era, Robert MacNeil discusses the different use of language, and Robert Hall gives a brief rendition of how the poetry would have sounded in Elizabethan times.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Users are told about sets and scenery, and even musical adaptations. There are clips from both Tchaikovsky's and Berlioz's ''Romeo and Juliet'' and from Verdi's ''Macbeth''. Critical comments on the plays, from Dryden to the <i>Guardian</i>, are available. Click on a character and it is possible to compare past performances.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the technology improves, much more can be expected. One American computer company has already published ''Romeo and Juliet'', ''Macbeth'' and ''A Midsummer Night's Dream'' on an interactive <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> so that you can choose a part to play. Can multimedia Valentine's Day cards be far away?
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
