<html><head><title>Back to the surfing board</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<img src="2gr15.gif" alt="review graphic">
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Making a CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Back to the surfing board</h2>
<p><b>Book writers have to forget almost all they know when they write a CD-ROM</b></p>
<ul>
</ul>
<p>SEDITIOUS books get burnt, their authors gain notoriety. Seditious <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, once they start to appear, will have to be melted -- but who will be seen as mad, bad and dangerous to know? For whereas most books are written by lone individuals, <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, like films or <font size=-1>TV</font> programmes, are complex collaborations. <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are indeed written. They may even have authors. But there is a big difference. Writing a book is like creating a wave you can surf on; writing a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is more like making a box of chocolates.
Open a book to any page, read a few sentences, turn back a few pages, read a bit more -- most books are not written to be read in this way. Prose is intrinsically linear; a good book carries the reader forward on the crest of the words. Sometimes the speed might be scary, the power almost overwhelming, but at the end the reader lands safely on the beach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Admittedly, some books are not designed to be read straight through. For example, ''Who's Who'', dictionaries, encyclopedias, almanacs, restaurant guides and even cookery books are stuffed with information that is meant to be dipped in and out of. These non-linear books make terrific <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s. Searching and cross-referencing can be done efficiently; vast stacks of information can be trawled. After all, the first edition of the ''Oxford English Dictionary'' was more than 15 gigantic volumes but the whole thing fits on one <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>. But producing <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s for information search-and-retrieval is by now old hat. Multimedia enthusiasts are far more ambitious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They dream of a multi-level, interactive multimedia experience -- a combination of education and play analogous to a good science museum, with displays of information alongside buttons to press and levers to pull. Video clips jostle with stills, text vies with voice-overs -- it will be better than a book, a film or an exhibition. The whole family will be able to appreciate it -- there will be something for everyone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just as ''Dungeons and Dragons'', a role-playing fantasy game, transforms ''The Lord of the Rings'' into an interactive and endlessly varying adventure beyond the boundaries of Tolkein's pages, a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> should be far beyond a book -- and it should be imaginative, flexible and varied to boot. At its best, a trip through a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> will be different each time. For the children, the interactivity must be like a game. For the grown-ups, a database of further information must be readily accessible. For the writers of <font size=-1>CD-ROMs</font>, these demands pose particular difficulties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So writing a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is very different from writing a book, play, film, radio broadcast or television show. First, <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are humongous -- witness the <font size=-1>OED</font> or the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> of the ''Dictionary of National Biography'' that is now in the works. There is no point in their being only half full. Second, unlike <font size=-1>CD-ROMs</font>, all the monomedia are linear. The advent of video means that films can be rewound and favourite scenes watched again and again, but only weirdos skip about systematically. Admittedly, some types of books, sophisticated textbooks, for instance, are constructed to be modular. But these are neither interactive nor multi-level. And they are driven by text: photographs, drawings, graphs and tables are supplementary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even media that do not explicitly include written words may have an underlying textual basis. For a play or a film, it is a script or a screenplay. In a play, actors deliver the words to the audience, while in a film the words (and actions) are mediated through cameras. Writing a play, however, consists of writing a script. This is evidently different from writing a book -- a script is essentially dialogue. Radio plays are a similar exercise. But some radio programmes are strings of interviews linked together. These are interesting because they are written backwards -- that is, after the interviews have taken place. When the interviewer returns to the studio and listens to the tapes, the script is built so that the interviewer will appear to ask the right leading questions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> combines all these kinds of writing and adds some of its own. <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s require text at several different stages, each aimed at a different audience. If a disk has a theme -- violin music, say, or evolution -- then the team of researchers, designers and programmers will probably not know much about it. So the writer's first job is to structure and explain all of the information that needs to be included in order that the production team, especially the designers, can do their bit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each portion of the subject matter -- Beethoven's violin concerto, or the voyage of the <i>Beagle</i> -- must be as self-contained as possible. After all, the eventual user of the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> might happen on it from any of a number of directions. The writer, then, must distil the information into brief, descriptive capsules. Each capsule must include a list of ingredients -- which pictures, whose voices -- and instructions on how the ingredients could be mixed together to the greatest advantage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The next stage of <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> construction depends much more on the production team than on the writer. On many <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s the structure of the material provided by the writer is translated into an architectural metaphor of some kind; much of the designers' work is the construction of this imaginary space. Then, as if planning an exhibition, the designers must chart the details of what to animate, what to film, who to interview, how to arrange the information in the space they have built and so on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, the programmers must decide how to engineer the disk so that parts of it are properly interactive and to try to ensure that each time the user enters the experience is different -- for instance, which corners must contain treasures to be discovered only one time out of three. During this process, the writer becomes a consultant -- yes, a portrait of Beethoven will be useful, no, Darwin did not suddenly think of evolution while on the Galapagos Islands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, the writer is again called on to write. This time, the job is to provide the text that will actually appear. Such text falls into two parts: words to go with the work of the designers, and the database of further information. The database is easy to handle. It will often consist of glossaries, lists for further reading, larger chunks of text from the listed books, and short articles by the writer. The programmes link all these together so that the user can find information easily.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is the writing of the words for the screen that is hardest for the author. In principle, these passages could be quite long. After all, the user can scroll through any text provided. But this is not deemed good <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> practice -- the other media hold centre screen. So the text must be short and snappy, like the captions under the chocolates in a large fancy box. For the writer, this can all be rather frustrating. Like the chocolates, in the end, the taste and the texture matter more than the words.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
