<html><head><title>Neva had it so good</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Peter's Russian capital</b></p>
<h2>Neva had it so good</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex16-1.html">S<font size=-1>T</font> P<font size=-1>ETERSBURG</font>: A C<font size=-1>ULTURAL</font> H<font size=-1>ISTORY</font></a> &nbsp By Solomon Volkov. <br>
</ul>
<p>ALTHOUGH Stalin thought Peter the Great too gentle a ruler, the emperor had enough cruelty in him for most tastes. He tortured his own son for disloyalty, beheaded rebels, and enjoyed practising dentistry on his courtiers. A nobler side of his personality came out in his drive to modernise Russia. He promoted civil servants on merit, frightened the church and authorised a first newspaper. His cruelty and his grandeur came together in the most enduring of his projects, the creation of a new, modern capital city on a hitherto bare portion of the Baltic coast, a fantastic endeavour in those, or any, times.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peter found Moscow pokey and mired in Tatar antiquity. He wanted an airy place of canals and perspectives. An admirer of Amsterdam, he gave his own creation a Dutch name: Sankt-Peterburg. The site was chosen in 1702. The main work began seven years later and by 1725 the city had more than 40,000 inhabitants, an eighth of Russia's urban population. Below ground lay perhaps three times as many corpses -- of the peasants conscripted to build the new capital without shelter, food or tools.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps because it was struck off the brain of a single man, St Petersburg seemed to retain within it something of the quality of an imagined, or imaginary, city. The writers and artists who gathered there, whether because it was Russia's capital or because it was stylish and beautiful, made St Petersburg a theme as well as a home, finding in it an inexhaustible source of material and metaphor. Across a long, gold-and-silver century that can for convenience be dated from Pushkin's poem, ''The Bronze Horseman'', in 1833 to Shostakovich's Seventh Symphony in 1941, the greatest works of the St Petersburg artists were accretions to a Petrine myth. Nikolai Gogol breathed over the city his nightmare of fog and darkness. Anna Akhmatova mourned it as a martyred place of literally unspeakable suffering. Dostoyevsky, Tchaikovsky, Rimsky-Korsakov, Blok, Diaghilev and Mandelstam added their voices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Volkov wills into being a heroic narrative, a ''Petersburg mythos'', that contains the city and its great artists but exists independently of them. If he does not quite succeed, it scarcely matters. This is a rich and enjoyable work that need be no more than the sum of its parts. A musicologist and child of St Petersburg himself, Mr Volkov brings to the world he describes not just personal knowledge and affection but an extraordinary depth of secondary characters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among them may be glimpsed Daniil Yuvachev, a playwright who insists he is a wizard, drinks milk at home only when the doors and windows have been shut tight and the cracks stuffed with cotton, and who bows to old lamp-posts because Pushkin might have looked on them; or Ivan Sollertinsky, a musicologist fluent in at least 32 languages who keeps his diary in Sanskrit and knows Shakespeare, Pushkin, Gogol, Aristotle and Plato by heart; or Vasilik Gnedov, a futurist ''notorious for his 'Poem of the End', which consisted of a single sharp circular movement of the arm''; or Sergei Dovlatov, a writer who never uses two words starting with the same letter in the same sentence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 20th century presents problems, reflecting how far Mr Volkov has written less a cultural history of St Petersburg than a history of St Petersburg culture. The horrors of Stalinist oppression and Nazi siege are refracted through wondrous sensibilities, such as those of Akhmatova and Mandelstam, that can find even in the death of millions inspiration for poems of perverse beauty. You end up half-wanting to have been there, which cannot be right at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the end, St Petersburg culture has emigrated to America with Balanchine, Baryshnikov, Brodsky and the author. St Petersburg's is a great tale that has grown, one senses, with the telling: and thanks to Mr Volkov it has grown, marvellously, a little bit more.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
