<html><head><title>Behind the ears</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<p><b>Europe's gypsies</b></p>
<h2>Behind the ears</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="2ex8-1.html">B<font size=-1>URY</font> M<font size=-1>E</font> S<font size=-1>TANDING</font>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>YPSIES</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THEIR</font> J<font size=-1>OURNEY</font></a> &nbsp By Isabel Fonseca. <br>
</ul>
<p>WHEN Isabel Fonseca spent several weeks in a shack on the outskirts of Tirana as the guest of Albanian gypsies, she found that the local rules of hospitality required someone else to wash her. Two daughters-in-law, the household's <i>bonnes--tout-faire</i>, scrubbed her down with a chip from a ''Parmesan glacier'' of rough soap. The bar she had prudently brought along with her was sceptically eyed like a ''palm-top computer'' and stayed in its wrapping.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The soap story is one of many in this intriguing book which anyone who would like to know more about Europe's 8m gypsies will want to read. Ms Fonseca travelled in Albania, Romania, Bulgaria, Slovakia, Moldova, Poland and Germany. She met a variety of groups including the uprooted, glue-sniffing street kids of Sofia and the proud <i>Kalderash</i> of Transylvania, whose men trade second-hand cars and whose women plait their hair with gold Habsburg coins.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book details exploitation<i> </i>in the past -- gypsies were enslaved in early 19th-century Romania -- as well as poverty and harrassment in the present. In Slovakia the average gypsy male dies before 40 and not long ago Romani-speaking children were put into schools for the backward or packed off to Christian orphanages. In many places gypsies are still not safe from attack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The popular image is not all myth, Ms Fonseca reports. Gypsies feud, marry off children, steal potatoes and use window-frames for firewood. At gypsy conferences the author notes a dilemma. Are gypsies a nation, the Roma, or something special and elusive? Should they defend national rights or their hard-to-define otherness? Without reaching hard conclusions, this book is reasonably optimistic: with a resilient culture, entrepreneurial flair and disregard for rules, gypsies may be adapting better on Europe's post-communist frontier than some of their more dispirited countrymen.
</p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p><p>
<i>&#169; Copyright 1995 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
