<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top>

</td></tr></table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/
instrap.gif"></td><td>
<br>
<h2>What the world is reading</h2>

<p>THESE bestseller lists dramatise the hold of television on the popular imagination in the United States and Japan. "Say That You Love Me" , number ten on the Japanese fiction list, is a novel adapted from a television programme. The ruminations of a baseball hero, number five on the Japanese non-fiction list, appeared earlier as a series of television chats. The top non-fiction book in Japan sells because the author, Hitoshi Matsumoto, appears almost every day in the nation's living rooms.</p>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The influence of broadcasting generally is even more pronounced on the American non-fiction list. Howard Stern, the writer of the top seller, hosts a radio talk show. Charles Kuralt, at number three, is an avuncular television reporter who travels to the oddest corners of America to meet the oddest people. David Brinkley, whose autobiography stands at number six, is a venerable political pundit whose languid television manner belies a sharp tongue. Ellen DeGeneres is a comedienne who has achieved celebrity status through television stardom.
</p>


