<html><head><title>SHORT NOT TALL STORIES</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-5.jpg"><img src="2cs2-5.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>HORT</font> <font size=-1>NOT</font> T<font size=-1>ALL</font> S<font size=-1>TORIES</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Gomolemo Mokae. <br><i>Key Publications; 134 pages; 35.99 rand.</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb2-5.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="2bt2-5.html">Biography</a></p>
<p><b>Extract</b></p>
<p>
<p>A Warm Reception<p>
<p>As he came to, it dawned on him that the dream could not approximate the nightmare of his cold, conscious reality.<p>
<p>Actually, the terrifying dream had become a regular, nocturnal feature, and was the type which psychoanalysts had long identified as part of the symptoms complex of harassed, haunted souls like himself.<p>
<p>You know the type: you are frantically running away from a bloodhungry horde of Neanderthals bearing blood-curdling, gut-wrenching clubs . You look back and they are catching up on you, literally breathing down your neck; the halitosis a harrowing foretaste of things to come. You come to the edge of a cliff and, before you, there is an abysmal valley. You jump and, just as you are about to hit the ground, you are jolted into consciousness.<p>
<p>A deep sigh of relief, for it was just a dream!<p>
<p>However, as he wiped the cobwebs from his eyes with the palm of his hand and searched for a fag stub, he could not feel too relieved.<p>
<p>He was alive to the fact that nothing, but nothing, could make the mouth drier, the heart gallop faster, teeth gnash harder, and the spine tingle more, than his nightmarish reality.<p>
<p>And that, he could not awake from.<p>
<p>Not because of the overwhelming, ubiquitous odour of unwashed bodies, which was the order of the day and night. Day in, day out.<p>
<p>Not because of the bare bricks, the mouldy mortar, the chilly grills, or the soggy slab. Nor the melancholic, funereal hymn-singing by ruthless murderers, rapists and tricksters, who had found Jesus just as the noose was about to find them.<p>
<p>Nor the inhospitable inhabitants of this bowel of drooping dreams and supine, spent spirits; the lice, mice and inveterate criminals who, with their very lives, had opted to dice.<p>
<p>No, he ruminated, this much, however mildewy, he could master.<p>
<p>Something else, more bewildering, more blistering, sought to wilt his will.<p>
<p>'How is Cain this morning? Ready to break the fast, I suppose?' the rotund, portly figure above him enquired, flaunting his rotten teeth as he grinned.<p>
<p>Startled, he wondered why he had not heard the jarring clanking of keys and banging of grills which he had come to associate with the warder's entrance.<p>
<p>Perhaps he had been deeply lost in thoughts.<p>
<p>'Not quite a la carte, I agree; but still nourishing, all the same!' the warder retorted to the prisoner's protesting, cynical look after he had shoved the ritual special treat in his direction.<p>
<p>The treat was a paltry, pallid plate of porridge, an almost desiccated morsel of meat, and a slimy solution whose attempt to pass for gravy was a damp, watery squib.<p>
<p>'Not quite a 'la carte'?' the prisoner smiled as he silently pondered upon the warder's description. 'Though almost, not quite from the sewer; if you ask me!' he argued inwardly.<p>
<p>Reflected in the bowl, the prisoner saw the montage of events leading to his bizarre association with the warder; a relationship which had taken root as soon as the latter had sighted his not so inconsiderable purse.<p>
<p>More a relationship of mutual abuse than commensalism, the prisoner reckoned.<p>
<p>'A stout lout who chanced upon clout in the prison's service!' he would sometimes swear at the warder when he angered him, which was too often.<p>
<p>However, like cow dung, which can redeem itself as fertilizer, the warder had his own redeeming qualities too.<p>
<p>'You've been looking this gift horse in the mouth for far too long!' boomed the warder's voice, and the prisoner was awoken from his reverie by his Pickwickian wheeze as he bent down to retrieve the bowl<p>
<p>The hare shall always outsprint the elephant. The prisoner beat him to the bowl, and immediately proceeded to stuff the gift foal into his mouth.<p>
<p>In his spell in the dungeon, he had learnt at least one thing: you have to count, and cherish your blessings.<p>
<p></p>

<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
