<html><head><title>THE CHANGE OF SEASONS</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-6.jpg"><img src="2cs2-6.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>EASONS</font><br>
</h2>
<p>Edited by Andries Walter Oliphant. <br><i>Cosaw; 188 pages; 29.99 rand</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb2-6.html">Jacket Copy</a></p>
<p><b>Extract</b></p>
<p>
<p>The Differences - Ivan Vladislavic<p>
<p>No one who visits City Deep, the congested heart of High Hope Province, can fail to notice the mine-dumps that are the waste products of its prosperity. The citizens are divided on the merits of these historic tailings: some say they contribute to the rough-and-ready atmosphere which is part of the city's charm, and want them preserved for future generations; others say they are dirty and ugly, and encourage the City Council to demolish them, or else to grow grass over them in the hope that this will make them look like hills.<p>
<p>Scattered among the run-of-the-mine dumps are a few of an unusual origin. These are greatly admired by the advocates of preservation, and equally loathed by their opponents, because they are made entirely of metal. If you look closely you can tell that this metal was piled there in pieces once, but now it is all rusted together into a lumpy conglomerate. Naturally, nothing will grow on these dumps. They are riddled with holes, and in the windy months they announce their presence in a discordant music of howls and whistles. Apparently they also boom like drums when you walk upon them, although you do so at your own risk, as the Council's signs insist.<p>
<p>Ask the people of City Deep where these metal objects come from and you will hear that they are doodads cast off by the mines and factories. But the truth is that the dumps are the monumental remains of the Differences, a dimly remembered wave of civil disorders that swept through High Hope Province at the turn of the century.<p>
<p>It all began with a metalworker named Blikslager, who owned a foundry and retail outlet in Twist Street, where the Secret Police now have their Headquarters. It began, you see, with the intricacics of the everyday, as such things do.<p>
<p>Blikslager produced all kinds of metal goods - from a tin pot to a bag of nails, as they say. But like his father and his grandfather before him, he specialized in the manufacture of bells. He cast bells in every shape and size. He made cowbells, dinner-bells and school-bells. He made church-bells - small ones for the altar and large ones for the steeple. He even made sleigh-bells, although there was no demand for them at all (snow had not fallen in High Hope Province in living memory).<p>
<p></p>

<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
