<html><head><title>THE ALEXANDRA TALES</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-3.jpg"><img src="2cs2-3.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>LEXANDRA</font> T<font size=-1>ALES</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Isaac Mogotsi. <br><i>Ravan Press; 172 pages; 29.64 rand.</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb2-3.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="2bt2-3.html">Biography</a></p>
<p><b>Extract</b></p>
<p>
<p>Dear Mother,<p>
<p>It has taken me more than fifteen years to decide to write these memoirs. In them I shall try to tell you about the anger, the frustrations, the dangers, the risks and the challenges of growing up without my biological mother.<p>
<p>Many have been the sleepless nights I have spent thinking about you.<p>
<p>It is a long, long time since we saw each other. I have grown up a motherless child, although you are still alive. I wonder if you would still see your son in me. I would not be able to recognise you.<p>
<p>As you well know, I am now thirty years of age. These have been thirty long years without the warmth, care and solace of a mother.<p>
<p>I hope that my monologue, in the form of these memoirs, will result in our dialogue. You will never know the agonies I went through in deciding their form, let alone content.<p>
<p>This is not the first time I have attempted to communicate my thoughts and feelings to you. A long time ago, when I was still a small boy, I wrote you letters. Although my message remains basically the same, those letters were cruder. In them I insulted you, cursed you and even renounced you. I tried to show you the bitterness I felt. It is a devastating blow for a young boy to realise that a parent is uncaring.<p>
<p>I never sent you those letters. I wrote them secretly, without the knowledge of my family. I wrote them in the dead of the night, when I was sure that no one would see me.<p>
<p>Instead of relieving my sense of frustration, those letters left me yearning even more for your presence, your touch, your look, your tenderness, even your rebuke.<p>
<p>You should regret that I have lost the letters. They were written with the candour and simplicity of a child, and represented a daily account of my life.<p>
<p>Parents, like neighbours, are not chosen. They are destined. So whatever I may think about you in anger, you are my mother and will always remain so.<p>
<p>That I was conceived, that I was born, that I am, I owe to you, as to my father. For that you deserve my eternal gratitude. No other woman was capable of that particular act of procreation.<p>
<p></p>

<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
