<html><head><title>THE END OF THE NATION STATE</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl13-2.jpg"><img src="2cs13-2.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>ND</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>ATION</font> S<font size=-1>TATE</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Kenichi Ohmae. <br><i>HarperCollins; 224 pages; 16.99.</i> <i>Free Press; $24.50</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb13-2.html">Jacket Copy</a></p><p><b>Biography</b></p>
<p>KENICHI OHMAE, a former Senior Partner of McKinsey &amp; Company, has counseled major corporations and governments on their international strategies and operations for 20 years. Widely recognized as one of today's top business gurus, he is the author of the highly acclaimed Triad Power (The Free Press, 1985) and The Borderless World (1990). He lives in Tokyo.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
