<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>UMMONS</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Peter Lovesey. <br><i>Mysterious Press; 359 pages; $21.95</i>. <i>Little, Brown; 15.99.</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb1-7.html">Jacket Copy</a></p><p><b>Biography</b></p>
<p>PETER LOVESEY, recent chairman of Britain s Crime Writers Association, is one of the most beloved names in mystery fiction. Creator of the Sergeant Cribb and Constable Thackeray Victorian crime novels and the "Bertie" suspense series, Lovesey has won both a Silver Dagger and Gold Dagger Award. He took the prized Anthony Award for best mystery with The Last Detective, the book that introduced Peter Diamond. Lovesey lives near Bath, England.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
