<html><head><title>L IS FOR LAWLESS</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl1-4.jpg"><img src="2cs1-4.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>L <font size=-1>IS</font> <font size=-1>FOR</font> L<font size=-1>AWLESS</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Sue Grafton. <br><i>Henry Holt; 290 pages; $24.</i> <i>Macmillan; 15.99.</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt1-4.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>'I don't mean to bitch, but in the future I intend to hesitate before I do a favor for a friend of a friend. Never have I taken on such a load of grief. At the outset, it all seemed so innocent. I swear there's no way I could have guessed what was coming down . . .'<p>
<p>It was a Thursday in November, the week before Thanksgiving, when Californian PI Kinsey Millhone first heard the sad story of Johnny Lee. The World War II fighter pilot had died a few months before and his grandson Bucky was trying to claim military funeral benefits. Except none of the authorities have any record of Fighter J. Lee. A case of mistaken identity? Or, as his son Chester argues, was the old man once a US spy? Perhaps Kinsey could make a few calls, straighten things out?<p>
<p>Kinsey has little to go on - until she hears Johnny's apartment has been broken into and ransacked. In the debris Chester and Bucky have uncovered a hidden safe. And in that safe is a mysterious key marked LAWLESS . . .<p>
<p>That night, Kinsey pops out for some milk - and ends up on a plane to Dallas, on the trail of the dark stranger she sees leaving Lee's empty apartment. With little money, no clean clothes, and a suspicious hotel supervisor on her back, she's living on her wits. Then she finds herself pursued by a fire-raising psychopath bearing a forty-year-old grudge . . .<p>
<p>And on top of that she's got to get home fast for a very important wedding . . .<p>
<p>With L is for Lawless Sue Grafton nears the halfway point of her dazzling alphabet of crime. The twelfth mystery in a compulsively addictive series is a thrilling rollercoaster ride through Texas and Kentucky on the trail of long-buried treasure and desperate hard men.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
