<html><head><title>SMOKE</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl1-8.jpg"><img src="2cs1-8.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>MOKE</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Donald E. Westlake. <br><i>Mysterious Press; 454 pages $21.95</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt1-8.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>SURGEON GENERAS WARNING:<p>
<p>Reading Donald E. Westlake may lead to shortness of breath, prolonged chortles, outbreaks of hysterical laughter, and sudden, drop-dead surprises.<p>
<p>Donald E. Westlake, master of the comic caper, is back - with a novel so outrageous it ought to be illegal.<p>
<p>SMOKE<p>
<p>There was nothing secondhand about this: Freddie Urban Noon broke into a cancer research lab - where two scientists were getting paid big money by the American Tobacco Research Institute to prove that smoking is good for you. By the end of the night the researchers, the Institute, and Freddie himself were in a whole lot of trouble. Freddie Urban Noon was still a burglar, a liar, and a gentleman; but now he had one more claim to fame: He was an invisible man.<p>
<p>It's not an easy condition. Yet, for a burglar, it does have its advantages - if you can figure out a way to pocket the loot when you're walking around naked. An invisible man could also become the greatest spy in history - just ask the tobacco magnates once they have a whiff of the results of Freddie's experiment. Most of all, invisibility could be worth millions - a fact not lost on a crooked New York cop with dollar signs in his eyes and grand larceny in his heart.<p>
<p>Suddenly, everyone wants to get a glimpse of Freddie: good guys, bad guys, even Freddie's girlfriend, Peg, who is getting tired of pulling off heists and then making love to someone she can't see. But Freddie doesn't dare show his face, his shadow, or even so much as his underware. Because Freddie Noon has gotten a taste of invisibility - and he can't quit now.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
