</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ERMAIDS</font> S<font size=-1>INGING</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Val McDermid. <br><i>HarperCollins; 289 pages; 9.99.</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt1-5.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>A serial killer is on the loose in the northern city of Bradfield. Four men have been brutally killed by savage knife wounds. In each case, the men have been mutilated and tortured, though the mutilations are not identical and nothing obvious appears to connect the victims.<p>
<p>Fear grips the city; no man feels safe. Clinical psychologist Tony Hill is brought in to profile the killer, to work alongside Detective Inspector Carol Jordan. A man with more than enough problems of his own, Tony himself becomes embroiled in a battle of wits and wills where he has to use every ounce of his professional skill and personal nerve to survive.<p>
<p>The Mermaids Singing is a tense psychological thriller that explores the tormented world of a serial killer unlike any the world of fiction has ever seen.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
