<html><head><title>SHORT NOT TALL STORIES</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-5.jpg"><img src="2cs2-5.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>S<font size=-1>HORT</font> <font size=-1>NOT</font> T<font size=-1>ALL</font> S<font size=-1>TORIES</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Gomolemo Mokae. <br><i>Key Publications; 134 pages; 35.99 rand.</i></p>
<p><a href="2jb2-5.html">Jacket Copy</a></p><p><b>Biography</b></p>
<p>Gomolemo Mokae is a son of a retired Methodist Church Minister. His father was frequently transferred by the Church from one mission station to another, and this is how Mokae came to be born in Ga-Mokopane (near PP Rust) and grow up in Makapanstat, Ga-Marishane (Sekhukhuneland), Warrnbaths, Nylstroom and Ga-Rpnkuwe.<p>
<p>He matriculated at Mmakau's (near Ga-Rankuwa) Tsogo High School and enrolled for an MB.ChB degree with the University of Natal Medical School in 1982. He qualified as a medical doctor in 1987 and is presently running a private practice in Ga-Rankuwa (Pretoria).<p>
<p>On the literary front, Mokae is a recipient of the 'African Achiever's Award' from Ekyaya Promotions. He has been a finalist for the ' VO Betrams Literary Award' with the poetry anthology Purgatory Rhymes and was the Amstel 'Playwright of the Year' in 1993 with the play The Way the Cookie Crumbles. Recently an excerpt from one of the stories in this collection, Graveyard Tales, was one of the winners of a short story competition run by the National Arts Coalition.<p>
<p>Mokae has had short stories published in 'Tribute' and the BBC 'Focus in Africa' magazine. Poems have been published in 'Echo', 'Imprint', 'AWA Collection' and 'Soundings'.<p>
<p>Politically, Mokae has had a long association with the Azanian People's Organisation (AZAPO). He has served as AZAPO's Transvaal Vice-President, Secretary for Education and Publicity and Information Secretary.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
