<html><head><title>THE CHANGE OF SEASONS</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-6.jpg"><img src="2cs2-6.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>HANGE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>EASONS</font><br>
</h2>
<p>Edited by Andries Walter Oliphant. <br><i>Cosaw; 188 pages; 29.99 rand</i></p>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>In celebration of the changes brought about in South Africa, in 1994 The National Arts Coalition and the Bartel Arts Trust organised country-wide Festivals of Laughter. This included sponsoring a literature contest which invited writers to shake off the dead weight of the old by spreading some gaiety amid all the gloom and self-serving oratory of politicians.<p>
<p>The stories collected here were the finalists in this contest. It is a collection in which writers simultaneously engage the present and bid farewell to the past as they anticipate the future. From this point there can be no turning back.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
