<html><head><title>THE SMELL OF APPLES</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl2-4.jpg"><img src="2cs2-4.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>MELL</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>PPLES</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Mark Behr. <br><i>Abacus. 200 pages; 60.99 rand.</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt2-4.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>It was the visit of Mr Smith that began the changes. Just before the holidays, in the last weeks of 1973, he came to stay at the house in Cape Town, bringing with him stories of war in far-away countries and leaving gifts that only Marnus didn't want.<p>
<p>Marnus was eleven then. Proud to be his father's son, terrified he wouldn't fulfil the expectations of an elite Afrikaner family, he spends his time waiting to grow up, hanging out with his best friend Frikkie and cursing his know-all sister. His father Johan was the youngest ever Major-General in the South African Defence Force, setting the trend of the Erasmus family as achievers; born to rule the land they consider their own, secure in the own unquestioned superiority.<p>
<p>But Mr Smith - Mr Smith made things different. Johan said he was a General from Chile, and that his visit was to be kept a secret. All Marnus knew was that after he left everything had changed, a vertiginous and irrevocable shift had taken place - in his life, his values, his very understanding of all he held dear ...<p>
<p>The Smell of Apples is an understated timebomb of a novel, an indictment of apartheid's twisted logic made breathtakingly savage through its very subtlety. Brilliantly juxtaposing the clouded but growing awareness of the young Marnus with his own pervasive cynicism fifteen years late, as he fights another century's war in Angola, it is a disturbing, powerful and utterly credible story of a child's introduction to hypocrisy and disillusion. Debunking the Afrikaner mentality with devastating irony, The Smell of Apples places Mark Behr at the very forefront of South African literature, alongside writers such as Alan Paton, J.M. Coetzee and Nadine Gordimer.<p>
<p>It is a quite exceptional debut.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
