<html><head><title>BALKAN ODYSSEY</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl7-1.jpg"><img src="2cs7-1.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>ALKAN</font> O<font size=-1>DYSSEY</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By David Owen. <br><i>Victor Gollancz</i>;<i> 4</i>16<i> pages</i>; <i>20</i>. <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font><i>. the electric company; standard 25 and academic 150</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt7-1.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>'It had been a long and eventful journey, my almost three-year Balkan odyssey, and I could only hope that no negotiator would ever again have to experience anything like the frustration, torment and tragedy that had unfolded during this period of Balkan history.'<p>
<p>No single individual has been as closely identified with attempts to bring peace to the war-torn Balkans as David Owen.<p>
<p>In 1992 the former Foreign Secretary was appointed the European negotiator charged with bringing the conflicting parties around the conference table to hammer out compromises that could then be implemented on the battlefield, and for three years he strove both to contain the various wars in the former Yugoslavia and to impose a peace plan on a political impasse which consistently defied solution.<p>
<p>Balkan Odyssey is Lord Owen's personal account of how the international community strove to cope with the events of these turbulent years, the story of the struggle for a peace settlement amidst the horror and torment of ethnic cleansing, war crimes, racism, nationalism and religious intolerance.<p>
<p>It is rare to be taken inside the secretive world of diplomacy and military strategy, to experience the broken promises, lies and propaganda in an arena where ceasefires are scattered like confetti and crimes against humanity are commonplace. David Owen's compelling account of his quest for a peaceful solution provides a ringside seat as the European Union grapples with the problem of how to forge an effective common foreign and security policy without the dangers which he perceives of developing into a 'United States of Europe'. Other crucial issues aired include the deterioration in Europe's relations with the USA, the challenge of working with Russia, the EU-UN partnership and the UN-NATO co-operation .<p>
<p>Balkan Odyssey is for the many people who want to understand the complexity as well as the enormity of what has gone on in the Balkans over this period of upheaval and torment - the most traumatic event of recent European history.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
