<html><head><title>ANCESTRAL VOICES & PROPHESYING PEACE: DIARIES 1942-1945</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl11-1.jpg"><img src="2cs11-1.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A<font size=-1>NCESTRAL</font> V<font size=-1>OICES</font> & P<font size=-1>ROPHESYING</font> P<font size=-1>EACE</font>:<br>
D<font size=-1>IARIES</font> <font size=-1>1942-1945</font></h2>
<p>By James Lees-Milne. <br><i>John Murray; 504 pages; 25</i></p>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>JAMES LEES-MILNE'S diaries are perhaps the very best this century has produced. They are full of wit, gossip, comment, and malice, and of memorable - occasionally scandalous - anecdotes. His four volumes covering the war years and the late 1940s, which he spent inspecting historic buildings offered by eccentric or impecunious owners to the National Trust, present a wonderfully entertaining view of a world now sadly vanished altogether.<p>
<p>These books, though classics, have been unobtainable for some time. The first two are here republished in one volume with a new introduction.<p>
<p>John Betjeman called Ancestral Voices 'funny and touching, honest and personal, prejudiced and tolerant ... full of strangely rivetting anecdotes'. Arthur Calder Marshall described it as full of delicious surprises: 'Mr Lees-Milne was the right man for the job; he loves fine objects and enjoys weird people.' Of Prophesying Peace, Maurice Richardson wrote: 'James Lees-Milne has that special gift of catching your fancy, so that you can see through his eyes without having to share his opinions or prejudices. A naturally gifted writer, he is as observant as a fly and a master of detail.'<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
