<html><head><title>FIDELITY'S WORLD</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl12-1.jpg"><img src="2cs12-1.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>F<font size=-1>IDELITY'S</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font><br>
</h2>
<p>By Diana Henriques. <br><i>Charles Scribner's Sons; 416 pages; $26</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt12-1.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>Fidelity Investments has more than 8 million individual and corporate accounts worth $400 billion, making it the largest mutual fund company in the country. But for all its power and influence, Fidelity remains a largely unexamined institution, cloaked in its own carefully cultivated image of benign, "hands-off" investing guided by bedrock American values. Fidelity's World takes readers behind the polished public relations image and examines the private faces of Fidelity: the personalities of the two eccentric but little-known men who built the empire, the people they recruited to turn their ideas into reality, and the methods - sometimes subtle, occasionally brash and brutal - that they have used to remake their industry and to reshape the investing habits of millions of Americans.<p>
<p>Veteran New York Times investigative reporter Diana B. Henriques weaves together solid financial detective work with vivid personality portraits as she explores Fidelity and the entire mutual fund industry. The millions of Americans who invest in mutual funds generally do so because they think it is a relatively safe way to invest, but Fidelity's World will make them think twice about that assumption and is for that reason required reading for those trying to protect their life's savings.<p>
<p>Fidelity's founder, the enigmatic Edward C. Johnson 2d, redefined the way mutual funds were run in the post-World War II period. The founder's somewhat reclusive son and namesake, Ned Johnson, took over the firm in the early 1970s and quickly turned it into a complex international corporation. He was a pioneer of the mass-marketing of mutual funds, using high tech consumer service and constant product innovations to bypass Wall Street and sell directly to individual investors.<p>
<p>Increasingly, there are signs that Ned Johnson is willing to wield every bit of the vast power that the mutual fund empire has put in his hands. He has dictated the outcome of corporate boardroom battles and bankruptcy cases, and he has faced down some of the biggest celebrities on Wall Street, including KKR's Henry Kravis. Johnson's trailblazing tactics raise serious concerns about whether the laws drawn up a half century ago to regulate the scandal-ridden mutual fund industry are still equal to the task of policing a worldwide empire like Fidelity Investments.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
