<html><head><title>BURY ME STANDING: THE GYPSIES AND THEIR JOURNEY</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top>
<a href="2cl8-1.jpg"><img src="2cs8-1.gif" alt="review graphic"><p>Full Image</a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>URY</font> M<font size=-1>E</font> S<font size=-1>TANDING</font>:<br>
T<font size=-1>HE</font> G<font size=-1>YPSIES</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THEIR</font> J<font size=-1>OURNEY</font></h2>
<p>By Isabel Fonseca. <br><i>Chatto &amp; Windus; 322 pages; 18.99</i>. <i>Knopf; $24.95</i></p>
<p><a href="2bt8-1.html">Biography</a></p><p><b>Jacket Copy</b></p>
<p>Fabled, feared, romanticised and reviled, the Gypsies are perhaps the least understood people in the world. They have survived for a millennium, yet their history is obscure; their nation is a worldwide diaspora of twelve million, but their language remains unwritten and their culture largely mute.<p>
<p>After the revolutions of 1989, Isabel Fonseca lived and travelled with the Gypsies of Eastern Europe - in Bulgaria, Poland, the Czech Republic and Slovakia, Romania and Albania - sharing their daily lives, and recording their stories and their attempts to become something more than despised outsiders. Here are unforgettable portraits of individuals - the poet, the MP, the child prostitute - alongside insights into the Gypsies' wit, wisdom, language and taboos. In a compelling narrative account of this large and landless minority, she traces the Gypsies from their exodus out of India, to their enslavement by the princes of medieval Romania; from their massacre by the Nazis and forced assimilation under the Communist regimes, to their new and violently contested presence in the political arena .<p>
<p>Whether as handy scapegoats or figments of the romantic imagination, the Gypsies have always been with us. But never before have they been brought so vividly to life.<p>
<p>
<p>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?819064800,rev">Search</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a> &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
