<html><head><title>Twilight's new gleaming</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr1.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h1>Twilight's new gleaming</h1>
<h2>Is America, as several new books argue, entering a new progressive era?</h2><ul><li>I<font size=-1>N</font> D<font size=-1>EFENCE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> G<font size=-1>OVERNMENT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jacob Weisberg. <br>
<li><a href="5ex115.html">T<font size=-1>HEY</font> O<font size=-1>NLY</font> L<font size=-1>OOK</font> D<font size=-1>EAD</font></a>: W<font size=-1>HY</font> P<font size=-1>ROGRESSIVES</font> W<font size=-1>ILL</font> D<font size=-1>OMINATE</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>EXT</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICAL</font> E<font size=-1>RA</font>.&nbsp;  By E. J. Dionne Jr. <br>
<li><a href="5ex107.html">U.S.A. 2012</a>: A<font size=-1>FTER</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> M<font size=-1>IDDLE-CLASS</font> R<font size=-1>EVOLUTION</font>.&nbsp;  By Kenneth Dolbeare and Janette Kay Hubbell. <br>
<li><a href="5ex111.html">S<font size=-1>TORMING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> G<font size=-1>ATES</font></a>: P<font size=-1>ROTEST</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICS</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> R<font size=-1>EPUBLICAN</font> R<font size=-1>EVIVAL</font>.&nbsp;  By Dan Balz and Ronald Brownstein. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>

<p>CALLING himself a different kind of Democrat, Bill Clinton ended the Republicans' 12-year hold of the White House in 1992 and a new party era seemed to dawn. Two years later, Republicans swept to control of both houses of Congress for the first time in 40 years and a conservative revolution--odd coupling as that sounds--looked unstoppable. But the revolution sputtered and stalled, and its leader, Newt Gingrich, the House speaker, fell to Nixonian depths of unpopularity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Through these puzzling swings of party fortune, most Americans continue to believe that the country is on the wrong track, be their worries about lost jobs, static pay, disintegrating families, dangerous streets or all of those things put together. This anxious majority includes Americans who would look to government for a cure if only it would work better, and Americans who see in the federal government a cause, perhaps the cause, of such ills.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Theoretically at odds as they are, the two sorts of worrier often end up in surprising agreement, at least in their anger with "Washington" and their eagerness to throw the rascals out. That alone is a startling change and one which makes the lives of Washington politicians, not to mention Washington commentators, so much harder than it was. In the late 1950s, three out of four Americans said they trusted the federal government to do the right thing most of the time; now only one in five do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Disgruntlement with "big government" feeds easily into dissatisfaction with the standard choice of two parties. Ross Perot, a successful businessman who believes in balanced budgets, trade protection and one-line answers to hard questions, won 19% of the popular vote for president in 1992 and may well try again in November. Though by no means the first independent or third-party candidate of recent times, he was the most successful. (The segregationist George Wallace reached double figures in 1968, but most of his support was in the South.) To find a comparable dent in America's party duopoly you must go back to the Progressive era early this century--the era in which "big government" began.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The seeming creakiness of the two-party system is one of the tempting likenesses between then and now. Another is the technical and economic shift shaking American society. At the end of the last century too, America was changing: from farm and commerce to city and industry. Then, as now, old habits of government looked wrong for the times. One powerful reaction was Progressivism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In its left- or right-wing varieties, the movement appealed to farmers and blue-collar workers as well as to reformist fat-cats. Some progressives favoured direct democracy, some not. But modernising government they all agreed on. They never reached the White House under their own label. But many of their ideas did. During the presidencies of Teddy Roosevelt, a progressive Republican, and Woodrow Wilson, a progressive Democrat, Americans got food and drug laws, railway regulation, a federal trade commission, a federal-reserve banking system and a constitutionally secure income tax. It took the New Deal and the second world war to put muscle on this new creature. But "Washington" in the modern sense had been born.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After the Republicans' victory in 1994 came a cluster of books charting further stages of the promised conservative, "less government" revolution. Now as if in reaction, but with a similar mixture of prediction and promotion, comes a crop of books mapping out a new Progressive era.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jacob Weisberg of <i>New York</i> magazine has written a well-argued tract in defence of active government. He acknowledges government's current weaknesses: it is overextended and inflexible, and has too often lost sight of its proper job. But its faults should be fixed, he argues, not made an excuse for dismantlement. Active government is needed more than anything, Mr Weisberg believes, to tackle America's racial wounds and its class divisions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Active-government types once proudly called themselves liberals. But the badge has not worn well and "progressive" is fast taking its place. The progressive tradition, Mr Weisberg says, offers "liberalism without a century's accretion of bad habits". The government he wants would recognise its limits, be sparing with spending and regulation, and have lots of sunset provisions. He leaves open whether Democrats or some third force would be the best mouthpiece of these ideas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;E. J. Dionne of the <i>Washington Post</i> foresees a new progressive era. The "Republican revolution" will fail, he thinks, because Americans will not put up with a version of the small-government conservatism of the Gilded Age--the free-for-all boom years after the Civil War--"dressed up in the finery of a high-tech age". He likens the scale of America's current social and economic upheavals to those that shook it towards the end of the 19th century. Americans then were fed up with no government; today's are tired of bad government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No Luddites, Mr Dionne's progressives accept that resisting technical change is largely pointless and that there is no plausible alternative to market economics. They accept, too, that government's capacities are limited. But they refuse to believe that government can simply ignore the gulf between rich and poor Americans or the drop in living standards many middle-class ones face, leaving it to markets to correct these things. Rather, they believe that government has a part in easing economic transition and widening opportunities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That sounds remarkably like Mr Clinton and, indeed, Mr Dionne describes Mr Clinton's mission as "nothing short of a reinvention of the Progressive tradition". That he has achieved so little Mr Dionne puts down to the president's own shortcomings and to the lack of support and discipline among the Democrats in Congress.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though Mr Dionne argues well, his book raises two problems. One is that it treats Mr Clinton's difficulties as failures of technique without firmly confronting the possibility that the progressive programme itself is at key places flawed or empty. Another is that too much of his argument rests on an over-literal reading of the Republicans' own anti-government slogans. Republicans believe that government can do no good and should be stripped to the barest essentials, or so Mr Dionne too often seems to argue. But with exceptions, this is a risky account of Republican policy. Certainly, it is not how Republicans act in office. They want to balance, not abolish, the federal budget. They want states to do some things the federal government now does. The Republican candidate for president, Bob Dole, tells campaign audiences that government does good as well as harm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chastened Democratic liberals calling themselves progressives and chastened Republican conservatives speaking up for government sound very like Washington politicians committed to business as usual. With primaries out of the way, the standard play-book of both sides says, "Go for the centre". No wonder some "third-force" supporters want stronger stuff.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Kenneth Dolbeare and Janette Kay Hubbell despise Democrats and Republicans alike. A husband-and-wife team, they describe themselves as an eastern iconoclast and a south-western populist. They resent the "systematic looting of the middle class on behalf of the particular special interests" that the big parties represent. They would smash the two-party system in a "drastic middle-class Jeffersonian revolution" committed to economic nationalism and direct democracy. Their economics is crude. But in their corrosive suspicion of America's elites, of the global marketplace, of transnational corporations and of the spreading indifference they think they detect to their own "middle-class" values, they share ample ground with know-nothing Republican populists such as Pat Buchanan. Though unlikely to become a majority voice, theirs is not to be taken lightly. You do not need your person in the White House or a majority in Congress to affect what goes on there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The least viewy of these books is by Dan Balz of the <i>Washington Post</i> and Ronald Brownstein of the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>. It is spiced with insights into on-the-run, <font size=-1>U</font>-turn policy-making by Mr Clinton and Mr Gingrich in the age of <font size=-1>CNN</font>, all-talk radio and the net. Republicans, the authors think, are likeliest to see Washington into the next century if only for their grip on the South--but not if they frighten off floating voters with zealotry. Extremism in the defence of anything is seldom a lasting vote-getter.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
