<html><head><title>Progress report</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>American history</b></p>
<h2>Progress report</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex121.html">G<font size=-1>RAND</font> E<font size=-1>XPECTATIONS</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> U<font size=-1>NITED</font> S<font size=-1>TATES</font>, 1945-1974.&nbsp;  By James Patterson. <br>
</ul>

<p>AT THE end of the second world war, Churchill observed that America stood at the summit of the world. Truman even asserted that the United States possessed the greatest strength and the greatest power that man had ever reached. These claims were not hyperbole but simple fact.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Walter Lippmann, the most thoughtful of American columnists, predicted that as Rome was to the ancients and Britain to the moderns, America would be to the future. Sole possession of the atomic bomb was coupled with an economy that, in 1947, was producing half of the world's manufactures and nearly three-fifths of its steel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By 1974, when Richard Nixon was forced to resign the presidency in the aftermath of the Watergate scandals, America had undergone the traumas of the assassinations of the two Kennedys and Martin Luther King, rioting in its big cities and the war in Vietnam. An acute observer compared America's state of mind to something like the angry confusion and despair of Weimar Germany.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This tumultuous period is authoritatively covered by James Patterson, a professor of history at Brown University, in "Grand Expectations", a volume in the Oxford History of the United States. His unifying theme is that Americans during the 25 or so years after the war developed ever-greater expectations about the capability of the United States to create a better world abroad and a happier society at home. These expectations, fuelled by vibrant economic growth, peaked in the 1960s when faith in the capacity of the federal government aroused unprecedented consciousness about rights on the home front. This affected all groups of Americans. Blacks, the poor, women and many others demanded greater access to the improving society that was blossoming about them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than ever before--or since--Americans came to believe that they could shape the world in their image while forging a society of equal opportunity. There seemed to be no limits to what the United States could accomplish. Inevitably, this hubris confronted reality. But the outcome was far from a disaster. As Mr Patterson concludes, no comparable period of American history witnessed such civic and economic progress; the United States was on its way to becoming perhaps "the least racist white- majority society in the world."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Back in 1945 anti-Catholic feelings remained strong. Jews were discriminated against in admissions to top colleges and academic posts. Blacks were segregated in the South and without real political power anywhere. Women were told to strive for "receptivity and passiveness". The homophobia displayed by President Truman is striking. A gauge of rapid change is that by 1962 one-third of women considered themselves victims of discrimination; by 1974 the fraction had doubled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Grand Expectations" contains an annoying number of mistakes, usually minor. On foreign affairs it is less informed than on domestic matters. But Mr Patterson's overall achievement is compelling. He has pulled together recent findings in political, social, legal and economic history while maintaining a strong narrative flow. His eye for detail is acute; his judgments on exclusion or inclusion hard to fault. Objectivity is not compromised. Martin Luther King's accomplishments are described at length but his philandering and plagiarism are not omitted. While dealing well with such a vast array of events, Mr Patterson consistently manages to produce subtle and sophisticated conclusions. "Grand Expectations" is a definitive history of post-war America.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
