<html><head><title>Best sleep alone</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Royal marriages</b></p>
<h2>Best sleep alone</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex63.html">T<font size=-1>HE </font>U<font size=-1>NRULY</font> Q<font size=-1>UEEN</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Q<font size=-1>UEEN</font> C<font size=-1>AROLINE</font>.&nbsp;  By Flora Fraser. <br>
<li><a href="5ex54.html">M<font size=-1>ONARCHY</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> M<font size=-1>ATRIMONY</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>OURTSHIPS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> E<font size=-1>LIZABETH</font> I.&nbsp;  By Susan Doran. <br>
</ul>


</i>
<p>WHEN the heir to the throne and his wife appeared together in public, they faced away from each other like the heads of a heraldic eagle. The Prince of Wales had already lost his heart to another woman and refused to renounce her. The new princess never stood a chance. Soon lovers and rumours of lovers began to circle about her, yet it was the princess rather than her distant, pompous husband whom the people lined the streets to cheer, in their thousands. As Lord Holland remarked at the time, a childish love of royalty prevailed in the land.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is fun, and strangely reassuring, to find contemporary resonances in the antics of the royal family of George III, though perhaps not quite fair to Flora Fraser. Written with elegance, wit and a narrative zest that novelists might envy, her book carries its researches lightly, yet they are far-reaching and impressive. The portrait of Caroline of Brunswick is composed of a thousand telling details, and only occasionally do we sense that the artist has a bias towards her sitter. One such moment occurs when Caroline's husband is informed of the death of Napoleon. This is how Ms Fraser puts it: "King George IV received the news: 'Sir, your bitterest enemy is dead'. 'Is she, by God!' was his tender reply."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His reaction on first seeing her was to call for brandy; he spent their wedding night in a drunken stupor under the grate where, she said, he fell. By some miracle they stayed together long enough (three weeks, she reckoned) to allow for the conception of Princess Charlotte but thereafter never willingly met. Yet the young Caroline--incidentally, his first cousin--though fatally lacking commonsense, was fair, pretty, good-natured and spirited. However, when Lord Malmesbury first went to Brunswick to fetch her, he was worried: he saw her life had been dogged by "privation, injunction and menace".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Malmesbury advised her to wash more thoroughly so as to please the fastidious prince, but perhaps she ignored the advice. Her miserably constrained existence was to continue for years until she broke free, escaped to the continent and began to let rip. There are outrageous stories of her at 50, in a new black wig with pencilled eyebrows to match, handsome Italian lover at her side, riding into Jerusalem on a donkey--or through Genoa in an illuminated phaeton, plump in gauzy pink, led by a dimpled cherub, loving it all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over more than 20 years, her every move was reported to her husband by his spies, resulting in the so-called Delicate Investigation, the scandalous Milan Commission, the Secret Committee and finally the infamous trial for adultery (at which she was acquitted). His last gesture towards her was to employ pugilists to keep her from Westminster Abbey during his coronation. "Fate", said Max Beerbohm much later, "wrote her a tremendous tragedy, and she played it in tights."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Royalty must make marriages of convenience which seldom result in happiness; so Caroline's father had gloomily opined. Or, of course, royal personages can stay single. There is a portrait of Elizabeth I in Susan Doran's book in which she holds a sieve. This oddly domestic implement was a reminder of the vestal virgin who proved her innocence by carrying water from the Tiber in such a vessel, without spilling a drop. Thus was Elizabeth's virginity seen as an icon of the impenetrable, invulnerable state she ruled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Doran's theory, however, which she argues persuasively, is that Elizabeth would have liked to marry Robert Dudley, her Master of Horse. He was reasonably aristocratic and extremely attractive. Unfortunately, he already had a wife, Amy Robsart. Amy's convenient death--she apparently fell downstairs and died without even disturbing her head-dress--ironically ruined his chances. Reluctantly, remembering her cousin Mary Stuart's experience, the politician in Elizabeth overrode the lover.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By this time, the suitably Protestant princes who courted the queen had withdrawn. She could have had the dashing Adolphus of Holstein or the romantic Eric of Sweden, whose emissary, Nils Guildenstern, led a troupe of courtiers, all sporting red velvet hearts pierced by javelins. She was left to the attentions of the Catholic monarchs who courted her so assiduously. And how she strung them along! Her brother-in-law, Philip II, was first, which courtship gratifyingly ratified her slightly dubious legitimacy. Then came the Archduke of Austria and the King of France, but the one she liked was her "little frog", the young bandy-legged, gravelly-voiced Francis, Duke of Alen&ccedil;on, whose attentive gallantry nearly overcame her religious scruples.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Doran's learned book takes for granted a knowledge of the intrigues of Elizabethan history. It aims to show how wily and oblique were the means used by the queen's courtiers to dissuade her from marriage. Masques, plays and poems, often subtle beyond detailed modern interpretation, were used to plead the causes of their shadowy commissioners. In the end, she resigned herself to remain, not the Queen of Hearts, but the Virgin Queen of the Sieve. Uneasy, indeed, lies the head that wears a crown, but it sleeps more easily alone.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
