</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Pitiless logic</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr4.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Modern philosophers</b></p>
<h2>Pitiless logic</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex120.html">B<font size=-1>ERTRAND </font>R<font size=-1>USSELL</a>:</font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>PIRIT OF </font>S<font size=-1>OLITUDE</font>.&nbsp;  By Ray Monk. <br>
</ul>

<p>BERTRAND RUSSELL was a philosopher in both the popular and the academic senses of the word. He was a sage who offered lessons to mankind on life, love and society; and he was a logician who made revolutionary contributions to the foundations of technical philosophy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For his work as a sage Russell received a diversity of rewards ranging from imprisonment to a Nobel prize. He was sentenced to prison in 1918 and again in 1962 (at the age of 90) for his opposition to war and weapons of war. His Nobel prize for literature was awarded partway between and cited especially his book "Marriage and Morals", which, on first publication, had been condemned as obscene, thereby losing Russell his job. This very book, together with others of Russell's social writings, helped to transform the moral climate of the western world. Any social history of the 20th century would, if complete, have to mention Russell's part in this revolution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For his work as a technical philosopher Russell has, as his monument, "analytical philosophy", the dominant style of 20th-century Anglophone thought. Analytical philosophy consists in rigorous examination of the main concepts people use in trying to understand themselves and the world, based on the techniques of mathematical logic and on an alertness to science. Russell not only set the tone of this austere, precise, thoroughgoing approach, but--more importantly--provided its tools in the form of significant logical techniques and insights.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because Russell lived so long and did so much, the task of recording his life is gargantuan. Biographers of Russell need to be well and widely equipped to master the range of his thought, and at the same time to subordinate the fermenting mass of personal detail provided by his correspondence, and the letters and diaries of the dozens of contemporaries with whom he had friendships, love affairs, quarrels and controversies. No one has so far succeeded, but if anyone might be expected to fit the bill, Ray Monk is that person.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is both a philosopher and an outstanding biographer, as his account of Ludwig Wittgenstein's life famously shows. He has the biographer's indispensable trait of obsessiveness, the magpie's eye which discovers a place for each last detail. And, like all genuinely good biographers, he writes with a sharply defined picture of his subject before him, a confidence, even a certitude, about what his subject was like, not just as he appeared to those who knew him, but as he seemed to himself in his deepest fears and darkest depressions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that is where this huge book (huge, but only the first of two volumes, taking us to the half-way point of Russell's life in the early 1920s) goes wrong. For Mr Monk dislikes Russell--intensely, it transpires--and his unblinking eye sees in much that Russell privately did and said a monstrous cruelty which, we are repeatedly told, blasted the lives of those who came into his orbit. The Russell of this book is a disturbed man, not merely egotistical and cold but literally murderous in his impulses, who had to struggle to prevent himself throttling people when in a rage; who was horribly insensitive to the suffering of others, and always ready to sacrifice them to his own insecurities and desires; who wore out his lovers with obsessions and intensity before tossing them aside in preparation for his next victim--and who, to cap it all, suffered at times from bad breath and impotence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is an ugly picture, and sits oddly with Russell's extraordinary output of marvellous work, his labours for peace and freedom, and the remark of a friend, quoted by Mr Monk: "He was like a happy child, and he made me realise from his tenderness and brilliant mind why, with all his waywardness, I love him so devotedly."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a tribute to the biographer, nonetheless, that the materials for a corrective to his pitiless view are to be found in the book itself. It records the melancholy isolation of Russell's boyhood in his grandmother's puritanical and emotionally stunted household, a tormenting upbringing for one who had begun as an affectionate child, and who therefore, first orphaned and then oppressed and wholly starved of love by those around him, was avid for affection throughout his life, at times contemplating suicide when it seemed unattainable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russell wrote numerous letters each day--a habit of the pre-telephonic age--most of them to lovers and friends, containing much about his feelings. From these is built up a portrait of Russell as vampire, devil, ice-man, woman-eater. Mr Monk achieves this by quoting Russell's own anguished claims to be exactly these things and, seeking to paint him with warts, is much helped by his subject's hyperbolic style. How would anybody fare if their expostulations and vehemences were written down in evidence against them? "I could kill that child!" cries the noise-tormented parent--who, if Mr Monk is the biographer, enters the ledger as a would-be child-murderer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bulk of this life consists in a painstakingly minute exploration of Russell's relationships with women. There is only a faint sense of the outside world and the historical setting; even the first world war's intrusions on the narrative are cursory. The result is a claustrophobic and relentless story; when released from the toils of Russell's love-life, the reader emerges gasping with the wish that this book had been more selective in quotation and more summary in exposition. Much more might have been vouchsafed of Russell's times, of the other people he knew--Joseph Conrad, D.H. Lawrence, Lytton Strachey, G.E. Moore, Maynard Keynes, Katherine Mansfield, all of whom make fleeting appearances in the story--and of the impact of the world upon Russell and Russell upon the world. When Mr Monk does do such things, his skill is dazzling: but there is tantalisingly too little of them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Monk does a far better job than any previous biographer of Russell at explaining the essence of his philosophical work simply, even if the exposition is at times over-technical for most non-specialists and for practitioners in places controversial. He deserves admiration for immense scholarship and expert handling of so much detail. Yet on finishing this book it is impossible not to be disappointed at the hostile and therefore one-sided image it seeks to leave. Seeks, but does not succeed. The book gives too much information about Russell's achievement and better thoughts, his generosity, his intellect, his wit and his hunger for love, to make us believe the version of Russell Mr Monk would like us to accept.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
