<DOCNO>WT21-B40-354</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000279-B020-191</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev5/rv5/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113184230 text/html 6388
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:38:44 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:09 GMT
Content-length: 6203
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Not so dark</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Early European history</b></p>
<h2>Not so dark</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex106.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> R<font size=-1>ISE OF</font> W<font size=-1>ESTERN</font> C<font size=-1>HRISTENDOM</font></a>: T<font size=-1>RIUMPH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> D<font size=-1>IVERSITY</font>, <font size=-1>AD</font> 200-1000.&nbsp;  By Peter Brown. <br>
</ul>

THE five international publishers who are putting out parallel versions of a new history series, "The Making of Europe", have created a polyglot venture that is already proving more than the sum of its parts. Under the directorship of a French historian, Jacques Le Goff, the publishers Beck (Germany), Blackwell (America and Britain), Critica (Spain), Laterza (Italy) and Le Seuil (France) have achieved something refreshing and unpredictable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To include studies of food, individualism and people's relationship to the sea, alongside more run-of-the-mill topics such as language, the peasantry and political revolutions, is an inspired start. So too is the choice of authors, who are being urged to stray imaginatively beyond narrow specialties and tackle ambitious themes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peter Brown, a professor at Princeton, needs no special prompting. The range of his knowledge and the brilliance of his style would entice even the least committed Europeanist to consider the whole series. It may be disputed whether there is such a thing as a typically European city, but there can be no doubt of the centrality of Christendom to Europe. Not only was the Christian faith in many ways fundamental to Europe's early development. The very notion of Europe was itself more or less synonymous with Christendom in the 800 years up to the first millennium.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under Mr Brown's sympathetic control, the late antique and medieval exponents of this faith speak across the centuries, evoking the hopes and fears of their times. They do so directly, in the quotations that dot the pages, but yet more vividly thanks to the author's magical evocation of moments of stress and doubt that assailed even men and women of iron will.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Through his selection of fascinating detail, the early history of Europe is painted in a rainbow of subtle shades that stress its variety. Yet this does not distract from the basic story of how local cults, ancient traditions, older gods and goddesses, usually linked with natural phenomena, retreated to the margins of society, dwindled in significance and eventually paled into the collective memory to make way for the vision of salvation possessed by followers of Jesus.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Brown highlights age-old contrasts between the written and the spoken, giving full strength to those unwritten forms of worship dismissed as barbarian. And he sets them in the context of the contrast between centre and periphery, where "no one sees sculptors, painters, perfumers, money changers and poets". This characterisation of city life comes down from Bardaisan, a Christian author of the second century, the first of many colourful figures who accompany each stage of the story.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There was more here than triumphant conquest. This was a story also of diversity, of local histories that made each part of what later became Europe so particular. Nor in these centuries was Christianity expanding only into Western Europe. The author's range is shown in passages on the Nestorian missionaries in Hsain-fu, who defended monotheism to the Chinese emperor in 635, with the Christians in Muslim Spain who expressed themselves in correct and elegant Arabic, with the Jewish communities of the Near East, or with Persians, Armenians and many others.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Brown is in his element in Ireland and places farther north, describing the renunciation of works and words required of early converts: Woden, Thunor, Saxnote; and the "spirit-locking" spell learned in Iceland, which a prophetess in Greenland invoked to ward off famine. Yet he never loses sight of the seed ground of Christianity in the Mediterranean world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Byzantine iconoclasm takes pride of place in the period of divergence. The eastern dispute over icons and idolatry provoked a distinctive western response. Under Charlemagne, Frankish bishops made their own judicious interpretation: images are the bibles of the illiterate, as Gregory the Great said, but true veneration is for God alone. So guided, Christians in Charlemagne's lands, which became the Holy Roman Empire in 800, began to adopt a western identity of their own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the dramatic presence of so many people from these centuries leaves little space for more explanatory considerations. The economy of western Christendom is somewhat neglected, despite the frequent telling detail. The interpretation of iconoclasm is rather conventional. In its English version the volume fails to make the best of the maps (too small) and the chronologies (awkward to use, and with odd errors such as the date of Constantinople's foundation, 330). But there is no better introduction to what western Christendom became than this fine and delightfully readable study.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
