<html><head><title>In the frame</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Israel</b></p>
<h2>In the frame</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex129.html">S<font size=-1>HALOM</font>, F<font size=-1>RIEND</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>AND LEGACY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> Y<font size=-1>ITZHAK</font> R<font size=-1>ABIN</font>.&nbsp;  Edited by David Horovitz. <br>
</ul>


<p>QUICKEST is not necessarily best, and this instant book on Yitzhak Rabin, rushed out in response to intense interest in America and elsewhere, is a series of snapshots, not a rounded portrait. But they are clever, often ironical snapshots by a group of Israeli journalists on the fortnightly <i>Jerusalem Report</i>, artfully stitched together by the magazine's managing editor, David Horovitz.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The salient points of Rabin's career are briskly recounted, from his nursery days in charge of the school donkey onwards. His character is harder to convey: outsiders knew his chain-smoking gruffness; friends speak of his warmth--and his reserve: "Getting him going", says one, "was like lighting damp matches."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The team excel, as they should, in describing his murder: the abysmal security, based on the belief that no Jew could be a danger, and the confusion afterwards when Rabin's driver was forced by the crowds to take the dying man on the long route to the nearest hospital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prime minister died violently leading a campaign against violence. He was persuaded to attend the rally in Tel Aviv not because it was pro-peace but because it was anti-violence. He wanted to moderate the often hysterical tone of debate inside Israel. Cabinet ministers had been attacked by right-wing mobs; posters had the prime minister in Nazi uniform, placards had shown his features overlaid with the cross-hairs of a rifle sight--a clear incitement to murder. In tragic fashion he succeeded: for a time after his murder, Israelis were "shocked into gentler behaviour, speaking more quietly, driving more carefully." Then came the Hamas suicide-bombs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rabin, say the authors, was "a soldier who became a statesman but never shed his uniform". Prime minister in 1974 after six months in the Knesset (and forced to resign three years later when his wife was revealed to have an illegal dollar account), he was contemptuous of those who disagreed with him. He was a new-found politician who disdained politics and other politicians. Above all, he disdained the one he called an "inveterate schemer", his rival for the Labour leadership, Shimon Peres.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Palestinians meant little to him until much later. When the <i>intifada</i> (uprising) broke out in 1987, he blamed Iran and Syria (as his successors now blame Iran for the suicide-bombs). Whether or not, as defence minister, he actually told his soldiers to "break bones", this was the sum of his message. Yet it was the <i>intifada</i>, say the authors perceptively, that "turned the Palestinian people into a proper enemy. And as such, they had earned the right in Rabin's eyes to a proper peace."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In pursuit of that peace, Mr Peres and Rabin, "Israel's unlikeliest duo", at long last became good partners. To begin with, Rabin was intensely suspicious of the Oslo peace process but, over time, the distinction between Palestinian rejectionists and <font size=-1>PLO</font> peacemakers established itself in his mind. From then on, the team worked well: Mr Peres was the driving spirit; Rabin, the security-minded pragmatist who could sell peace to his countrymen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But not, alas, to enough of them. Now Mr Peres, left behind as half a once-strong team, has to be both driving force and salesman, missing the man he used to fight.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
