<html><head><title>Gorbachev: villain for whom?</title></head>
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Jul-1996 -->
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>Gorbachev: villain for whom?</h2>
<p><b>Why the Soviet empire suddenly fell apart in 1991 will occupy historians for years. Meanwhile "Books in Brief" looks at four eyewitness accounts</b></p><ul><li><a href="#1">A<font size=-1>UTOPSY</font> <font size=-1>ON</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> E<font size=-1>MPIRE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Jack Matlock. <br>
<li><a href="#2">F<font size=-1>INAL</font> D<font size=-1>AYS</font></a>: T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>NSIDE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE C</font><font size=-1>OLLAPSE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>OVIET</font> U<font size=-1>NION</font>.&nbsp;  By Andrei Grachev. <br>
<li><a href="#3">T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> H<font size=-1>UNDRED </font>D<font size=-1>AYS OF THE </font>S<font size=-1>OVIET</font> U<font size=-1>NION</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Boris Pankin. <br>
<li><a href="#4">I<font size=-1>N</font> C<font size=-1>ONFIDENCE</font></a>: M<font size=-1>OSCOW'S</font> A<font size=-1>MBASSADOR</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA'S</font> S<font size=-1>IX</font> C<font size=-1>OLD</font> W<font size=-1>AR</font> P<font size=-1>RESIDENTS</font>.&nbsp;  By Anatoly Dobrynin.<br>
</ul>


</td></tr></table>
<a name="1"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>A<font size=-1>UTOPSY</font> <font size=-1>ON</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> E<font size=-1>MPIRE</font>.<br>
 By Jack Matlock. <br>
<i>Random House; 836 pages; $40</i><br>
<a href="5ex66.html">Extract</a> - <a href="5jb66.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="5bt66.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>JACK MATLOCK was America's ambassador to the Soviet Union during the exhilarating but bewildering years of 1987-91. His book seeks to explain why the Soviet Union collapsed, and why it collapsed when it did. Along the way he provides an impressive narrative of the last years of the Soviet empire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On Mr Matlock's account, his masters in Washington were slow to recognise how fast things were sliding from under Mikhail Gorbachev and how important it was to open lines to others, notably Boris Yeltsin. He is diplomatically critical of President Bush and his advisers, more favourable to Ronald Reagan, president from 1981 to 1989, whom, he believes, had a knack with Soviet leaders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Matlock's judgment on Mr Gorbachev is severe. The last Soviet leader's achievements are impressive, we are told. But Mr Matlock stresses the flaws in Mr Gorbachev, personal and political. In his view, Mr Gorbachev's hesitations and manoeuvring are not the only reason for the shabby condition in which the Soviet Union collapsed at the end of 1991, but they played a large part.</td></tr></table>
<a name="2"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>F<font size=-1>INAL</font> D<font size=-1>AYS</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> I<font size=-1>NSIDE</font> S<font size=-1>TORY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE C</font><font size=-1>OLLAPSE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> S<font size=-1>OVIET</font> U<font size=-1>NION</font>.<br>
 By Andrei Grachev. <br>
<i>Westview Press; 240 pages; $29.50 and &#163;21.95</i><br>
<a href="5ex65.html">Extract</a> - <a href="5jb65.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="5bt65.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>FEW were better placed to observe Mr Gorbachev at close quarters as the end neared than Andrei Grachev, a long-time adviser of his. Mr Grachev does not conceal his admiration for his mentor. Nonetheless, his assessment is objective. He blames him not for inevitable compromises but for betrayals of principle, when he chose the "bureaucratic moves of an apparatchik over democratic procedures", secrecy over openness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Western readers may well find such strictures surprising. As most of them would see it, Mr Gorbachev bravely undertook a long, uncertain venture that brought the cold war to an end and led his country from communism to something, however fragile and imperfect, that can be called democracy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are historic achievements. Mr Gorbachev was rightly hailed as an extraordinary leader--outside the Soviet Union. Inside, his reputation was much more complex. Leaders are judged also on the material condition they leave a country in. Mr Gorbachev left his free of communism. But he left it also in an economic mess. Mr Grachev's judgment sounds harsh, but it is--or was--common in Russia. When Mr Gorbachev left office at the end of 1991, in Mr Grachev's words, "he left behind a splintered, ruined country, torn by conflicts and in doubt about its future, a country whose division may be a threat to world peace--a kind of Chernobyl on a global scale."</td></tr></table>
<a name="3"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> H<font size=-1>UNDRED </font>D<font size=-1>AYS OF THE </font>S<font size=-1>OVIET</font> U<font size=-1>NION</font>.<br>
 By Boris Pankin. <br>
<i>I.B. Tauris; 288 pages; &#163;19.95</i><br>
<a href="5ex64.html">Extract</a> - <a href="5jb64.html">Jacket Copy</a> - <a href="5bt64.html">Biography</a><br>


<p>AMONG Soviet ambassadors Boris Pankin was virtually alone in condemning the attempted coup against President Gorbachev in August 1991, an act not just brave but well-judged. When the ill-prepared and unpopular coup ended in rout, Mr Pankin was plucked back from Prague to be foreign minister.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Earlier, Mr Pankin had been a critic of the Soviet regime, though careful never to stray into the police-book as a dissident. A man who straddled journalism, art and politics, who knew how life was lived in the West and who wanted better for his own country, he was in many ways a typical "Gorbachev" communist. Yet like Mr Yeltsin, Mr Pankin plumped for democracy when it mattered, rather than groping instinctively for "order"--or waiting to see how the chips fell.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Admirable as that was, it did not prepare Mr Pankin for what followed. He was out of his depth, unable to slow or even grasp the speed of events, let alone the increasingly desperate actions of his boss. Before long he was replaced by Edward Shevardnadze, who returned briefly to his old job. Mr Pankin ended his diplomatic career as ambassador in London. It would be nice to be able to say that this good man had written a memorable memoir, but even for students of Russian history the pickings are scant.</td></tr></table>
<a name="4"></a><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left width=60><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br><hr size=5 width=170 align=left>I<font size=-1>N</font> C<font size=-1>ONFIDENCE</font>:<br> M<font size=-1>OSCOW'S</font> A<font size=-1>MBASSADOR</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA'S</font> S<font size=-1>IX</font> C<font size=-1>OLD</font> W<font size=-1>AR</font> P<font size=-1>RESIDENTS</font>.<br>
 By Anatoly Dobrynin.<br>
<i> Random House; 672 pages; $30</i><br>
<a href="5ex67.html">Extract</a> - <a href="5jb67.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>


<p>THE pickings in Anatoly Dobrynin's fascinating book could not be less scant. As a newly trained aircraft engineer, he was spotted by party talent-scouts and earmarked for diplomacy. That was in 1944 and Joseph Stalin was at the apogee of power. In March 1962, at the age of 43, Mr Dobrynin presented his credentials to President Kennedy as Soviet ambassador. Soon he was helping to open a "confidential channel" between American and Soviet leaders, so playing a part in averting war between the two nuclear superpowers over Cuba.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Washington Mr Dobrynin served his country with distinction during the presidencies of Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon and those of Ford, Carter and Reagan. As striking was the list of general or first secretaries of the Soviet Communist Party who wanted to keep him there: Khrushchev, Brezhnev, Andropov, Chernenko and, briefly, Mr Gorbachev.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dobrynin was more than a conduit between Moscow and Washington. He taught a succession of Soviet leaders about the United States. Whatever their native talents or capacities, these were men whose intellectual horizons were narrow, whose knowledge of the outside world was sparse and whose political reflexes were conditioned by the twin horrors of war and Stalinism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What benefit Mr Gorbachev thought might be gained from plucking Mr Dobrynin out of his North American milieu in March 1986 and making him head of the Communist Party's International Department is a good question. To give the department more prestige, Mr Gorbachev told him. This bit of the Central Committee dealt with the confined and seemingly esoteric world of "fraternal" allies--other communist countries. Did Mr Gorbachev, hearing the ice crack in Eastern Europe, want the skilful Mr Dobrynin at his side as an empire came apart? Or was he pushing him aside?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dobrynin's final assessment of Mr Gorbachev is strikingly similar to those of Jack Matlock and Andrei Grachev. "The political and economic chaos created by Gorbachev's own confusion over how to go about the difficult task of necessary reform," he writes, "combined with the upheavals of the latter part of 1991, led to his personal political downfall and the collapse of the Soviet Union."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not yet published in Russian, Mr Dobrynin's book provides English-speaking readers with fascinating insights into superpower diplomacy from a Soviet vantage point through 24 years of the cold war. It is a classic of its genre.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
