<html><head><title>Hands on the till</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr8.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Japanese money</b></p>
<h2>Hands on the till</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex118.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>EIGHT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> Y<font size=-1>EN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By R. Taggart Murphy. <br>
</ul>


<p>THE author hopes he has written a handbook for the American administration in its trade dealings with Japan. Surveying the history of the yen/dollar exchange rate over the past 20 years, when the Japanese currency appreciated from 360 to a high of around 80 to the dollar, he seeks to explain why, contrary to the theories of orthodox economics, Japanese trade surpluses persisted despite the strengthening yen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He argues that the Japanese economy has been structurally geared towards aggressive exporting. To this end, savings have been exacted from the workforce and handed over, at low cost, to export-oriented manufacturers who put market share above profits. Protected home markets, powerless shareholders and over-priced domestic goods have reinforced this policy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Ministry for International Trade and Industry (<font size=-1>MITI</font>) may, he says, have been responsible for selecting strategic industries and then protecting their progress, but the Ministry of Finance has been in charge of the financial side of the Japanese export drive. So, as Mr Murphy sees it, the finance ministry is the real villain in the history of the Japanese trade surpluses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He holds that even after the Plaza Accord of September 1985, when the leaders of the <font size=-1>G7</font> countries agreed to the controlled devaluation of the dollar against other leading currencies, the ministry prevented Japanese trade surpluses from shrinking by refusing to sanction an increase in government spending. Furthermore, it encouraged speculation in shares and property in order to give Japanese companies access to cheap capital as they remodelled themselves to compete internationally despite the stronger yen. He says:
<ul><font size=-1>Now, it is true that the ministry, through "administrative guidance" and the placement of its former officials in top financial jobs, is a powerful institution. It is also true that it has aimed to ensure that Japanese industry was supplied with low-cost capital. However, to charge the ministry with sole responsibility for one of the largest asset bubbles in history is grandiloquent even by its own standards of self-importance and does not withstand scrutiny.</font></ul>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ministry wanted high share prices in the mid-1980s not only so that business could raise capital cheaply but also also because it was itself in the middle of a privatisation programme and wanted to make big sums for the government. Japanese banks had an added interest in rising share and property markets after the Bank for International Settlements agreed to allow some of their unrealised capital gains on shareholdings to count towards their capital-adequacy requirements. Politicians benefiting from handouts of Recruit Cosmos and other shares stood to benefit from a rising stockmarket. Japanese companies, finding it ever harder to profit from exports, became more dependent on rising share prices as they turned to <i>zaitech</i> (financial engineering) to boost profits. The liquidity provided by falling interest rates after the Plaza Accord allowed the collective interest of these groups to be realised.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, the preconditions for the bubble economy were there before September 1985. Some of these were a sign of weakening ministerial control: for example, the freeing of capital flows and domestic interest rates, the development of the Eurobond warrant and swaps market, the emergence of the notorious <i>tokkin</i> accounts (which allowed companies to speculate in shares without incurring capital-gains liabilities on their historic shareholdings). Much speculation during the bubble happened beyond the ministry's ken through the <i>tokkin</i> accounts and the lending of 20,000 or so "non-banks".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Japanese system was unable to withstand the forces of globalisation and financial deregulation which overwhelmed all developed economies in the 1980s. The Plaza Accord made matters worse in preventing the Japanese authorities from using monetary policy to control incipient financial mania in a country experiencing increasing economic hubris.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Ministry of Finance is one of the most powerful Japanese institutions. Because foreigners (especially bankers) have frequent dealings with it, they tend to exaggerate its domestic importance and to minimise the role of other ministerial fiefs.The finance ministry may have played a big role in generating Japanese surpluses, despoiling the Japanese saver and promoting the bubble economy, but Mr Murphy would have been more accurate if he had made it <i>primus inter pares</i>, rather than prime mover, in his plot.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
