HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:39:32 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:09 GMT
Content-length: 5607
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Loss leaders</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>American banking</b></p>
<h2>Loss leaders</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex134.html">W<font size=-1>ALTER </font> W<font size=-1>RISTON</font>, C<font size=-1>ITIBANK</font>, <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> R<font size=-1>ISE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> F<font size=-1>ALL</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> A<font size=-1>MERICAN</font> F<font size=-1>INANCIAL</font> S<font size=-1>UPREMACY</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Phillip Zweig. <br>
</ul>

<p>THIS fat book's sub-title reveals its ambitious scope and explains its ultimate failure. Conceived more than a decade ago as a biography of Walter Wriston, the boss of Citibank for 17 years until he retired in 1984, it gradually expanded into a history of post-war American and international banking as seen through the prism of the world's top bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For every level at which Phillip Zweig succeeds there is, sadly, another at which he falls short. Take Mr Wriston, for instance. Although he is the central character his presence often appears shadowy. The reader is told of his boyhood and education. Much is made of his complicated relations with his father, Henry, an influential but frustrated academic whose self-control and belief in free markets were inherited by his son. Yet Walter Wriston, as portrayed by the author, seems an unrounded character. His obvious dour and scholarly sides provide few clues to how he rose so fast and so high within Citibank. Mr Zweig fails to account for his subject's (often, it is true, suppressed) generosity and warmth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Big events in Mr Wriston's personal life, such as the death of his first wife in 1966, are passed over with tantalising comments that raise more questions than they answer. For instance, Mr Zweig quotes Mr Wriston as calling himself a "basket case" after his wife's death. Colleagues thought he was clinically depressed. Yet Mr Zweig plunges on with his broader story unperturbed by the implications of these striking personal observations. A mere 20 pages after he is found sunk in mourning and melancholy, Mr Wriston re-emerges happily married to a woman 20 years younger than he is, and almost nothing more is said about his health and happiness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wriston's tendency to disappear from his own biography is especially evident in the final third of the book. By then Mr Zweig is more interested in John Reed, Mr Wriston's hand-picked successor. There is something to be said for this approach. Since Mr Reed took it over, Citibank has provided the money markets with lots of excitement. It has twice nearly collapsed under the weight of its own remarkably foolish lending, first to poor countries and then to American property speculators. Recently it has emerged as one of the world's most profitable banks. Mr Reed's own reputation has moved in line with the bank's fortunes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, bad lending aside, many of the strategies undertaken in the Wriston years, strategies which helped to shape today's Citibank, originated in the consumer banking division run by Mr Reed. During the late 1960s and 1970s Citibank poured zillions into technology investment, much of it wasted. But it also pioneered brilliant innovations which have become part of everyday banking--automated teller machines being the best example.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zweig will not give credit where credit is due. He fails to examine Mr Reed's evident determination to turn Citibank back from the brink of disaster in 1990-91 and the successful management strategy he used to do this. Indeed, Mr Zweig's picture of Citibank is so unflattering that the reader begins to wonder how the institution ever survived its own wranglings and incompetence. A context is missing. Somehow overlooked is the fact that other banks went through similar topsy-turvy changes in direction and fortune in the wake of their industry's lengthy deregulation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For all its failings, this semi-biography has strong points too. Its descriptions of American banking's hectic transition from the 1950s to the present are as clear as any yet written. Its accounts of Citibank are too uniformly harsh to be persuasive but it makes the point that a business often requires crisis management rather than considered judgments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In his researches, Mr Zweig spoke to most of the leading actors as well as to the bit players, gathering valuable testimony and setting the industry in its broadest international context. But his big book ought to have been two or even three smaller ones. It is something for scholars to plunder, not for lay readers to enjoy.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
