<html><head><title>Don't laugh</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr10.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Economics and society</b></p>
<h2>Don't laugh</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex116.html">A<font size=-1>GING</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> O<font size=-1>LD</font> A<font size=-1>GE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Richard Posner. <br>
</ul>

<p>HAVING taken on the economics of race, sex and crime, Richard Posner has aimed his intellect at a subject of urgent interest to a 55-year-old judge: age. A professor of law as well as a federal appeals-court judge, Mr Posner finds that older Americans are healthier, wealthier and happier than ever before and argues that their lust for entitlements is not bankrupting the country. With clear conscience he will be able to join them at the trough, though probably will not need to since judges, he stresses, can do a perfectly good job well into their 70s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Following the example of Gary Becker, a Nobel prize-winning economist and fellow luminary of the neo-liberal Chicago school, Mr Posner has made a specialty of applying economics in "non-market" situations, not just to big social problems but to the homeliest and most familiar-seeming of human actions. Everyone aims, on this theory, to get as much as they can of what they want, and, if they are rational about it, will work out the best ways how, weighing preferences and probabilities. Known as rational-choice theory, this approach is fruitful, speculative and controversial. It can also, as here, be unintentionally funny.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why do old people talk a lot? Because the "opportunity costs of time" for them are low. How does the "surplus" of elderly women to elderly men affect their love lives? They swap "spot" for "relational" contracting in the sex-market. When the good judge notes that old drivers have car smashes because their eyes and reflexes are going, readers will want to scream that the opportunity costs of their time are too high to put up with crashing bores.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But laughter will not deflect Mr Posner. A contrarian, he likes to prick comfortable intuitions. He argues, for example, that relaxing rules for doctors against helping suicides might actually lower the incentive for old people to kill themselves. An optimist, too, he is convinced that the fiscal burden of growing old in America is overstated. This unusual view he reaches with the help of "multiple selves analysis" (<font size=-1>MSA</font>)--roughly the idea that our young and old selves are so different as to be distinct people sharing the same cluster of cells. That startling notion is controversial, to say the least, even among philosophers. But Mr Posner cannot resist a new idea, however quirky, and his mind is nimble enough to bend it to his argument.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In practical terms, he defends the present system of transferring income from the younger to the older generation. He argues that keeping up a high level of income for the elderly is a way of making sure that provision for our old selves remains generous. Moreover, transfers to the old benefit the young by allowing granny and grandpa to live on their own, which both generations prefer. And if such transfers do become burdensome, a reaction will set in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Remember, Mr Posner says, what old folk bring to the party. They have paid to educate two generations. Their indifference to fashion aids social stability. They pay taxes, commit few crimes and bestow love and bequests on their descendants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Posner also kindly provides facts that undercut his benign view of America's old-age provisions. People who retired in the mid-1980s got about two-thirds more in Social Security payments than they put in; but those born after 1960 can expect to get less. Old people with money for private medicine get free Medicare; the sick working poor are out of luck. And while it may be true that America can deal with a looming old-age entitlements blow-out by delaying implementation of reform (and thus placating today's old folks), this may not be equitable. Cutting future benefits does lower working people's current tax burden--but it also ensures that their retirement will be meaner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is hard to avoid the conclusion that this generation of American pensioners has got a rare deal: they are the least likely age group in America to be poor, and the average individual on Medicare uses about $100,000-worth more than he or she contributed. There will be no such golden goose for the next generation. As Mr Posner concedes, today's young self "may be a net loser over its life span". Too right. The inter-generational contract is fraying, not because the young are ungenerous, but because too many of America's old are.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
