<html><head><title>Textbooks on CD-ROM</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr11.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<h2>Textbooks on CD-ROM</h2>
<p><b>Multimedia in education is better for college students than for school tots</b></p><ul></ul>

<p>WHEN children struggle with reading and mathematics, does it make sense to distract them with the pictures and sounds that embellish the growing number of <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s aimed at the educational market? As it becomes harder to buy a personal computer without a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> drive, more and more children are using them for games and play. But many schools, short of cash for teaching materials, wonder whether <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s in the classroom are a new-fangled way of wasting time and money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All told, sales of educational software in the United States amount to between $750m and $1 billion a year, according to Bob Broadwater of Veronis, Suhler, an American investment bank specialising in the entertainment industry. Much "edutainment" is sold directly to parents rather than to schools. The gap between education and entertainment has been narrowing. Last year Disney produced two bestselling educational titles, "Lion King Storybook" and "Aladdin Activity Centre". <font size=-1>MECC</font>, a Minnesota-based software company that specialises in educational materials, thinks the school market for educational software in 1992-93 was $570m and growing at 10-20% a year. Its home sales are roughly twice as big as its sales to schools.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While parents may be wooed by the thought of giving children something more improving to do than playing fantasy games, schools have on the whole tended to keep <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s in the library. Joan Kenny of the Educational Technology Centre at Harvard University, thinks it is a "safe estimate that 95% of computers in American classrooms do not have <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> capability." Instead, the first products that schools usually buy are encyclopedias such Grolier's or Microsoft's "Encarta", to be used on a machine in the library.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Britain, a project run by the National Council for Educational Technology (<font size=-1>NCET</font>), supported by the Department for Education, has put <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> drives and discs into about one-third of all primary schools over the past couple of years. A team from the Open University, which evaluated the project, found that teachers liked <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s much more than other sorts of information technology, and most thought that they increased children's understanding of the subjects they were studying. One of the most interesting findings was that dim or lazy children seemed to use <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s as much as the brighter youngsters and to find them an unthreatening way to learn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other educationalists are more sceptical. Harvey Mellar, of London University's Institute of Education, thinks that <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are often too complicated to set up and are not sufficiently interactive to be good teaching tools. They are bad at displaying video clips (a home-made copy of a good television programme may be more use in a classroom), and they often contain too little information for a pupil doing a research project. "If you are doing a project on 19th-century prisons, say, you might find a couple of paragraphs on a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>--but three or four books in a decent library with perhaps a chapter on the subject." Margaret Cox, at King's College London, shares some of his reservations: "the problem is that pupils often get diverted or waylaid: teachers need to do lots of preparation to make sure that they are used effectively."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How to know which educational software is best? One excellent service that does regular reviews (including testing on children) is the Children's Software Review, which can be reached on the Internet at <a href="http://www.superkids.com">http://www.superkids.com.</a> And the <font size=-1>NCET</font> produces an annual review of <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> titles in education, reachable at the following site: <a href="http://ncet.csv.warwick.ac.uk">http://ncet.csv.warwick.ac.uk</a><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Probably the most promising uses for <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s are in higher education. There, they have two big advantages over books. First, they offer a relatively inexpensive way to collate information for highly specialised disciplines. And second, they are good at simulating practical tasks, whether it be running a nuclear-power plant or flying an aeroplane. Already armchair pilots can play with flight simulators that teach them skills that only the most experienced aviators would once have possessed--and without crashing a single plane.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The interactive division of Addison-Wesley International, an educational publisher, is using <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s to attempt things textbooks cannot do, such as batching collections of physics problems or differential equations and allowing students to manipulate series of data and to change parameters to see what happens. Chip Price, who is in charge of the division, points out that 20-25% of American university students have personal computers. He thinks that textbooks may become simpler and cheaper to produce if they are combined with <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s: fancy colour illustrations are much cheaper to put on a disc than on paper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similar considerations have encouraged Churchill Livingstone, Europe's largest medical publishers, to develop the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> as an alternative to medical textbooks. To make and pack a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> costs perhaps $8-10, says Bill Marovitz, the company's chief executive (making the actual disc is, of course, far cheaper); to make and pack a textbook can cost $30-35. Runs for many medical textbooks are short: the world market for a textbook on kidney transplants might be about 10,000, which is only about 60% of the run needed to be cost-effective. Publishing on a <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> thus makes far more economic sense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s have other advantages. Increasingly, a couple of clicks of a mouse can take a user to a related Internet site, or to a data base with regularly updated articles, or to a contact point with the author. "We're starting to see a total blending between book, <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> and web-site," Mr Marovitz says. There also seems to be a blurring of medical drama and education. The company offers medical simulations on <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>, which produce a random selection of virtual patients (some of them computer-destined for the morgue) with sound-effects to mimic the confusion and distraction of a real emergency room. "You sit there and watch experienced doctors use the thing, and they start to sweat. If they lose a patient, they throw chairs across the room," says Mr Marovitz with grim satisfaction. Who needs hospital dramas on television when you can train to be a heart surgeon at home?

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
