<html><head><title>The active eye</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr12.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Understanding sight</b></p>
<h2>The active eye</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex122.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> O<font size=-1>BJECT</font> S<font size=-1>TARES</font> B<font size=-1>ACK</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By James Elkins. <br>
<li><a href="5ex123.html">O<font size=-1>N</font> B<font size=-1>LINDNESS</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Bryan Magee and Martin Milligan.<br>
<li><a href="5ex124.html">C<font size=-1>ATCHING</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> L<font size=-1>IGHT</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Arthur Zajonc.<br>
</ul>

</i>
</i>
<p>EMPEDOCLES, a Greek philosopher of the fifth century <font size=-1>BC</font>, described how the goddess Aphrodite blended earth, air, fire and water and sealed them with rivets of love to form the sphere of a human eye. Lit with divine fire, the eye shone out a fine ray that played over objects like a lantern beam. Plato was less interested in the origins than in the mechanism of sight and explained it so: light from within the eye coalesces with external daylight to form one thread along which subtle motions can pass from an object to a person and so produce the sensation of seeing. For subsequent philosophers and scientists sight has been a more passive process--photons stream into the eye but no feelers reach out from it--but artists continue to see seeing as an exchange. And so do art historians.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;James Elkins, an art historian at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago, is concerned not simply with the nature of the observer's rapacious "gaze" but with how "the object stares back". The world is full of eyes: real ones of humans or other creatures, imagined ones glimpsed in dark alleys, or false ones on peacocks' tails and butterflies' wings. Between them hang the stares and glances, loaded with expectation or hollowed out by surprise, that fascinate him. He aims to uncover more of what goes on in them by studying five forms of visual exchange: the discovery of things usually missed, sights so shocking that the eye turns from them, human readiness to see bodies, and to read faces, and, lastly, blindness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though avowedly scornful of simplifying for clarity's sake, Mr Elkins writes well. He uses powerful images. The chapter on "looking away, and seeing too much" confirms La Rochefoucauld's maxim that nobody can look directly at death or the sun with quite horrific photographs of a Chinese execution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He refers to many paintings, most of which are reproduced, but he is as good at looking generally. He ponders the struggles of early microscopists to interpret the wriggles of the animalcules they saw by analogy with bodies and organs they understood. He wonders at the bizarre Amazonian lantern fly, which has a tiny imitation of a crocodile's head growing from its own. He tells you how to detect your blindspots. His beautiful examination of the peacock's tail combines biology with artistic imagination. Constantly fascinating details of this kind challenge readers to look more closely and to notice what happens when they do. His book sets all sorts of inquiries in motion; it does not strive for answers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bryan Magee set out on a more ambitious quest. "On Blindness" opens with an exchange of letters with Martin Milligan, a philosopher who had been blind from the age of one and a half and remembered nothing of seeing. In asking Mr Milligan how he knew that he lacked a sense others had, and what his conception of this sense was, Mr Magee hoped to gain a better understanding of the nature of sight and therefore of the linkage between knowledge and experience.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The quest failed. In the course of drafting the eighth letter Mr Milligan died. But even those letters written quickly veered from the assigned task into what stands on its own as a stimulating discussion of what it is to be blind. Common misapprehensions are corrected, normal curiosities satisfied. Blindness is not darkness. Blind people's dreams are like those of the sighted: narratives of thought garlanded with sensory imagery of the sort had when awake--in the case of the blind these are sounds, kinaesthetics and "space-sense".
For the ancients, the difference was clear: for the blind the internal light which reaches out to mingle with that of the world had been extinguished. Arthur Zajonc's delightful "Catching the Light" (1993), which has recently been reissued, traces what became of this idea in a "biography" of light from the earliest mythologies to the latest quantum mysteries. It is a marvellous thread to follow. Mr Zajonc roams even more widely than Messrs Elkins, Magee and Milligan, and shows that light and the mind have always reached out to entwine each other.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
