<DOCNO>WT21-B40-362</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000279-B021-135</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/review/rev5/rv13/review.html 199.173.162.110 19970113184500 text/html 3875
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 18:41:13 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:08 GMT
Content-length: 3690
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Mouse-eye view</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>CD-ROM atlases</b></p>
<h2>Mouse-eye view</h2><ul><li>C<font size=-1>ARTOPEDIA</font></a>: <font size=-1>A</font> W<font size=-1>ORLD</font> R<font size=-1>EFERENCE</font> A<font size=-1>TLAS</font>.<br>
</ul>


<p>THIS useful <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> has a mongrel name and a hybrid nature. Its best features are the "Political World" and the country "<font size=-1>A</font> to <font size=-1>Z</font>". Together these make a richly stocked gazetteer to over 190 countries that would be hard to beat. The two differ mainly in their points of entry: the "Political World" is reached by clicking on a spot on the world map, the "<font size=-1>A</font> to <font size=-1>Z</font>" by choosing from a written index.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By either route, pick, say, Tuvalu. Up pops a finely laid-out index-card with a map and a brief description of that little country, a string of nine Pacific atolls. Click on a red megaphone and a voice says "Tuvalu" correctly in mid-Atlantic English. Hit the country-profile box and up come eight one-line tips about Tuvalu's politics and economics. A grid of 15 smaller boxes marked by easy-to-understand symbols opens a treasure box of further facts: a potted history, details on the health, wealth, background and beliefs of the people, a guide to institutions, parties and foreign relations, as well as copious economic data including placings in the United Nations development index. The country in view may be compared with any other on one of many indicators at the click of a mouse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For countries with far-flung dependencies such as America or France, a map of them all is a click from the main index card. A polyglot glossary lists scores of terms English-speakers might stumble on including "<i>wan</i>" (bay in Chinese), "<i>nosy</i>" (island in Malagasy) or "<i>gory</i>" (mountains for Russians). A list of international organisations gives refreshingly terse job-descriptions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If in greed for fact you lose your bearings, a touch on a small spinning globe pinpoints your position, or rather stops and enlarges the globe, marking the rough region you are in with a blue square. Here is a catch. The physical maps are done country by country, making it hard to follow, say, the course of rivers or mountains. A helpful "finder" rings places sought in red. A "zoom" (accompanied by a sucking noise) allows for map magnification. But scales vary widely. Some are too small. Longitude and latitude are not marked. There is no easy way to tell which, say, is farther north, New York or Beijing. In sum, this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> is a better guide to the virtual "space" of country statistics than to the three-dimensional crust charted by geographers. As an atlas, indeed, it fails.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
