<html><head><title>Read my lips</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Music on CD-ROM</b></p>
<h2>Read my lips</h2><ul><li>T<font size=-1>HE</font> A<font size=-1>RT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>INGING</font>.</a><br>
</ul>


<p>THIS disc is a chance missed. Serving more than a single sense is one of multimedia's most basic appeals. By combining sight and sound, <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> ought to be ideal for introducing reader-listeners to the art of the voice. What is a contralto? Or coloratura? How does a diva warm up? Answers in just words are dead. Matched with sung examples, words guide and sharpen the ear, making it an excitement to learn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How frustrating, therefore, to enter the "virtual" doors of The Academy of Song on this <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> and to get lost as on the first day at a school. Once "in" the study room, a vast bank of knowledge about singers and singing is available. Disappointingly, words are not accompanied by musical examples. A good musical encyclopedia would be quicker and simpler to use.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On leaving the study room, you can "visit" stars' dressing rooms. Click on the make-up mirror and a famous singer's head appears to talk. To get Joan Sutherland's recorded voice you must first decorate her room correctly with swatches of fabric from a clothes chest. Tottering back frame-by-frame through imaginary halls like a tipsy minicam operator, you may with luck reach a box office offering "tickets" to sung concert snatches. This electronically challenged reviewer asked for Schubert and got Mozart.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Learning and looking up need not be chores. But must they be games? The <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> has marvellous potential not realised here. "The Art of Singing" is done with visual imagination and technical skill. But the hoped-for marriage of sight and sound goes unconsummated.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
