<html><head><title>Not a nice man</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr15.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Great pianists</b></p>
<h2>Not a nice man</h2><ul><li>A<font size=-1>RTHUR</font> R<font size=-1>UBINSTEIN</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Harvey Sachs. <br>
</ul>

<p>THE world no longer produces musicians like Arthur Rubinstein. Born in 1887, he learnt his art in the shadow of Paderewski, Busoni and other great 19th-century pianists, not forgetting his namesake, Anton. He did not take on their mantle until his 40s, just as the technologies of recording and broadcasting were turning virtuosi into stars.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Polyglot, cosmopolitan and erudite, Rubinstein belonged to a vanishing species of performer. He loved travelling, he was witty and he was a tireless womaniser. Most of all, he was an exceptionally gifted musician, and this was not really a question of technique. Rubinstein, who called practising scales "cleaning the teeth of the piano", used to simplify some of the harder pieces. His gift was an astonishing and by all accounts inborn musicianship.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This natural facility got him out of many scrapes. At a rehearsal of Tchaikovsky's first piano concerto under the baton of his future father-in-law, Emil Mlynarski, Rubinstein was slapdash and confused. Afterwards he confessed that he had not seen the score of the concerto, but thought he knew it well enough. An unimpressed Mlynarski thrust a copy at Rubinstein, who devoted an afternoon's practice to the work. That evening he gave a brilliant performance. "If only Arthur wanted to work really hard," the conductor later complained, "he would be the best pianist in the world."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That was in 1915. After his marriage in 1932, Rubinstein began to work harder, though he later warned a student: "Never practise more than three or four hours a day." And this effort added discipline to what was always the most memorable aspect of Rubinstein's playing, his ability to interpret a piece. Even at his last concert, when Rubinstein was aged 89 and too blind to be able to see the keyboard, he was still capable of delivering Chopin's Scherzo No. 2 in what a London critic called "a performance, for all its passing and forgettable inaccuracies, of satanic energy and force".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A bourgeois Jew from Lodz, an industrial town in Poland, the young Rubinstein soon left his family behind. His friends in Poland included Szymanowski, one of several contemporary composers--Villa-Lobos was another--whose music Rubinstein championed. Before and after the first world war, the pianist befriended other composers such as Stravinsky and Milhaud; and in the London house of his friend Muriel Draper, a society hostess, he performed impromptu chamber music with the likes of Casals and Ysaye.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though Rubinstein did a memoir of his own, it is patchy and confusing, and this biography from Harvey Sachs aims to fill gaps. Some of its new information is useful and interesting, particularly a chapter based on interviews with members of his family that brings out the costs of living with self-centred brilliance. "From one minute to the next," one of them remembers, "he could change completely and do disastrous, demonic things."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rubinstein was cruelly inconsiderate, as well as vain. Part of his wedding afternoon he spent with another woman. Fear of being heard to snore or fart kept him from actually sleeping with any of his many mistresses, or so he explained to a puzzled daughter. At 89 abandoned his wife of 44 years and moved in with a 31-year-old Englishwoman.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Too often, though, the personal detail is trivial and does not even make for good gossip. The discovery, for example, that Rubinstein had an affair with Mrs Y in July 1924 and not, as he wrote, with Miss Z in March 1922 will fail to divert even pedants. Research of that kind does not justify a new biography, particularly one that fails for all its length to explain the sudden creation of the Rubinstein legend, which began only in his middle years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rubinstein and his contemporaries--Heifetz, Horowitz, Furtw&aumlt;ngler--grew up at the end of a late-Romantic era in which great musicians were treated as domineering immortals. Today's more down-to-earth musical world is crowded with polished and technically brilliant performers, women as well as men, and the words "legend" or "genius" are less often heard. Soloists nowadays are thrust into the competitive limelight much younger than they used to be. A public almost spoiled for choice in the number of top-flight performers is much less minded to deify them. What do these changes amount to? Rubinstein straddled both worlds. But Mr Sachs fails to draw out of his life interesting answers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor does Mr Sachs's emphasis on the personal side carry conviction. Not long before his death in 1982, Rubinstein told some fellow musicians, "I am really not a very nice person. I have a bad character. Just ask my family--they will tell you. But when it comes to the music, the music--ah, that is where I have total integrity."

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
