<html><head><title>Eaten every one</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="5gr16.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Shellfish</b></p>
<h2>Eaten every one</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex112.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> E<font size=-1>NGLISH</font>, T<font size=-1>HE</font> F<font size=-1>RENCH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> O<font size=-1>YSTER</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Robert Neild. <br>
</ul>

<p>STATISTICS, like shellfish, are not always reliable. But each year France is estimated to fill its collective belly with 2 billion home-grown oysters, while Britain can force down only a few million. It was not ever thus. In the 1850s Britons ate 500m oysters a year, roughly what their <i>fr&egrave;res ennemis</i> across the Channel were consuming during the 1870s. In explaining (and lamenting) Britain's oyster decline, Robert Neild, a noted British economist, offers a cautionary tale: here, you are told, is what is worst about <i>laisser-faire</i> Britain and best about <i>dirigiste</i> France.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a way Mr Neild is right. During the good years oysters were so abundant that, as Sam Weller put it in the "Pickwick Papers" of Charles Dickens, "poverty and oysters always seems to go together". Britain's oyster catch had failed by the 1880s because the government did not intervene to prevent disease and over-fishing. For a while, imports from America helped satisfy demand. But at the beginning of this century, sewage got into the British oyster beds. Local authorities did almost nothing to improve hygiene. There were deaths, newspaper articles and a gradual collapse in demand, from which British oyster-farming never recovered.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 19th-century France, by contrast, the authorities preserved oyster beds by limiting oyster-fishing. Later, oystermen were encouraged to husband beds with the grant of concessions to trained cultivators and over the years new methods were readily fostered with state help. France coped with sewage (which was less of a problem, because most oyster beds are farther away from the big towns than in Britain) by setting up a labelling system for oysters. Mr Neild is so impressed that, like the juice of a lemon, the name of Jean-Baptiste Colbert, a minister of Louis XIV and successful champion of economic regulation, is freely sprinkled throughout.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Halfway down, however, Mr Neild's parable catches in the throat. The oyster's main enemy in Britain was not an absence of state help, but one error and two constitutional confusions. The error--soon put right--was to deny that over-fishing was a threat to oysters. The confusions involved the ownership of the foreshore (an oyster farmer must own his shellfish if farming is to begin) and the balance of powers between central and local government (a struggle in which dealing with pollution became a part). The fault, if anything, lay in Britain's class-system, because in all three matters its poor oyster-fishermen were routinely disregarded.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
