<html><head><title>Where the truth lies</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>


<p><b>Fiction from India</b></p>
<h2>Where the truth lies</h2><ul><li><a href="5ex108.html">A F<font size=-1>INE</font> B<font size=-1>ALANCE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Rohinton Mistry. <br>
<li><a href="5ex110.html">H<font size=-1>EM</font> &amp; M<font size=-1>AXINE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Nalinashka Bhattacharaya. <br>
<li><a href="5ex109.html">S<font size=-1>TEPS</font> F<font size=-1>ROM</font> P<font size=-1>ARADISE</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Timeri Murari. <br>
<li><a href="5ex117.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> H<font size=-1>EART</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> I<font size=-1>NDIA</font>.</a>&nbsp;  By Mark Tully. <br>
</ul><ul></ul>


MOMENTOUS times, momentous events, momentous fictions. In Victorian England, in pre-revolutionary Russia, in depressed America, in contemporary South America, it is the fiction writers who tell "the truth". People should trust novelists against historians, trust the human imagination against statistics, facts and political speeches.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Read the superb fiction emanating from the sub-continent in recent years, and you begin to understand how an American chemical company can be allowed to spread death and disease in Bhopal or how the Indian army could incinerate the holiest of Sikh shrines. After riots at a recent World Cup cricket match between India and Sri Lanka, two spectators killed themselves. These big and small tragedies do not seem incredible at all if you read the novels of Salman Rushdie or Vikram Seth, the short stories of Prem Chand or Ruth Prawer Jhabvala, or Rohinton Mistry's masterpiece. In the epigraph to "A Fine Balance", he cites Balzac's "Le P&egrave;re Goriot":

<ul><font size=-1>After you have read the story of great misfortunes, you will no doubt dine well, blaming the author for your own insensitivity, accusing him of wild exaggeration and flights of fancy. But... this tragedy is not a fiction. All is true.</font></ul>"A Fine Balance" has a high body count. There are two deaths by bus crushing, deaths by torture of untouchables exercising their voting rights and of a student revolutionary, deaths by stabbing of a beggar-master and of two of his beggars (for their luxuriant hair), the triple suicide by hanging themselves from a <i>punkah</i> of three young sisters, and finally the death of a man who has come through but who nevertheless throws himself under a train. Those who survive sudden death lose their legs, their testicles, their hair, their homes and everything that makes them human--except their spirit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is unusual to read the lives of those who have nothing told without condescension. "India lives in her 700,000 villages" said Mahatma Gandhi, and, even as the village culture breaks down, a foreigner can best understand the lives of the townspeople if he learns about the villages they come from. "A Fine Balance" moves from villages to cities, and returns the reader, a little wiser and a good deal sadder, to the villages again at the end.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The story is straightforward. Two tailors, Ishvar and Omprakash, uncle and nephew, untouchables but keen to improve themselves, travel to the city to find work. On the train they engage in sporadic conversation with Maneck, the son of privileged parents, whose business, a village shop selling home-made cola, is unable to compete with the fast-food chains. Maneck is to study refrigeration and air conditioning at college. The tailors hope to find work with Dina Dalal, a Parsi widow, whose eyes are no longer sharp enough to do the work herself. It is to Dina's house that Maneck is also travelling, for it is intended that he should become her paying guest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The history of these four, their struggles to survive grabbing landlords, corrupt bureaucrats, savage policemen and cynical government form the substance of the book. As Dina works away at a patchwork quilt made up of off-cuts, so the patchwork of the grand events, the emergency, the cynical "beautification" of the cities, the enforced family planning, are intricately sewn together with the lives of those they affect. They include a monkeyman inconsolable for the loss of his monkeys, a rent collector, a garrulous lawyer, a family-planning motivator--his story alone would make a substantial novel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The style is detached, humorous and symbolic. But it is hard to take comfort in Mr Mistry's magnificent novel, despite its generosity: it is too true.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After such recent novels as Vikram Seth's "A Suitable Boy", Vikram Chandra's "Red Earth and Pouring Rain" and Salman Rushdie's "The Moor's Last Sigh", the reader might be forgiven for thinking that there is little more to be said about the subcontinent, past or present. Yet there remains a cheerful dottiness, exemplified in the books of Nalinashka Bhattacharaya and Timeri Murari.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Hem &amp; Maxine" is a sequel to "Hem &amp; Football", and features the same improbable heroine, who is to Bengali women's soccer what Indira Gandhi was to Indian politics. As far as can be ascertained, Hem owes the scars on her face to the violence of Babu, her husband, confined to a psychiatric ward, as well as to the uninhibited play of opposing forwards. The Rani Jhansi Club has as its trainer a redoubtable Marxist, Miss Nag, recently returned from re-education in Hungary.
<ul><font size=-1>Chaudhury, our fat ever-smiling general secretary about the utmost neccessity of a protein-rich tiffin whenever those two functionaries came to watch our performances.</font></ul>Hem's adventures include a desk job with the local mafia, a stint in a women's prison in which she is energetically raped, a period in Mrs Blistop's Calcutta Finishing School ("or husband-catching academy") and a lesbian marriage. The novel, which is politically incorrect in most particulars, is a Candide-like telling of Hem's adventures as she attempts to blackmail Gour Basak, an <font size=-1>MP</font> with improper designs upon her, and to satisfy her own desires for Mrs Basak, an aristocratic memsahib with a secret past.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The weakness of the novel is a first person narrative, which requires Hem to know a great deal about people and about Louis XVI spindle-back chairs which she could not possibly know, but its strength is its irresistible irreverence. Football, political corruption, Calcutta society, the intricacies of the volley pass: "Hem &amp; Maxine" is absurdly entertaining.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Timeri Murari, author of historical novels and such sari-rippers as "Lovers are not People", has a new novel. "Steps From Paradise" covers the same period as "A Fine Balance", and concerns itself with the inruption of an English step-mother into the vast estate of a powerful Madras family. The style is clich&eacute;d and ridiculous, but no more so than the hugely popular extravaganzas that are shown in Indian cinemas. Surrender to the "indolent eyelids" and "pretty wrinkled noses" of the women, and enjoy the self-confident sweep of the story.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mark Tully's "The Heart of India" is a series of short stories, set in Uttar Pradesh. Mr Tully was born in Calcutta and holds Indian citizenship. But though these stories are disguised as fiction, he had them certified by a friend: "Yes, it could have happened like that." Giveaways are the glossary of Indian terms and the implication that Mr Tully is acting as an intermediary between village life in India and the British literary establishment. There could be no better go-between, as his broadcasting work shows. Disappointingly, his stories are more observed than experienced.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><font size=-1><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
