<html><head><title>What the world is reading</title></head><body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><br><h2>What the world is reading</h2><p>AMERICA's two top sellers are about trials: in-court of O.J. Simpson, out-of-court of Bill Clinton. Most other top books are about improving the inner or outer person. British readers stay true to type: pets, military reminiscences, Jane Austen and two flops (a royal marriage and a grand bank) are the spring's non-fiction topics.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The late President Mitterrand still sells books in France. But new bestsellers on Bosnia and on Albert Camus, a great mid-century writer, suggest the Mitterrand wave may be cresting. German women are reading tips for handling bosses and husbands. <i>Nabelschau </i>(navel-gazing) remains popular: self-betterment favourites include natural, lunar and Tibetan tips for healthy living.<br><h3>Non-fiction bestsellers<a href="#foot">*</a></h3><ul><li><a href="#usa">United States</a><li><a href="#br">Britain</a><li><a href="#fr">France</a><li><a href="#gr">Germany</a></ul></td></tr></table><a name="usa"><br></a><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td><hr size=5 width=70 align=left><h4>United States</h4><ol><li>In Contempt<i> by Christopher Darden</i>. &#160; An account of O.J. Simpson trial</li><li>Blood Sport<i> by James Stewart</i>. &#160; The Clintons and Whitewater</li><li>Men are from Mars, Women are from Venus<i> by John Gray</i>. &#160; Re