<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A<font size=-1>UTOPSY</font> <font size=-1>ON</font> <font size=-1>AN</font> E<font size=-1>MPIRE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Jack Matlock. <br>
<i>Random House; 836 pages; $40</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5jb66.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>

JACK F. MATLOCK, JR., was the American ambassador to the Soviet Union
from 1987 to 1991. First posted to Moscow in 1961, when he reported
Khrushchev's de-Stalinization policy and the Cuban Missile Crisis and
translated the Kenned Khrushchev correspondence, he has spent eleven his
thirty-f1ve years in the American Foreign Service in the Soviet Union. As
special assistant to the president from 1983 to 1986, he formulated Ronald
Reagan's negotiating approach to the Soviet Union Matlock has received
numerous awards for k service, including the Wilbur J. Carr Award. He
currently the Kathryn and Shelby Cullom Davis Professor in the Practice of
International Diploma at Columbia University.<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
