<html><head><title>The Last Hundred Days of the Soviet Union.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl64.jpg"><img src="cs64.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> L<font size=-1>AST</font> H<font size=-1>UNDRED </font>D<font size=-1>AYS OF THE </font>S<font size=-1>OVIET</font> U<font size=-1>NION</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Boris Pankin. <br>
<i>I.B. Tauris; 288 pages; &#163;19.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5bt64.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

When Boris Pankin, Soviet Ambassador in Prague, received a call from
Mikhail Gorbachev in late August 1991, he did not know what to expect. As
one of the only Soviet diplomats to denounce the Moscow putsch immediately
and unequivocally well before it collapsed, Pankin knew that Gorbachev had
appreciated the stance he had taken. But he certainly did not expect the offer
Gorbachev made to him: to become the new Foreign Minister of the USSR,
inheriting the mantle of Vishinsky, Molotov and Gromyko.
<p>Pankin was Foreign Minister in the last days of the Soviet Union. While an empire was crumbling around him, Pankin's job was to project the continuity of Soviet power and influence, and at the same time to present the new post- totalitarian face of his country to the world.</p>
<p>This extraordinary memoir provides important new information and fresh insights into political and diplomatic activities in the crucial last three months of Soviet life: the Madrid Middle East Peace Conference, which Pankin co- chaired; the US-Soviet disarmament process; the evaporation of East Germany and the redefinition of relations with Eastern Europe; the reassessment of Moscow's attitudes towards the USA, Western Europe, the Arab world, Israel, Afghanistan, Japan, Africa and Cuba. Pankin presided over Soviet foreign policy during the strangest period of his country's history. In the process, he came to know well all of the world's most important leaders.</p>
<p>A memoir replete with fascinating insights on, and anecdotes about, John Major, George Bush, Boris Yeltsin, Mikhail Gorbachev, Vaclav Havel, Yasser Arafat, Yitzhak Shamir, and others, The Last Hundred Days of the Soviet Union offers a unique perspective on three months when the world changed beyond all recognition.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
