<html><head><title>In Confidence</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl67.jpg"><img src="cs67.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>I<font size=-1>N</font> C<font size=-1>ONFIDENCE</font>:<br> M<font size=-1>OSCOW'S</font> A<font size=-1>MBASSADOR</font> <font size=-1>TO</font> A<font size=-1>MERICA'S</font> S<font size=-1>IX</font> C<font size=-1>OLD</font> W<font size=-1>AR</font> P<font size=-1>RESIDENTS</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Anatoly Dobrynin.<br>
<i> Random House; 672 pages; $30</i><br>
</p><br>
<b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

ANATOLY DOBRYNIN arrived in Washington in 1962. He was only forty-
three, the youngest man ever to serve as Soviet ambassador to the United
States. Amazingly, he remained in Washington through the presidencies of
Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, and Reagan. Dobrynin became the
main back channel for the White House and the Kremlin to exchange ideas,
negotiate in secret, and set up sumrnit meetings. This arrangement became
known as the confidential channel. Through this channel and his more public
duties as ambassador he came to know the presidents, their most senior
officials, and many members of the American establishment intimately. In
Confidence is the story of those relationships.
<p>Although Dobrynin writes vividly of Moscow from inside the Politburo, In Confidence is mainly a story of Washington at the highest levels. Dobrynin was master of his job. Big and hearty, he made presidents and secretaries of state feel that he understood their problems. Even in the chilliest moments of the Cold War, Dobrynin was never personally blamed. From Dean Rusk to Robert McNamara and from Henry Kissinger to George Shultz, Dobrynin worked among the major players of American government nearly as though he were one of them.</p>
<p>There were few major events of the sixties, seventies, or eighties in which Dobrynin did not have a hand or for which he did not have a ringside seat. Among the material that appears for the first time here are Dobrynin's account of the Cuban Missile Crisis, which reveals that the deadlock was finally broken when a deal was quietly cut to withdraw American missiles from Turkey. Dobrynin was the man who informed Lyndon Johnson that the Sovirt Union had invaded Czechoslovakia, and witnessed the president's oblivious reaction to the news. Dobrynin recounts the tortured history of the Vietnam War, and of Moscow's inability to influence Hanoi. He explains how Moscow stumbled into Afghanistan. His descriptions of the Reagan administration's arms buildup and of his own meetings with Ronald Reagan are indispensable to any understanding of the end of the Cold War.</p>
<p>In Confidence is full of revelations that give us new insight into our own history, as well as into the saga of Soviet-American relations. To write it, Dobrynin spent months reviewing his own contemporary no and official dispatches, as well as extensive material the Foreign Ministry archives in Moscow. His memoir is an eyewitness document no student of the twentieth century can afford to miss.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
