<html><head><title>They Only Look Dead</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl115.jpg"><img src="cs115.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HEY</font> O<font size=-1>NLY</font> L<font size=-1>OOK</font> D<font size=-1>EAD</font>:<br> W<font size=-1>HY</font> P<font size=-1>ROGRESSIVES</font> W<font size=-1>ILL</font> D<font size=-1>OMINATE</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> N<font size=-1>EXT</font> P<font size=-1>OLITICAL</font> E<font size=-1>RA</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By E. J. Dionne Jr. <br>
<i>Simon &amp; Schuster; 352 pages; $24.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5bt115.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

In a bold and engaging challenge to the conventional wisdom, the award
winning E. J. Dionne Jr. shows why American politics is headed not toward the
right, as so many believe, but toward a New Progressive Era. They Only Look
Dead is a shrewd and eye-opening chronicle of what has happened to American
politics in the era of Bill Clinton and Newt Gingrich. It is also an eloquent call
upon Democratic liberals and centrists, moderate Republicans and political
independents to forge a reform-minded political movement aimed at dealing
with the country's real economic and moral anxieties.
<p>Dionne, the author of the best-selling Why Americans Hate Politics, again demonstrates his special feeling for the disaffected voter, stressing the importance of America's "Anxious Middle," which is the motive force behind calls for third parties and support for Colin Powell and Ross Perot. He explains that America's political chaos--including the nastiness of the advertising, the relentless scandalmongering and the disrepute of politicians--is not the result of a whining electorate. Rather, he writes, Americans are responding to four genuine crises--in economics, in politics, in morality and in the country's understanding of its role in the world. His provocative but fair-minded evocation of these crises will set the terrns of debate for liberals, moderates and conservatives alike.</p>
<p>With flair and wit, Dionne dissects the "dysfunctional Democrats" and shows how Democratic failures, not a surge toward conservatism, accounted for the 1994 President Clinton, will regain their drive and coherence only by embracing their historic commitment to America's Progressive project.</p>
<p>Looking behind the sound bites and the negative ads, Dionne examines the little-noticed "Quiet Revolution" in the Republican Party and the thinkers and strategists who created it. He provides the clearest and most compelling look to date at where Newt Gingrich's ideas come from.</p>
<p>Dionne's Why Americans Hate Politics foresaw the major themes of the campaigns of Bill Clinton and Ross Perot in 1992, and predicted trouble for George Bush. In the same spirit, They Only Look Dead takes us beneath the surface and beyond the tired punditry to show how rumors of the death of liberalism have been greatly exaggerated. It shows once again that things are not what they seem. It will be the essential book of 1996.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
