<html><head><title>Monarchy and Matrimony</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl54.jpg"><img src="cs54.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>M<font size=-1>ONARCHY</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> M<font size=-1>ATRIMONY</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>HE</font> C<font size=-1>OURTSHIPS</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> E<font size=-1>LIZABETH</font> I.<br></h2>
<p> By Susan Doran. <br>
<i>Routledge; 296 pages; &#163;25 and $29.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

MONARCHY &amp; MATRIMONY
THE COURTSHIPS OF ELIZABETH I
<p>Susan Doran examines in detail the different suits for Elizabeth I's hand from her childhood until 1581 when she was considered too old for childbearing and consequently for marriage.</p>
<p>She places each courtship within its political context and explains the ultimate failure of the negotiations and the effects this had on the reign. The principal suitors include Robert Dudley, Archduke Charles of Austria, Charles IX of France, Henry of Anjou, and Francis, Duke of Alencon and Anjou.</p>
<p>Monarchy and Matrimony concludes that the existing historiography on the subject is unsatisfactory. Contrary to conventional thinking, Elizabeth took each of her suitors seriously and did not choose to remain single. Her courtships foundered on political and religious difficulties which divided her council.</p>
<p>Those interested in Elizaberh or in the history of England in this period will find this account of her marriage attempts of critical interest.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
