<html><head><title>Bertrand RUSSELL</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl120.jpg"><img src="cs120.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>B<font size=-1>ERTRAND </font>R<font size=-1>USSELL:<br></font> T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>PIRIT OF </font>S<font size=-1>OLITUDE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Ray Monk. <br>
<i>Jonathan Cape; 700 pages; &#163;25</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5bt120.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

BERTRAND RUSSELL is one of the most remarkable figures of the twentieth
century. Intellectually, his achievements in logic and mathematics have
established him as one of its key thinkers. Politically, he will be remembered as
the inspiration behind several waves of popular protest. He is still widely read,
indeed perhaps the only great philosopher ever to have reached a genuinely
wide audience.
<p>The Spirit of Solitude is the first volume of a biography that seeks to describe Russell's intellectual achievements, his political work and his tortured emotional life in a single narrative, in such a way as to shed new light on all three. Russell's philosophy, treated perfunctorily in existing biographies, is here explained fully and yet readably and accessibly, placed in the context of the most searching examination of his character yet published. Rich in quotation, the book allows Russell's personality, in all its contradictions--the fear of loneliness and his retreat into emotional isolation, the demand for logical clarity and the emotional attraction towards mysticism and religious faith, the optimistic rationalism and the obsessive fear of madness--to reveal itself. It is the product of over five years' research into Russell's vast oeuvre of published work and into the original documents--letters, manuscripts and papers--that Russsell left behind. Many of these sources used have previously been unpublished, including hitherto embargoed letters to his lover Constance Malleson and his second wife, Dora.</p>
<p>The personality that is thus revealed is complex, passionate and occasionally disturbing, justifying Russell's own apparently odd remark that, of all the characters in fiction, the one closest to him was the murderously jealous figure of Rogojin in Dostoevsky's The Idiot. Perhaps the greatest achievement of the book is to show how such a person could be, at one and the same time, a man whose passions are Dostoevskian in their intensity and the co-author of Principia Mathematica.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
