<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> R<font size=-1>ISE OF</font> W<font size=-1>ESTERN</font> C<font size=-1>HRISTENDOM</font>:<br> T<font size=-1>RIUMPH</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> D<font size=-1>IVERSITY</font>, <font size=-1>AD</font> 200-1000.<br></h2>
<p> By Peter Brown. <br>
<i>Blackwell; 353 pages; &#163;20 and $24.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5jb106.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>

Peter Brown is Rollins Professor of History at Princeton University, before
which he has been Reader in History at the University of Oxford, Professor of
History at Royal Holloway, University of London, and Professor of History and
Classics at the University of California, Berkeley. He is a Fellow of the
American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Royal Historical Society.
His previous books include: The Cult of the Saints: its rise and function in
Latin Christianity (1980); Society and the Holy in Late Antiquity (1982); The
Body and Society; men, women and sexual renunciation in Early Christianity
(1989) and Power and Persuasian in Late Antiquity: towards a Christian Empire
(1992).<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
