<html><head><title>The Weight of the Yen.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl118.jpg"><img src="cs118.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> W<font size=-1>EIGHT</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> Y<font size=-1>EN</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By R. Taggart Murphy. <br>
<i>Norton; 352 pages; $25</i>. 
<br>Published in Britain as T<font size=-1>HE</font> R<font size=-1>EAL</font> P<font size=-1>RICE</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> J<font size=-1>APANESE</font> M<font size=-1>ONEY</font>. 
<br><i>Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson; 288 pages; &#163;20</i></br></br><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5bt118.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

As an investment banker in Tokyo in the 1980s, R. Taggart Murphy had a
ringside view of one of the greatest transfers of credit in history as in seven
short years from 1981 to 1988 America turned itsclf from the world's greatest
creditor nation to the world's greatest debtor.
<p>The Real Price of Japanese Money tells the story of how postwar Japan accumulated its vast surplus; of Japanese financial strategy, and why the Japanese do not give up overseas markets even when they are losing money; of the powerful business alliances and affiliations in which loyalty is exchanged for security and protection; of the conditions of life for the ordinary Japanese; of America's desperate need in 1981 for credit, as the new Reagan government cut taxes but not spending; of the 1987 stock market crash, as Japanese investors saw no end to the dollar depreciation; of Japan's 'bubble economy', thc financial chaos, and the frenzy and glitter of late eightiesTokyo; of post- bubble Japan, whose industries are still dominant and fully competitive on world markets despite the acute problems of the financial sector; and of the resounding failure of America to deal with its huge trade deficit with Japan.</p>
<p>The real price of Japan's loans to America is the loss of much of America's manufacturing base, the inability to generate good jobs forAmericans, and a collapse of confidence in the dollar. The Japanese people have paid a heavy price too. Perhaps at last they will begin to insist that their companies, their banks, their bureaucracies, their schools and their politicians serve them, and not the other way around.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
