<html><head><title>A Fine Balance.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl108.jpg"><img src="cs108.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>A F<font size=-1>INE</font> B<font size=-1>ALANCE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Rohinton Mistry. <br>
<i>Faber; 614 pages; &#163;15.99. Knopf; $26.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="5jb108.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>

Rohinton Mistry was born in Bombay in 1952 and has lived in Canada since
1975. He is the author of a collection of short stories, Tales From Firozsha
Baag, and a novel, Such a Long Journey, which was shortlisted for the Booker
Prize and won the Commonwealth Writers Prize for Best Book, the Governor
General's Award and the W.H. Smith/Books in Canada First Novel Award. A
Fine Balance is Rohinton Mistry's second novel.<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
