<html><head><title>Hem &amp; Maxine.</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl110.jpg"><img src="cs110.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>H<font size=-1>EM</font> &amp; M<font size=-1>AXINE</font>.<br></h2>
<p> By Nalinashka Bhattacharaya. <br>
<i>Jonathan Cape; 320 pages; &#163;10.99.</i><br>
</p><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>

IN HIS FIRST NOVEL, Hem and Football, Nalinaksha Bhattacharya
introduced one of the most irresistible comic character in modern fiction, Hem,
the Calcutta schoolgirl obsessed with playing women's football.
<p>In his new novel Hem is back, older and wiser, now a star player with the Rani Jhansi club. But the club's finances are in bad shape and when Gour Basak, a lecherous MP, takes a fancy to Hem, she is dispatched to his tea plantation to do her duty. Hem does not succumb to Mr Basak's advances; she has eyes only for Maxine, Mr Basak's pukka memsahib wife.</p>
<p>A pulsating tale of interracial lesbianism and Bengali women's football, Hem and Maxine is a delicious comic novel by an extremely talented writer. As Time Out said of Hem and Football, 'The style, humour and sheer raw energy of this novel remind one of Roddy Doyle's The Commitments; the two books share cheekiness and vitality that transcend race and nationality.'</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
