<html><head><title>The Most Dangerous Man in Detroit</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl5.jpg"><img src="cs5.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>OST</font> D<font size=-1>ANGEROUS</font> M<font size=-1>AN</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> D<font size=-1>ETROIT</font><br></h2>
<p>By Nelson Lichtenstein.<br>
<i>HarperCollins Basic Books; 575 pages; $35</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt5.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>"In an ideal union of scholarship and literature, Nelson Lichtenstein properly places labor leader Walter Reuther in the center of the most important social and political movements of the twentieth century. This is an important book." - JULIAN BOND
</p><p>A stirring biography of a hero in the struggle for economic justice, this book probes the question: Whatever happened to labor liberalism in America?
</p><p>Walter Reuther, the most imaginative and powerful trade union leader of the past half-century, confronted the same problems facing millions of working Americans today: how to use the spectacular productivity of our economy to sustain and improve the standard of living and security of ordinary Americans. As Nelson Lichtenstein observes, Reuther, the president of the United Automobile Workers from 1946 to 1970, may not have had all the answers, but at least he was asking the right questions.
</p><p>Reuther was a visionary who sought to link working-class power with government authority to equalize the balance of power between rich and poor. "Management has no divine rights," he once declared. Its jealously guarded "prerogatives" were but "usurpations of power and privelege to which no group of men have exclusive right in a democratic nation." Reuther put this vision to the test in two great battles during the 1940s: the fight to convert Detroit to aircraft production a year before Pearl Harbor, and the long strike against General Motors in 194546 that sought wage increases without a rise in the price of cars.
</p><p>The Most Dangerous Man in Detroit vividly recounts Reuther's remarkable ascent: his days as a skilled worker at Henry Ford's great River Rouge complex, his two-year odyssey in the Soviet Union's infant auto industry in the early 1930s, and his immersion in the violent labor upheavals of the last 1930s that gave rise to the CIO. Under Reuther, the autoworkers' standard of living doubled.
</p><p>But as this biography poignantly reveals, Reuther grew increasingly frustrated, imprisoned within a stolid union structure he himself had done much to forge. In the early 1950s the dynamic and experimental character of American trade unionism gave way to an increasingly routine process of collective bargaining. Reuther, once renowned for his militance, found himself fending off attacks from disgruntled workers, both black and white. While championing the cause of civil rights, Reuther was so dependent on his ties to President Lyndon Johnson and the Democratic Party that he failed to challenge the escalation of the Vietnam War, not could he do much to stop the deindustrialization of urban America or the stagnation of the labor movement, <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
