<html><head><title>Gallant loser</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Walter Reuther</b></p>
<h2>Gallant loser</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex5.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>OST</font> D<font size=-1>ANGEROUS</font> M<font size=-1>AN</font> <font size=-1>IN</font> D<font size=-1>ETROIT</font></a>&nbsp; By Nelson Lichtenstein.<br>
</ul>


<p>IN THE 1950s Walter Reuther, leader of the 1.6m United Auto Workers (<font size=-1>UAW</font>), was hailed as the prophet of the brave new world of industrial relations in which progressive employers would work harmoniously with democratic unions. In 1955 the<i> Daily Herald</i>, a left-wing British newspaper, greeted him as "the Pied Piper of Hope", the bringer of "the American dream, the dawn of the era when social peace and plenty are inseparable."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much effort was put into selling this vision of what Nelson Lichtenstein calls "a mythic industrial landscape". But 40 years later American trade unionism is in sorry shape. The proportion of American wage- earners represented by a union has fallen from 30% to 17%. In the upper mid-west, where the <font size=-1>UAW</font> was once a political giant, plant closures and deunionisation have stripped it of 600,000 members.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What was once the most powerful industrial empire in the world is now the "rust belt", albeit past its rustiest. The <font size=-1>UAW</font>'s vision of social and racial harmony is in tatters. Opposition to busing and other liberal measures long ago turned Macomb County, where Detroit car workers live, from a Democratic stronghold into a conservative Republican fief.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Corporate spokesmen and some union officials claim that "flexible" working has brought a new democracy into American industrial relations. Many union stalwarts disagree. For them the trendy new production methods are nothing better than a subtle version of the hated speed-up. Mr Lichtenstein shows that the picture of constructive co-operation between enlightened employers and responsible unions was only briefly and partially true. The Big Three car makers--Chrysler, Ford and General Motors (<font size=-1>GM</font>)--fought with all their might to resist the union's demands for much of Reuther's 40 years in Detroit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1950 <font size=-1>GM</font> did negotiate with Reuther what <i>Fortune</i> called "the treaty of Detroit", guaranteeing its workers a 20% wage rise over five years. Reuther himself called this "the most significant development in labour relations since the mass production industries were organised." The <i>New York Times</i> thought he had put himself on the road to the White House. But the win was illusory. Inflation ate away at the rise. And, as Daniel Bell, then an industrial journalist, wrote, "<font size=-1>GM</font> paid a billion for peace, but it got a bargain", as employers got back control over key management functions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason America's labour movement could not change relations of power in industry, Mr Lichtenstein argues, is that it failed to build durable political alliances. Reuther's father was an immigrant German socialist; he himself was a member of the Socialist Party until 1938 and at one time close to, perhaps briefly even in, the Communist Party. From 1933 to 1935 he and his brother Victor worked at a tractor plant in the Soviet Union. His enemies never failed to quote a letter the youthful Victor wrote full of callow enthusiasm for Soviet industrialisation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reuther was badly beaten by thugs from Ford's "service department" in 1937. (He was also wounded in a Mafia assassination attempt.) Yet he became a symbol of anti-communist unionism and a hero for anti-communist, pro-cold-war liberals, even though he differed sharply from the conservative leader of the American Federation of Labour, George Meany, over the Vietnam war, which Reuther first tried to defend, then found an embarrassment. He was killed in a plane crash in 1970.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like any effective labour leader, Reuther was tactically flexible. But Mr Lichtenstein's important (if occasionally careless) study argues that he never swerved for long from his never-realised goal of a liberal-labour alliance in politics, outside or inside the Democratic Party. Mr Lichtenstein argues persuasively that the causes of his failure lay not in his personal shortcomings but in the racial conflicts that tormented Detroit, divided the unions and frustrated the Democratic Party in the 1960s.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
