<html><head><title>Not repeatable</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr6.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>British history</b></p>
<h2>Not repeatable</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex24.html">G<font size=-1>LADSTONE</font></a>&nbsp; By Roy Jenkins.<br>
</ul>


<p>IN THE course of a long life, William Ewart Gladstone read 20,000 books and pamphlets. He had a full command of ancient Greek and Latin and in his old age translated Horace. Among modern languages, he spoke French, German and Italian fluently (if not always grammatically) and at the age of 76 embarked on Norwegian. He was a considerable amateur theologian, with books to his credit on the relations between church and state, the Homeric basis of Christianity and the works of an 18th-century divine, Bishop Butler. He numbered among his friends Lords Acton and Tennyson, Cardinals Manning and Newman, John Bright, Arthur Hallam, John Morley, Sidney Herbert and (sometimes) Arthur Balfour. Among his adversaries he numbered Queen Victoria, Benjamin Disraeli and Joseph Chamberlain (roughly in that order).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First elected to Parliament in 1832, he served with one short break till 1895, representing constituencies as diverse as Newark (then a rotten, or certainly over-ripe, borough), Oxford University, South Lancashire and Midlothian; and he dominated the House of Commons during at least half that time. He achieved junior office at the age of 26 and reached the cabinet at 35. He served as chancellor of the exchequer on seven separate occasions. He was also prime minister on four occasions (for a total of 12 years). His time in politics began within months of the 1832 Reform Act. It ended on the eve of Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gladstone began life as a Tory but supported Peel's repeal of the Corn Laws and in the 1850s helped found the modern Liberal Party. Governments under him disestablished the Anglican church in Ireland, reformed English education, the army and the civil service, created parish councils, introduced the secret ballot and brought Britain nearer to being a genuine democracy by extending the franchise to the rural working classes. He failed, however, in the greatest single enterprise of his life: his attempt to bring home rule to Ireland. And, in failing, he split his party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although a late-developing political radical, Gladstone remained a social conservative. Nevertheless, he was the first major British politician to take his case to the people. His "excursions to the populace" shocked the Queen and the conservative establishment. His pamphlet denouncing Turkish atrocities in Bulgaria sold 200,000 copies, and in 1876 he addressed a rapt audience of 10,000 on the subject in driving rain on Blackheath. Three years later on his Midlothian campaign, he spoke on one occasion to 20,000 in Edinburgh's Waverley Market. Those who fainted were lifted over the crowd's heads as though dead. That apart, he was an extraordinary creature. He kept a diary almost every day for 69 years. He travelled widely and walked far (thinking nothing, aged 65, of covering 29 rough miles in the Alps). He collected pictures and china, swam in the sea and executed other men's wills (even when prime minister). For some reason, he rejoiced in felling trees. "The forest laments", Lord Randolph Churchill commented, "in order that Mr Gladstone may perspire." He also spent evenings in some of the seedier parts of London "rescuing" prostitutes. Overcome with guilt (for what?) he indulged in self-flagellation. He may have been sado-masochist.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, "the people's William" was one of the most amazing men who ever lived, towering over all his successors, save possibly Winston Churchill, as he did above his contemporaries. Under the circumstances, it is not surprising that he has daunted biographers. Apart from innumerable brief lives and scholarly monographs, there have been only two full-length biographies since his death nearly a century ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But now in Roy Jenkins, a fine writer and a former home secretary, chancellor of the exchequer and president of the European Commission, the Grand Old Man has met his ideal biographer. Theology aside, Lord Jenkins's interests are almost as capacious as his subject's. He writes of Gladstone as he might of a near-contemporary, with affection and intimate knowledge, but also with wry detachment. His style nears a gentle parody of Gladstone's own, with deliberate archaisms, convoluted syntax and a calculated absence of commas. He takes the great man seriously, but not too seriously.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not the least of Lord Jenkins's strengths is his own experience, which gives him the knowledge and the confidence to judge, for example, Gladstone's handling of home rule: sadly, Gladstone "responded with courage and passion but without a tactical dexterity to match his strategic vision." He totally mishandled, in particular, his personal relations with Joseph Chamberlain. But this is not a narrowly political work. It is an in-the-flesh and in-the-round portrait of (in Lord Jenkins's own phrase) "a remarkable specimen of humanity". "Gladstone" is, quite simply, a masterpiece of the biographer's art--a book that will instruct and entertain for generations to come.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
