<html><head><title>The Sacred Chain</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl22.jpg"><img src="cs22.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>ACRED</font> C<font size=-1>HAIN</font><br></h2>
<p>By Norman Cantor.<br>
<i>HarperCollins; 480 pages; $15 and &#163;20.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3jb22.html">Jacket Copy</a><br>
<p><b>Biography</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>NORMAN CANTOR is Professor of History, Sociology and Comparative Literature at New York University. He is the author of many books, including Inventing the Middle Ages, which was nominated for the American National Book Critics Circle Award, Twentieth Century Culture, Medieval Lives, and The Civilization of the Middle Ages. Among his many academic honours are appointments as a Rhodes Scholar, Porter Ogden Jacobus Fellow at Princeton University, Professor of Medieval Studies at the State University of New York, and Fulbright Professor at Tel Aviv University. He lives in New York Ciy and Sag Harbor, Long Island. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
