<html><head><title>A long goodbye?</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr7.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Jewish history</b></p>
<h2>A long goodbye?</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex22.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> S<font size=-1>ACRED</font> C<font size=-1>HAIN</font></a>&nbsp; By Norman Cantor.<br>
<li><a href="3ex26.html"></i>V<font size=-1>ANISHING</font> D<font size=-1>IASPORA</font></a>&nbsp; By Bernard Wasserstein.<br>
</ul>


<p>NOBODY could accuse Norman Cantor of telling Jews only what they want to hear. An eminent Jewish professor of history at New York University, he is well placed to be provocative without risking the slur of anti-Semitism. He exploits this position to the full. Few non-Jews would dare to write, for example, of the "skill of some Jewish billionaires in skirting the limits of the law with the aid of high-priced New York Jewish attorneys."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In almost every episode of Jewish history, Mr Cantor finds something to complain about and something with which to berate the Jews. To cap it all he says their troubled story is about to end as the chosen people choose to disappear by assimilation, intermarriage and underbreeding. He mournfully concludes that they are "going home now into the mist of history, into the remembrance of times long past, to rest with their God." Which recalls the joke about the Jew who complains about the terrible food in a restaurant, adding "and such small portions!"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The origin of the Jews is so uncertain as to be speculative, as Mr Cantor shows in the absorbing first part of his study. Verifiable evidence begins only with the end of the Davidic era at the beginning of the first millennium <font size=-1>BC</font>; anything before that, he credibly argues, is the stuff of myth. What is clear is that the Jews have always been a people apart, so singular as to arouse the conjecture that they may have arrived on this planet from outer space (not to mention the all-too-widespread wish that they would return there). The peculiar creative energy of the Jews is an undeniable fact, the author repeatedly asserts, for which they have been persecuted down the ages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What explains the achievements of the Jews, which are indeed so disproportionate as not to need Mr Cantor's occasional attempts to exaggerate them? He seems to regard it as obvious both that Jews are genetically superior to other races and that the notion of race itself is unproblematical. Without a lot more said, however, the claim to genetic advantage is as baffling as the idea of extra-terrestrial origin. Mr Cantor may be on to part of something when he mentions selective breeding. By and large, Jewish elites have been aristocracies of intellect. In which other cultures have fathers tried so hard to marry off daughters to the inheritors not of land but of brains--that is, to rabbis' sons?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Be that as it may, rabbis are not exactly Mr Cantor's favourite people. He blames the traditional religious establishment for holding back the Jewish spirit throughout the ages and in all parts of the diaspora. Not for him the romanticisation of the compulsively pious East European <i>shtetl</i>. In the world of "Fiddler on the Roof" that is still aped by the ultra-orthodox, Mr Cantor sees only "the suffocating, conservative detritus that shut the Jews off from the technological and intellectual projects of the modern world." Among his recommendations for a healthier Jewish future are a broader education for rabbis, shorter and livelier services, and a redirection of Jewish philanthropy away from the state of Israel and towards the dispersed communities themselves. But he does not expect to be heeded in time by the rabbis or by their dwindling flocks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The resources exist, Mr Cantor claims, for a renaissance of Jewish culture, though he predicts that these resources will not be used. One has to agree with this part of his pessimism because it is not clear how they could be. What he seems to have dreamily in mind is some sort of rapprochement between "post-modernism", which he identifies as a movement stimulated by four Jews--Claude L&eacute;vi-Strauss, Noam Chomsky, Harold Bloom and Jacques Derrida--and traditional Judaism. Neither modernism nor post-modernism is rendered more perspicuous by Mr Cantor's efforts to Judaise these nebulous ideas by attributing them solely to thinkers of Jewish origin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The Sacred Chain" is something of a mixture. Nearly always an absorbing read, the book is especially interesting on the development of Jewish culture in Europe during the Middle Ages. But sloppiness creeps in too often (Levi Eshkol, not Golda Meir, was Israel's prime minister during the Six Day War of 1967, for example). There is just enough intellectual and factual vagueness to give effective ammunition to those Jews who will hate the book anyway for its harsh home truths and its debunking tone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Professor Bernard Wasserstein's "Vanishing Diaspora" is a more careful and focused work that offers an authoritative account of European Jewry since 1945. The legacies of fascism and communism hang heavily over his well-told story, as they must. Although Mr Wasserstein substitutes hard demographic fact for Mr Cantor's woollier cultural diagnoses, the conclusion encapsulated in his title is reached by a similar non sequitur: the Jews are changing, <i>ergo</i> they are disappearing. How can two Jewish historians forget that from the prophets onwards the Jews have repeatedly believed that they were finished, only to find themselves metamorphosed yet very much still there? The Jews' history of resourcefulness and adaptability suggests it would make more sense to argue that they are changing, <i>ergo</i> they will not disappear.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
<p><i><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 The Economist Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</i></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
