<html><head><title>Vanishing Diaspora</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl26.jpg"><img src="cs26.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2></i>V<font size=-1>ANISHING</font> D<font size=-1>IASPORA</font><br></h2>
<p>By Bernard Wasserstein.<br>
<i>Hamish Hamilton; 352 pages; &#163;20. Harvard; $27.95</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt26.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>The Jews are disappearing from Europe. In 1939 there were ten million. After Hitler there were four million. Now there are under two million. On current projections the Jews will become virtually extinct as a significant element in European society over the course of the twenty-first century. Why is this happening?
</p><p>Vanishing Diaspora examines the reasons and places them in the larger context of contemporary European history. It relates demographic issues to the stubborn recurrence of the Jewish problem, in different forms, in the post-war period particularly in central and eastern Europe. It shows how this is connected with other issues: the memory of Nazi genocide, the failures of communism, the impact of Israel, and the effort to overcome Christian antisemitism.
</p><p>With exceptional eloquence and conviction, Vanishing Diaspora argues that survival for European Jews will ultimately depend on choices made by Jews themselves, who boast an alarming imbalance in their death-to-birth ratio, who have jettisoned religious observance in the spirit of a secular Europe, and who have lost their cultural distinctiveness to such an extent that many acknowledge their heritage solely through the 'entry and exit rituals of male circumcision and Jewish burial'.
</p><p>Drawing on a rich variety of sources, many hitherto unpublished, and written with Bernard Wasserstein's characteristic clarity and intelligence, Vanishing Diaspora is the first comprehensive social and political history of the Jews in post-war Europe. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
