<html><head><title>US Intelligence at the Crossroads</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl35.jpg"><img src="cs35.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2></i>US I<font size=-1>NTELLIGENCE</font> <font size=-1>AT</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> C<font size=-1>ROSSROADS</font><br></h2>
<p>Edited by Roy Godson, Ernest May and Gary Schmitt.<br>
<i>Brassey's; 315 pages; $25.95 and &#163;20.95.</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt35.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>U.S. intelligence stands at the crossroads. As the new security era unfolds, fundamental questions about the roles and missions of intelligence are now at center stage. This timely volume highlights key issues at the heart of that debate. Meeting over the past two years, the Working Group on Intelligence Reform, whose membership includes the country's most experienced practitioners and scholars of intelligence, has identified the principal issues of intelligence reform and developed innovative approaches to solving the problems associated with a major shift in policy. U.S. Intelligence at the Crossroads presents fresh, divergent perspectives on topics ranging from the very purpose of intelligence to pressing policy concerns about weapons proliferation, economic espionage, and threats posed by nonstate actors such as criminal and terrorist organizations. Contributors include high-ranking officials from the CIA, FBI, and the departments of State and Defense, as well as leading academic specialists such as Joseph Nye, Abram Shulsky, and James Q. Wilson. The agendas for reform laid out here will remain at the center of the arguments about intelligence in the halls of Congress, the intelligence community, and the media for years to come. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
