Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>False advertising</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr2.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>Intelligence</b></p>
<h2>False advertising</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex52.html">A C<font size=-1>ENTURY</font> <font size=-1>OF</font> S<font size=-1>PIES</font></a>&nbsp; By Jeffrey Richelson.<br>
<li><a href="3ex37.html">D<font size=-1>IRTY</font> T<font size=-1>RICKS</font> <font size=-1>OR</font> T<font size=-1>RUMP</font> C<font size=-1>ARDS</font></a>&nbsp; By Roy Godson.<br>
<li><a href="3ex35.html"></i>US I<font size=-1>NTELLIGENCE</font> <font size=-1>AT</font> <font size=-1>THE</font> C<font size=-1>ROSSROADS</font></a>&nbsp; Edited by Roy Godson, Ernest May and Gary Schmitt.<br>
<li><a href="3ex53.html"></i>T<font size=-1>WILIGHT</font> W<font size=-1>ARRIORS</font></a>&nbsp; By Martin Arostegui.<br>
</ul>


<p>SPIES and counter-spies trade under the wonderful, if misleading, brand name of "intelligence". But, as with many fine brands, the product is old-fashioned and demand is declining. Russia's far-flung agents and analysts have seen their empire fade away. Western teams have lost their favourite target but, like any dying industry, insist that more state spending will prove their value in non-traditional activities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"A Century of Spies" is enlivened by tales of the multiple betrayals that resulted. Jeffrey Richelson is part of the apparatus he describes, or at least related to it. He is a senior fellow of the National Security Archive in America--presumably crammed with classified information which its fellows are sworn not to divulge--and he seems to have set out to provide a reference book for graduate students of espionage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He offers short, but not exactly snappy, accounts of the trade since the first world war, when wireless interception and aerial observation began. The Americans then got out of the business, when their secretary of state, Henry Stimson, opined: "Gentlemen do not read each other's mail." It was the second world war that gave rise, with British advice and bitter in-fighting, to America's vast secret bureaucracies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But discussing a century's worth of intelligence means sketching in a century's worth of history, which inevitably congests the narrative. Moreover, well-informed insiders may know the full story--but as insiders they must not say things that outsiders are not meant to know. The vigilant reader must always be asking why he is offered this fact, not that one. For instance, Mr Richelson gives an account of the muddles that led to the shooting down of a South Korean airliner by Soviet fighters in 1983, and (with ample references to published sources) lays the main blame on navigational errors by the civilian pilot. But he does not mention the equally horrible failure that caused the <font size=-1>USS</font> Vincennes to shoot down an Iranian airliner in 1988.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Richelson touches upon Israeli intelligence lightly, and only where it affected America's. He says little about French operations, some of which have been ruthlessly effective. He does not mention Africa, although for three decades the Americans and Russians played expensive, ineffectual and blood-soaked games in Zaire, Angola and Somalia. This is a sketchy history of the big league, when little-league games are the ones worth watching.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Roy Godson, a university professor, is another intelligence insider. In "Dirty Tricks or Trump Cards" he covers much of the same historical ground as Mr Richelson, but more polemically; he seems nostalgic for the old days of transatlantic unity, when the British counted and the Americans used muscle against clearly identified foes. He ends by pleading for, as he puts it, "reducing the intelligence deficit in the interest of future security". It is understandable that he thinks his own business needs more support. But he does not suggest how much it should cost, how it should be managed or what it should do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The field of view is widened in a set of essays edited by the same Mr Godson, with Ernest May and Gary Schmitt. In "<font size=-1>US</font> Intelligence at the Crossroads" some active and former bureaucrats, and some academics who moonlight for the business, discuss what real management-consultants might call the repositioning of intelligence. Several writers frankly, if mildly, admit past errors. None manages to identify a useful future for the spying trade. The best essay, by Randall Fort, an intelligence man now employed in industry, explains why it is foolish to think that government agencies can usefully undertake industrial espionage. To put it more bluntly than he does, if banks and investors and contractors want confidential studies of prospective rivals, they can employ better people than governments can afford on public-sector salaries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Good people employed in intelligence work (and there are some) often grow indignant that their trade has a bad name. The book by Martin Arostegui, "Twilight Warriors", helps to explain why. He admires the "special forces" whose operatives, by his account, are rude to everybody including their own officers, and spend their time calling in helicopter strikes, swinging from ropes into windows and shooting bad guys. Violent anecdotes, purportedly true, are told in no particular sequence, with no particular understanding and no attempt to establish a context. But it is nice to be assured that the director of operations of the Grupo Especial de Operaciones in Spain's national police force is Inspector Carrion, and that parachutists of the French Foreign Legion who, if Mr Arostegui is to be believed, man the Commandos de Renseignement et d'Action dans la Profondeur are <font size=-1>CRAP</font>.

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
