<html><head><title>Twilight Warriors</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl53.jpg"><img src="cs53.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2></i>T<font size=-1>WILIGHT</font> W<font size=-1>ARRIORS</font><br></h2>
<p>By Martin Arostegui.<br>
<i>Bloomsbury; 313 pages; &#163;16.99</i>.<br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt53.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>FROM THE SECRET BUT ULTIMATELY abortive plan to murder Hitler, through the Iranian Embassy siege in London and the dramatic scud hunt in the Gulf War, to the storming of a hijacked airliner in Marseilles in 1994, Twilight Warriors reports on the covert actions of the world's most elite special forces from World War II to the present.
</p><p>Although it focuses principally on Britain's SAS, the USA's Delta Force, Seals, Green Berets and Rangers, Germany's GSG9, France's GIGN and the Australian SAS, Twilight Warriors also covers less well known organizations, including Britain's SBS, Spain's GEO and BOEL and France's 2REP. Moving between Europe, the USA, South-East Asia, Central America and the Middle East, it supplements a wide-ranging account of the origins, development and major undercover operations of special forces with a detailed examination of their selection procedures and training, weaponry, cornmunications and tactics.
</p><p>Drawing on three years' research and exclusive interviews with key special forces personnel, Twilight Warriors reveals much that has not previously been disclosed about this necessarily secretive field and provides the most comprehensive survey yet published. <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
