<html><head><title>Don't exaggerate</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td><td align=center valign=top><img src="3gr3.gif" align=center alt="review graphic"></td></tr></table>
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td>
<td valign=top>
<br>

<p><b>American schools</b></p>
<h2>Don't exaggerate</h2><ul><li><a href="3ex33.html">D<font size=-1>UMBING</font> D<font size=-1>OWN</font> O<font size=-1>UR</font> K<font size=-1>IDS</font></a>&nbsp; By Charles Sykes.<br>
<li><a href="3ex34.html">T<font size=-1>HE</font> M<font size=-1>ANUFACTURED</font> C<font size=-1>RISIS</font></a>&nbsp; By David Berliner and Bruce Biddle.<br>
<li><a href="3ex32.html">T<font size=-1>INKERING</font> T<font size=-1>OWARDS</font> U<font size=-1>TOPIA</font></a>&nbsp; By David Tyack and Larry Cuban.<br>
</ul>


<p>"EVERYONE has won, and all must have prizes," said the Dodo in "Alice in Wonderland". Charles Sykes claims that this philosophy predominates in America's schools. Obsessed with the self-esteem of children, educators are determined to wipe out grading of pupils' work, in case less than A-plus gives the dears a breakdown. Or so he strongly argues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pumping up children's self-esteem at any cost is a lunacy which Mr Sykes alleges is imposed on American schools by a creature called "the Blob". This is a nickname for a despised "education establishment" coined by a former Republican education secretary, William Bennett. The Blob, argues Mr Sykes, is destroying serious teaching in order to make education more relevant to children's lives. The Blob's aim is to turn schools into all-purpose social-engineering and psychotherapy centres. Classrooms, on this view, are becoming touchy-feely places where two-plus-two equals whatever the kids are comfortable with.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sinister brain he diagnoses as throbbing away at the head of the Blob is the National Education Association (<font size=-1>NEA</font>), a "weird institutional mutant" which is part trade union, part professional body and part political party. The <font size=-1>NEA</font> and its child-centred philosophy are often identified with the 1960s but, as he points out, battles between educational "progressives" and "traditionalists" have been raging for more than a century, with the progressive, child-centred camp drawing inspiration from leaders of the Enlightenment and with the traditionalists launching counter-attacks as long ago as the 1890s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Almost every page of "Dumbing Down Our Kids" contains an anecdote about a crazy scheme of the Blob's. Blame and mockery are trowelled on. Kids cannot spell? Call their mistakes "invented spelling". Kids cannot add up? Get them to form a committee to argue out what four plus four equals. If the group's answer is wrong, the question must be too hard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sykes predicts a parent-led counter-revolution: bad teachers will be sacked and the rest will get performance-related pay; failing schools will be shut and surviving ones will spend more time on exam results, less on their pupils' feelings. He calls also for the abolition of the federal and of state education departments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Readers who think they have heard a lot of all this before will be right. The quarrel in America between "civics" and "basics" is almost as old as public education itself. Americans have always wanted schools to have a social mission but have agonised equally about the damage such ideals might do to the three <font size=-1>R</font>s. A century ago the mission was to turn immigrants into American citizens; nowadays, sensibly enough, it is to teach children to beware of stereotypes and to avoid racism or sexism. Mr Sykes is decidedly among the agonisers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A contrary view is "The Manufactured Crisis" by David Berliner and Bruce Biddle. Their book, they say, was "written in outrage" at the baseless exaggeration of educational critics such as Mr Sykes. Recalling Hitler's maxim that people will more readily believe a big lie than a small one, they accuse "reactionary voices" among Republicans, on the religious right and in conservative think-tanks of a big, motivated lie: the aim, the authors argue, is the replacement of public schooling with a private, voucher-funded system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no hard evidence of a decline in school results, argue Messrs Berliner and Biddle. National attainment results, they report, have hardly changed since the 1960s. They cite a study which found that average scores in <font size=-1>IQ</font> tests have been rising steadily since 1932. They note also that the share of Americans completing high school and the share graduating from college has shot up over the past 50 years. And despite complaints about poorly-educated workers, America, they add, has the highest productivity in the world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In attempting to demolish every last shred of evidence of academic decline, Messrs Biddle and Berliner go too far. Their definition of learning at times sounds conveniently elastic. For example, they urge Americans not to worry about the early algebraic attainments of some children in Asian countries because Americans of like age do more sport and have lots of hobbies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Dumbing Down Our Kids" and "The Manufactured Crisis" should be treated as mutual antidotes. As a useful chaser for the two of them, "Tinkering Towards Utopia" describes how little impact the education-policy folk have actually had over the years: the "basic grammar" of schools was set in concrete in the mid-19th century and attempts at reform have made only dents.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The core of that grammar does not change: children are divided into classes by age and often by perceived ability; one teacher teaches them at a time; pupils get set tasks for which they get grades; for older pupils, the school day divides into subjects; exams measure pupils' "attainment".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As David Tyack and Larry Cuban argue, this is how parents and teachers think a "real school" should be run. Even reform schemes which appeared at first to produce great change had little impact. For instance, when kindergartens and junior high schools were invented to cure the supposed failings of elementary and high schools, they soon came to resemble them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reformers tend to come in two guises: liberal-minded progressives, whom Mr Sykes lambasts, and business-minded types, who insist that by adopting the production-line methods of Frederick Taylor and Henry Ford schools will become efficient, responsive and even profitable. These reformers share many faults, say Messrs Tyack and Cuban, particularly a neglect of history and a deafness to teachers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All three books are tolerably written and plausibly argued. Together they make a balanced set. A love of drama, if nothing else, is likely to make Mr Sykes's the most popular. He tells of looming disaster, finds villains and offers clear-sounding "solutions", a much catchier package than the sceptical "Everything's been tried before" or "It's not as bad as you think."

<br><br><p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; -  &nbsp  <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a></p>
