<html><head><title>James Thurber</title></head>
<body background="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td valign=top align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/rlogo.gif" alt="review logo"></td>
<td align=center valign=top>
<a href="cl38.jpg"><img src="cs38.gif" alt="cover image"><p>Full Image</p></a>
</td></tr></table>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td valign=bottom align=left><img src="http://www.economist.com/review/images/instrap.gif"></td><td>
<h2>J<font size=-1>AMES </font>T<font size=-1>HURBER</font>:<br> H<font size=-1>IS</font> L<font size=-1>IFE</font> <font size=-1>AND</font> T<font size=-1>IMES</font><br></h2>
<p>By Harrison Kinney.<br>
<i>Henry Holt; 1,238 pages; $40</i><br>
</p><br>
<a href="3bt38.html">Biography</a><br>
<p><b>Jacket Copy</p></b>
<p>
</p><p>
</p><p>In 1950 James Thurber wrote to a Time magazine reporter to suggest six close friends as sources for a forthcoming profile. "There is also," he noted, "a young man named Harrison Kinney, who can be reached through the New Yorker offices, whose thesis on my work, done last.year for Columbia University, contains more facts than I had known." In the years since, armed with the advantage of a personal acquaintance with Thurber, Kinney has interviewed scores of his subject's contemporaries to fashion this graceful, witty, and compelling narrative of a life and its circle.
</p><p>Born in Columbus, Ohio, to the eccentric family re-created in his classic memoir, My Life and Hard Times,  James Thurber lurched from stint to stint as a newspaper reporter before landing, in 1927, the job that would make his career and help to define the future of The New Yorker rnagazine. Sharing an office with E. B. White, with whom he later co-authored his first book, Is Sex Necessary?, Thurber quickly mastered his new terrain, if not the uninhibited social life that came with it. His first work reveals its author's frustrations with women - from his first marriage to Althea Adams through his intense, longtime romance with Ann Honeycutt. Nor does Thurber's second wife emerge unscathed; though she saw him through the trauma of blindness at age forty- five and provided a stable backdrop for his work until his death.
</p><p>Kinney's portrait is a sympathetic but full study, one that reveals the complexities and contradictions of character. Thurber's post-cocktail outbursts are balanced against his sweetness to the underdog; his fantasies inform the real glory of his prose and drawings. "Humor is my sword and my shield," Thurber remarked, and both aspects of his art are represented in this splendid volume <br>
</p>
<p><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,rev">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/archive.html">Review Archive</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/review/index.html">Review List</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="review.html">This Review</a></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
